<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-TV-FASHION-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL TV: TUNING IN TO FASHION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES -- one showing the cast of ``Family Law'' and
the other featuring David Boreanaz, who stars in ``Angel'' -- are
available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of this article. The art can
be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please specify that you want the
art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files. Also, this
article gives a thorough roundup of the fashions from the fall TV
shows. However, you may pick certain shows and cut others to lower
the word count.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROSE-MARIE TURK 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The fall TV lineup is bursting at the seams with
women who are passionate about fashion and costume designers who
are meeting their needs _ not only with designer labels, vintage
looks and brand names, but with lots of sexy clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Whether any of the fall shows will produce the next ``Y''
necklace, Jennifer Aniston haircut or Ally McBeal's short skirt is
still a question, but this season's offerings are still bound to
amuse viewers who focus on what the characters wear as much as on
what they say and whom they covet.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the looks now popping up on the small screen are Vera
Wang and Zandra Rhodes gowns, full karate-style pants, cropped
cargo pants, Levi's L-2 line and 701 brands, trendy leathers, vinyl
and fake fur. In addition, there are Zelda velvet jackets,
Native-American pieces and over-the-top looks such as Moschino's
fur-trimmed sweaters and leopard pants.
</P>
<P>
   Costume designers say they scour both coasts, Canada and Europe
for hot looks and vintage pieces. Neiman Marcus, Betsey Johnson,
Patricia Field, Bebe, BCBG, Holt Renfrew, Decades, Wasteland, Jet
Rag, Saks Fifth Avenue, Urban Outfitters, Gucci and Diesel are
among their favorite haunts. Some costumers even design their own
clothes for their characters.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a look that will take off is less of a concern to most
costume designers than simply doing their job, which is wardrobing
their characters week after week.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a guide to the fall shows, the costumes and the costume
designers' favorite shops.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Popular'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Network: WB.
</P>
<P>
   Concept: The trials and tribulations of the high school pecking
order, in which clothes _ from Jean Paul Gaultier to the Gap _ play
a prominent role.
</P>
<P>
   Costume designer: Carol Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   Clothes: With 60 to 80 changes per episode for the principals,
who include three ``wealthy girls,'' the labels include Gaultier,
Theory, Chakin &AMP; Capone, BCBG, Mooks, Banana Republic, Gap, Sold
and ``a little bit of Betsey Johnson when we want to inject that
funkiness here and there,'' Ramsey said.
</P>
<P>
   Stores: Ramsey shops Madison and Curve on Robertson Boulevard,
Ambrosia in Beverly Hills, where she finds ``a lot of interesting
things from Europe,'' and Urban Outfitters ``for that high-school
funky look.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Love and Money'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Network: CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Concept: Will it be love or money (and more Vera Wang) for Paget
Brewster, who plays the heiress/teacher lead in this romantic
comedy, which also features Swoosie Kurtz as her wealthy mother in
stellar threads.
</P>
<P>
   Costume designer: Simon Tuke.
</P>
<P>
   Clothes: A Vera Wang wedding gown with full tulle skirt, Ralph
Lauren and Donna Karan pants along with Laundry's ``very classic,
simple dresses'' and sweaters. Tuke, who prefers short, fitted
sweaters in soft colors, is also using Autumn Cashmere. Kurtz wears
Vera Wang, a mix of Herve Leger and St. John Knit dresses, as well
as a green velvet bias-cut Zandra Rhodes gown.
</P>
<P>
   Stores: Tuke shops Diane Merrick on Melrose Avenue, Saks Fifth
Avenue, Betsey Johnson, Neiman Marcus and features used jewelry by
Allison Schmidt of Marble Canyon Metalworks in Sedona, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Wasteland'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Network: ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Concept: A group of twentysomething friends in Manhattan face
the realities of life-and-dress after college.
</P>
<P>
   Costume designer: Trish Summerville.
</P>
<P>
   Clothes: Summerville has the task of dressing seven main
characters, aged 26 to 29, who live in New York. Summerville is
using cords and ``jean-cut'' velvet pants ``in a great array of
colors'' from Earl Jeans. Her pants resources include Dockers and
Pauline, whose silhouettes range from fuller karate styles to slim
legs in stretch fabrics. Along with Levi's cropped cargo pants, she
has included Levi's sweaters and hooded tops.
</P>
<P>
   Among her ``finds'' are Dockers' ``very cute girls' leather
jackets'' and ``funky, abstract'' short-sleeved shirts by Cow Moos.
She is also using Native-American-inspired pieces that range from a
halter top and long skirt with a fringed hem by Josephine Loka to
beaded bracelets and single-strand necklaces from Stormie.
</P>
<P>
   Stores: In addition to shopping Los Angeles, New York and San
Francisco, Summerville has pieces custom made. They include a long
patchwork suede skirt, leather motocross jackets and suede pants
from Los Angeles designer Varla Vortex.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Once and Again'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Network: ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Concept: A romantic comedy set in the Midwest that centers on
the very attractive 40-ish Sela Ward and Billy Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Costume designer: Kathryn Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   Clothes: ``We keep her sexy yet simple,'' Morrison said, noting
the star's basically casual wardrobe includes Levi's 701 jeans and
Armani Exchange sweaters. ``She has a staple necklace as well,''
Morrison said, describing a delicate diamond-and-gold pendant
created for Ward by Los Angeles designer Devon Page McCleary.
</P>
<P>
   With a cast of female characters ranging from a teen to a lawyer
to Ward's sexy best friend, Morrison is using labels such as
Diesel, Bulldog, Donna Karan and Calvin Klein. She is also using
Juliana suits for Susanna Thompson, who plays the lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Ward's 14-year old daughter, played by Julia Whelan, wears a lot
of ``basic Gap,'' including loose-fit button-fly jeans. She wears
Levi's L-2 line, because, she said, ``It's very urban and
contemporary for high school kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Stores: Express and Forever 21 to Barneys, Neiman Marcus and
Nordstrom's Woodland Hills, where she likes the junior department,
and Aldo in the Beverly Center for shoes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Jack &AMP; Jill'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Network: WB.
</P>
<P>
   Concept: A romantic comedy set in New York with a tricky love
triangle, in which he is Jill, she is Jack and the costume design
is ``realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Costume designer: Debra McGuire.
</P>
<P>
   Clothes: She's using ``a softer palette'' from a variety of Los
Angeles designers, including skirts, sweaters and dresses from
Shelli Segal of Laundry; suits from William B.; Daryl K pants, and
tops and pants from Trina Turk. But with three female leads, who
include Jaime Pressly as a dancer and Sara Paulson as a seasoned
journalist, McGuire's eclectic mix also includes Dossa, Betsey
Johnson, Fi Fi, Easel, Earl Jeans, Danskin, Bebe, ABS and Toska.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Snoops'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Network: ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Concept: A high-tech private-eye series, featuring Gina Gershon
and some sleek leather jumpsuits inspired by Emma Peel and ``The
Avengers.''
</P>
<P>
   Costume designer: Alexandra Welker.
</P>
<P>
   Clothes: ``I'm designing a lot of her clothes, which is a luxury
in TV,'' said Welker, who is using trendy leathers, vinyl and fake
fur. Her custom pieces range from a skin-baring burgundy suede top
to low-slung black leather pants and a zipper-trimmed lambskin
jumpsuit. Additional separates include an embroidered and fringed
olive silk skirt by Catherine, which Gershon wears with a John
Eshaya T-shirt, Diesel denim jacket and knee-high Charles David
boots.
</P>
<P>
   The show's two other sleuths, played by Paula Marshall and Paula
Jai Parker, appear in an array of labels and silhouettes that
includes Emporio Armani suits and knee-length pencil-slim skirts;
more suits from Tahari, Calvin Klein and Oscar de la Renta; fitted
blouses by Theory and Carrie Rosten, and unusual knit tops from
Tehen and Petro Zillia.
</P>
<P>
   Stores: Welker's retail finds include a number of Gucci pieces,
such as pants, a bright red wrap-waist blouse and a leather jacket
that is ``a cross between a scuba and motorcycle jacket.'' In Los
Angeles, Welker shops vintage stores, such as Decades, Wasteland,
Jet Rag and Aardvarks, as well as Neiman Marcus, Barneys, Saks,
Macy's, Bloomingdale's, Fred Segal and American Rag. When in New
York, she shops The Find boutique, vintage stores and small
specialty stores such as Alpana Bawa, where she found ``great
bright and tropical pieces that I can work into the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Family Law'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Network: CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Concept: A legal drama that runs the gamut from a sophisticated
single mom to an ambitious younger woman to an
ex-con-turned-attorney, played by Dixie Carter, gussied up with
splashy jewelry and sexy suits.
</P>
<P>
   Costume designer: Linda Bass.
</P>
<P>
   Clothes: For Kathleen Quinlan, in the role of single mom and
lawyer, Bass decided on ``a contemporary retro look.'' The mix
includes fitted Zelda velvet jackets, Calvin Klein skirts and
flat-front pants, Donna Karan and Calvin Klein blouses or vintage
Forties shirts and Katayone Adeli sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   As the series' ``young ambitious lawyer,'' Julie Warner wears
``more traditional power suits _ Emporio Armani, Donna Karan,
Tahari,'' Bass said, noting her footwear is a combination of Robert
Clergerie, Prada and Miu Miu.
</P>
<P>
   For Dixie Carter, cast as a country-and-western
singer/convict-turned-lawyer, ``anything goes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very flamboyant,'' said Bass, rattling off a source list
that includes Rifat Ozbek, Todd Oldham, St. John and Valentino.
``Then I mix it with something I find on Hollywood Boulevard to
make it really crazy.'' There are also such items as a Moschino
fur-trimmed sweater and Cache leopard skin pants and red bustier.
Carter's accessories range from bold pieces of St. John jewelry to
``classic Chanel bags in every color.''
</P>
<P>
   Stores: Quinlan's shoes, from Barneys private label collection,
include heeled Mary Janes, ``that work with everything,'' and black
pumps. Her ``delicate, romantic'' jewelry comes from Barneys and
the San Francisco-based Museum of Jewelry catalog.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Action'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Network: Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Concept: A cynical, over-the-top look at Hollywood, with a
wardrobe to match for Illeana Douglas, who plays a
former-child-star-turned-prostitute-turned-movie exec.
</P>
<P>
   Costume designer: Jane Janiger.
</P>
<P>
   Clothes: Cynthia Rowley and Nanette Lapore, both ``personal
friends'' of Douglas', according to Janiger, are well represented
on the show. Predominant silhouettes include slipdresses paired
with everything from BCBG shoes to black spandex Gucci boots or
colorful Yves Saint Laurent boots. Additional Gucci pieces include
a pair of '60s-inspired velvet pants and matching purse that
Douglas wears with a Bette Page fringed top. From Versace, there
are miniskirts and a strapless black wool pinstripe jumpsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Stores: Going for an ``offbeat'' look, Janiger said she is
making some pieces and shopping a range of stores that includes
Playclothes in Studio City, for her vintage finds, and Loehmann's.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Angel'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Network: WB.
</P>
<P>
   Concept: In this ``Buffy the Vampire'' spin-off, Charisma
Carpenter is a struggling actress with moxie and a bohemian-chic
wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Costume designer: Jessica Pazdernik.
</P>
<P>
   Clothes: There are silk-satin, back-baring halter tops from
Urban Outfitters on Melrose, which Pazdernik combines with black
Theory pants (``cropped at the ankle to give that fresh funky
look'') and Steve Madden's black thick-heeled thong wedges.
Carpenter's jewelry statement is a mix of a Nike men's sports watch
with beaded bracelets from Madison and Jennifer Kaufman in Los
Angeles and Urban Outfitters.
</P>
<P>
   Pants include Earl Jeans worn with rolled up cuffs.
Fringe-trimmed Levi's are worn oversized ``so they hang down past
her belly button.'' And among the Daryl K pants is a black twill
pair with a gray stripe around one thigh.
</P>
<P>
   There are also denim jackets from Levi's and denim-style cord
jackets from Theory and Katayone Adeli. Additional Adeli pieces
include soft cotton-knit novelty tank tops and straight-leg pants.
And there are Calvin Klein camisoles ``in every color I could
find,'' Pazdernik noted. Carpenter's dressier outfits include a
Barneys black strapless satin-voile dress worn with an XOXO black
crocheted shawl.
</P>
<P>
   Stores: A favorite outfit includes a long Amy Jean denim skirt
with suede inserts, from Traffic in the Beverly Center, combined
with an ``ethnic'' beaded halter tank from Lisa Kline, on Robertson
Boulevard, and velvet wedge flip flops from Rinaldi, also on
Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Sex and the City'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Network: HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Concept: Four single women are on the loose in New York City.
The show is in reruns now, which gives viewers a chance to relive
such thrills as the Fendi ``baguette'' bag in its many
incarnations.
</P>
<P>
   Costume designers: Patricia Field and Rebecca Field (no relation
to each other).
</P>
<P>
   Clothes: The show's popularity is high, and viewers, according
to Patricia Field, have responded to a number of fashion
statements, including the gold ``name'' necklace that was made for
Sarah Jessica Parker's character, as well as a Donna Karan
``invisible-strap'' dress.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is what Patricia Field calls ``the bag of the year''
_ the Fendi baguette Parker carried for most of the season in many
incarnations.
</P>
<P>
   Stores: The overall look for the show is ``hippie rock 'n' roll
couture. It could be a $5 shawl with a $400 pair of shoes _ a mix
of a whole range of things,'' Patricia Field noted, describing a
Parker outfit that mixes a leather halter top from a Patricia Field
store with an Alberta Feretti taffeta ballgown skirt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Spin City'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Network: ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Concept: Heather Locklear moves from ``Melrose Place'' to the
mayor's office in New York and gets a sexy, sophisticated new look.
</P>
<P>
   Costume designer: Patricia Field.
</P>
<P>
   Clothes: Among a number of Gucci pieces for Locklear is what
Field calls a ``sharply cut'' pantsuit. There is also a Chloe silk
dress ``with a mellow print,'' as well as a range of selections
from Dolce &AMP; Gabbana and Ralph Lauren. Skirts are knee-length and
the color palette includes black, white, bone and red.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Rose-Marie Turk is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
