<HEADER>
A0671 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SAFRICA-ELECT-BOS &LR;      12-06 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ELECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TWO AFRICAN COUNTRIES, DEMOCRACY COMES HARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAPUTO, Mozambique _ To the west lies Namibia: arid, scrubby,
battered by cold Atlantic swells. To the east is Mozambique:
fertile as Eden, teased by the warm lapping tides of the Indian
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   There was little suspense to the elections held over the past
several days in these two countries along Africa's southern rim,
the last African ballots in a century that brought this continent
great despair. Few doubt that the incumbents will be back at work
when all the votes are counted.
</P>
<P>
   But that is where the similarity in the voting ends, and behind
the results lies a parable of Africa's progress on the eve of what
South African President Thabo Mbeki hopes will be ``the African
century.'' For while the continent has made great strides in the
past decade, shedding such scourges as apartheid and Zaire's
dictator, Mobutu Sese Seko, the elections in Namibia and
Mozambique, as divergent as the two countries' terrain, reflect the
critical struggle in Africa between domination and accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is holding in Namibia is the old nationalist model,'' in
which the liberating or ruling party ``is the custodian of the
nation, and anyone who disagrees is unpatriotic,'' said Mahmood
Mamdani, a specialist on Africa at Columbia University in New York.
``That model cracked in Mozambique. The ruling party was forced to
recognize its opponent. Mozambique is way ahead politically as a
pointer in how to deal with tensions in a postnationalist
society.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the elections _ Namibia's third, Mozambique's
second _ are benchmarks of the continent's progress. Ten years ago
Africa was torn apart by Cold War rivalry, Mobutu, and white-ruled
South Africa's regional war to preserve apartheid. Mozambique, like
Angola, another former Portuguese colony, was mired in a brutal,
decades-old war. Nelson Mandela was still in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Namibia is celebrating a decade of independence. South
Africa has majority rule. Nigeria has a civilian leader for the
first time in 20 years. Mozambique is peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   But the past 10 years were as bloody as they were transforming.
Ethiopia and Eritrea stopped fighting, and then started again.
Sudan's civil war never ceased. Liberia and Sierra Leone imploded.
More than 10,000 South Africans died in the final flames of
apartheid. Hutu killed roughly 800,000 Tutsi in Rwanda in 1994. An
international military coalition drove Mobutu out of Zaire in 1997,
and a year later the renamed Congo became a battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have cease-fires and elections forged democracies in Africa.
Angola emerged from decades of civil war in 1992, brokered a peace
pact, held elections, and descended back into chaos when the losers
returned to the bush.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 20th century, the positive changes of the past
decade have encouraged prominent leaders on the continent to talk
about an African renaissance. They want debt relief, an end to
Northern dominance in the United Nations, and greater cooperation
among developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more than any other two events, however, the elections
in Namibia and Mozambique illustrate that African nations,
individually and collectively, hold the key to their own success or
failure. The voting in both countries will be deemed substantially
fair, and polling stations were generally free of the intimidating
presence of police and military.
</P>
<P>
   But Namibia and Mozambique approached their elections from
decidedly different angles.
</P>
<P>
   Gaining independence in 1989 after a long and arduous liberation
struggle with South Africa, Namibia at first showed encouraging
signs. It encouraged the growth of civil society and strove for
fair and good governance. The trend did not last. President Sam
Nujoma and his former liberation movement, the South-West Africa
People's Organization, held a monopoly on power. By their second
term in power, priorities changed.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where the average person would be unable to afford
$1.40 test for the AIDS virus, members of parliament rushed through
a bill prior to the election granting themselves huge retirement
packages, whether or not they leave office. Earlier this year,
Nujoma spurred constitutional changes allowing him to seek a third
term, and persuaded the legislature to fund a large new home for
himself. The party used government letterhead for its campaign
materials.
</P>
<P>
   Namibia's is a well-trod path in Africa. Liberation movements
become ruling parties, start off well-meaning, but veer without the
checks and balances of political opposition. In the 1960s there was
Jomo Kenyatta of Kenya and Kenneth Kaunda of Zambia. By the 1980s
there was Daniel arap Moi of Kenya and Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe.
Unsatisfied with 19 years in power, Mugabe is rewriting Zimbabwe's
Constitution to allow him to rule until 2014.
</P>
<P>
   Some now worry that South Africa, ruled by the unrivaled African
National Congress, could go the same way as Namibia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The postcolonial state is the legacy of the subjugation of
Africa by other continents,'' said Makau Mutua, a law professor at
the State University of New York at Buffalo. ``Liberation
movements, riding the emotion of independence, delegitimize
opposition to their rule. It is an open question whether these
states can cohere into viable entities, and whether democracy is
the device that will do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mozambique may provide the answer. It fell quickly into war
after independence in 1975. The Soviets backed the Marxist
government. The United States and South Africa, each serving its
own ends, built up a rebel movement. By the time the war ended in
1992, the country was devastated, ranking as the poorest nation on
Earth, according to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Now Mozambique is an African success story. The economy, though
still modest, has doubled in size since 1992, growing at 7.4
percent each of the last three years. Privatization is well
underway and the budget deficit has been cut to 7 percent of gross
domestic product since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The end of apartheid in South Africa has had a huge impact. Once
bent on destroying Mozambique, Pretoria is now an important
development partner. The road linking Maputo harbor to South
Africa's industrial heartland around Johannesburg is under
reconstruction. So is Maputo, Mozambique's capital and major port.
And South Africa is also one of the main partners in the
construction of a new $1.34 billion aluminum smelter outside
Maputo.
</P>
<P>
   But foreign aid would not be pouring into Mozambique at the rate
of $1 billion annually, nor would foreign investment have risen 70
percent since 1993, without political stability. With neither side
able to win control of the country on the battlefield, Mozambique's
warring parties agreed in 1992 to coexist. In the first democratic
elections in 1994, the former rebel movement, Renamo, won 112 out
of 250 seats in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is a bigger test than 1994,'' said Obede Baloi,
a sociologist at Eduardo Mondlane University in Maputo. ``If the
vote goes well, we're back to normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the accommodation has held. Both sides campaigned freely
and openly ahead of the weekend election and vowed to honor the
result. The government allowed a third day of voting Sunday to
ensure the elections reached remote rural villages. Power may
split: President Joaquim Chissano is expected to retain his job,
but Renamo may gain a slight majority in the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   On a continent long abused by strongmen and their parties, that
might be the best possible outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to Mozambique is wise leadership,'' said James Coates,
head of the World Bank in Maputo. ``The depth and severity of the
war has showed people the alternative to democracy. The
negotiations for peace were for real, and the party in power opened
itself to the idea of competition from other parties. Trust has
been developed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
