<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0672 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TRADE-PRESSURES-BOS &LR;      12-06 1671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-PRESSURES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD DISCONTENT REACHES HIGH HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week's Battle in Seattle may have surprised the World Trade
Organization and the high priests of US foreign policy, but the
demonstrations and violence that turned the Emerald City into an
armed camp reflect frustrations years in the making.
</P>
<P>
   For the last half decade, the discontent with America's trade
policy has been masked by a strong economy and a basic consensus
among major presidential aspirants about the overall value of free
and untrammeled trade.
</P>
<P>
   But as unions, progressives, and environmentalists have
witnessed an erosion of their prerogatives, power, and protection,
they have become convinced that the current trading regime hasn't
lived up to its promise.
</P>
<P>
   Although politically polyglot, the group is unified by its
opposition to value-neutral free trade, open markets, and an
unrestricted flow of capital. The key phrase, of course, is
value-neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Told that trade would lift most boats, those groups think what
globalization has actually wrought is an invidious race to the
bottom, pitting US workers and their sensibilities against
countries that repress labor and despoil the environment.
</P>
<P>
   That has happened against the backdrop of speculator-driven
currency crises that have thrown nations into panic, International
Monetary Fund strictures that have favored the preservation of
investment climates over stimulating employment, and a growing
backlash against the loss of cultural identity that has accompanied
globalization in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movement has been building for the last 10 years,'' said
Robert Scott, an economist who works on trade issues for the
Economic Policy Institute, a progressive think tank based in
Washington, D.C. ``Now it has really reached the boiling point.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the anger bubbling over on the Seattle streets is
that those groups have had little effect on policy by working
inside the system.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bush and Clinton administrations, the mainstream policy
mantra in Washington has been simple: Unfettered trade will
naturally maximize wealth by focusing each country's economy on
what it does best. And if jobs are lost to foreign competitors, the
market will reallocate that displaced labor to a more productive
function. Or so goes free-trade theory, as developed by classical
economists Adam Smith and David Ricardo.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly today's free-traders see the current economy as proof
that the theory is right. ``Here we are with the best economy we
have ever had, with unemployment at historically low levels, with
the Fed expected to raise interest rates because the economy is so
tight,'' said Clyde Prestowitz, chief trade negotiator for Asia
under President Reagan and now president of the Economic Strategy
Institute, a Washington policy research group. ``There is just no
evidence that trading with these countries is having any (negative)
effect on us.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's hardly the way the skeptics see it. They started to
grow dubious in the 1970s, when a dramatic increase in trade
coincided with a stagnating economy and the start of a long decline
in income.
</P>
<P>
   In anything less than a full-employment economy, labor displaced
by trade wouldn't necessarily be put to a more productive use,
those skeptics said. Rather, experience taught that the more
probable effect was for unemployed workers to swell the labor pool,
increase supply, and thus drive down wages.
</P>
<P>
   What's notable about last week's huge protests, however, is that
they came at a time when record prosperity has driven joblessness
down to a level below what economists had theretofore regarded as
full employment.
</P>
<P>
   So why the discontent in a time of seeming economic plenty?
</P>
<P>
   One reason is the different effects trade has on various sectors
of the economy. It's a bit of a generalization, yet basically
accurate, to say that the United States exports sophisticated,
high-value-added products while importing lower-end goods.
</P>
<P>
   Thus well-educated workers do well under a policy that maximizes
free trade. ``Highly skilled professionals seem to be largely
immune from trade and probably benefit because we have lower prices
for goods that we buy,'' says Barry Bluestone, a professor of
political economy at Northeastern University.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for lesser-skilled workers, and particularly those in the
manufacturing sector, who have long borne the brunt of competition
with low-wage foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expanding trade almost by definition means stiffer competition
at the lower end, and some of what working people are reacting to
is definitely connected to that,'' says James K. Galbraith, an
economist at the Lyndon B. Johnson School of Public Affairs at the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In sectors where international competition is fierce, the
questions those workers are asking are good ones _ and the answers
they are getting are not.
</P>
<P>
   Take labor conditions. The cost of labor is key to the price of
a product. Is it fair that workers in the United States, where the
minimum wage sets a floor, are forced to compete with foreign
workers who earn only a fraction of US wages?
</P>
<P>
   A pure free-trader would say yes, since low wages are the
comparative advantage a developing country commands.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the low-wage country has suppressed unions, thereby
keeping wages artificially low, as, for example, is the case in
China? Or what if US factories are competing with goods produced by
child labor? Should that repression or exploitation of labor also
be considered part of a country's natural comparative advantage?
</P>
<P>
   Although the World Trade Organization is attuned to business
concerns such as subsidized exports or copyright violations, it
hasn't addressed workers' concerns with similar alacrity, said Thea
Lee, assistant director of public policy for the AFL-CIO, in an
interview from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, its response has been that those labor concerns are not
appropriate issues for its sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very resistant, and that is why we are out on the
streets,'' said Lee. ``We want the World Trade Organization to
address these issues with the same vigor and effectiveness with
which it currently addresses issues of concern to business.''
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns have driven the AFL-CIO to advocate the inclusion
of five basic labor standards _ freedom of association, the right
to organize and bargain collectively, and prohibitions on child
labor, forced labor, and discrimination in employment _ into the
WTO and world trading rules.
</P>
<P>
   That's perhaps the best crystallization of the tenets of the
growing fair-trade movement: Proper international trade policy
would lift working conditions in developing countries rather than
see competition erode US wages and working standards.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentally, the issues are different, but the underlying
concerns are the same: an erosion of US protections as a result of
competition with lower-standard countries.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental community cites a string of WTO decisions that
have essentially degraded US environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most recent is the October 1998 ruling that, though
recognizing the legitimacy of the statute's goal, nevertheless
undercut a US law banning the importation of shrimp from countries
that don't include ``turtle excluder'' devices on all shrimp nets.
The WTO said the law violated world trade rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice that they acknowledged that this kind of law was
legitimate, but we still lost a case we should have won,'' said
David Shorr, director of the World Wildlife Fund's sustainable
commerce program. ``The case reflects a consistent bias of WTO
rules against environmental priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem for free-trade skeptics is the lack of a plausible
candidate to carry their message nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Of this year's presidential hopefuls, only Pat Buchanan, former
Republican, current Reform Party member, has broken with the
free-trade establishment _ and his views on other issues are
sufficiently outside the mainstream that he is hardly credible.
Party founder Ross Perot, meanwhile, probably hurt the cause of
fair trade with his blunderbuss predictions of disaster if the
North American Free Trade Agreement passed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the skeptics fare much better in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton won on NAFTA in 1993 and on the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade in 1994, he has since suffered a
string of defeats and frustrations as he has sought fast-track
negotiating authority and tried to expand NAFTA-like free trade to
Africa and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   US Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat, says
growing numbers of lawmakers think the old model must be changed to
include standards to protect workers and the environment. He
compares the effort to Franklin D. Roosevelt's determination to
take the rough edges off capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really the New Deal versus trickle-down, taken
internationally,'' Frank says. ``They are saying, `Just let capital
go where it can get the best return,' and we are saying, `No, that
is not enough, you have to look at the adverse economic effects.'
''
</P>
<P>
   In an immediate sense, the protesters have scored an important
victory in Seattle. Their efforts made front-page news of arcane
issues often all but ignored by the mainstream press.
</P>
<P>
   And President Clinton's speech on Wednesday championed their
cause, urging the WTO to address labor and environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Frank thinks the issue could grow to be as important, powerful,
and divisive as the Vietnam War or civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   And though free-traders reflexively label any other system
protectionist, as if that term itself should deter debate, smart,
thoughtful people are reconsidering old verities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a wake-up call about the need to reexamine the
values underlying our international economic policy,'' says
Galbraith.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Scot Lehigh is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
