<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0674 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-BOND-BOS &LR;      12-06 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSION ACCOMPLISHED FOR 007 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's talk legs, the movie kind.
</P>
<P>
   James Bond has the best in the business. He is the Cyd Charisse
of the box office. No other franchise in film history approaches
the Bond oeuvre, which spans early Kennedy to late Clinton.
Thirty-seven years after Ursula Andress walked out of the ocean in
``Dr. No'' like a new species of amphibian, Bond still gets the job
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing else that comes remotely close,'' notes Peter
Graves, former president of marketing for Polygram Films.
</P>
<P>
   Take the latest offering, ``The World Is Not Enough,'' with
Pierce Brosnan as 007. It opened two weekends ago with a $35
million gross to grab the top spot at the domestic box office.
</P>
<P>
   Its theatrical take alone _ it is being released in 51 countries
_ should approach $400 million worldwide. In South Africa, for
example, it opened larger than did ``Titanic'' or ``The Phantom
Menace.'' With video and television, it will earn more than $1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, too, the annual juggernaut of Bond films aired since
1991 on cable by TBS Superstation. The ``15 Days of 007'' is up
once again, with former Monty Python stalwart John Cleese flacking.
It boosted the station's normal prime-time audience by 30 percent
on opening night.
</P>
<P>
   There is also an on-line orgy on the TBS Web page called
CyberBond that runs trivia games as the movies are being shown. The
turnout has been scary. Two years ago, there were 977,000 hits
during the programming on the page. Last year, the number
mushroomed to 2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   What is going on here?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the Bond franchise has immunized its movies from
the judgments of film critics. Bond films are routinely lambasted
by serious reviewers, yet audiences that make gimlet-eyed calls
about other movies suspend such critical thinking at the theater
door when they watch a Bond flick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four percent of our audiences reads the reviews,'' confirms
Michael Wilson, stepson of the creator of the Bond franchise,
Albert ``Cubby'' Broccoli, who died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Then too, the Bond formula is treated like the Holy Grail by its
owners. ``It is a promise kept,'' says Ira Teller, who has run his
own motion picture advertising business in Los Angeles for 22
years, ``You can ask, `Why not a better script or why not a better
villain?' But it doesn't matter. Why mess around with that
formula?''
</P>
<P>
   Why indeed? The worldwide theatrical grosses for the first 18
movies topped $2.8 billion, excluding video and television.
Somewhere around 2 billion people have seen Bond in one of those
three mediums.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, there have been 19 movies in the Bond canon. Not
included for legal reasons are a weird 1967 spoof of ``Casino
Royale'' with David Niven as Bond and a 1983 remake of
``Thunderball'' called ``Never Say Never Again'' with an aging
Connery at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there's a spiral notebook explaining how to make a
Bond film that has been passed down,'' says Graves. ``I started
thinking of them as Kabuki plays a long time ago. There is a
perfect balance of X amount of this and that. There is a reassuring
cadence to the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond movies are confected from dollops of action, cleavage, and
gadgets. In the end, they are staid affairs. There has never been,
and presumably never will be, an R-rated Bond flick. There has
never been nudity, swearing, or believable violence on the watch of
Broccoli or his daughter, Barbara, and stepson who have succeeded
him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there is safe, predictable family entertainment that in
a weird way resembles Disney fare. And PG-13 is Hollywood's yellow
brick road. Broccoli and his former partner, the late Harry
Saltzman, figured that out early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not `Pokemon' or `Toy Story' entertainment. We're not
going that low. But we don't want to make it embarrassing for a
mother and father with their children,'' says Wilson, from London,
where EON Productions, the Broccoli film arm, is based.
</P>
<P>
   Bond's core audience, men over 35, includes those who have been
watching him since they began to express their interest in the
opposite sex at drive-ins during the Cuban missile crisis. For
them, a Bond movie _ any Bond movie _ is as comfy as an old flannel
shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movies connect you back with your younger days. It's that
simple,'' says Rusty Aertsen, who is pushing 50 and saw the latest
movie last weekend with his two college-age children. ``I've seen
every single one of them when they opened in theaters. You can
watch them over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the reasons for such affection are the spectacular stunts
pioneered by the Bond franchise that are the norm in action films
today. Nothing, says Wilson, will ever match the sequence in ``The
Spy Who Loved Me'' where Roger Moore skis off a cliff in the
Austrian Alps and, after falling ghostlike through the ether, opens
a parachute that becomes a giant Union Jack. This is the echt Bond
blend of sangfroid and bravado.
</P>
<P>
   Such footage matters hugely to the Broccoli team. At the
beginning of ``Moonraker,'' Moore jumps from a plane without a
parachute and eventually wrestles one from another soul who is also
descending. That stunt, according to Wilson, took six weeks and 88
jumps to wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Bond people also trumpet the numerous live action shots that
still dominate the series. Larry Gleason, president of worldwide
theatrical distribution for MGM, the studio that distributes the
films, estimates that 90 percent of the action footage in the
latest Pierce Brosnan vehicle was shot live _ the reverse, he
claims, of the industry norm these days where roughly the same
percentage is hatched with computer graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Hard as it is to contemplate now, there was a time when Bond had
no gadgets. Sean Connery was on his own against Dr. No in 1962. It
was not until the third offering, ``Goldfinger,'' that audiences
were introduced to an Aston Martin with an ejector seat.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, we've been introduced to a dizzying array of things
that go bang. The Bond movies pioneered the techno-action we take
for granted on the screen today. But the growth in gadgetry has
come at the expense of good scripts and acting. With rare
exceptions, the Bond villains sleepwalk through their parts,
perhaps to satisfy divorce decrees or pay for new houses in the
Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   The gadgetry has reached a fever pitch in the last three Bond
films because of the critical need to attract younger audiences. To
that end, a huge promotional connection with MTV has been mounted
to draw more younger viewers into theaters. The video game from
``Goldeneye'' has been a big hit, and much is expected from the
video offering for ``Tomorrow Never Dies'' that has just been
released.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this was done specifically to appeal to younger
audiences,'' explains Gleason, who says the campaign is working.
Sixty-five percent of the audience before ``Goldeneye,'' Brosnan's
first, was over 25, he says, whereas 60 percent in the latest thus
far is under 25.
</P>
<P>
   Many younger viewers have no clue who Sean Connery is. But he
remains the definitive Bond. Ian Fleming initially wanted Cary
Grant, who never gave it serious consideration. Good call. ``You
can't have Cary Grant shooting people in the back,'' says Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   George Lazenby was, by all accounts, a disaster in one of the
best written Bonds of all, ``On Her Majesty's Secret Service.''
(The formidable Diana Rigg so despised him, according to one James
Bond Web site, that she chewed garlic before the love scenes.)
</P>
<P>
   Then came Roger Moore, a likable fellow who lacked the necessary
testicular fortitude to be convincing in the role and by the end of
his run resembled a mannequin in Madame Tussaud's. Timothy Dalton
was considered too dark to succeed as Bond. In the latest
incarnation, we arrive at Pierce Brosnan, accepted by all as a nice
blend of Connery and Moore.
</P>
<P>
   The ubiquity of Bond tells us more about ourselves than we may
want to know. The Bond franchise is one of the great cash cows in
the history of entertainment because it assumes we really don't
want a lot of heavy lifting when the lights go down. Fellini?
Forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   If Bond was modern in 1962, he is kitsch in 1999. No matter.
Pilloried for sexism, superficiality, predictability, the man
transcends it all. He is, after all, the mind candy of the global
village.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
