<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART BOOKS: IRELAND TO PICASSO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sure, Georgia O'Keeffe's flowers were erotic. But do they really
require a plain brown wrapper? That's what they get with the
cardboard case around the new two-volume catalog raisonne of
O'Keeffe's work by Barbara Buhler Lynes (Yale, $195). It's the
culmination of a recent spate of O'Keeffe books, and also an
indication of another art-world trend: The catalog as carry-on
luggage. ``Georgia O'Keeffe'' weighs in at 20 pounds, and that
cardboard box comes with a suitcase handle.
</P>
<P>
   Books on African art, once rare, are more plentiful this year.
The most spectacular 1999 example is another two-volume
extravaganza, ``African Ceremonies'' (Abrams, $150), part of an
ongoing collaboration by photographers Carol Beckwith and Angela
Fisher. They've produced an opulent record of contemporary ritual
across the continent. ``To Conserve a Legacy: American Art from
Historically Black Colleges and Universities'' (MIT Press, $60) by
Richard Powell and Jock Reynolds documents a project involving the
conservation and exhibition of a rich array of art owned by the
nation's black schools. It's a fascinating read. African masks, so
influential in 20th-century art, are put into context in ``Masks:
Faces of Culture'' (Abrams, $60) by John Nunley and Cara McCarty,
who examine masks from ancient funerary examples to Darth Vader's.
Egypt _ an African nation, although that fact jolts some people _
is the country of origin for antiquities avidly collected by other
nations. There are masterworks that stayed at home, though, as
attested by ``Egyptian Treasures from the Egyptian Museum in
Cairo'' (Abrams, $75), edited by Francesco Tiradritti. Araldo De
Luca's lavish photography gives a better view of the objects than
you get in the actual museum, where they're stifled by their
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Of this year's Asian art books, ``The Golden Age of Chinese
Archeology: Celebrated Discoveries from the People's Republic of
China'' (Yale, $75), edited by Xiaoneng Yang, offers breathtaking
images of jade and bronzes, and captivating photographs of the
objects being dug up.
</P>
<P>
   Reputations are being resuscitated with fat books this season.
In ``Victorian Painting'' (Phaidon, $59.95), former Victoria &AMP;
Albert Museum curator Lionel Lambourne makes a case for the smarmy,
the sentimental, and for John Singer Sargent, one of Boston's
best-loved artists. The irradiated, star-gazing nude maidens and
Hallmark-worthy landscapes of one of America's most popular
painters are reconsidered in ``Maxfield Parrish: 1870-1966''
(Abrams, $39.95). And in ``Norman Rockwell: Pictures for the
American People'' (Abrams, $35), Maureen Hennessey and Anne Knutson
reexamine the homey world of the much-loved Stockbridge resident,
focusing in part on the evolution of his Christmas imagery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Land of the Winged Horsemen: Art in Poland 1572-1764'' (Yale,
$65) by Jan Ostrowski and ``Poland's Gourmet Cuisine'' (Hippocrene,
$35) by Bernard Lussiana and Mary Pininska will go a long way
toward correcting the stereotypes about that Eastern European
country. The former chronicles the lifestyle of Poland's monarchs,
merchants, military, and churchmen during the Baroque era, through
a look at exquisitely fabricated artifacts from swords to silk
sashes. The Polish food book offers a total aesthetic experience.
Moody, misty photographs of the Polish countryside and fragments of
Polish poetry are interspersed with instructions for saucing wild
boar. The recipes _ all translated into American measurements _ are
by Lussiana, executive chef at Warsaw's Hotel Bristol, the
country's most elegant hostelry. For any benighted soul who still
thinks kielbasa is the beginning and end of Polish cuisine, the
book will be a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   After Christianity came to Ireland in the fifth century,
ecclesiastical art flourished in that country: The Book of Kells
and the Ardagh Chalice are among the most celebrated examples of
the treasures produced there during the Middle Ages, their hallmark
that eccentric, obsessive interlace that crawls over every
available surface. Peter Harbison examines the phenomenon in ``The
Golden Age of Irish Art: The Medieval Achievement, 600-1200''
(Thames &AMP; Hudson, $95).
</P>
<P>
   Words, not pictures, dominate ``Late Antiquity: A Guide to the
Postclassical World'' (Harvard, $49.95) by G. W. Bowersock, Peter
Brown, and Oleg Grabar. A scholarly book, it will also fascinate
the lay reader. Dipping into 11 essays and more than 500 individual
entries, you discover, say, the significance of angels in Islamic
as well as Judeo-Christian and classical culture, or that
physicians in antiquity believed that homosexual lovemaking between
men was more tiring than ``straight'' sex. Just the sort of thing
to elevate your holiday party conversation from the Pokemon level.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalind Krauss is one of our foremost feminist critics. Clement
Greenberg was an influential champion of macho art. Books of the
writings of both are out this year. In ``Bachelors'' (MIT, $29.95),
Krauss looks at nine women artists, Cindy Sherman and Agnes Martin
among them, and argues that ``art made by women needs no special
pleading.'' ``Homemade Esthetics: Observations on Art and Taste''
(Oxford, $27.95) includes the transcripts of Greenberg's 1971
seminars at Bennington College, where he articulated his rigid
views on taste and quality.
</P>
<P>
   Most welcome 1999 book on a brand-name artist: ``Picasso:
Painter and Sculptor in Clay'' (Abrams, $60), edited by Marilyn
McCully. In addition to being one of the century's groundbreaking
painters, Picasso was one of its great ceramists. This gorgeously
illustrated book shows how he sometimes adapted his imagery to
conventional shapes like the round plate, and how at other times he
let figure and form erupt out of the clay together.
</P>
<P>
   Most welcome 1999 book on a single artwork: Luciano Bellosi's
``Duccio: The Maesta'' (Thames &AMP; Hudson, $120). The ``Virgin in
Majesty'' cycle that Duccio painted early in the 14th century for
the Siena cathedral is the pinnacle of Sienese painting. It is also
arguably the finest surviving Italian altarpiece. Bellosi's book
lovingly documents the complex masterpiece in its entirety, front
and back. Its most dazzling aspect is a wealth of detail shots
reproduced to scale, each shown with the ultimate artbook luxury _
a blank facing page, so there's nothing to distract you.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig Bemelmans is famous for his ``Madeline'' books about the
little girl who lived in the ``old house in Paris that was covered
in vines.'' But he was also a novelist, muralist, bon vivant, and
painter of juicy, joyful, Dufy-like urban and bucolic scenes. In
``Bemelmans: The Life &AMP; Art of Madeline's Creator'' (Viking, $40),
his grandson, John Bemelmans Marciano, offers a suitably charming
account of the grandfather he never met.
</P>
<P>
   Some 4,600 years ago, a lot of people arranged a lot of big
rocks in a big circle in Wiltshire, England. On that everyone
agrees. The accumulated lore about Stonehenge since then involves
human sacrifice, Druid ceremonies, and the widely accepted notion
that the stones were dragged all the way from Wales. Nonsense,
writes stone circle authority Aubrey Burl in ``Great Stone Circles:
Fables, Fictions, Facts'' (Yale, $30). It was glaciers that
deposited the stones on the Wiltshire Plain, he contends, not
thousands of people in an effort worthy of a Cecil B. De Mille
epic. He also argues, on stylistic grounds, that this most British
of monuments was not even made by Britons, but by foreigners. In
this sacred season, Burl demonstrates that nothing is sacred.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
