<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-FICTION-BOS &LR;      12-06 1680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FICTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASON'S GREETINGS: THE BEST FICTION OF 1999 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the good old days, when fin de siecle actually meant
something, people used it to refer to a particularly world-weary
school of late-19th-century artistic expression. I'm not surprised
it's been resurrected for this end-of-century, given our propensity
for recycling and the generally effete state of the arts. Not with
a bang but a whimper, indeed. This was the year publishing
rediscovered Hemingway by churning out his so-called fictional
memoir, ``True at First Light,'' which should have never seen
morning and did nothing but insult a master. Ralph Ellison's
finally released (but never finished) second novel, ``Juneteenth,''
didn't exalt his memory either, except by way of what might have
been.
</P>
<P>
   Now rumors abound of the imminent appearance of Fitzgerald's
``Trimalchio,'' the novel he wrote before Maxwell Perkins
(publishing's legendary Mr. Fix-It) helped him turn it into ``The
Great Gatsby.'' Some three-score of Chekhov's previously
uncollected stories were rounded up (never mind that they were
uncollected for a reason); likewise the complete short fiction of
Evelyn Waugh (who would have scowled inimitably at such a desperate
venture). Even the pop maestros at the other end of the spectrum
seemed fonder of the past: Michael Crichton had his Yalies go
medieval in ``Timeline,'' and Thomas Harris tried to out-gross his
own previous ``Silence of the Lambs'' with the return appearance of
his flesh-eating psychiatrist in ``Hannibal.'' No nostalgia for
Kurt Andersen, though: His high-octane ``Turn of the Century'' was
the top Zeitgeist contribution to the millennial craze, replete as
it was with day trading, cyber-conspiracies, and the hegemony of
Starbucks. With all that edge and caffeine paranoia, who says we
aren't ready for the future?
</P>
<P>
   But the best writers don't care what year it is, of course, and
so there are always exceptions to such grumblings. This year, some
of the finest consistent work was done in the short story. Nathan
Englander's first collection, ``For the Relief of Unbearable
Urges,'' announced a young heir to I. B. Singer and Cynthia Ozick _
his stories range from Russia to Jerusalem to New York's Orthodox
Jewish community, and all of them are taut, evocative, and
perfectly contained. David Gates, whose drier-than-dry-ice novels,
``Jernigan'' and ``Preston Falls,'' have left some cult readers
reeling for more, gave us more of that drop-dead narrative voice in
``Wonders of the Invisible World.'' Local heroes Gish Jen and
Christopher Tilghman both made wonderful additions to the form
with, respectively, ``Who's Irish?'' and ``The Way People Run.''
Thom Jones gave us more down-and-dirty revelations about Nietszche
and hard living in ``Sonny Liston Was a Friend of Mine.'' Bliss
Broyard waxed poignant in her debut stories, ``My Father,
Dancing''; there were also contributions from Alice Adams (``The
Last Lovely City''), A. S. Byatt (``Elementals: Stories of Fire and
Ice''), and Chris Offutt (``Out of the Woods'').
</P>
<P>
   The novel, which every couple of years is said to be ailing, in
fact seems more resilient than ever, if only because of its range
in both subject and technique. Claire Messud wrote a beautifully
haunting exploration of the past's intrusion on the present,
between America and French Algeria, in ``The Last Life.'' Ward Just
captured splendidly the nonchalant cruelties of the bureaucratic
war machine in Vietnam in ``A Dangerous Friend.'' Ha Jin took us
into a world of personal sorrows in communist China in ``Waiting,''
which won the National Book Award last month, while Kent Haruf
delivered the dawn's glow of ordinary life in rural Colorado in
``Plainsong.'' Peter Matthieson finished his Florida-based Watson
trilogy in ``Bone by Bone,'' while Andre Dubus III would have
surely made his father proud with his anti-pastoral ``House of Sand
and Fog.'' And Stewart O'Nan masterfully emulated the quiet horrors
of the classic ``Wisconsin Death Trip'' in his understated Gothic,
``A Prayer for the Dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Salman Rushdie, proving that exile has hurt neither his love for
rock 'n' roll nor his unstoppable prose, combined both in his
globally footloose ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet.'' Wayne Johnston
was similarly abundant in his gravelly epic about Newfoundland,
``The Colony of Unrequited Dreams.'' Oscar Hijuelos stayed
stateside in ``Empress of the Splendid Season,'' where he displayed
his usual humanity in capturing the life of a housekeeper in New
York. Gail Godwin wrote a quiet novel about devotion and staying
put in ``Evensong,'' and David Guterson headed inland from Puget
Sound in ``East of the Mountains.'' Sue Miller gave us a Big Chill
suspense story in ``While I Was Gone''; Leslie Epstein revisited
the foibles of his Leib Goldkorn in ``Ice Fire Water.'' In yet
another nod to yesterday's lure, Sena Jeter Naslund imagined
``Moby-Dick'' from another point of view in ``Ahab's Wife: Or, The
Star-Gazer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mother-daughter novels are by now endemic to contemporary
fiction, and this year's yield was headed by Elizabeth Strout's
wistful psychological portrait in ``Amy and Isabelle.'' Janet
Fitch's ``White Oleander'' had its moments as well, despite a
propensity for catastrophic repetition. Elizabeth Graver was more
delicate and less dramatic in her second novel, ``The Honey
Thief.'' A good crop of comic novels included Michael Frayn's
``Headlong,'' Elinor Lipman's ``The Ladies' Man,'' and Jane
Shapiro's farcical ``The Dangerous Husband.'' The intellectually
haunting Kathryn Davis returned with ``The Walking Tour'';
Katharine Weber wrote about the collision of art and politics in
``The Music Lesson''; and A. M. Homes added another wildly creepy
novel to the suburban genre with ``Music for Torching.'' In the
ongoing effort to produce the Gidget-ized version of ``Bridget
Jones's Diary,'' Melissa Bank enjoyed her 12 minutes upon the stage
with ``The Girls' Guide to Hunting and Fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli A. B.Yehoshua took on history and the diaspora in ``A
Journey to the End of the Millennium''; Japanese Haruki Murakami
explored the world of ill-fated lovers in ``South of the Border,
West of the Sun.'' The South African writer J. M. Coetzee won his
second Booker Prize for ``Disgrace,'' a fierce, laconic novel set
in a post-apartheid world. From Scotland, A. L. Kennedy, whose
strange, forceful prose is beginning to be read here, wrote about a
Glaswegian woman in ``Original Bliss.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brits did their usual hogging of the stage in English
letters; the sun may have set on imperialism, but certainly not on
the motherland's way with words. Pat Barker's shadowy domestic
drama, ``Another World,'' had the spectral presence of the First
World War in its drawing room. Sebastian Faulks, whose earlier
``Birdsong'' captured trench warfare with such acuity, went to the
dark moral center of Occupied France in ``Charlotte Gray.'' John le
Carre managed to make international finance interesting in ``Single
&AMP; Single,'' while Penelope Lively made a retired anthropologist's
rural life less than bucolic in ``Spiderweb.'' Julian Barnes, whose
penchant for satire is decidedly Brit, fancied his birthplace a
theme park in ``England, England.''
</P>
<P>
   So: Despite all the hype and folly and millennium prophecies,
not such a bad showing in the world of fiction after all. But the
best fiction of 1999 took us even further aflight _ to the desolate
beauty of Wyoming, the hellish memories of Burma during World War
II, the infinite pleasures and past of Ireland, and, finally, to
this century's own written evidence of the triumph of the
imagination. The brevity of this list _ two novels, one story
collection, and one anthology _ is not meant to seem chary. It's
simply that these four titles are each so elegant that they deserve
a little room of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Star Called Henry'' by Roddy Doyle. In the first volume of a
projected trilogy spanning the 20th century, Doyle's evocation of
Dublin _ its slums, its heartbroken mothers, its political factions
_ is as ambitious as it is emotionally generous. But its real
achievement is the voice of its cheeky protagonist, Henry Smart,
who delivers the inner geography of this story with the mouth of a
wiseacre and the soul of a poet.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Gesture Life'' by Chang-rae Lee. Lee's elegant, exquisitely
careful novel concerns the story of old Doc Hata, a retired
Japanese-American businessman who is trying to live by his own code
of honor in Bedley Run, N.Y. With the same titrated secrecy and
narrative precision that defined Kazuo Ishiguro's ``Remains of the
Day,'' Lee returns to the dark burial grounds of Hata's past in
order to illuminate the present. The result is a quiet tragedy set
to the tone of a single cello.
</P>
<P>
   ``Close Range: Wyoming Stories'' by Annie Proulx. Cast against
the magical badlands of the American West, Proulx's most recent
short fiction can stand up to anything she has written. Her subject
matter is hard-edged and genuine: a kid on a bull that could break
his back; an old man at the mercy of the land; a couple of cowboys
whose love may break your heart. With its whitewater cadences that
beg to be read aloud, ``Close Range'' has the breathtaking
authenticity of a spring blizzard in the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best American Short Stories of the Century,'' edited by John
Updike; series editor Katrina Kenison. Selected from the original
motherlode of some 2,000 stories published in Houghton Mifflin's
annual series since 1915, this volume is an extraordinary testament
to modern America: its literature, its street corners, its suburban
hopes, and city-lights illusions. From the expected (Sherwood
Anderson, Saul Bellow) to the slightly idiosyncratic (an early
Philip Roth), you can feel the imprint of Updike's critical acumen.
By the time you get to Raymond Carver, Tim O'Brien, and Lorrie
Moore, you know how splendid American fiction really can be.
</P>
<P>
   Happy sojourns, everybody.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0677 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-GIFT-BOS &LR;      12-06 1727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GIFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YEAR'S BEST GIFT BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's gift books range in subject from the universe to
Elvis _ or, if you prefer, the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   The cosmos is represented by a gorgeous object called ``The
Invisible Universe'' by the astronomical scientist and celestial
photographer David Malin (Bullfinch/
</P>
<P>
   Little, Brown, $50). The images are staggeringly beautiful and
mysterious _ phenomena of light as much as 50 million light-years
away, phenomena that can be ``seen'' only in the complex way these
photographs represent, but phenomena that can also be immediately
felt.
</P>
<P>
   Our own world is a traditional subject for gift books, and one
of the most fascinating this year is ``Voyages of Discovery''
(Clarkson Potter, $60). This is Dr. Tony Rice's genial and
enthralling survey of three centuries in the study of natural
history, as reflected in the collections of the Natural History
Museum in London. There are chapters on Sir Hans Sloane's voyage to
Jamaica in the last part of the 17th century, and Captain Cook in
the Pacific, Charles Darwin on the Beagle, and the Challenger
expedition to explore the deep seas in the last part of the 19th
century. One is left with a profound appreciation of natural
wonders, not the least of which is human curiosity and valor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gothic,'' edited by Rolf Toman (Koenemann, $39.95), surveys an
era of human achievement that can still inspire awe. The first
Gothic buildings were erected in France in the middle of the 12th
century, and the style spread throughout Europe. The book
concentrates not just on cathedrals but on sculpture and painting
as well, working through them to understand the world view that
created these prodigious structures and beautiful objects; there
are also chapters on other pertinent subjects, like stained glass,
and the advances of technology that made these wonders possible.
</P>
<P>
   Other historical gift books of interest include a pair on Egypt,
once more a focus of international and especially local interest.
``Gold of the Pharaohs'' by Hans Wolfgang Mueller and Eberhard
Thiem (Cornell University Press, $60) presents photographs of the
staggering caches of gold in the great Egyptian tombs; the text
describes both the symbolism of gold and jewels in this culture and
the practicalities of how gold was mined, refined, and transformed
into art. ``Sacred Luxuries'' by Lise Manniche, with photographs by
Werner Forman (Cornell University Press, $39.95), surveys the
important place of fragrance, aromatherapy, and cosmetics in
ancient Egyptian culture and provides recipes for herbal potions.
Baldness, the makers of Rogaine might want to know, was treated
``with fat of powerful animals such as lion, crocodile,
hippopotamus, ibex, cat, and serpent. If these creatures were not
available, hedgehog bristles provided an appropriate substitute.
The tooth of a donkey ground in honey was also recommended.''
</P>
<P>
   ``North American Indian Jewelry and Adornment'' by Lois Sherr
Dubin (Abrams, $75) surveys its colorful subject from prehistory to
the present; as in Egyptian culture, jewelry was totemic for Native
Americans. The craftsmanship that went into the beautiful objects
in these photographs was an exercise not only in artistry but in
religious discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War: Unstilled Voices'' by Chuck Lawliss (Crown
Publishers, $29.95) is described as a ``three-dimensional
interactive book.'' What it represents is a designer run amok.
Every page _ and there are only 33 of them _ brings something new
to unfold, untie, or unwrap, usually a reproduction of a letter or
document related to the subject of each two-page chapter. ``The
Fanatic,'' John Brown, is represented by the note he handed to a
guard on his way to the gallows; ``The Blacks'' by a recruiting
poster; ``The Generals'' by a field dispatch from Stonewall
Jackson. The reproductions, not always chosen in the best of taste
(there is a pair of tickets for the dress circle in Ford's Theater
for April 14, 1865), eerily make the past feel simultaneously more
present and more distant.
</P>
<P>
   ``National Geographic: Eyewitness to the 20th Century''
(National Geographic Society, $40) is a convenient digest of the
last 100 years, organized by decade, with special focus on topics
the magazine has treated over the years. Essays introduce each
decade, but probably most readers will scan the ``Trends and
Trivia'' column first. This collection of miscellaneous facts is
simultaneously interesting, arbitrary, and sometimes slovenly.
Where else could you learn at a glance that Simon and Garfunkel's
``The 59th Street Bridge Song'' was released the same year as
``Cabaret,'' not to mention the same year that Bill Russell signed
on as Celtics coach for $125,000 and that the chemical structure of
DNA was discovered?
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment is always a prime topic for gift books. One
historic form of entertainment, the art of geisha, has newly
fascinated Westerners thanks to Arthur Golden's recent novel,
``Memoirs of a Geisha'' (the fascination will redouble when the
movie is completed and released). ``The Life of a Geisha'' by
Eleanor Underwood (Smithmark Publishers, $9.98) is a small, elegant
book, only 64 pages, illustrated by woodblock prints, photographs,
old postcards, and posters along with actual geisha songs and poems
in translation _ and a jacket testimonial from Golden.
</P>
<P>
   Trends are another form of entertainment, but ``Dreads'' by
Francesco Mastalia and Alfonse Pagano (Artisan, $35) treats
dreadlocks as a form of cultural expression; the keynote address is
by Alice Walker (``After all, if this major mystery could be
discovered right on top of one's head, I thought, what other
wonders might not be experienced in the Universe's exuberant,
inexhaustible store?''). ``Looking for Jackie: American Fashion
Icons'' by Kathleen Craughwell-Varda (Hearst Books, $50) treats 13
women who changed the way other American women wanted to look _
from Dolley Madison through Katharine Hepburn, with sidelong
glances at figures as diverse as today's Madonna and Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurt Weill Foundation for Music has done an extraordinary
job of preserving and promoting the legacy of Kurt Weill and Lotte
Lenya. Last year there was a gorgeous picture book concentrating on
Lenya; this year, in conjunction with an exhibit sponsored by the
foundation in the library for the performing arts at Lincoln
Center, there comes ``Kurt Weill: A Life in Pictures and
Documents'' (Overlook Press, $75), a book that seeks to
depolemicize and depoliticize a figure who was actively involved in
politics and polemics but whose achievement was not defined or
restricted by them. It is a wonderful survey of a life that spanned
some of the most important events of the first half of our century
_ and that has helped our half of the century understand them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Century of Country: An Illustrated History of Country
Music'' by Robert K. Oermann (TV Books, $39.95) is an entertaining
survey of a strand of musical history that should neither be
worshiped nor condescended to. Oermann tends to write in
hyper-English (``Dixie Chicks cooked up a musical stew that
virtually everyone approved of . . . (Their debut album) stunned
and delighted the industry by selling more than six million
copies,'' which pretty much takes care of the issue of art versus
commerce). But the story is an entertaining and paradigmatic one,
about how the art tries to remain faithful to its roots while
remaining contemporary by reflecting its own times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny Ladies'' by Stephen M. Silverman traces ``100 years of
great comediennes,'' a word that, like ``actress,'' is on the
endangered list even though what the word defines is still merrily
flourishing among us. Silverman begins with Fanny Brice and Mabel
Normand and ends up with Cameron Diaz, and there is many a salty
anecdote and sizzling one-liner in his survey. Try the paragraphs
on Belle Barth, for example, who specialized in ``blue'' humor and
gave Bette Midler one of her best lines. Many of these women were
years ahead of the society that surrounded them, and out of that
conflict they created humor that still stings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Cooper Off Camera'' is an affectionate photographic
memoir of the American screen icon by his daughter Maria Cooper
Janis (Abrams, $35.00), with a quiet and telling introduction about
screen acting by Tom Hanks. Janis has her points, too: ``Acting
isn't so bad as long as you always know the difference, and can
drop the act or mask at will.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other Hollywood books are fun. ``Sin in Soft Focus'' by Mark
A. Vieira (Abrams, $39.95) is a survey of early ``suggestive''
Hollywood films and a photographic record of the cunning through
which artists and charlatans pushed the envelope, found themselves
faced with the draconian demands of the Production Code, and got
around it with limitless guile _ although only today are we able to
see some pictures from the early '30s with sequences the censors
deleted. ``The Noir Style'' by Alain Silver and James Ursini
(Overlook Press, $50) surveys a style that helped define the 1940s
(but whose origins the authors trace back to such diverse sources
as German expressionism, the paintings of Edward Hopper,
hard-boiled fiction, and improved film stocks) and whose
consequences linger today in such movies as ``The Player'' and
``Murder in the First.'' Period production stills still create
uneasy moods that don't have anything to do with period.
</P>
<P>
   And what about Elvis? Well, there's ``Elvis: The Official
Auction Catalogue,'' documenting the materials from the Graceland
archives that were auctioned in October at the MGM Grand Hotel and
Casino in Las Vegas (Abrams, $40). Item A is Elvis's 6th grade
report card _ he didn't always do too well in Reliability and
Industry, or even in Cooperation and Courtesy, although he excelled
in Music, Spelling, and Phys. Ed. (minimum bid, $10,000); the last
item is a Smith's Food King credit card issued to Priscilla Presley
(minimum bid, only $200). The book affords a paper trail through
Elvis's life, which is more enjoyably traced on vinyl and CD, and
it is testimony to the nesting instinct, and to the sentimental
value of clutter _ which the book not only documents but
represents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
