<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOND-ACTOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST IN ROLE WAS NELSON, BARRY NELSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the beginning, there was Barry Nelson, not Sean Connery.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Fleming's first book, ``Casino Royale,'' was adapted into a
one-hour television show that aired in 1954 as part of a series
called ``Climax.''
</P>
<P>
   In this bizarre spectacle, Nelson plays ``card sense Jimmy
Bond,'' an operative known for his skills at baccarat. He is up
against the evil Le Chiffre, played by Peter Lorre. A mere glimpse
of Lorre reminds us how fabulous he would have been as a villain in
a full-blown Bond vehicle on the big screen. Linda Christian plays
a French operative from the Deuxieme Bureau who can't keep her
hands off Jimmy.
</P>
<P>
   Appalling as it is to contemplate, Bond in this first
incarnation is an American who drinks scotch and water, not the
Brit who sips vodka martinis, shaken not stirred. And Felix Leiter,
the stolid CIA agent in all of the Bond movies, is named Clarence
Leiter here and is British. Go figure. This is primitive stuff. The
sets, the acting and the script have the whiff of a high school
play. Never mind. This is still the birth of Bond on the screen.
Curiosity, if not respect, is due.
</P>
<P>
   It would be eight more years before Sean Connery appeared as
Bond to bed Ursula Andress and demolish Dr. No in an impressive
display of testosterone. The rest is history. But, for the record,
it all began with Barry Nelson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
