<HEADER>
A0682 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHENS-BOS &LR;      12-06 1730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH SIDES AVOWING VICTORY IN NO-WIN BATTLE OF CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV AND DMITRY SHALGANOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARGUN, Russia _ The Russians are in the mud, the Chechens are in
the mountains, and both sides are convinced they are winning.
</P>
<P>
   Russians and Chechens are made for each other, locked in a
bloody but chronic conflict where each side can claim victory
regularly without ever defeating the other.
</P>
<P>
   In a muddy field on the outskirts of Argun, the last rebel
stronghold east of Chechnya's capital, Grozny, Russia's commanders
were feeling cocky four days into a fierce battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rebels are offering fierce resistance, but they know the
end is near,'' Russian General Gennady Troshev said Thursday as his
filthy troops brushed mud off a battery of howitzers during a break
in the shelling. Nearby, helicopter gunships prepared to take off
on another deadly raid.
</P>
<P>
   But in the high mountains to the south, across Chechnya's border
with the former Soviet republic of Georgia, Troshev's words brought
a derisive round of laughter to a group of rebels taking a break
from the fighting. The view up here is that the Chechens are
winning their war against the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is going fine,'' said a rebel fighter who gave only
his first name, Musa, and who arrived from the front line in Argun
on Wednesday. ``The Russians can bombard us from afar, but they are
afraid to fight us. Whenever they get close, we wipe them out. They
are losing many men and weapons. They can never take Argun, but
even if they did, it would not matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Who is right: the Russians, with their confidence in the mud, or
the Chechens, with their bravado in the mountains? The answer is
both, and neither.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops and Chechen insurgents are facing off on the
battlefield, but they might as well be fighting in different wars.
This is true not only because of the vastly different tactics and
strategies used by the two sides, but also because of a basic
incompatibilty of their societies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This war is about a clash of histories,'' said Fiona Hill,
deputy director of the Washington-based Eurasia Foundation. ``It is
about one side building up an extensive empire, the other trying to
forge a national entity, and each side being totally unprepared for
dealing with the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia is fighting to control a warrior nation on its southern
border that has resisted Moscow's rule for nearly 300 years.
``Imagine if America's Indian wars had never ended, except that now
the Apaches possessed hand-held missile launchers, Kalashnikov
assault rifles, and state-of-the-art communications,'' a Russian
reporter recently asked an American.
</P>
<P>
   Russians believe failure to control Chechnya produces drastic
consequences, both on a geopolitical level _ the loss of influence
in the oil-rich Caspian Sea basin _ and especially for domestic
security. Russians blame a two-year epidemic of kidnappings, a year
of increasingly bold attacks on neighboring regions, and last
summer's deadly apartment bombings in Moscow on Islamic militants
operating out of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But Russians are also looking to the military to restore
national pride battered by years of setbacks beginning with the
Soviet debacle in Afghanistan and continuing through Moscow's
failed 1994-1996 campaign to tame Chechnya. As the latest Russian
campaign in Chechnya has intensified, its popularity has increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to stop somewhere, as we have been retreating for 15
years,'' Russia's most celebrated living writer, former Soviet
exile Alexander Solzhenitsyn, said recently, capturing the public
mood. ``We have capitulated everywhere. We capitulated in 1996. Our
country cannot abandon the right to defend itself, and defense
means completing the operation in some way.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking the other way &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But there is a sinister side to the unity behind Russia's
hawkish stance toward Chechnya. The indiscriminate shelling and
shootings of civilians; the poor treatment of hundreds of thousands
of refugees; allegations of looting and of abuse of suspected
terrorists goes largely unreported, and uncritized, in Russian
society.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Grozny Saturday described a massacre of as many as
40 civilians by Russian commandos who fired on a column of refugees
at point-blank range. Russian officials denied the reports as
``disinformation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen insurgents, meanwhile, said they are fighting for
their existence as a nation, prolonging a tradition of gallant
resistance against Russia that began when Peter the Great sent his
armies into the Caucasus in 1722 and continued against czars,
Bolsheviks, Stalin, and now post-Soviet Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Always outnumbered and outgunned, the Chechens have tried to sap
the Russians of their resolve by launching ambushes and raids in
the wars of the 19th century and the wars of the 1990s. The idea is
to exact heavy casualties on their adversary, then to retreat to
fight another day. This is what appears to be happening in Argun;
the Russians will take the town, and the majority of the Chechen
defenders will get away.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Chechens' defeats have been resounding, such
as the failed rebellion that led Stalin in 1944 to deport the
entire Chechen nation and their ethnic cousins the Ingush. But such
setbacks have produced a series of heroic role models, and a sense
of national resolve in the face of an enemy, that have made the
Chechens what British analyst Anatol Lieven describes as ``one of
the great martial peoples of modern history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past 280 years, the Chechens have been surpressed and
forced to submit to the Russians,'' said Lieven, author of a book
on the 1994-1996 Chechnya war. ``But whenever Moscow is weak, or
too oppressive, they revolt and fight again.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stereotypes prevail &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The conflict is fueled by each side's romantic view of itself,
and basic misperceptions about the other side.
</P>
<P>
   For Russians, the Chechens are a bandit nation, forever
entrenched in a clan-like society that rejects modern traditions of
hierarchical organization and laws. A 19th-century czarist general
branded them ``a people who cannot be assimilated,'' and poet
Mikhail Lermontov described the ``evil Chechen, crawling along the
bank, sharpening his knife.'' Those stereotypes remain the defining
characteristics of Chechens held by Russians.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian image of the Chechens is encapsuled in the violent
footage shown on nationwide news, depicting Chechen captors
torturing and murdering their hostages, and enjoying it. One
popular program repeatedly played a video of Chechens shooting the
fingers off the hand of a small boy, laughing as he pleaded for
mercy.
</P>
<P>
   The message: Chechen civilians may be suffering under the
Russian military assault, but by their complicity in the chronic
lawlessness and violence that took root in Chechnya during the past
three years of de-facto independence, they deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lest you should worry too much about those refugees, I'll show
this videotape again,'' said the show's anchor, Sergei Dorenko.
</P>
<P>
   Chechens, too, have a favorite videotape: ``Braveheart,'' the
1995 film that cast Mel Gibson as William Wallace, the highland
rebel who united diverse Scottish clans to hold off, for a while,
the British oppressor.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace eventually lost. The Chechens are convinced they can
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought no Russian could ever beat a Chechen in
anything,'' said Apti, a Chechen rebel resting in Georgia last
week.``They have the numbers, but they are weak. They are afraid to
fight, but we enjoy it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Courageous and complacent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain informality to the Chechen resistance that
the Russians do not seem to understand. Troshev, the Russian
general in Argun, said Chechen rebels are demoralized and continue
to fight only because they are afraid of rebel leader Shamil
Basayev. But Chechens seem to drift in and out of the combat zone
at their own whim. One Chechen named Bilal spent last week in the
trenches at Argun; next week, he plans to travel to Europe to work
on his career as a rap musician.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chechens are great individualists,'' Bilal said. ``This is why
we always beat the Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   Yo'av Karny, a Washington-based journalist who has written
extensively on Chechnya, said this confidence points to what he
calls ``a profound flaw in Chechen society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Chechens think that fighting, killing, for that matter
being killed, is fun,'' he said. ``They have profound courage. But
as peacetime politicians, they have failed. Where does law-breaking
end, and where does national salvation begin?''
</P>
<P>
   Russian politicians say they are trying to fill this void. They
have visited recaptured regions and promised to rebuild damaged
schools, hospitals and homes; but no one reasonably believes Moscow
will see through an economic revival here that it has been unable
to fashion anywhere else outside Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Another force, Islamic fundamentalism, is competing for
influence in Chechen society. The rebels themselves argue over
whether they need radical Islam, and whether it is responsible for
the events that led to the latest war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Islamic fighters are coming from Afghanistan and Arab
countries and I don't want this to happen,'' Apti said. ``I like my
Chechen religion and traditions the way they are. But if the war
continues, we will not be able to stop the Islamic fighters.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No win situations &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And the Russian military assault shows no signs of abating. ``We
must not stop,'' said Yevgeny Ganyukov, a Russian major stationed
outside Argun. ``Once we've started to pound them, we have to pound
them to the end, so that not one living soul remains.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chechens will never win that way.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the hatred of the federal forces grows with every
civilian casualty.
</P>
<P>
   Russia will never win that way.
</P>
<P>
   The reason was found high in the mountains to the south, in a
small border hamlet filled with women and children who have fled
the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   There, a Chechen named Musa, all of 4 years old, was asked where
his father was.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's at home, fighting the Russians,'' the child said. ``And
one day, I'll grow up and fight them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Filipov reported from the Chechen-Georgian border, Shalganov
reported from Argun.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
