<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING FOR AN INFANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am going to have a baby in March and my parents have
offered to give us $5,000 to invest toward the child's education.
How would you invest this money to get the best returns over the
next 18 years? My father says bonds are the best choice; my husband
and I say stocks. We currently have money invested in Twentieth
Century Ultra, Templeton Foreign I, Putnam OTC. and Putnam Emerging
Growth funds, as well as Cisco Systems common stock, all of which
have been doing extremely well in this market. Are there better
funds for this type of investing? Also, do you recommend putting
the investment in the child's name?
</P>
<P>
   J.B., Brookline, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Before I get into what I would do, I would suggest you think
about an old adage I have always followed, which is that the gift
must please the giver.
</P>
<P>
   If your parents have provided the money and strongly suggest
that it go into bonds or a bond fund, that's really what you should
do. And if your parents propose to give the money to the yet-unborn
child, it's not really up to you to decide whose name the money
should be in.
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, I certainly agree that stock investments would
be better than bonds. I don't think I'd go with investments as
aggressive as your current holdings, but I think one of the many
Standard &AMP; Poor's Index 500 funds would be a good holding for the
first 13 years, followed by five years in a balanced fund, and
then, upon the child's entry into college, a money market fund. You
might do this with Vanguard by using Vanguard Index 500, followed
by Vanguard Balanced Index, followed by its Prime Money Market
fund.
</P>
<P>
   If you followed that plan and if the Index 500 fund produced
average 10 percent returns for 13 years, followed by 8 percent
returns from the Balanced Index fund for the next five years, the
accumulation would be $25,362 after 18 years. If you simply went
into a bond fund for the 18-year duration and produced total
returns of 6.5 percent, you would have $15,533.
</P>
<P>
   As for the question of whose name is best for the investment,
the general byword is that unless you anticipate that you will be
rich _ really, really rich _ by the time the student enters
college, the funds are best put in the parents' name, where they
will be taxed much less heavily by the authorities who determine
financial aid eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current rules, these authorities deem that up to 5.65
percent of the parents' assets should be available for college
expenses, but that up to 50 percent of the student's assets should
be available to meet each year's college expenses.
</P>
<P>
   But to end up where I started, I think the wishes of the giver
of this gift should be a prime consideration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 35 and make $35,000 a year. I have a wife and two kids
at home. My wife doesn't work; the money she would earn would all
be spent on day care, so it doesn't make economic sense. My
employer doesn't have a 401(k) plan, but I've put $2,000 a year
into an IRA account, which is currently worth more than $10,000. We
have no assets and no other investments. Our checking account has
about $1,000 in it, depending on the time of the month and whether
we've just paid our rent. We have no significant debts, carefully
paying off our credit cards each month. I try to set aside more
money, but car repairs, school supplies, and the occasional dental
visit seem to empty the account every month. I have read your
column for some time now. You give advice to people with a half
million dollars in various accounts and who earn between $80,000
and $200,000 a year. They all want to retire at around age 50 or
55. My income is about the median for people my age and gender;
half the people in the country earn less than me. I also would like
to retire someday. I would also like to be able to send my kids to
college. What financial advice do you have for me? Will my kids go
to college? Will I ever be able to retire?
</P>
<P>
   M.J., Seattle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It sure does look a long way away, doesn't it? What you need
to do is set yourself small goals, and then keep plugging away at
them.
</P>
<P>
   The $2,000 a year that you're putting into your IRA represents
5.7 percent of your earnings. If you keep contributing the maximum
to the IRA until you're 65 years old, you would accumulate a total
of $518,558.
</P>
<P>
   That presumes average investment returns of 10 percent, which
would be a reasonable expectation if you have the money in a stock
mutual fund; if you have it with a bank, you might expect long-term
returns in the area of 6 percent, which would take you to $219,896.
</P>
<P>
   Begin with a modest increase _ basically a token. To take your
savings rate to 6 percent would require saving only an additional
$100 a year. Just that additional $100 a year would take the
accumulation to $535,775 after 30 years, using the stock investment
assumption.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever you get a raise, give your retirement savings a raise
as well. Suppose you got a 3 percent raise, taking your earnings to
$36,050. If you're serious about retirement you could not only
increase your dollar savings to reflect the raise, but also
increase the savings level.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose with the raise you boosted your savings level to 6.5
percent of your earnings. This would mean total retirement savings
of $2,343.25 for that year. Then, when you get another raise, do it
again. If you keep at such a schedule, the increases should not
hurt too much, and over time they would build handsome rewards.
</P>
<P>
   As for an investment vehicle for the extra savings, the tax laws
now allow your wife to put as much as $2,000 into an IRA each year,
even if she doesnt work.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the extra savings into an IRA account for her would at
least give her a small sense of a tangible reward for the work she
does, which is every bit as much work as if she were toiling away
at a job to pay for day care.
</P>
<P>
   Finally comes the question of college. The brutal fact of the
current reality is that mediocre students who have a lot of money
behind them can go to college with no problems, but only the good
students can obtain financial aid to cover their college expenses,
regardless of the family's financial situation.
</P>
<P>
   (And your assets in retirement accounts such as IRAs aren't
counted when tallying the parents' assets on the current financial
aid forms.)
</P>
<P>
   So it would behoove you to get your children to take their
schooling seriously, teaching them that what they do in elementary
and high school will largely shape their future careers and earning
power.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Your reply to R.S. of Newburyport, Mass. raised a question
that might interest many readers: How much can you withdraw from
savings in retirement without running out of money? When you told
R.S. that $589,844 would last 30 years, that implied a withdrawal
rate of about 7.4 percent. A recent piece at www.morningstar.net by
Frank Armstrong, ``Making It Last Forever,'' provides historical
calculations indicating that at 7.4 percent withdrawals, you'd have
perhaps a 14 percent chance of going broke. Once withdrawal rates
exceed 7 percent, things go downhill rapidly, Armstrong argues. Is
he being too conservative?
</P>
<P>
   M.S., Wayland, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think you misunderstood what I was saying to R.S. This was
a fellow who had a fairly modest retirement nest egg and believed
that if other people were worried about their retirement situation,
he should be frantic.
</P>
<P>
   But what he also had was a substantial pension, and the
calculation I made (which presumed a 6.5 portfolio yield) was
simply to demonstrate how much capital he would require to supply
the same income stream as the pension over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   In his case, since what's in question is a pension rather than a
pool of savings, the money would never run out, although it would
become steadily less valuable as inflation took its toll.
Fortunately, R.S. was building a supplementary retirement account,
upon which he could rely to offset the effect of inflation in his
later years of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in our calculations was that you simply tallied
that $43,750 a year represents 7.4 percent of the pool. But if you
calculate the portfolio with monthly withdrawals from a pool
returning 6.5 percent, you get to zero shortly after 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   All that aside, Armstrong's column is an excellent one,
describing a study that showed historical results of what he calls
successful portfolios over various time periods with various rates
of withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, a successful portfolio is one that still exists at
the end of the period. The primary focus on the study was to
determine what portfolio mix of stocks and bonds fared best at
various levels of withdrawal. I recommend it highly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
