<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Dec. 7:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   MONACO-SAFRA (Paris) _ An American nurse has confessed to
setting the fire that killed billionaire banker Edmond Safra,
authorities in Monaco said Monday. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-RUSSIA (Dateline to come) _ Russians drop leaflets in
Grozny telling Chechnyans to leave their capital by Saturday or be
killed. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With a map.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-BANKS-HOLOCAUST (Washington or undated) _ The Volcker
Commission, after a three-year investigation of Swiss banks, says
there are up to 54,000 unclaimed accounts that may have belonged to
Holocaust victims and that their value is unclear, but the $1.25
billion settlement last year with two biggest banks won't be
jeopardized. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-TRADE (Rio de Janiero or Sao Paulo, Brazil) _ Trade,
globalization, and American dominance: the view from Brazil. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-HOLBROOKE (Pretoria, South Africa) _ Richard Holbrooke,
the U.S. representative to the United Nations, in a speech on
Africa, says international observers won't go to Congo until the
factions stop fighting.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-DELEGATION (Washington) _ Delegation led by British
Northern Ireland Secretary visits Washington. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-GUN-CONTROL (Montreal) _ A look at gun control in Canada
on the 10th anniversary of the mass killing that prompted changes
in the law. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-SCHOOL-SHOOT (Fort Gibson, Okla.) _ Four students at a
rural middle school were shot and wounded Monday morning and a
13-year-old seventh-grader was in custody after a teacher grabbed
the gun from him. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   With a map.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH-CAMP-ATTACK (Cedar City, Utah) _ Seven teen-agers vanished
into the rocky southern Utah desert after allegedly attacking and
tying up two counselors during a camping trip for troubled youth.
By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   With a map.
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-CRACKDOWN (San Francisco) _ At the richest time in the
nation's history, housing that the poor can afford is at an
all-time low, fueling an increase in homelessness, according to the
U.S. Conference of Mayors. And with complaints about beggars and
bag ladies and mumbling, stumbling vagrants growing as well, cities
are fighting to move homeless people out of public spaces as never
before. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-CRIME (Philadelphia) _ A look at the rising crime rate in
Chestnut Hill, the wealthy, quaint area of Philadelphia, where a
Philadelphia Daily News columnist was stabbed to death during a
botched mugging; a suspect was arrested Monday. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With a map.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-COALITION (Detroit) _ In a concession to environmentalists,
the Ford Motor Co., the world's second-largest corporation, said
Monday that it would pull out of the Global Climate Coalition, a
group of big manufacturers and oil companies that has been lobbying
against restrictions on emissions of gases linked to global
warming. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-BENEFITS (Washington) _ A federal advisory panel says the
government has underestimated the financial problems of Social
Security because people are living longer than expected, and
therefore will draw more in retirement benefits. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   With a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MIRANDA (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to take
up an important case on the fate of Miranda rights, and will decide
whether Congress legislatively overruled requirements for police to
issue the famous warning in a long-ignored law that says a
confession may be admitted as evidence so long as it is given
voluntary _ whether or not it is accompanied by Miranda warnings.
By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLICANS-DEBATE (Phoenix) _ Republican presidential
candidates debate again, in the home state of the only candidate
who won't be there in person. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
