<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0699 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CENTURY-EDISON-BOS &LR;      12-06 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-EDISON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN FOR THE CENTURY: THOMAS ALVAH EDISON GAVE US LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So who's it going to be _ Stalin or Hitler? Churchill
or Roosevelt? Einstein or Gandhi or Martin Luther King?
</P>
<P>
   The great debate is coming to a close over who will win the
title ``Man of the Century'' _ or ``Person of the Century,'' as at
least half the planet (and admirers of Mother Teresa) would prefer
it.
</P>
<P>
   It is a prize that several publications, most dramatically Time
magazine, will bestow in coming weeks, in an era-ending ritual that
is inherently absurd _ how could one person epitomize 100 years of
earthly existence? _ but also good sport.
</P>
<P>
   In that spirit: A case could be made for any of the
larger-than-life figures cited above. This, after all, has been the
Century of Totalitarianism, the Century of the Warrior-Statesman,
the Century of Peaceful Disobedience, the Century of the Bomb.
</P>
<P>
   But looking beyond the sheen of politics and into the structures
of daily life _ the transformations that have set the 20th century
apart from the eons preceding _ a few things stand out: the
incandescent bulb, which lit up the night; the electric power
plant, which spread light and energy to virtually every town around
the world; the motion picture, which forever altered the way we
look at ourselves; the phonograph, which preserved sounds and music
that would otherwise vanish into the air.
</P>
<P>
   All these things were invented by one man, Thomas Alva Edison,
and if anyone deserves to be called the most influential soul of
the century _ the person who shaped the century most broadly and
deeply _ Edison fits the bill.
</P>
<P>
   True, he worked out his most famous inventions toward the end of
the 19th century, but they were not in much use, nor was their full
impact clear, until after the start of the 20th. He also lived long
enough into the 20th century _ he died in 1931, at the age of 84 _
to see his creations transform the fabric of society and to find
himself revered as a central figure of the modern era. &QL; 
 &QL; 
1,093 patents, one person &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edison successfully filed 1,093 patents for inventions, the most
granted to one person. The biographer Robert Conot has likened them
to ``the building blocks of an obelisk rising out of the history of
the world,'' adding, ``No other man has ever been responsible for
striking the spring of so much wealth, nor had such influence on
the lives of so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   He was obsessive in his search for nature's secrets, oblivious
to others, disheveled, often working 24 hours straight, except for
frequent five-minute naps, which he had a knack for taking
anywhere, including on his lab's hard floor.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, he casually talked of devising ``a minor
invention every 10 days and a big thing every six months or so.''
And he very nearly kept to his schedule.
</P>
<P>
   However, contrary to schoolbooks that paint him as a lone
tinkerer, Edison also created the first modern research laboratory,
with vast staffs, project teams, and outside funding. He was the
first inventor to link up with the titans of corporate finance,
forging a new kind of relationship between technology and
capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   The incandescent lamp and the electric power plant would be
cause enough for giving Edison the century's prize. Before their
invention, in the age of gas and kerosene lamps, only a few homes
had enough ``candlepower'' for reading at night. Today, the typical
household generates as much light as an entire village of the 19th
century.
</P>
<P>
   But electricity meant more than the lightbulb, of course. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The skyscraper's the limit &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It meant that elevators, previously powered by steam, could rise
to limitless heights, making the skyscraper possible.
</P>
<P>
   Factories, which had relied on coal and water for their power,
continued to grow in the cities, spurring an urban migration.
</P>
<P>
   Horses, once the mainstay of urban transportation, could be put
out to pasture and replaced with electric trains and trolleys.
</P>
<P>
   Dentists could drill and repair cavities, rather than simply
pull teeth. Everything became quicker and easier, making work more
productive and leaving more time _ including night time _ for
leisure. Or more work.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most striking things about Edison's geyser of
invention is that his was a genius largely untrammeled by
education. The son of a ne'er-do-well grain and lumber
entrepreneur, he dropped out of school at age 12 (though he later
took a college chemistry course when he felt the need). It is also
striking that the things he made and the puzzles he solved, for the
most part, were not on the verge of being made or solved by anyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   The electron had not been discovered when he started work on
electricity in the 1870s. The measurement of inductance and
resistance was dimly grasped, at best. As one of his researchers,
Francis Jehl, later put it, ``There were no instruments for
measuring volts and amperes _ it was like a carpenter without his
foot rule.''
</P>
<P>
   His breakthroughs, which he announced with a showman's gusto
before a pack of reporters, were often ridiculed by the
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   After he proclaimed success at designing an incandescent
lightbulb, the British Parliament formed a board of inquiry, which
concluded that Edison's claim was physically impossible and
``unworthy of the attention of practical or scientific men.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar derision greeted his claim of inventing the phonograph.
A Yale University professor assured the New York Sun, ``The idea of
a talking machine is ridiculous.'' The heads of the French Academy
scoffed that Edison was obviously a fraud and a ventriloquist.
</P>
<P>
   When these inventions were finally proved real beyond all doubt,
a reporter asked Lord Kelvin, a physicist and the most
distinguished inventor of the day, why no one else had thought of
these things. ``The only answer I can think of,'' he replied, ``is
that no one else is Edison.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A World's Fair plaudit &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The World's Fair of 1904 in St. Louis, with its
home-of-the-future exhibit called ``Palace of Electricity,'' marked
the first recognition that his inventions would change the nature
and tempo of life everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``Thomas A. Edison and the Modernization of
America,'' Martin V. Melosi said that during the 20th century's
first decade, the number of industrial electric motors expanded by
580 percent. By 1920, companies were making electric stoves,
washing machines, dishwashers, vacuum cleaners. By 1927, two-thirds
of US households had electricity.
</P>
<P>
   When Edison first demonstrated his feats, usually in or near his
lab in Menlo Park, N.J., or, later, West Orange (which stands
preserved as a landmark site by the National Park Service), they
were viewed as almost supernatural events, greeted with an awe
unmatched until men walked on the moon. He was hailed as ``The
Wizard of Menlo Park,'' ``The Prometheus of Light,'' ``The Napoleon
of Science.''
</P>
<P>
   When he displayed the talking machine at the 1889 Exhibition in
Paris, 30,000 people lined up to see it, an attraction second only
to the Eiffel Tower.
</P>
<P>
   When his first movies were shown in a Broadway parlor _
90-second flicks, viewed through a nickel-drop peephole, heralded
by a banner that read ``The Wizard's Latest Invention!'' _ riots
nearly broke out as impatient crowds waited all day and long into
the night for a peek. &QL; 
 &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
