<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW OSHA STANDARDS: GOOD FOR EVERYONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Many businesses across the nation say it would be a
bureaucratic nightmare that could cost them untold billions of
dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration _ OSHA _ says,
on the other hand, that its proposed new ergonomics standard could
prevent 300,000 job-related injuries a year and save businesses an
estimated $9 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules are designed to prevent musculoskeletal disorders
(known as MSDs) which, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics,
constitute the largest number of job-related injuries and illness
problems in the US workplace.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the new OSHA standard would be the most significant
worker and safety law of the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups such as the Chamber of Commerce and their allies
in Congress have been trying to block passage of the proposed
standard. But if they succeed, businesses could end up paying
billions more in costs because of work-related injuries that are
preventable. Already, companies are spending $15 million to $20
million per year in workers' compensation costs for work-related
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Under OSHA's proposed rules, employers must: provide for
management leadership and employee participation; inform workers of
common MSD hazards; analyze problem jobs and control the hazard;
provide training about MSDs; provide medical attention to injured
workers; and occasionally evaluate whether the chosen method to
control the hazard is working.
</P>
<P>
   The rules would cover general industry employers and workers in
manual-handling or manufacturing jobs at about 1.6 million work
sites. Those rules would also eventually apply at other general
industry sites at which one or more workers had suffered from a
musculoskeletal disorder. Construction, maritime, and agricultural
industry workers would be excluded.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed standard is not as far-reaching as it could have
been. Overall, it would apply to only 25 percent of general
industry employers; the other 75 percent would not be affected
unless a documented, work-related injury occurred at their work
sites.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA defines ergonomics as ``the science of fitting the job to
the worker.'' Ergonomic programs help prevent musculoskeletal
disorders when there is a mismatch between a worker and his task.
</P>
<P>
   Such mismatches have resulted in 1.8 million injuries related to
overexertion or repetitive motion, and some 600,000 of these
resulted in lost time from work.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups argue that the new standard would cost employers
far more than do the current number of work-related injuries, but
if OSHA's numbers and fact sheets are even half-correct, opponents
may have a tough time explaining why OSHA's proposal should not
become law.
</P>
<P>
   Along with preventing an average of 300,000 musculoskeletal
disorders per year over 10 years, the new standard would:
</P>
<P>
   --Protect 27.3 million workers at 1.9 million work sites.
</P>
<P>
   --Save $22,500 in direct costs for each MSD prevented ($6.75
billion per year), for a total average savings of $9 billion each
year. According to OSHA, the total cost to employers for fixing
work stations to meet the new standard would be $4.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the obvious benefits, physical and financial, to
both the employers and their workers, business groups are using
every available tactic to delay passage of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   At their prodding, Congress recently passed a bill that would
prohibit OSHA from issuing a final ergonomic standard until the
National Academy of Science completes another study in 2001. But
OSHA sees this for what it is _ another delaying tactic.
</P>
<P>
   In its report titled ``Misleading Myths on Ergonomics,'' OSHA
said that a second NAS study ``is unlikely to alter the firm
conclusions from the first that musculoskeletal disorders are
work-related and that ergonomic programs can reduce the incidence
of these injuries.'' The second NAS study, OHSA adds, ``is
essentially another analysis of much of the same body of evidence
that (the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health, or
NIOSH) and NAS reviewed previously.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the proposal contend that ergonomics has not proved
that musculoskeletal disorders are necessarily related to the
workplace. However, in 1997 NIOSH _ after evaluating 600 studies _
concluded that there is a link. NIOSH's finding was confirmed by 27
peer reviewers.
</P>
<P>
   While OSHA acknowledges that workplace injuries and illnesses
are on the decline, it notes that work-related MSDs ``remain the
most prevalent, most expensive, and most preventable occupational
injuries in the US today.''
</P>
<P>
   Musculoskeletal disorders account for more than one-third (or
600,000) of the injuries and illnesses each year that force people
to miss work. An additional 1.2 million injuries are severe enough
to cause workers to seek medical attention or light duty. There is
no doubt among specialists in MSD that OSHA's proposed standard
could dramatically reduce the problem.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress does not pass this most important bill, working
people will have a great opportunity to make their voices heard in
the next election, before many more thousands of them miss work
with injuries that an ergonomic standard could have prevented.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1404EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
