<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0702 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CENTURY-EDISON-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     12-06 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-EDISON-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... for a peek.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few spectators could have foreseen how dramatically these
marvels would alter daily life. Edison did.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1878, Edison listed the possible uses of the
phonograph _ dictation without a stenographer, books for the blind,
music (``the phonograph will undoubtedly be liberally devoted to
music,'' he wrote), and the preservation of speeches after the
speaker is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad, given that many of those who gaped at the machine,
including the industrialists who would end up making lots of money
from it, saw little more than a parlor trick.
</P>
<P>
   His evolution as an inventor both reflected and shaped his
times. Born in 1847, Edison came of age during the Civil War, as
the frontier was closing, steel mills were prospering, railroads
were expanding. There was a great need for new technology to
process raw materials, devise consumer products, transport both,
and unify the continent into a network of suppliers and markets.
</P>
<P>
   Edison was hardly the only one trying to fill those needs. In
the 40 years following the Civil War, 1 million patents were filed
with the US government. Yet no inventor approached Edison in
volume, versatility, or doggedness.
</P>
<P>
   During his hunt for the ideal material to use as filament in his
lamp, Edison tested, as he put it later, ``no fewer than 6,000
vegetable growths.'' By chance, he happened upon a strip of bamboo
from the lab's fan and, finding it highly durable under extreme
heat, scattered his men to the West Indies, Japan, and Central
America (one of them died of yellow fever in Cuba) in search of the
best bamboo.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists of a later era would roll their eyes at this
scattershot approach. Even Karl Compton, in an otherwise
appreciative obituary in Science magazine, acknowledged that it led
Edison to ``many futile experiments.'' However, as he also noted,
Edison was not just inventing new products but discovering new
principles. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Staying the course &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many of his inventions, seen in retrospect, followed a logical
course, one leading to the next. This may explain why he threw so
many scientists for a loop; they weren't following his course,
weren't sifting through the 1,001 things he had accumulated from
his earlier experiments.
</P>
<P>
   He started as a telegraph operator, and his first invention, at
age 16, was for his own use _ a device that repeated a Morse code
signal at a slower speed, so he could more easily transcribe the
messages.
</P>
<P>
   This led him to invent a machine that converted the Morse code's
dots and dashes into Roman letters, which he turned into the ticker
tape that conveyed stock-market prices to brokerage houses. It was
the first invention that made him money and put him in touch with
big business.
</P>
<P>
   That invention led him to design a wire that could
simultaneously transmit telegraphic messages in opposite
directions. That led to the idea of a telephone. When Alexander
Graham Bell barely beat him, he rechanneled his own idea for a
telephone speaker into the phonograph, which sparked the idea for
movies. (``It should be possible,'' he wrote in his notebook, ``to
devise an apparatus to do for the eye what the phonograph was
designed to do for the ear.'')
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he designed improvements to the phone,
including a carbon-button transmitter that made the signal much
louder and clearer. This experiment with carbon led to his design
for an incandescent lamp, and on it went.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Josephson, an early biographer, estimated that by the
time of Edison's death in 1931, the electric light and power
industry was worth $15 billion in the United States alone. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Worst businessman'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Little if any of it wound up in Edison's pockets. He did make
lots of money in his lifetime, from contracts signed with Cornelius
Vanderbilt (who owned Western Union) and J. Pierpont Morgan (whose
bank underwrote Edison's first commercial power station, in lower
Manhattan).
</P>
<P>
   But he was cut out of his own companies when they grew big
(General Electric started out as Edison General Electric, before
his backers removed Edison in more ways than one). What money he
did make he lavished on his otherwise neglected family and on
experiments in search of further inventions.
</P>
<P>
   His friend and admirer, Henry Ford, called Edison ``the world's
greatest inventor and worst businessman.'' This wasn't quite true;
Edison died a millionaire. But, as Paul Israel, editor of the
Edison papers at Rutgers University, says, ``He was interested in
solving technical problems and bringing them to market; he wasn't
interested in running a business.'' So, he never dominated an
industry in a sustained way, as Ford did with cars, Rockefeller
with oil, or Carnegie with steel.
</P>
<P>
   He also made some bad turns at critical junctures. He championed
DC power, when George Westinghouse pushed and won with AC. He
invented and stuck with an electric-battery car, while Ford (who
learned how to build cars at Detroit Edison before leaving to form
his own company) put out a cheaper, more convenient gas-engine
model. He dumped millions into pre-fab concrete houses and an
ore-separating project, neither of which panned out. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A late-life vindication &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His vindication came in August 1929, two years before he died.
Ford (perhaps the century's second-most-important figure) threw a
jubilee in Dearborn, Mich., to celebrate the 40th anniversary of
Edison's lightbulb. Orville Wright, Marie Curie, and President
Herbert Hoover were among the hundreds who came to honor him.
</P>
<P>
   Ford had reconstructed a mockup of Edison's original lab in
Menlo Park, complete with old bulbs, beakers, and ticker tape. (An
ailing but spirited Edison told Ford, ``You've got this 99 1/2
percent perfect,'' complaining only, ``We never kept it this
clean.'')
</P>
<P>
   At the evening's end, Edison pulled a switch, as he had done
back in the real Menlo Park long ago, and the filaments of lamps
all across Dearborn lit to a blaze. As the crowd cheered, the NBC
radio announcer, who was broadcasting the festival live, excitedly
told the millions of Americans tuning in from their electrified
homes, ``And Edison said, `Let there be light!' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1405EST &QL; 
