<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0705 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-SMOKING-BOS &LR;      12-06 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SMOKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGING FOR AN OLD HABIT SUFFUSES POETIC `SMOKING BOOK' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE SMOKING BOOK 
By Lesley Stern 
University of Chicago Press, 238 pp., $22 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Smoking Book'' does not concern itself with the ongoing
tobacco wars, cigarette use among teen-agers, or the long-term
effects of second-hand smoke.
</P>
<P>
   It's a love story.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the smoker, smoking becomes second nature _ like breathing
and talking and eating and touching,'' writes Lesley Stern. ``Every
act of smoking is potentially ceremonial, a staged performance of
the everyday, a way of enabling so many daily pleasures and
struggles, repititious moments of work and leisure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Smoking Book'' is one woman's ode to a great love lost, a
wistful caress of memories from a long romance with cigarettes.
Composed of essays and vignettes, this is a book so defiantly out
of step with popular and conventional belief that Stern even calls
one of her chapters ``Life-Giving Mist,'' borrowing a term from the
Mbuya-guarani tribe of South America, who believed tobacco was a
source of vitality and made the smoking of it a sacred ritual
reserved for shamans. Here, Stern examines her own smoking rituals
_ the anticipation of that first drag of the morning, a postcoital
cigarette shared between lovers, the mating dances performed in a
trail of blue smoke.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when some consider cigarettes as dangerous as bullets
and smokers are society's favorite pariahs, Stern has written a
fever-dream reminiscence about smoking, even as she details her
efforts to leave the lover _ tobacco _ that may eventually kill
her.
</P>
<P>
   It can be said that Stern was born to love cigarettes. She was
raised on a tobacco farm in Rhodesia (now Zimbabwe). One of her
favorite photographs features her father, standing in the midst of
his tobacco seedbeds, holding Stern as an infant in one hand and
cradling a cigarette in the other. Stern grew up with the smell of
tobacco, and its aromas summon ``childhood sensations from the
past,'' just as the smell of biscuits might revive the warmth of a
grandmother's kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Stern was barely old enough to see over a store
counter, she was swapping a handful of coins for a pack of
cigarettes to be shared with her older sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first deep breath they take, drawing in the nicotine, is
sickening; nausea wells up and their bodies are shaken by
coughing,'' she writes, recalling that first cigarette. ``As the
spasms subside they stub out, but do not relinquish, the
cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be the last time for many years that Stern would stub
out a cigarette. Oh, there would be attempts to quit, such as those
hilariously recalled in ``Burial.'' She tried massage, and attended
meetings of Smoke Stoppers. She recalled the words of a former
boyfriend who said kissing a smoker was like ``putting your tongue
into a cremation urn _ full of the ashes of a dead person.'' In an
effort to literally bury her addiction, Stern would dig a ``grave''
for her last pack of cigarettes in her yard. But inevitably she
would always be drawn back to the spot, shovel in hand; she
realizes that it wasn't a burial spot as much as a ``safety deposit
box, a last resort, a final refuge.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Stern would eventually quit, she is unabashed in
remembering how profoundly cigarettes affected her life. They were
a tool for dating when a handsome stranger offered a light, a means
to begin a casual conversation. Along with a glass of scotch and
Sinatra on the stereo, they were comfort and companion on a long,
lonely night.
</P>
<P>
   Stern does not spend a lot of time mixing it up with the
antismoking commandos, though she believes their campaign
``operates within an economy of moralism, with a rhetoric of
abhorrence that appeals to the `common good,' '' and that ``smokers
are made to feel socially guilty, as though acting criminally
against the common good.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stern isn't really interested in rants. Instead, she has
fashioned a book with the dexterity of a jazz riff and the ethereal
beauty of a smoke ring. One need not be a smoker to understand or
appreciate Stern's work. In a way, it's a book about all vices and
about every craving we know is not good for us, but is nonetheless
oh-so-good to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We project, we invest the object with all our desires, all our
needs for curative affect, all our fantasies of divine
transcendence, all our fears of dirt, contamination and death,''
she writes. ``And it _ not the object in itself but that smoky ring
of desire in which the object is conjured into being and circulates
_ returns us to ourselves more complete, almost completely
satisfied.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
