<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0706 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-06 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALREADY LAYING PLANS FOR 3000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time capsule fever is gripping the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is time capsule crazy right now,'' Paul Hudson,
founder of the Atlanta-based International Time Capsule Society,
recently told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that. There are so many time capsules that Hudson felt
the need to start an organization to keep track of them all. He has
his hands full, because, as he told the AP, most of the world's
10,000 known time capsules are missing. Some are doubtless
destroyed, but many others are still out there, lost, waiting to be
found. It seems that people tend to forget where they put time
capsules, especially if they're buried, as most of them are. Don't
squirrels do something similar with nuts?
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Magazine devoted its entire 212-page issue
Sunday to The Times Capsule, a project aimed at capturing the
essence of our time for whoever or whatever happens to be around to
find it in the year 3000. The Times sponsored a competition for the
capsule's design. A number of ingenious ideas were put forward, but
in the end the Times went with something traditional, in function
if not in form. The winner was Spanish architect Santiagao
Calatrava's many-chambered stainless steel capsule, a graceful
design ``reminiscent of an origami flower or fortune cookie.''
</P>
<P>
   I was pleased to read that conservation expert Margaret MacLean
put the kibosh on the newspaper's plans to fill the capsule with
digital records, which last a few decades at most. The
longest-enduring medium is good-quality, acid-free paper. For a
born-again Luddite, it's exhilarating to think that paper may well
outlast the new technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Capsule panel decided against burying it. Instead, it
will go on permanent display in the courtyard of the American
Museum of Natural History, where, it is hoped, it will endure until
the year 3000. Among its contents will be a copy of Sunday's New
York Time Magazine. Looking through it, I wondered what people
1,000 years hence might make of it, and concluded that one of the
few things that may still be relevant to life in the year 3000 is
the nine-page supplement extolling the timeless delights of Scotch
whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   Humans have an abiding interest in fermented beverages. Mead, a
light wine made from honey, was ``the reveler's drink of choice,''
around the turn of the last millennium, according to ``The Year
1000,'' Robert Lacey's and Danny Danziger's most interesting book
about life in England 1,000 years ago. Ale was the everyday drink,
safer than water, ``probably quite a sweet beverage with a porridgy
consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   What will people in the year 3000 want to know about the way we
lived? Probably the same sorts of things that Lacey and Danziger
write about life in 1000 A.D. What we ate and drank. How we loved,
or didn't. What we used for money. How we coped with disease and
infirmity. What we worshiped. How we amused ourselves. How we
treated women, children, old people. All the ordinary stuff of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies are selling do-it-yourself time capsule kits.
I have one here, called ``The Ark To the Future,'' touted as ``a
priceless gift your family will treasure _ forever.'' For $27.50
you get a couple of metal containers, plus a ``memory album'' and a
family tree to fill in. There's room in the containers for a few
artifacts that will capture the essence of your particular life in
the late 20th century. What would I include in mine? I'm making a
list. So far I have Prozac, the SelfCare catalog, the ``Y2K
Citizens Action Guide,'' the current issue of The National Enquirer
(``Hilary Demands Divorce: Bill Goes Berserk''), a Collin Street
Bakery fruitcake, and a bottle of Glenlivet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
