<HEADER>
A0710 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-INJECT-BOS &LR;      12-06 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJECTABLE POLIO VACCINE IS MAKING A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine-year-old David Salamone of Oakton, Va., has polio. But he
didn't catch it from someone, he got it from a vaccine. The last
natural US case of polio, which paralyzed hundreds of thousands of
Americans in the early part of the century, was in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Out of millions of children vaccinated for polio in the United
States each year, David was, unfortunately, one of a handful who
become paralyzed from the oral vaccine, which is made from a
weakened form of the live polio virus. About 1 out of 2.5 million
children becomes paralyzed from the oral vaccine each year, an
astronomically small number statistically speaking, but a
devastating one if it's your child.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems ridiculous that the only polio cases are from the
vaccines designed to prevent it,'' said John Salamone, David's
father.
</P>
<P>
   And with polio on the verge of being eradicated worldwide,
public health officials apparently agree.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in January, the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention is calling for all polio vaccines to be given in the
older injected form, which is made from the killed virus, instead
of the oral form that has been used since the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   This week the American Academy of Pediatrics plans to release
its own new polio vaccine guidelines. Already, a phase-out plan has
been in place since last January: The first two doses have been
recommended to be the injected virus and the last two doses the
oral drops.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sean Palfrey, director of the immunization initiative for
the Massachusetts chapter of the AAP, said, ``The country has been
so concerned about the six to eight people who end up with
paralytic polio that we are making a change in policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of the polio vaccine is one of medicine's greatest
triumphs. In the early part of the 20th century, no disease caused
greater terror than polio.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s, Jonas Salk developed the original polio
vaccine, made from an inactivated virus. By 1955, the incidence of
polio had fallen by 90 percent. By the early 1960s, an oral form of
the vaccine, pioneered by Albert Sabin, and made from an
attenuated, or weakened, live form of the virus, had supplanted the
Salk vaccine because it was more effective. Ironically, it is the
less successful Salk vaccine that the United States is now
returning to.
</P>
<P>
   As the world gets closer to eradicating polio, parents like John
Salamone want to see that other children use a safer alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not anti-vaccine,'' said Salamone, who took his son
from doctor to doctor for nearly two years before one determined
that his son's paralysis was related to the vaccine, probably
because he was born with an immune deficiency that made him
susceptible to polio.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son has paid a huge personal price for mass immunization,''
Salamone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1411EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
