<HEADER>
A0714 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-HOLLY-BOS &LR;      12-06 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-HOLLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUDDY' REMEMBERS EARLY ROCK'S INNOCENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The recent TV miniseries, ``Shake, Rattle &AMP; Roll,''
showed there's still interest in the roots of rock. Hence, it seems
like perfect timing to have ``Buddy: The Buddy Holly Story'' back
in town. A theatrical tribute to Rock and Roll Hall of Famer Holly,
the show is primed for a 60-week national run, starting Tuesday at
the Shubert Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   If you missed ``Buddy'' on its first go-round in Boston, seven
years ago, you missed a lively night that recalled rock's
pre-cynical age when innocence, not star-tripping, was king.
</P>
<P>
   Although Holly's death was considered rock's first great tragedy
_ dubbed ``the day the music died'' when he, Ritchie Valens, and
the Big Bopper (J. P. Richardson) perished in a 1959 plane crash in
a frozen Iowa cornfield _ the touring musical celebrates his life
without slipping into melodrama. It's based on a production that
has played for the past 11 years in London, where Holly in his '50s
heyday was even more popular than he was in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans wanted the glamour and the style of Elvis, where the
English mentality at the time was that we wanted the boy next door
_ somebody we could be like,'' says ``Buddy'' director Paul Mills.
``So the nerdy guy with glasses, we could all aspire to that.''
</P>
<P>
   This latest production is helmed by Mills and another
Englishman, Steve Gibb, the show's music director, who memorized
Holly guitar solos as a youth and can tell you that the first song
the Beatles cut on a demo tape was Holly's ``That'll Be the Day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing about Holly was that he was a guy writing his
own songs _ up until then most stars didn't _ and writing about
subjects that touched him and other kids,'' Gibb says of the
musician from Lubbock, Texas. ``He was terrific at fusing styles
together. His main influence was Hank Williams, but when he saw
Elvis, he stuck the two together.''
</P>
<P>
   While the British are behind the latest ``Buddy,'' most of the
cast is American, including the Atlanta-bred Van Zeiler, 27, who
stars as Holly. It's a long way from Zeiler's self-described
``frat-boy rock days'' at the University of Virginia, where he
admits to knowing much less about Holly than about Led Zeppelin. It
was his lack of awe toward Holly (``Van didn't come in and try to
impersonate him,'' says Gibb) that helped land him the job after he
struggled as an actor for two years in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I knew of Buddy Holly was `That'll Be the Day,' and I
don't think I even knew the full name of that song,'' says Zeiler.
``When I was cast in the role, I had to put the CD on repeat as I
went to sleep to try to learn the words to the song. It's been an
amazing journey ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeiler has played Holly for two years, starring in the London
production and, oddly enough, marrying in real life the British
woman who played Holly's wife, Maria Elena, in the production. The
actress is Victoria Stilwell, who says, ``I met Van on the first
day of rehearsals. I said, `Hi, I'm playing your wife.' And then a
couple of months into it, we started dating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This show is pretty phenomenal in how many lives it's
changed,'' says Zeiler. (Music director Gibb also met his wife,
Emily Wells, in the show: She's the assistant stage manager.)
</P>
<P>
   Holly's better-known songs, from ``Rave On'' to ``Peggy Sue''
and ``Not Fade Away,'' influenced everyone from the Beatles and
Bruce Springsteen to the Grateful Dead. But it's his ballads (such
as ``Rainin' in My Heart'') that Zeiler finds the most challenging
to sing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the rock songs, you can sing them while thinking of
Buddy's unashamed exuberance for music and life, but the ballads
have a sense of wisdom beyond his years,'' says Zeiler.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the success or failure of ``Buddy'' rests on re-creating
the innocence of those years before rock became big business. Holly
went from a teenage nobody in Texas to a worldwide star by age 22,
yet his songs, with few exceptions, remained a beacon of optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we try to do is teach the cast to play with the same sort
of innocence,'' says Gibb. ``The music then was obviously brand
new. We're now playing this stuff with 40 years of music culture
behind us, so it's hard to imagine that we're playing it for the
first time that it's ever been heard. But that's what we try to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   What further distinguishes ``Buddy'' is the multidimensional
nature of the cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``People write to me saying `I'd love to be a backup singer in
the show,' '' says Mills. ``And I write back and say, `Don't you
remember when you saw it that that backup singer actually was the
actress that also played his wife?' Everybody does everything _ and
they all get a great buzz from it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy'' is a natural theatrical vehicle because it has the
built-in climax of the famed Surf Ballroom concert at Clear Lake,
Iowa, on Feb. 2, 1959, featuring Holly, Valens, and the Big Bopper.
While Holly played the show with a small combo, the theater
production features the entire cast during this finale, which can
drive audiences to a fever pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Some cast members have made the pilgrimage to the Surf Ballroom,
which still exists. ``You might think it's touristy, but then you
get down there and see everything as it was,'' says Mills. ``And
you can hear all the ghosts. It's quite extraordinary. You see that
stage and it's like, `Oh my God, this is where it all happened.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Zeiler also made the trip to Clear Lake and found himself
humming ``Peggy Sue'' while sitting in the ballroom's empty seats.
It also made him wonder just what might have happened had Holly
lived past the tender age of 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy was always pushing to a different plane in everything he
did,'' says Zeiler. ``At the time of his death, he was into a
different thing than `That'll Be the Day,' `Oh Boy,' and his other
straight-ahead rock stuff. He was experimenting more with
instrumentation. That's what I try to keep in my mind as we go
through the show every night. I think of his opening of doors and
his moving into rockabilly, but also of his breaking the color
barrier by being the first white act to play at the Apollo Theatre
(in New York). In everything _ socially and musically _ he just
didn't care about what was normally done. He went a step further
and pushed it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
