<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0717 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ART-SHOWS-BOS &LR;      12-06 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-SHOWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETROSPECTIVES FOR A POET AND A PAINTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Brazilian artist Cildo Meireles and the
Italian-born painter Francesco Clemente are contemporaries:
Meireles was born in 1948, Clemente in 1952. Although both are
citizens of the world, Meireles has remained based in Rio, which
was considered a contemporary-art backwater until the relatively
recent ``discovery'' of major artists working there, while Clemente
moved to New York in 1981. Geography has had something to do with
the trajectories of their respective careers. That, and several
other factors. Clemente paints; Meireles works in more unwieldy
materials, like talc by the ton or folding yardsticks by the
thousands. Clemente was categorized early on as an Expressionist
and one of the ``Three C's,'' as he and fellow Italians Sandro Chia
and Enzo Cucchi were famously dubbed. Meireles is more elusive.
</P>
<P>
   Both are the subjects of ambitious retrospectives now in New
York museums: Clemente's fills nearly all of the uptown Guggenheim;
Meireles's has taken over the New Museum in SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   If Meireles is familiar to Bostonians, it's because of the
pioneering show of his work that Milena Kalinovska brought to the
Institute of Contemporary Art in 1997 when she was its director.
One of its highlights, ``Volatile,'' which requires the visitor to
slog through a room ankle-deep in talc, reappears in the New
Museum. Like Meireles's other large-scale pieces, this one alters
perception _ in this case, the basic experience of walking. The
talc slows you down, and the textureless substance creates strange
sensations as you push against it.
</P>
<P>
   The ICA show was organized in Spain and also appeared in
Portugal. The New Museum show will travel to Rio de Janeiro and Sao
Paulo. Meireles is typecast as ``Latin,'' although there's little
or nothing in his art that fits the stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   He's a poet with everyday materials, and with color. The big
installations that have made his the most ambitious show the New
Museum has mounted in its 23-year history tend to be monochromatic.
``Red Shift,'' for instance, is a vintage 1960s living room in
which everything _ the furniture, the knockoffs of paintings by
Pollock and Rothko, even the tropical fish _ is red. After a while,
your eyeballs throb. A red epoxy ``spill'' on the floor winds down
a corridor ending in a sink spouting red water. What would it be
like, you wonder, to live in a world where there was only one
color?
</P>
<P>
   The merging of colors is the point of ``Cinza,'' a pair of
canvas-walled roomlets, one carpeted in chalk, the other in ash.
Walking from one to the other, you carry and marry these opposites.
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 ``Fontes'' is a golden yellow the artist borrowed from
van Gogh. The whole room is suffused with the shade, which is also
the dominant hue of the 6,000 wooden yardsticks dangling from the
ceiling in a giant spiral you walk through, the corridor becoming
ever narrower, so that no matter how skinny you are, you feel
gently squeezed. As you push aside the jungle of sticks, they
oblige with a delightful clackety sound that turns up in the
soundtrack, too. At the center of the spiral the sticks are too
dense to penetrate, so you retrace your steps. Doing so is
something of a disappointment, but also a chance to contemplate the
half million little black plastic numbers scattered on the floor,
as if all the order the yardsticks represented had disappeared.
Blanketing the walls are a thousand yellow clocks, set at different
times, all out of synch. Provocative, yes, but ``Fontes'' is
pleasurable, too. Like the van Gogh ``Wheat Field Under Threatening
Skies With Crows'' that inspired its color, ``Fontes'' suggests a
world gone awry, but it does so through beauty.
</P>
<P>
   In his sculpture, Meireles likes to thwart or tweak everyday
objects including Coca-Cola bottles and dollar bills, both symbols
of US capitalism. Sometimes the results are one-liners, as in the
1970 ``Blind Mirror,'' a white metal medicine chest whose mirror is
blocked out by gray goo. In another '70s piece, metal and paper
chains hang side by side, so you note the difference. This doesn't
take long. The 1976 ``Reason/Madness'' requires more time to
absorb. A pair of bamboo bows are held taut by padlocked chains.
The key to one lock dangles above its target; the key to the other
hangs below. Neither reason nor madness is the solution, Meireles
seems to say. Meanwhile, like those tense arcs, we exist in a state
of suspense.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Francesco Clemente's world, man and woman can merge, the tail
of a brown mouse can intertwine with a long pink tail spinning out
of a distinctly human derriere, people can be spotted or striped
like leopards or tigers, and faces can appear within the eye and
mouth cavities of other faces. The body is infinitely plastic. Skin
is penetrable. All life forms mingle. All the forms of Clemente's
art mingle in the Guggenheim show, which includes more than 200 of
his oil and fresco paintings, watercolors, pastels, sculptures and
book illustrations, dating from the 1970s to now.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Naples to an ancient aristocratic family who had lost
their lands in the 19th century, Clemente studied architecture in
Rome in the '70s, in a climate of political unrest, demonstrations,
and strikes. Like others of his generation, he made long
pilgrimages to India in search of a different and more spiritual
aesthetic. While based in New York for nearly two decades now, he
is not an artist you can identify with any particular country. He
may be Italian by birth, but his painting has more of an affinity
with Northern European art. His splotchy, wayward watercolors are
reminiscent of Nolde's, and his mosaiclike patterning sometimes
resembles Klimt's. The Indian influence is apparent in the multiple
eyes or breasts his figures sprout, while his joining of human and
animal into a single creature goes back to Egyptian pharaohs
represented as sphinxes. In whatever medium he chooses to work, his
handling is plush and seductive; you want to roll around in his
voluptuous world.
</P>
<P>
   The show's curator, Lisa Dennison, has divided the exhibition
into eight thematic sections, starting with one called ``I.'' She
could have stopped there. Among the rather large category of
artists obsessed with themselves, no one tops Clemente. He presents
himself as sensual or sinister, a chameleon capable of more
metamorphoses than any Greek god. In the 1982 ``Alba and
Francesco,'' he presents his face and his wife's floating together,
overlapping but with their eyes and lips not quite matching up,
creating a woozy, drunken effect. Roses hover in the background,
free of gravity, a motif borrowed from Symbolist painting.
Weightlessness is common in Clemente's fantasy world. In the 1986
``Usary of Love,'' a man and woman float horizontally, joined in an
ecstatic kiss. Instead of embracing, their arms stretch over their
heads, as if they're flying. ``Usary of Love'' is huge _ Clemente
dreams large scale _ and, other than the figures, consists of a
nebulous atmosphere of cloudy white paint and the gold leaf of a
Renaissance altarpiece.
</P>
<P>
   In the macabre, Mapplethorpian pastel ``Self-Portrait With Black
Gloves'' Clemente is naked except for the gloves. He holds his
index fingers against his temples, like a child playing at shooting
himself. In addition to the implied violence in his work, there's
plenty of sex. The two figures in ``Memory'' take the form of
African sculptures, like early Picassos. A bottle levitates over
the crotch of the reclining male, who is pulling out its stopper,
as if to release the scent of some previous encounter.
Orifice-happy anyway, Clemente has a field day with in-your-face
vaginas: In the 1994-95 pastel ``Sky'' he confronts you with a
golden, mythic female figure throwing her head back and flaunting a
vagina in which a blue sky with white clouds appears. Here is
infinity in a single body.
</P>
<P>
   Clemente is the youngest artist ever to have a full-museum
retrospective at the Guggenheim. Does he deserve the star
treatment? The mode of painting he practices, Expressionist
figuration, is outmoded, according to artworld gurus. But the
Guggenheim show makes a surprisingly strong case for it _ and for
him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1416EST &QL; 
