<HEADER>
A0718 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GREED-BOS &LR;      12-06 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GREED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVEALING THE TRUE `GREED' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Erich von Stroheim is the cinema's mad genius.
</P>
<P>
   His movies were too long. He was uncompromising in an industry
based on collaboration. None of his films were ever released in a
form that pleased him. He carried a pistol to his sets and not many
on his staff believed he wouldn't use it. But he made what may be
the greatest of all silent films _ ``Greed'' (1924). While the
Vienna-born actor-director who started his career as an extra in
``Birth of a Nation'' (1915) also made a handful of other films,
nothing ever came close to the heart and soul of ``Greed.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner Classic Movies is offering a restored version of
Stroheim's masterpiece, which debuts this week in a rather odd, but
ultimately wondrous, form.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Stroheim's film adaptation of Frank Norris's 1899
novel, ``McTeague,'' ran for more than nine hours. Only a handful
of friends saw that version of ``Greed'' in a special screening.
Then, in 1924, disaster struck. Goldwyn Studios, the studio behind
``Greed,'' merged with Metro Pictures, creating
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer. And it placed Erich von Stroheim under the
watchful eye of his mortal enemy, MGM production chief, Irving
Thalberg. The director, under duress, cut the film to about four
hours. But that wasn't enough. Stroheim was disgusted and refused
to cut it any more and asked his colleague, Rex Ingram, to make
additional trims. That still wasn't enough. Thalberg went through
``Greed'' with a hatchet, replacing long, detailed, dramatic
sequences with title cards. Eventually, it was released at just
over two hours and the career of Erich von Stroheim was effectively
over. To make matters worse, the MGM executives melted down the
excised footage to save the silver content. No one will ever see
``Greed'' as Erich von Stroheim intended.
</P>
<P>
   The TCM version is as close as we'll likely get.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tough story. McTeague (Gibson Gowland) is a dentist who
falls in love with Trina (ZaSu Pitts), fiancee of his best friend,
Marcus (Jean Hersholt). When Trina wins $5,000 in a lottery, Marcus
decides he was hasty in his selflessness and ignites a series of
events that spiral into inevitable tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Rick Schmidlin, who cut his filmmaking teeth on The
Doors' 1982 music video, ``Love Me Two Times'' and led the
acclaimed restoration on Orson Welles's ``Touch of Evil'' last
year, did a marvelous job on ``Greed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was much different than `Touch of Evil,''' he said, in an
interview from his home near Hollywood. ``There was no footage to
restore.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidlin, using Stroheim's continuity script, Herman Weinberg's
exhaustive book on the film, and approximately 650 production
stills from the University of Southern California library,
re-worked many of the missing sequences. He added 145 minutes to
the 135-minute original release. At 4 1/2 hours, it's a long ride
for an audience conditioned by music videos and flashy commercials.
But it's worth every minute.
</P>
<P>
   The technique of animating still photographs, popularized by Ken
Burns in his television documentary, ``The Civil War,'' fits the
film very well.
</P>
<P>
   Through panning and other filmic devices, Schmidlin and his
associates, particularly historian Richard Koszarski, integrate the
production stills into the moving picture as inobtrusively as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The added images reinforce Stroheim's obsessive attention to
detail. There's an early sequence, set in a Gold Rush saloon, where
a fight results in cracked skulls and bloody flesh. The movies
wouldn't see as much realistic violence again until Sam Peckinpah's
``The Wild Bunch'' in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidlin wisely added sequences that were slashed from the
original theatrical release including a brutal scene of spousal
abuse by a junk dealer.
</P>
<P>
   During the climactic fight in ``Greed,'' where the two stars
battle temperatures averaging 125 degrees in the middle of Death
Valley, the pistol-waving director reportedly screamed, ``Fight,
fight. Try to hate each other as much as you hate me.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Mayer, the Turner executive who green-lighted the project,
deserves a special commendation. Unlike some studio executives who
turned down the chance to redeem the industry's initial mishandling
of ``Greed,'' Mayer grabbed the chance to polish the industry's
tarnished image. It's unlikely that the restoration of a silent
movie would be greeted with great delight by stockholders, but it
will be hailed by film fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are film literate people at Turner,'' says Schmidlin.
``When you go into Roger Mayer's office, he doesn't have the latest
promotional items from his latest release. He's got history books
from the cinema. When you talk about the early days of film he
knows what you're talking about _ and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Stroheim received terrific notices and substantial box office
success with his next film, ``The Merry Widow'' (1925), an
adaptation of Franz Lehar's operetta with Mae Murray and John
Gilbert. But Stroheim was inconsolable. As he told reporters at the
time, ``When I saw how the censors mutilated `Greed,' which I did
really with my entire heart, I abandoned my ideals to create real
art pictures.. . . So I have quit realism entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early '50s, when Billy Wilder was looking for someone to
play Norma Desmond's manservant in ``Sunset Boulevard,'' the
director chose Stroheim. Who better to play the butler to a
washed-up star than a washed-up silent film director? Wilder, in an
attempt to accommodate his legendary predecessor, exclaimed that
Stroheim was a decade ahead of his time. Stroheim reportedly
responded, ``20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that it's a 75-year-old silent film constructed of bits
and pieces, ``Greed'' is still ahead of its time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1418EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0719 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS &LR;      12-06 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIFTS FOR LOVERS OF MYSTERY AND CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The holidays are almost upon us, and it's time to think about
presents for friends and relatives who enjoy mystery fiction.
Nonreaders of the genre always feel inadequate when trying to find
something suitable in the field _ and with good reason: It's my
experience that the typical nonreader hasn't a clue to what
attracts fans to this kind of fiction. Just as Edmund Wilson, in
his day America's most distinguished literary critic, condemned
mystery fiction after having read all the wrong books, today's
devotee of Updike, Rushdie, and Morrison will choose badly no
matter how good the intentions. So here are some thoughts for the
befuddled and bemused.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford University Press has long had in production its
``Oxford Companion to Crime and Mystery Writing'' ($49.95), and the
volume proves to have been worth waiting for. Edited by Rosemary
Herbert, with a team of Anglo-American advisers, this compilation
is idiosyncratic, informative, and charming, and the beauty of it
is that the book will appeal to novices and experts alike. There is
something here at every level for anyone with even a slight
interest in the subject, so putting this into the (very large)
stocking of friend or relative can hardly go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   There are essays on writers, on characters, on settings, on
themes, with the last much the most original and valuable. A reader
can cavil at the selection of authors for examination _ 149 of
them, with even the author of the entry on G. D. H. and Margaret
Cole admitting that most of their work is mediocre _ and perhaps at
the characters (85 of them). But one can only be delighted by and
grateful for the multiplicity of entries with such titles as
``Academic Milieu,'' ``Accidental Sleuth,'' ``Addresses and Abodes,
Famous,'' and the like. Full and clever cross-referencing lead the
reader on, and while there is some overlap and duplication
(``Friendship'' and ``Sidekicks and Sleuthing Teams,'' for
example), the effort at comprehensiveness is welcome. This is the
book to buy for the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford Companion shows some signs of its gestation. The
entry under Colin Dexter does not reveal Inspector Morse's first
name, though the entry under ``Sidekicks'' does (it's Endeavour, in
case you missed it). For Morse fanatics, there is a bundle of good
reading at hand, though it will need to be ordered quickly and may
require some trans-Atlantic negotiating: The books are so far
available only in the UK (call the publishers for exact prices in
dollars). ``John Thaw: The Biography'' by Stafford Hildred and Tim
Ewbank, has appeared in paperback from Andre Deutsch in London (76
Dean St., London, W1Z 5HA; call 011 44 0171 316 4450; about $12).
It's lightweight stuff but readable, and it provides some insights
into why Thaw was chosen to play Morse in the excellent television
series. Then there is ``The Oxford of Inspector Morse'' by Antony
Richards and Philip Attwell (Irregular Special Press, 163 Marine
Parade, Leigh-on-Sea, Essex, UK, about $5), which provides
background on all the Oxford scenes in both the novels and the
television films. ``The World of Inspector Morse'' by Christopher
Bird (Boxtree, a subsidiary of Macmillan; 25 Eccleston Place,
London SW 1W9 NF; call 011 44 0171 881 8000, about $20) is billed
as ``a complete A-Z reference for the Morse enthusiast.'' The
entries are intelligent and there are a number of attractive
illustrations. Wrap these up together with a membership in The
Inspector Morse Society (write to Antony Richards, 170 Woodland
Road, Sawston, Cambridge CB2 4DX), and if the recipient is a
Harvard graduate, mark Page 110 in ``The World'' with care. Sir
John Gielgud is speaking in his film role as Oxford's Chancellor,
Lord Hinksey, about honorary doctorates. A stuffy American tells
him he has two honorary degrees, and Lord Hinksey (actually the
name of a scruffy village just outside Oxford) responds, ``I've got
15 _ 16, if you count Yale.''
</P>
<P>
   My third idea for a gift is to combine Michael Connelly's
``Angels Flight'' (Little, Brown, $25) with Robert Crais's ``L.A.
Requiem'' (Doubleday, $23.95), both published earlier this year,
and give them to the true close reader among your friends. These
two tough, sprawling, yet tight crime thrillers _ Connelly's in
particular a mystery of the first order, with clues and red
herrings used with great intelligence _ speak to each other in
fascinating ways, and, read back to back, they are a bitter hymn of
love to the city of angels. As we near the end of the year, I do
not hesitate to vote Connelly's book the best of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you may just want to forget gifts, and the season,
and just read a good book yourself. I recommend ``Stone Quarry'' by
S. J. Rozan (St. Martin's, $23.95). This is Rozan's sixth book, yet
I had not read her before. She is a terrific writer who captures
small-town upstate New York to perfection. I very seldom do as the
reviewer's cliche has it and stay up all night to finish a book,
but this time I did, perhaps a little homesick for rural American
diction after all that hard Los Angeles talk and the calm tones of
donnish Oxford. I know what I want for Christmas: the first five
Rozan books.
</P>
<P>
   For the person who has everything, I suggest a subscription to
``Deadly Pleasures,'' recent winner of an Anthony Award, which will
set you back $14 a year for four issues (Refunding Makes Cents,
1718 South Ridge Point Drive, Bountiful, UT 84010). There are many
fanzines in this field, but this mystery magazine is one of the
best by my lights, and it has the interesting practice of
publishing several different reviews of the same book in the same
issue, which sounds repetitive, but is actually a lot of fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
