<HEADLINE>
LIVES, MEMOIRS, JOURNEYS: A 1999 NONFICTION SAMPLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID MEHEGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How casually we imagine that fiction is what is made up and
nonfiction what is true _ and how inaccurately. Each form borrows
from the other. The art of fiction discloses the most essential
truths in timeless ways: as Hamlet wrestles with his conscience
eternally and repeatedly, each time the play is acted. And a
nonfiction book, while it tells of facts that may be known by other
means (whereas Hamlet exists only in the play), is no less an
artifice, a thing of human hands.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, as in every year, many worthy nonfiction books have
been published. In this corner of the annual holiday issue, we try
to contrive a list not necessarily of the absolute best that has
been published, but of books of originality and excellence,
reviewed in our pages, which have a fair claim to be on such a
list. Any of these books would make a fine gift for a fine reader.
</P>
<P>
   The 16th-century painter Michelangelo Merisi, known as
Caravaggio, is endlessly fascinating and mysterious. His enormous
restored painting, ``The Beheading of John the Baptist,'' drew
crowds of hushed worshipers, one might say, when it was displayed
at the church of Santa Maria del Carmine in Florence last spring.
Notable among many recent exhibits and books devoted to him is
Helen Langdon's ``Caravaggio: A Life'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$30). Of Langdon, the Globe's Christine Temin wrote, ``Her strong
points are two. One is her descriptions of the paintings, many of
which are reproduced in color. . . . The other is the elaborate
context she creates. . . . She explains the temper of the times.''
Another book that ably combines the almost palpable presentation of
paintings and the artist and world they came from is Simon Schama's
just-published ``Rembrandt's Eyes'' (Knopf, $50).
</P>
<P>
   Alzheimer's disease and its griefs have elicited many books,
especially about the experience of the loving caregiver. There will
probably never be one more shrewd or lyrical than John Bayley's
``Elegy for Iris'' (St. Martin's, $22.95), about his late wife,
novelist Iris Murdoch. The book is divided into ``Then'' and
``Now'' _ the first half recalls their courtship and
early-to-middle married life; the second describes Murdoch's
decline and Bayley's determination to care for her himself as long
as he could. The Globe's chief book critic, Gail Caldwell, wrote,
``He is with her on the voyage. Sometimes the seas are stormy and
terrifying; more often, they are known but endless, granting an
occasional sense of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are actual terrifying seas, brilliantly recounted in
``The Endurance: Shackleton's Legendary Antarctic Expedition'' by
Caroline Alexander (Knopf, $29.95). Graced with many never-before
collected photographs by Frank Hurley, the book tells of the
1914-16 British epic of exploration in which a wise and brave
leader kept 27 stranded men alive for 20 months before they were
rescued. The Globe's book editor wrote of this story that while the
world was going mad with war and slaughter, ``Out on the
unforgiving, glittering ice, there was still sanity, romance, hope,
companionship, and tenacious life.''
</P>
<P>
   Scads of books about rock 'n' roll are published, usually shoddy
biographies of stars with empty offstage lives. But here is a book
for the intelligent fan: ``Flowers in the Dustbin: The Rise of Rock
and Roll, 1947-1977'' by James Miller (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $26).
Globe reviewer Joan Anderman wrote, ``Miller distills the cultural
essence, as much with exhaustive and ingenious synthesis of source
material as with plain old good storytelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides usually misspelling his name, most of us know little
more about the great landscape architect Frederick Law Olmsted than
that he designed Central Park in New York and Boston's Emerald
Necklace. But there is much more to know, and much to learn from
``A Clearing in the Distance: Frederick Law Olmsted and America in
the Nineteenth Century'' by Witold Rybczynski (Scribner, $28).
Described by reviewer David Rollow as ``the first biography of
Olmsted for a general audience,'' the book maintains that Olmsted
``was a reformer, an improver, as well as an artist. He wanted to
civilize America. That is the `clearing in the distance' of the
book's title.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Listener: A Psychoanalyst Examines His Life'' by Allen
Wheelis (Norton, $25.95) is an almost indescribably strange,
appalling, and beautiful book. Wheelis, who is in his early 80s and
practices in San Francisco, does three things: recalls his
childhood and his parents' lives, presents and accounts for his own
profoundly pessimistic understanding of the human predicament, and
confesses a faith in the importance of love to a happy life. The
Globe book editor wrote, in his review, ``Some such pessimists are
driven to cruelty, rage, or indifference. Others, such as . . .
Allen Wheelis, never lose their tenderheartedness, their sense of
the pathetic beauty of the human desire for union and meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Raban last year won the National Book Critics Circle
award for his history of Montana settlement, ``Badland: An American
Romance.'' This year he has produced a very different and equally
remarkable book, ``Passage to Juneau: A Sea and Its Meanings''
(Pantheon, $26.50). Raban, a British expat who lives in Seattle,
sailed his boat up the Inside Passage to Alaska, along the way
relating the stories of the native peoples and European explorers
of that region. Like Shackleton, Raban brought his crew (i.e.,
himself) back alive, but the crises and endings in his life on land
are the more poignant parts of the story. Reviewer David Barber
wrote, ``Chastening reckonings loom dead ahead for our castaway,
which a reviewer had better leave unremarked.''
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of overdoing biography (we admit to a weakness), we
offer one more: Judith Thurman's ``Secrets of the Flesh: A Life of
Colette'' (Knopf, $30). Sidonie Gabrielle Colette (1873-1954), the
great French writer and icon of feminine daring and romance, is the
perfect lens on the vibrant worlds of French culture and taste.
Reviewer Rachel Brownstein wrote, ``Thurman writes _ refreshingly,
without apology _ as an American of this fin de siecle, looking
back at the last one and the tumultuous half-century that followed
it. In sure, broad strokes, she sketches a complex, shifting
background: politics from the Dreyfus Affair to the Occupation,
theater from music halls to movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulgarian-born man of letters Elias Canetti (1905-1994) is known
today, to those who know him at all, for his 1935 novel
``Auto-da-Fe.'' But Canetti, who spent much of his adult life in
Britain, was also an indefatigable memoirist whose acquaintances
among the intellectual elite were legion. His three memoirs, ``The
Tongue Set Free,'' ``The Torch in My Ear'' and ``The Play of the
Eyes,'' are collected in ``The Memoirs of Elias Canetti'' (Farrar,
Straus &AMP; Giroux, $40). Reviewer George Scialabba wrote, ``It will
surely take its place . . . among the century's greatest
autobiographies.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a book as unusual and beguiling as Bayley's:
``Berryman's Shakespeare: Essays, Letters, and Other Writings by
John Berryman,'' edited by John Haffenden (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$35). The American poet John Berryman, who died in 1972, was a
great lover of the playwright, and wrote about and taught
Shakespeare vividly throughout his career. There have been
thousands of books about the poet of Avon, of course, and the
experts may not regard this one as essential. It is something of a
grab bag (it includes the parts of a never-finished biography);
still, in its treatments of various plays and of points of
scholarly controversy, it gives the double pleasure of encountering
a brilliant, passionate mind savoring the art of another brilliant
and passionate mind. In his Globe review, William Pritchard wrote
of ``this extraordinary volume'': It's the ``imaginative excess in
Berryman's criticism _ his refusal, like Shakespeare, to be a
`sensible' writer _ that gives this rich collection permanent
value.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Mehegan is the book editor of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1422EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
