<HEADER>
A0730 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-STERN-BOS &LR;      12-06 1653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-STERN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISAAC STERN GETS READY FOR THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The life-loving violinist Isaac Stern has confidently entitled
his new autobiography ``My First 79 Years.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was in town a couple of weeks ago to do some musical
coaching at Harvard, Stern came to lunch to talk about his book
(published by Knopf) and the life in music that it records. And he
made a joke about the title. ``My wife came up with the title we
used _ my own idea was `Have Mouth . . . Will Talk.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For all of his cheerfulness, the book ends on a note of
uncertainty. Some of his playing in recent seasons has distressed
the violinist as much as it has troubled his admirers; the cause,
he explains, is arthritis in both hands and carpal-tunnel syndrome.
At the time of writing, he was planning a surgical intervention and
hoping for the regeneration of both musicles and nerves. ```Should
this happen, I will have regained the physical and musical control
with which I can live proudly, and will be able to continue playing
chamber music with friends and to give an occasional solo
performance. By the time this book appears, I should have the
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Stern was tucking into his ostrich burger (this was
Cambridge), he could cheerfully report that the surgery had
successfully taken place. ``I am working every day and analyzing
myself _ it's fun, and I'm having a good time figuring out how I
did things I never had to think about. The hand and the bow arm are
coming back, and I am determined to be on the stage for a concert
in Beijing Nov. 19 that will celebrate the 20th anniversary of the
filming of the documentary about my first trip to China, `From Mao
to Mozart.' I will play the Beethoven Triple Concerto with the
young cellist from the movie, who has grown up, and my son David
will conduct. Later in the season I will play chamber music
concerts in several cities with my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The twice divorced Stern remarried in 1996, and seems a very
happy man today. The once portly Stern has lost a great deal of
weight, and attacks every conversational subject with vigor. His
book, written in collaboration with Chaim Potok, is entertaining,
informative, thoughtful, generous, and dignified; he didn't write
it to settle old scores, and its primary virtue is honesty.
Conductor George Szell once told Stern that if he hadn't spent so
much time doing other things and had just practiced more, he could
have been the greatest violinist in the world _ a remark reported,
as a matter-of-course, in Stern's book; a lesser man might have
omitted it.
</P>
<P>
   Stern says other people have wanted him to produce a book for
decades. He became interested himself a few years ago following
triple bypass surgery. ``I've been around young musicians for 40
years in what I like to call `encounters' rather than classes. And
over the years I've become exercised about what they don't know _
because nobody has bothered to tell them; for some young people,
history began six months ago. But without a knowledge of history,
you can't make sense of anything. You can't understand anything
about musical styles if you don't know why things happened _
without this knowledge you may be a good player, but you will not
be a musician. I wanted to write a book to tell where I came from
and how I got to be the kind of musician I am, and I do think I'm a
pretty good musician. I've been doing some radio shows to promote
this book, and the host usually interrupts the talking with music,
like the first recording I ever made, the C-Minor Sonata of
Beethoven, or the Mendelssohn Violin Concerto I recorded with
Eugene Ormandy. When I hear things like that, I think, `That guy
has talent.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Potok came into the picture at the suggestion of Stern's editor
at Knopf, Robert Gottlieb. ``I wanted to work on this book with
somebody I clicked with. When Chaim Potok was suggested, I asked
for copies of some of his books. I read them, and in them you heard
the characters speaking, not Potok; he has an extraordinary ear. So
the book is in my voice, not his _ but the organizational ability
and professional logic are not mine! I sound like an awkward kid
who grew up to be a slightly sarcastic guy with a giggle.''
</P>
<P>
   The book traces Stern's life from his youth in San Francisco,
through the difficult launch of his career, the wartime concerts
for soldiers, the years of triumph and traveling, the efforts to
save Carnegie Hall from the wrecker's ball, his three marriages _
Stern discusses his former wives with reticence and respect. What
makes the book significant are the themes that emerge, reappear,
and interact _ the importance of playing chamber music; what it
takes to be a soloist (``Two things are necessary for a life in
music: a clear idea of what you want to be, and the arrogance to
pursue it. You can't walk onstage and say to the public, `Excuse
me, I'm here.' You must believe in yourself and make immediately
clear to everyone, `I'm going to play. Listen!' ''); his love for
his family (two of his sons are conductors, and his daughter is a
rabbi); his affection and respect for colleagues; the relationship
of the violinist to the violin and, above all, to music.
</P>
<P>
   Stern calls chamber music the bedrock of his musicianship.
``Everything music is about appears in chamber music, in a very
distilled way. You have to understand structure. You have to learn
to listen vertically, and not just horizontally. You have to listen
to what your colleagues are doing and learn to make a concerted
effort. It is possible to play your instrument well without playing
music well. If you can play chamber music, you can play any other
music of any period or style. Eventually you learn how one note
leads to another, and idea leads to feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important characters in Stern's book is his
beloved violin, the Ysaye Guarnarius that once belonged to the
great Belgian violinist Eugene Ysaye and which Stern has owned
since 1965. ``It has strength, excitement, songfulness, masculinity
_ a thrust that resonates in my inner ear,'' he writes. It turns
out that one of the owners of the violin between Ysaye and Stern
was former Boston Symphony music director Charles Munch. ``He was a
lovely, lovely man. He sold the violin for $25,000 to someone who
sold it for $50,000 six months later. I played it for the first
time when it was still in the hands of a dealer and I fell in love
with it; it glowed. I like to say you don't play a violin; you
marry it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many artists today have been criticized for their crossover
activities. Stern himself is no fan of the recent film ``The Red
Violin,'' but writes entertainingly about being the hands for actor
John Garfield in the movie ``Humoresque''; he played on the
soundtrack of the film ``Fiddler on the Roof'' and became a popular
guest of the violin-playing comedian Jack Benny. ``If Jack had
played any better than he did, it wouldn't have been funny. But his
love for the fiddle shone through. It was easy for me to be on the
show because he loved the instrument and he loved music and he
respected artists, and he never made fun of those things. He became
a good and a close friend _ and he was less critical than anybody
else I ever knew in Hollywood; I never heard him say a bad word
about anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Stern displays an affection for the lively and
characteristic anecdote _ one particularly amusing example concerns
his debut with the Boston Symphony under Serge Koussevitzky in
1948. ``(S)uddenly Koussevitzky screamed, `EET EES NOT
FANTASTICAL!!' I didn't know what he meant; no one in the orchestra
knew what he meant. But at the performance that evening _ with the
concentraion, the ineffable wonder of playing a concert _ it was
fantastical.''
</P>
<P>
   But the book is also serious to the core, as Stern is, despite
all his affability of manner. The violinist is as aware as anyone
of widespread concern about the state of musical culture today but
he remains optimistic. ``I don't believe that any great art form,
any part of the history of man's accomplishments and civilization,
is as discardable as a used tissue. Music has seen times as
difficult as this. Today we can be overwhelmed by the flow of
information scudding across the computer or the television screen _
but it is predigested information, controlled information. The
excitement of discovery, of finding out something for yourself, of
thinking and feeling is almost gone. Yet what makes us human is the
ability to think and ask the question `why?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Stern warms to one of his favorite subjects, education. ``This
is a mantra, but who are we educating, about what, and how do you
do it. Teaching should be the highest paid and most honored
profession in the country, and it is not, yet the whole future of
this country lies in the minds of young people, who are the
greatest resource that we have. But we must realize and nurture
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today Stern lives with his wife Linda Reynolds Stern in
Connecticut and maintains a pied-a-terre in New York, where he can
keep a watchful eye on Carnegie Hall. Reviewing that story, one
wishes again that someone like Stern _ but is there anyone like
him? _ had become interested in the fate of the old Boston Opera
House, which was torn down in 1958, the same year Carnegie Hall
almost became rubble. Stern is particularly excited at the latest
development in Carnegie Hall, the construction of a 650-seat
auditorium in the space formerly occupied by the Carnegie Hall
cinema.
</P>
<P>
   And it's clear that he can't wait until his return to the
concert platform, where he has spent some of the richest hours of
his life. ``I have a weakness, I have to confess _ I love music.
George Bernard Shaw once remarked that the greatest thing in life
is to die young _ but to delay it as long as possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1423EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
