<SLUG> BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
  
 ART ADV.: Photos with SCI-VACCINES and AUTHOR-CULTURE, and a
graphic with SCI-VACCINES are being transmitted to NYT Photo
Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHENS (Argun, Russia) _ Russians and Chechens are
locked in a war that looks likely to become a bloody but chronic
conflict where each can claim victory regularly without ever
defeating the other. By David Filipov. 1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECT (Maputo, Mozambique) _ Two countries -- Namibia
and Mozambique -- hold elections this week. In Namibia lies a story
of the old African ways -- manipulated constitutions, unfair
elections, perpetual misrule. In Mozambique lies a story of Africa
emerging from colonialism, the cold war, and brutal civil war. By
Kurt Shillinger. 1380 words.
</P>
<P>
   QUEBEC-SEPARATISTS (Quebec City) _ Five years ago Canada seemed
a country about to rip itself apart as the restive province of
Quebec came within a few thousand votes of secession. Today,
Quebec's separatist movement lies in tatters, but Ottawa is
inexplicably baiting the bull. By Colin Nickerson. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CENTURY-EDISON (New York) _ If anyone deserves to be called the
most influential soul of the century _ the person who shaped the
century most broadly and deeply _ Thomas Alva Edison fits the bill.
By Fred Kaplan. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-ERRORS (Boston) _ Even as the National Institute of
Medicine was preparing its sobering study of hospital errors, the
medical community has been moving ahead in impressive ways to
recognize the crisis, and to redress it. By Larry Tye. 1000 words.
</P>
