<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, Dec. 7, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE _ PHOENIX, Ariz. _ Republican presidential contenders
meet to debate for the second time in as many weeks. This time,
though, the candidates will be allowed to question one another in
the CNN-sponsored forum in Sen. John McCain's home state. McCain,
who initially was going to skip Monday's debate, now will appear
via satellite. The debate comes as the latest poll puts Texas Gov.
George W. Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain in a dead heat for the
lead in New Hampshire. (Herman in Phoenix/Greenberger in Austin,
Austin American-Statesman). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Debate starts at 8 p.m. EDT. ETA on wire 10-10:15 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: A write-through is planned for later editions.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WHAT _ PHOENIX, Ariz. _What the candidates said on various
topics. (Greenberger in Austin, Austin American-Statesman). 15.
ETA: 9:45 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ As mediated settlement talks continue
in the Microsoft antitrust case, the government issues its response
Monday afternoon to the ``findings of fact'' released last month by
the presiding judge. (Glass).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-AUDIT _ WASHINGTON _ Education Department officials
who have lost track of millions of dollars will be asked to explain
the problem and propose a cure at a House hearing Monday.
(Mollison, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   WHITEHOUSE-HOLIDAY _ WASHINGTON _ The White House unveils its
annual holiday decorations. (Dart, Cox News Service). 25. WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GRAHAM-HONDURAS _ Evangelist Franklin Graham holds press
conference to discuss details of his trip to Honduras to deliver
Xmas gifts to needy children. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-KILLINGS _ CIUDAD JUAREZ, Chihuahua _ Francisco
Alcanter's eyes searched for tourists coming over the international
bridge from El Paso. ``Taxi?'' he asked, jockeying with other cab
drivers for business. Alcanter has seen the news about Mexican and
U.S. officials digging for bodies at two ranches near Juarez, where
they believe victims of the city's long-running drug war are
buried. The latest headlines bother Alcanter, who remains skeptical
of reports of mass graves. ``The publicity, unfortunately, hurts a
lot of families,'' he said. ``The tourists listen to the news, and
they're afraid to come here.'' In the past few years, Juarez, a
blue-collar factory city of almost 2 million people, has been the
scene of more than any city's share of bad news. More than 200
women have been slain in Juarez since 1993, many of them young
factory workers abducted as they returned home from jobs in one of
the city's 330 maquiladoras, the U.S.-owned plants where Mexican
workers assemble products for the American market. The string of
killings, which many Juarez residents suspect are the work of one
or more serial killers, ha-- attracted worldwide attention. (Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. PLEASE NOTE:
SPORTS STORIES will have an E.T.A. of 9:30 P.M. If news, business
or features stories will move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
