<SLUG> BC-PENNY-FUTURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THERE A CHANGE IN STORE FOR THAT PESKY PENNY? NOT LIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Is there anything more forsaken these days than
the one-cent piece? Clerks ignore them, customers leave them on
counters and almost nobody ever stoops down to pick one off the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Penny'' candy costs as much as a nickel. Some places, such as
the Garden State Parkway toll road in New Jersey, won't even accept
the coin anymore.
</P>
<P>
   There are 114 billion pennies in circulation, yet last summer
the nation still managed to suffer one of the biggest penny
shortages in recent memory _ mainly because so many people kept
taking them home and dumping them in jars or giant water-cooler
bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Is the penny is pooped as currency?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely annoying,'' said Annie Bogue of Albany, who was
on a shopping trip recently at a suburban shopping center. ``It
takes too much time, I have to dig for it and I'd rather they just
round it off.''
</P>
<P>
   The penny, a word that comes from the British pence, dates to
1793, when the U.S. government began to mint the nation's money.
Previously, Spanish gold and silver coins made from conquistador
plunder were used.
</P>
<P>
   The penny has changed a bit since then, going from a 100 percent
copper coin with an image of Lady Liberty to a coin today that is
made of 97.5 percent zinc bearing the image of Abraham Lincoln.
More than 300 billion pennies have been minted in the past 200
years. In 1999, 10 million were made at a cost of three-fourths of
a cent per coin.
</P>
<P>
   Coins have been done away with before. The halfpenny, for
instance, lasted only until 1857 before the government decided it
was pretty useless.
</P>
<P>
   James C. Benfield, a Washington lobbyist who in the past has
fought for longer daylight-saving time and the $1 coin being
released next year, took part in a Congressional Banking Committee
hearing on the penny in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   It was the zinc industry that protested most, he said, afraid of
the business they would lose if the penny died out. Today, Benfield
still thinks the coin should be done away with, but in an election
year, he said, no politician would touch it.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he still easily touts the benefits of getting rid
of the coin, such as the way it would speed up cash-register lines
and free up space in register tills for the new $1 coin.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Weller, a spokesman for the group Americans for Common
Cents in Washington, gets paid _ although not in pennies _ to
defend the coin. His lobbying organization is funded mostly by the
zinc industry, although others also have interest in the penny's
survival. For instance, fund-raising organizations say they get
some of their money by penny donations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is,'' Weller said, ``what's the
alternative?''
</P>
<P>
   Simple, say members of anti-penny factions. Just round purchases
off to the nearest nickel. That's what some retailers already have
started doing.
</P>
<P>
   It's also important to consider that items could still be
priced, for instance, $19.99 instead of $20. It would only be the
final bill, not the price of each item, that would be rounded off.
And credit card or check purchases could still be made out down to
the nearest cent.
</P>
<P>
   Weller says there are other reasons to keep the penny around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of the transactions under $10 are done in
cash,'' he said. ``You can't start with the assumption that
(rounding off) will just even out over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important reason the penny may be here to stay
is that history shows that the American people _ who soundly
rejected the metric system, the Susan B. Anthony dollar coin and
the $2 bill _ don't react well to change. Especially changing
change.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Allen, manager of Off Broadway Shoes, said his Albany store
rarely uses coins because most purchases are done by check or
charge. However, he still thinks the penny is vital, if not
valuable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's still got a place in the world,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
