<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX CUTS NOT AT THE TOP OF VOTERS' PRIORITY LIST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For most political candidates, especially
Republicans, proposing tax cuts ranks right up at the top of the
``must do'' list, on the same level as waving the flag and
endorsing motherhood and apple pie.
</P>
<P>
   So it was inevitable that Republican presidential hopeful George
W. Bush was going to lay out a tax-cut plan of his own.
</P>
<P>
   And it should have been no surprise that he did so just before
his first nationally televised debate with the other GOP
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   With the race for New Hampshire's first-in-the-nation primary
tightening up and a lot of public attention focused on whether
Bush's much-anticipated debate debut would boost or cripple his
frontrunner status, he tried to generate some positive, pre-debate
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas governor and other avowed tax-fighters may be
missing the boat with many voters.
</P>
<P>
   Most people would like to see their taxes reduced, to be sure,
but taxes apparently aren't as burning an issue with most voters as
they seemingly are with the candidates, at least not this year.
</P>
<P>
   In a national telephone poll conducted Nov. 19-23 for The
Associated Press, only about one out of 12 respondents said that
taxes were the most important issue facing the country today.
</P>
<P>
   Education, Social Security, Medicare, the economy, the nation's
moral values and health care _ which Bush and most other
presidential candidates also are attempting to address in one form
or another _ were identified as much more important to most people.
</P>
<P>
   Education, chosen by one of every four respondents, was clearly
the top concern.
</P>
<P>
   Although the economy was chosen as an important issue by about
one of every six people surveyed, the AP concluded that Americans
have generally positive feelings about their own financial
situations. Forty percent of the respondents said they were better
off than they were four years ago, and about the same number said
their economic standing was unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The mostly positive feelings about the economy were the main
reason that taxes were such a low concern, the AP suggested, and
that is probably correct.
</P>
<P>
   But there may be other contributing factors.
</P>
<P>
   One is a fear that tax cuts may jeopardize important public
services, such as education and Social Security, which were high on
Americans' priority lists.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible reason for tax-cut burnout among the voters is
a stream of unfulfilled tax-reduction promises by office-seekers.
Perhaps the most infamous in recent years was the broken
``read-my-lips'' anti-tax pledge that contributed to the 1992
re-election defeat of former President Bush, the governor's father.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of thing that makes many people simply tune out
political promises.
</P>
<P>
   Still another possible explanation, which covers much of Gov.
Bush's tax record in Texas, involves tax reductions that are
enacted, as promised, but are virtually invisible to many
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   In campaign stops throughout the country, including the
nationally televised debate from New Hampshire, Bush has bragged
about signing the two largest tax cuts in Texas history _ about $3
billion worth, mostly targeted at school property taxes, during the
last two state budget periods.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did sign the tax relief bills, and many Texans did benefit
with lower taxes. But the effects have been uneven, and many other
Texans have actually seen their school taxes increase during Bush's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 law that raised the homestead exemption for school taxes
was more than eaten up in many school districts when local
officials raised tax rates and increased property appraisals.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature, with Bush's backing, enacted two more
tax-relief bills this past spring. One provided for a number of
consumer and business tax cuts and credits that will be significant
for some taxpayers but worth only pocket change to many others.
</P>
<P>
   A second law last spring again produced school property tax cuts
in some districts but not in others. Almost 400 school districts
actually raised their tax rates this year. My school taxes in
Austin increased _ again _ because the local school board raised
the tax rate to help keep up with heavy enrollment growth.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to rising property values, many Houston-area residents
also are wondering what became of their much ballyhooed tax
``cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The local tax increases weren't Bush's fault, and the governor
can argue, with some validity, that school taxes would have gone up
even more without the tax relief that he and the Legislature
provided.
</P>
<P>
   But if many people don't get excited while Bush and the other
presidential candidates claw each other over who's the biggest
tax-cutter, who can blame them?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
