<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-RICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS WIDE RECEIVER ISN'T CALLING IT QUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Jerry Rice, the most prolific wide receiver in NFL
history, intends to return to the struggling San Francisco 49ers
next year for his 16th season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm coming back next year no matter what,'' Rice, 37, said
Sunday after turning in his most productive game in more than a
year. ``I don't want to go out like this. ... We're going to turn
this around. This one game didn't make me make up my mind. I was
going to come back no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 44-30 loss to the Cincinnati Bengals, Rice caught nine
passes for 157 yards and two touchdowns, all season bests. It was
his first 100-yard receiving game of the year, helped along by a
55-yard touchdown catch in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Since returning from two major operations on his left knee in
1997, Rice has struggled to regain his form. While the left knee
has healed and gives him no problem, Rice had been troubled for
more than a year by an injury to his right knee that cannot be
corrected by surgery. Only time can heal the injury to the
posterior part of the knee.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rice has been an affable sort throughout what will be
his first losing season with the 49ers, he has chafed at what he
perceives as a reduced role with the team. The circumstances of
Sunday's game compelled the 49ers to pass, and Rice still has life
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``A win, that's the most important thing,'' he said. ``I don't
think I have to prove anything. I do enjoy opportunities, though. I
felt we had opportunities today but we didn't win. It looked pretty
good. We were very aggressive. What I liked about the situation is
we didn't panic. We came out, put some points on the board and made
it a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday's turn-back-the-clock game by Rice, it appeared as
though he had lost that dynamic quality that separated him from his
peers. There was speculation that the game against Cincinnati would
be his final season with the 49ers. But if he completes the season
with more games like Sunday's, there is no reason he shouldn't be
back in 2000. Rice is signed through 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's two touchdowns against the Bengals increased his ongoing
league-record total to 179 overall, 168 on receptions. It was the
65th 100-yard reception game of his career and his 36th
multiple-touchdown game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
