<HEADER>
A0840 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-POTTER-ESSAY-1200(2TA     12-06 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTTER-ESSAY-1200(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DEFENSE OF HARRY POTTER AND POKEMON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to think about Destiny when you're worried about what
the construction on I-30 is going to do to your commute home. It's
impossible to ponder your ultimate fate when you're trying to find
wet towels for your child's sudden, inexplicable bloody nose.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that most of us don't contemplate Destiny on a
daily basis. We're too busy with the details of life _ pinballing
between relationships and work, from crisis to crisis. We live on
diversions. We live the unstudied life. This is the world of most
grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not where kids live.
</P>
<P>
   Kids live in a world of big-picture possibilities and terrors,
where the question of the day, every day, is who or what will I
``be''? They live in a world that's part fantasy. And for that
world they need heroes and role models.
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly why I love Harry Potter and Pokemon.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a popular opinion _ at least among the over-12 set.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter (a kid-lit protagonist), and Pokemon (a multimedia
phenomenon) are taking a beating these days as they stand at the
very top of the heap of children's popular culture. Kids,
obviously, love them, but mobs of vocal adults question whether the
pop phenoms are actually, well, evil.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the cover of ``Time'' magazine bannered Pokemon
as an ``addiction'' for kids (Pokemon being the collective
Nintendo-spawned assortment of Game Boy games, TV shows, trading
cards, toys and feature films all centering on a boy named Ash and
his adventures in a world filled with magical pocket monsters). The
statement was followed by the rhetorical nail-biter: ``Is it bad
for them?'' A recent story in ``Slate,'' an e-mag, noted that
across the nation, Pokemon has also ``spawned the usual
fundamentalist protests: One Colorado preacher made kids in his
congregation watch as he torched Pokemon cards and chopped a
Pokemon toy with his sword.'' Sayonara, Ash. Goodbye, Pikachu.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Harry Potter, the fictional 11-year-old apprentice
wizard who is the central character in J.K. Rowling's three
national bestsellers, who has taken the most recent public licking.
A story in the Fort Worth Star-Telegram last week reported that
Harry has been banned from several Tarrant County schools whose
educators question whether the books' references to wizardry and
witchcraft are appropriate for children. Teachers at Colleyville
Elementary School were told not to read the books in class or
recommend them for their students. An elementary library aide at
Fort Worth Christian, a private school in North Richland Hills
where the books are also banned, was strident in her Harry
harassment: ``We just don't have anything to do with that. You have
some children who are so prone to those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm not sure exactly what she meant by ``those things.''
Perhaps the kids in North Richland Hills think Harry Potter is real
and they are _ to be like Harry _ riding around on Nimbus 2000
broomsticks and practicing Defense against the Dark Arts duels.
Maybe they're even throwing around Pokeballs from Toys R Us and
hoping little monsters will pop out and battle each other.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't think so. I suspect kids in North Richland Hills and
elsewhere just want a good story.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a good story.
</P>
<P>
   Harry's 12 and he's scared.
</P>
<P>
   It's been two years since he learned his true identity _ that he
is a wizard and that his parents were magicians who were killed by
the evil wizard Lord Voldemort. Voldemort had tried to kill baby
Harry, too, but failed. The encounter left only a jagged scar on
Harry's forehead.
</P>
<P>
   Now Harry is in his second year at Hogwarts School of Witchcraft
and Wizardry. A series of harrowing adventures have led him to
understand that he, indeed, has great power. But he can't help but
wonder: Is it power for good _ or evil? What is his Destiny?
</P>
<P>
   The torturous soul-searching began when Harry arrived at
Hogwarts, and the Sorting Hat _ which places students into four
sort-of fraternities _ said Harry would do well in Slytherin, the
house founded by a once-great wizard who later turned to the Dark
Arts. It was the house Voldemort was in.
</P>
<P>
   Harry now brings his fears that he is Slytherin's rightful heir
to Dumbledore, the school headmaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the Sorting Hat) only put me in Gryffindor,'' said Harry
in a defeated voice, ``because I asked not to go in Slytherin.
...''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Exactly,' '' said Dumbledore, beaming once more. `` `Which
makes you very ``different'' from Tom Riddle (aka Voldemort). It is
our choices, Harry, that show us what we truly are, far more than
our abilities.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very theological,'' says Ulrich Knopflmacher, a
professor of English at Princeton University, about the scene from
``Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets.'' Knopflmacher teaches
children's literature. He also has a 9-year-old son who devoured
the Harry Potter books and is a Pokemaniac.
</P>
<P>
   Knopflmacher, expounding on Destiny in children's literature,
begins with a little history lesson about fairy tales. The word
``fairy'' derives from the Latin ``fatum,'' which means that which
has been spoken, or fate. Fairies were once the equivalent to the
Greek fates who spun the destinies of people.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Embedded in the genre of fairy tales is the whole question of
destiny,'' Knopflmacher says. In many fairy tales, like ``Sleeping
Beauty,'' there's a christening of a child, which both the good
fairy and the bad fairy attend, each trying to affect the child's
fate.
</P>
<P>
   Knopflmacher says the Texas educators who've banned Harry Potter
come from a long tradition. ``They're equating this modern version
of a fairy tale with witchcraft. That goes back to the Puritans.
The distrust of fairy tales as being pagan goes back a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of gnomes and sprites and other pagan spirits living in
Druid forests and affecting the futures of people apparently
repelled the leaders of Christian churches _ just as the idea of
Harry, and Ash and his magic monsters, are repelling groups of
grown-ups now _ because they seem anti-theological.
</P>
<P>
   The irony, Knopflmacher points out, is that the opposite is
true. He sees a parallel with George McDonald, an English clergyman
who wrote fantastic allegorical tales about animals, tales for
which he was defrocked. Later generations, though, were able to see
the tales as moral tales that could indeed serve ``a Christian
providential order.''
</P>
<P>
   Knopflmacher says it's a ``real sort of know-nothing attitude to
dismiss this'' (Harry Potter books).
</P>
<P>
   ``Now McDonald is sold in Christian bookstores,'' Knopflmacher
says. ``The same is going to happen with Harry Potter.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's another story. My son Jack, who's 9, is watching Pokemon
on TV. Ash has entered the great Pokemon League tournament. In
front of a stadium packed with fans, including his mom and his
mentor, Professor Oak, Ash goes into battle against a kid named
Richard.
</P>
<P>
   The Pokemon battle is one of strength and courage. It's not
about destroying an enemy _ in fact, the pocket monsters that fight
cannot be killed. The relationship between a trainer and his or her
Pokemon is a symbiotic friendship. Only if the trainer and Pokemon
trust each other and teach each other can both evolve, or grow.
</P>
<P>
   Ash fights hard _ and loses.
</P>
<P>
   My son is in shock.
</P>
<P>
   Ash is in shock, too. He flees the tournament, hating Richard.
</P>
<P>
   But then Richard loses the next round of battles. To Ash's
surprise, Richard isn't bitter. He says losing has taught him some
lessons and will help him be a Pokemon master some day.
</P>
<P>
   The two kids promise each other they're going to train harder.
They will be Pokemon masters one day! The theme song cues up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanna be the very best, like no one ever was ... Pokemon,
It's you and me, I know it's my destiny, Pokemon, You're my best
friend, in a world we must defend, Pokemon, our hearts so true, our
courage will pull us through, You teach me and I'll teach you,
Pokemon. ...''
</P>
<P>
   I think it's kinda sweet, and I look at my son.
</P>
<P>
   He's crying.
</P>
<P>
   The good stories I've read lately _ about both Harry Potter and
Pokemon _ talk about the late, controversial child psychologist
Bruno Bettelheim. Bettelheim believed that children live with great
terrors and that it is the primal terror in fairy tales that
children relate to. It is through the tale's resolution that kids
learn to work out their own problems.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, in fairy tales _ like Harry Potter and Pokemon _
children place themselves in the hero's shoes and find answers to
their own big picture _ questions such as Who or what will I
``be''?
</P>
<P>
   Alongside Ash and Harry, safe within their respective fantasy
worlds, our children are engaged in important, life-defining work.
They are confronting their Destiny.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
