<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MONACO-SAFRA-510&AMP;ADD-     12-06 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONACO-SAFRA-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE IN MONACO SAY SAFRA'S NURSE ADMITS SETTING FATAL FIRE
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Will be updated.) 
 (nk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ An American nurse employed by Edmond Safra admitted
Monday that he set the fire that killed the billionaire banker in
his luxury penthouse in Monte Carlo last Friday, Monaco's chief
prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Daniel Serdet, said the nurse, Ted Maher, 41,
from Dutchess County, N.Y., had concocted the story that the
harbor-side apartment was under attack by two hooded men with
knives and then set fire to a wastebasket in an effort to draw
attention to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Maher was ``jealous'' of Safra's other seven nurses, one of whom
died with Safra in a bathroom where they had taken refuge,
believing there were intruders in the apartment, the prosecutor
said. By claiming to have fought off the attackers, Maher hoped to
win approval, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to be a hero,'' Serdet said.
</P>
<P>
   The confession ended days of speculation over the events that
took place in the pre-dawn hours atop one of the principality's
most secure buildings, home to three different bank offices.
</P>
<P>
   Safra's death had stunned the rarified world of international
investment he had been part of for decades and triggered numerous
theories about why he might have been a target for attack.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers around the world speculated that Safra, who without
formal education built an international banking empire, might have
been killed because of his many business dealings, including those
with Russian investors.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of his death was also particularly poignant. Safra,
who suffered from Parkinson's disease, was on the verge of
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   A deal to sell his businesses, including the Republic National
Bank of New York, which would have brought him about $2.65 billion,
is in its final stages.
</P>
<P>
   But French investigators say there was no complicated intrigue:
Maher acted alone inspired, in part, by a dispute with another
nurse.
</P>
<P>
   After starting the fire and slashing himself twice with his own
switchblade, once in the thigh, and once in the stomach, Maher went
downstairs to get the concierge to call the police and firefighters
to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Serdet said Maher had not expected to kill anyone. Indeed,
investigating officials said on Saturday that Safra and the nurse
who died with him, Vivienne Torrent, could have escaped.
</P>
<P>
   But Safra, terrified that assailants were after him, refused to
leave the bathroom even when police and firefighters arrived on the
scene and his wife, Lily, talking to him by cell phone, tried to
coax him out.
</P>
<P>
   Both Safra and Ms. Torrent, 52, died of asphyxiation.
</P>
<P>
   Serdet said Maher would face a charge of arson without intent to
kill, which could bring him a life sentence. But the prosecutor
also said that first, Maher would be examined by psychiatrists to
determine his competence to stand trial. He said Maher was
apparently highly agitated and taking medication at the time of the
fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was psychologically fragile and under the influence of
medication,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maher's confession was announced on the day that Safra was
buried in Geneva.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At first the authorities, basing their accounts on Maher's
initial testimony, said that two men wearing hoods and brandishing
knives had burst into an infirmary that had recently been built for
Safra on the penthouse level.
</P>
<P>
   The pink stucco building sits along one of Monaco's most
gracious avenues, with views of a yacht-filled harbor and the
Monaco royal family palace. Safra, who shunned publicity, had homes
in New York, Paris, Geneva and a villa nearby on the French Riviera
in Villefranche-sur-Mer.
</P>
<P>
   But he spent a lot of time in Monaco, which offers the very rich
a income-tax-free haven. He apparently felt so safe there that he
did not have his bodyguards stay the night with him when he slept
in Monaco.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated questioning of Maher, who had been taken to Princess
Grace Hospital in Monaco to be treated for the wounds, produced
vague and conflicting accounts of the events, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday police officials said they had no evidence to
corroborate Maher's story. They continued to say they were unsure
how anyone could have gained access to the tightly secured
building.
</P>
<P>
   Late on Sunday night, the police formally put Maher under guard.
Serdet said that Maher confessed to setting the fire Monday
morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1557EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
