<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0846 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a BC-WATCH-YOUR-STEP-(NEW-     12-06 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATCH-YOUR-STEP-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCH HOW YOU WALK, YOU MAY INCRIMINATE YOURSELF  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., DEC. 6, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By DUNCAN GRAHAM-ROWE  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're planning a bank heist, it might be a good idea to
start practicing silly walks. A new security system being developed
in Britain can identify individuals by the unique way in which they
walk.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike faces and irises, someone's gait can be spotted from a
great distance with low-resolution cameras and so be observed from
just about any angle. It is also very difficult to mask, says Mark
Nixon, a computer scientist at London's Southampton University's
Image, Speech and Intelligent Systems group.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people rob banks they tend to wear motorbike helmets or
some form of disguise,'' he explains. But you can't disguise your
walk without drawing attention to yourself or impeding your escape.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by highly publicized crimes where the suspects were
caught on video but there were no clear shots of their faces, Nixon
decided to find out whether a person's gait could be just as
telling as a mugshot. He and his colleagues have so far adopted two
approaches to the problem, with promising results from both.
</P>
<P>
   The first analyzes the pendulumlike motion of the leg joints,
after extracting a person's silhouette from an image sequence. It
then measures the deviation of each joint movement from this simple
harmonic motion. According to Nixon, this works because people tend
to deviate in their own very characteristic ways.
</P>
<P>
   The second approach, published this month, uses a data-based
technique. This extracts particular features of a person's gait,
such as the shape and angular velocity of a limb, or the length of
a joint.
</P>
<P>
   At present, both techniques have their drawbacks. The pendulum
approach is not as effective as the data-based technique, but the
latter is poor at ignoring flapping clothing, such as skirts, when
analyzing a gait. Funding permitting, the Southampton team say it
would take them six months to develop an analysis system that draws
on the strengths of both systems.
</P>
<P>
   Although the initial trials involved just 10 subjects, Nixon
says the system proved accurate, and he is confident that they are
on the right track. Another use, Nixon says, could be to spot
female shoplifters who pretend to be pregnant and walk out with a
bellyful of merchandise. By using gait recognition, he says, you
could spot a genuinely pregnant woman easily, as the fetus's head
pushing down on their pelvis affects the way they walk.
</P>
<P>
   The Southampton project has already attracted the interest of
high street retailer Marks &AMP; Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1600EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0851 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-WTO-POKEMON-ASAHI-NYT     12-06 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-POKEMON-ASAHI-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POKEMON MELLOWS SEATTLE, WTO HEATS IT UP  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 775-word ``separate buy'' article is from the Asahi News
Service.)  
  
 (EDITORS: Get your news from Japan and the Pacific Rim straight
from the source _ the Asahi News Service. Its Monday through Friday
report of news, features and distinctive analysis is culled from
The Asahi Shimbun, Japan's foremost newspaper, renowned for its
integrity and thoroughness (with a daily circulation is 12
million.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By YOICHI FUNABASHI  
 c.1999 Asahi News Service  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I went into a movie theater called Pacific Place on a Seattle
main street to see ``Pokemon: The First Movie.'' It was shortly
after 3 p.m. on a weekday and the only other person in the audience
was an elderly woman.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered reading that when the movie was released on the
U.S. mainland two weeks ago, it raked in $32 million during that
weekend alone, making it a smash hit. The empty theater threw me
off balance.
</P>
<P>
   Pikachu, the leading Pokemon character, was cute. The way all
the characters exhibit fine teamwork reminded me of ``Doraemon,''
another popular Japanese animation series. Pokemon is unmistakably
Japanese, I kept saying in my mind.
</P>
<P>
   Battles over power and identity between Pokemons and humans,
Pokemon originals and clones and clones and humans develop on the
screen. It occurred to me that Pokemon is a product of the age of
genetic engineering.
</P>
<P>
   I heard that some Americans are saying the movie stimulates an
impulse to destroy and fight. Ironically, that sounds like the kind
of foreign criticism that is usually targeted at Hollywood movies.
</P>
<P>
   When I left the theater, I found myself one block away from the
Washington State Convention and Trade Center, the venue for the
ministerial meeting of the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   I was immediately surrounded by demonstrators chanting ``Save
the dolphin, save the giant turtle.'' Under current fishing
methods, dolphins and turtles get caught in fishing nets and die,
the demonstrators said, and they criticized the WTO for doing
nothing to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conserve forests, cut down WTO''...``Wash down
technology''...``Trade must be clean, green and fair''...``Cultural
diversity is needed.'' These were some of the slogans I saw on the
placards carried by the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   One of the signs showed a skull and crossbones under the words
genetic engineering. The criticism was targeted at the WTO's ruling
against a European Union decision to ban imports of U.S. beef from
cattle raised with growth hormones.
</P>
<P>
   Although biotechnology has advanced rapidly, not all the
information about food safety in the biotechnological ``black box''
has been made available to the public. That has given rise to
distrust and fear.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is also home to Microsoft Corp., which has become a
symbol of globalization.
</P>
<P>
   The company is running a campaign to abolish tariffs on
electronic commerce, but I saw no signs of protest against
Microsoft. Even the nongovernmental organizations that protested in
Seattle cannot do away with e-mail. The globalization of
information has become part of everyday life and is to the benefit
of the public.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced globalization leads to stronger calls for diversity in
cultures. It has led to wariness among the economically weak that
they might be forced to become clones of the economically strong.
Globalization raises uncertainty about cultural identity and unease
about external forces that are beyond the control of citizens.
</P>
<P>
   At the opening of the new round of WTO negotiations, a number of
countries, including France, raised objections to the trend of
making culture a part of trade. They assert that culture, like
agriculture, which some nations are arguing is a cultural and
social asset as well as having economic value, serves many
functions.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered the time I went to Punta del Este in Uruguay to
cover the Uruguay round of WTO talks, which started in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the hotel where I stayed did not have a fax
machine. It did not have English-language newspapers, either. There
were no demonstrators. Microsoft and e-commerce were unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Uruguay round got off the ground, many Asian and Latin
American countries have enjoyed the benefits of world trade and
have taken off economically one after another. However, there are
still countless people around the world that have been left behind.
</P>
<P>
   WTO director-general Mike Moore pleaded with the participants to
think about their poor brothers and sisters across the world and
stressed the importance of exports to bring them prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rubens Ricupero, secretary-general of the United
Nations Conference on Trade and Development, warned that unless the
WTO squarely deals with the difficult issues raised by
globalization, it could turn into a white elephant.
</P>
<P>
   As trade plays an increasingly important role in the development
and economic welfare of countries, both expectations of and
objections to globalization will become stronger.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO has become the setting for a battle royal over
globalization.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon in the Seattle movie theater, Pikachu created a
mellow ambience. Unfortunately, that does not seem to be the
prevailing mood at the WTO meeting. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Yoichi Funabashi is an Asahi Shimbun senior staff
writer and foreign affairs columnist.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 775-word article from the Asahi News Service, it
must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1604EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0852 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-WTO-POKEMON-ASAHI-NYT     12-06 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-POKEMON-ASAHI-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POKEMON MELLOWS SEATTLE, WTO HEATS IT UP  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 775-word ``separate buy'' article is from the Asahi News
Service.)  
  
