<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0861 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-HEART-SURGERY-TEX     12-06 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-SURGERY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INNOVATIVE BEATING-HEART SURGERY GIVES MAN NEW LEASE ON LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLOTTE HUFF 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Dr. Manucher Nazarian had performed the
still-uncommon form of bypass surgery more than 400 times, but this
patient made him nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin Knudson, alert despite two heart attacks, was 92 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   Twice, Nazarian refused to do the surgery. The ethics committee
at Harris Methodist Fort Worth hospital also discussed the case.
</P>
<P>
   Knudson's cardiologist, however, pushed for the procedure _
informally dubbed ``beating-heart'' surgery _ arguing that it
offered the Fort Worth man his best chance at quality life in his
final years.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery, which does not use a heart-lung machine, is
relatively new and not without controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew that if he was going to die, he would rather die in
combat for his life,'' said the cardiologist, Dr. Georgina
Sehapayak.
</P>
<P>
   Once other medical options had been exhausted, Nazarian agreed;
he performed the double bypass Nov. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, Knudson left All Saints Medical Center with his
85-year-old wife, Scharlene, and returned to their home on the
city's east side. His mobility is still limited, but he hopes to
return soon to the thick garden of mums that he planted several
months before he collapsed Oct. 25.
</P>
<P>
   If the surgery ``bought a few more good years,'' that would be
enough, Knudson said, a twinkle in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Given Knudson's age, Nazarian said he would not have attempted a
traditional bypass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chance of a stroke for him would have been exceedingly
high,'' Nazarian said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, bypass surgery requires stopping the heart so that
the organ's beating doesn't disrupt the delicate sewing necessary
to graft the new blood vessels in place. Meanwhile, the patient's
blood is pumped through a heart-lung machine so that it receives
sufficient oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   In beating-heart surgery, no heart-lung machine is required
because only a small area of the heart is stabilized while the new
vessel is grafted.
</P>
<P>
   Some heart surgeons haven't tried the new procedure, saying more
time and research are needed to determine its benefits. It's still
unclear, for example, how long bypasses sewn on in beating-heart
surgery will hold up.
</P>
<P>
   The American Heart Association has not taken a formal position
on the procedure pending more study.
</P>
<P>
   Some physicians, including Nazarian, say beating-heart surgery
shows potential to reduce problems with lung function, brain
function and with other difficulties that sometimes follow use of a
heart-lung machine.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Carter, a Euless, Texas-based heart surgeon who
estimates he uses the beating-heart procedure in 40 percent of his
bypass surgeries, said patients also appear to recover faster if
they haven't been exposed to the machine.
</P>
<P>
   The machine, Carter said, can make ``the patient feel like
they've had the flu for the next six to eight weeks, just because
of the trauma to the body.''
</P>
<P>
   The benefits may be more significant for patients who, because
of age or other organ damage, may be poor candidates for the
traditional bypass, said Fort Worth heart surgeon Al Yurvati,
president of the heart association's Fort Worth division.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, an estimated 600,000 Americans undergo bypass
surgery, which is designed to reroute blood around clogged arteries
by grafting on new ones to improve blood flow.
</P>
<P>
   Nazarian, considered to be a pioneer of the procedure in Fort
Worth, said better technology has made the beating-heart approach
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The device he uses, one of several on the market, resembles a
two-pronged fork.
</P>
<P>
   The prongs press down around the artery, immobilizing an area
about the size of a silver dollar. That area beats minimally,
Nazarian said, while the rest of the heart continues to thump
normally.
</P>
<P>
   At a medical conference earlier this year, Nazarian presented
the results of bypass surgery on 324 patients, half of whom had
undergone beating-heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the two approaches resulted in death 6 percent of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   But the beating-heart approach reduced the need for blood
transfusions from 25 percent to 10 percent, according to Nazarian's
data. And fewer patients spent extended post-surgical time on the
ventilator; 12 percent of the traditional bypass patients spent at
least four days, compared with 2 percent of the beating-heart
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Until he collapsed in October, Knudson had gone years without
seeing a doctor. He didn't swallow anything stronger than a
multivitamin each morning.
</P>
<P>
   He was raking leaves under a large pecan tree in his back yard
when the heart attack occurred. His wife became concerned when he
didn't come in, as was his habit, to watch ``The Price Is Right,''
and then she saw a neighbor sprinting down the street for help.
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics arrived within minutes and took Knudson to Harris
Methodist Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor on duty in the emergency room scared the daylights
out of me,'' Scharlene Knudson said. ``He said he was very critical
and he probably wouldn't leave there alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Knudson and his family, as well as two of his doctors, talked
candidly. The hospital's ethicist got involved, and at one point,
the case was taken before the ethics committee.
</P>
<P>
   Harris officials, citing confidentiality, wouldn't say why the
case was sent to the ethics committee.
</P>
<P>
   Nazarian said he initially had concerns about doing such an
aggressive procedure on someone of Knudson's advanced age, without
first exploring other options.
</P>
<P>
   But without the surgery, Knudson probably would not have been
able to leave the hospital, Sehapayak said. When a second heart
attack occurred a couple of days after the first, it became clear
that Knudson was vulnerable to additional attacks if he wasn't kept
on strong intravenous medication, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Before deciding on the beating-heart surgery, Nazarian discussed
it with Knudson and his extended family, grandson Craig Lehew said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we said he's lived an active life all of his
life,'' said Lehew, 28. ``We wanted him to be able to go back home
and go back into his garden again.''
</P>
<P>
   So Knudson was transferred for surgery to All Saints, where
Nazarian has done the bulk of his beating-heart cases.
</P>
<P>
   Just three days before the operation, the couple had celebrated
their 62nd wedding anniversary with a cake, courtesy of the nurses
at Harris.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery took less than an hour and a half, Scharlene Knudson
said, still beaming weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `The Good Lord wasn't through with you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
