A0869 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-DIET-WEB-SITES-NY     12-06 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DIET-WEB-SITES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSING POUNDS BY SURFING, ON THE WEB  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID RAMPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was probably inevitable that the World Wide Web would bloom
with sites for dieters. But to the surprise of professional
dietitians, many of these sites have turned out to be not only
popular but effective.
</P>
<P>
   From fee-based ventures like eDiets.com to free ones like
Cyberdiet.com, a cornucopia of sites has sprung up in the last year
or two to provide nutrition and diet advice. Many offer services
that are otherwise found through private dietitians or diet
companies like Weight Watchers, including personalized feedback and
support from a group of fellow dieters.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the first studies of the effectiveness of online
dieting, preliminary research at Brown University suggests that
``the Internet seems to be a great vehicle for what has proven
successful in face-to-face programs,'' in the words of the
principal researcher, Deborah Tate, a graduate student completing
her doctorate in clinical psychology.
</P>
<P>
   The study, to be completed early next year, compared two groups
of overweight people. Members of the first group, who were given
Web-based information about dieting, lost an average of 3 pounds in
the first 12 weeks of the program. But members of another group
that interacted on the Internet _ who reported on their meals and
exercise, had questions answered, got e-mail from professionals and
posted messages on bulletin boards _ lost 9 pounds in the 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Additional information alone, while helpful, doesn't appear to
be enough,'' Ms. Tate said.
</P>
<P>
   Felicia Busch, a dietitian in St. Paul, Minn., who is a
spokeswoman for the American Dietetic Association, an 82-year-old
organization of food and nutrition professionals, says online
dieting offers easy access to information and support from the
privacy of the dieter's home or office.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Dodd, a former president of the association, is on an
advisory committee that helps rate about 200 online nutrition sites
for the Tufts University School of Nutrition. The service, itself
on the Web at www.navigator.tufts.edu, gives high marks to a number
of dieting sites. For example, it calls Cyberdiet.com ``an oasis of
sane, fun and well-presented nutrition information.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Busch and Ms. Dodd say that in some cases there is no
substitute for an individual counselor, who can give personalized
recommendations and take a more exact diet history than might be
possible on the Web, and who may be covered by insurance.
</P>
<P>
   A dieter with special needs ``may be flirting with danger
online,'' Ms. Dodd said. Still, she added, Tufts' high-ranked sites
``are a really good starting point'' and provide quick answers to
dieting questions.
</P>
<P>
   The trend to online information and advice comes at a time when
Americans are heavier than ever. ``People are driving 10 minutes to
find a spot in front of the health club so they don't have to walk
too far,'' Ms. Busch said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most aggressive commercial sites, eDiets.com, has
offered nutrition, exercise and motivation advice for two years. It
is fairly typical of the online diets.
</P>
<P>
   New users, who sign up for $70, are asked to fill out a simple
profile, on topics like binge eating, desired weight loss and
amount of exercise they get. That results in a computer-generated
schedule for weight loss: a 12-week plan, with meal plans and
shopping lists, that is adjusted to reflect the diet's progress,
reported weekly.
</P>
<P>
   EDiets, based in Florida, has had about 50,000 paying customers
in two years, the company says. Its chairman, David Humble, said he
turned to the Net when he discovered that it offered an opportunity
``to change lifestyle as opposed to a quick diet that inevitably
doesn't work in the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has a dozen employees, including dietitians and
psychologists, and sends out free newsletters by e-mail to 700,000
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   EDiets offers ``the general supervision of the dietitian, but
not the one-on-one with a dietitian,'' Humble said, adding: ``But
also not the costs associated with that. Three months of
supervision online costs less probably than a single visit to a
dietitian off line.''
</P>
<P>
   The company says active participants report losing 1.8 pounds a
week; at that rate, members should reach a goal of losing 20 pounds
in three months, a period that dietitians say is long enough for
behavior changes to become ingrained, and for people to determine
why they had a problem in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Women from 25 to about 50 make up the largest group of users of
the site, but eDiets is also trying to develop special areas for
men, vegetarians and people with specialized diets. The company
says it tries to screen people whose health makes online dieting
unwise, including those with diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Cyberdiet.com, based in California, insists that it is not
primarily a diet program, because that ``means you are either on
something or off something,'' said Timi Gustafson, a co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in diets,'' he said. ``I believe in helping
people adopt a healthy lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyberdiet offers eight-week weight-loss programs, free, with
special menus, in four calorie ranges, modulated for diets those
who need to restrict their intakes of sodium, cholesterol, dairy or
other foods, and for people with problems like diabetes,
hypertension and heart disease. It also has a 12-week exercise
program, and workout drills.
</P>
<P>
   The free site was started by Ms. Gustafson, a registered
dietitian, and Cynthia Fink as something of a public service, and
was acquired this year by Mediconsult.com, which provides
information online for people affected directly or indirectly by
chronic illness.
</P>
<P>
   The site has lively message boards. One, for people trying to
lose 100 pounds or more, attracts 1,500 messages a week. It is so
popular that 40 of the dieters met in Chicago this summer to make
friends in person with people they had met online.
</P>
<P>
   Another site, eFit.com, offers 30-second video demonstrations of
exercises.
</P>
<P>
   For now, established weight-loss companies like Jenny Craig and
Weight Watchers are not jumping into the online market. Both
companies have Web sites, but they are mainly informational, used
to draw dieters to their established programs.
</P>
<P>
   But the success of their online competitors clearly has their
attention. Les Koll, senior vice president of marketing at Jenny
Craig, said of eDiets, ``We are watching them very closely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
