<HEADER>
A0874 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      12-06 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Vegetarian Dinosaurs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It may not do much for their reputations, but new research shows
that some dinosaurs may have had something in common with chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the United States, China, Mongolia and Japan,
examining the fossilized remains of 12 relatively small dinosaurs
from China, have discovered masses of mineral grains inside their
rib cages. The grains, the researchers write in the journal Nature,
may be the remnants of gizzards, which the creatures may have used
to grind up plant matter much as poultry and other plant-eating
birds do today.
</P>
<P>
   The dinosaurs, which date to the Upper Cretaceous period, about
70 million years ago, resemble ostriches, with long legs, small
heads and toothless beaks. While they have some birdlike features,
they are considered nonavian; they are called ornithomimids, or
bird mimickers, and belong to the large group of two-legged
dinosaurs known as theropods (the most famous member of which is T.
rex).
</P>
<P>
   Just what ornithomimids ate has long been a subject of debate.
The presence of a gizzard and lack of teeth both point to this
variety, at least, as eating plants, not meat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Good News on a Pollutant &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Acid rain brought on by sulfur emissions from industrial
smokestacks has been a cause of much concern in the Northeast, and
rightly so. But a new analysis of sulfur emissions worldwide shows
that the United States, along with parts of Europe and Russia, has
generally stabilized its emissions over the last two decades. A
growing problem, however, exists in China, which now leads the
world in the amount of sulfur put into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by a professor at Washington University in St. Louis
and published in the journal Atmospheric Environment, analyzed oil
and coal consumption and metal smelting activity, all contributors
to sulfur emissions, from 1850 to 1990. The results show emissions
in the United States declining since the 1970s, when new pollution
laws took effect and many factories and power plants were forced to
switch from burning high-sulfur coal to low-sulfur coal, oil or
gas. Industries in the former Soviet Union and some European
countries have also switched to natural gas from coal.
</P>
<P>
   But in China, which has abundant supplies of high-sulfur coal
feeding a rapidly growing industrial economy, sulfur emissions have
increased markedly. In 1990, China emitted 22 million metric tons
of sulfur, compared with 15 million by the United States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the increase in emissions has come an increase in
complaints about acid rain from China's Asian neighbors, similar to
the complaints of Northeastern states about sulfur pollution from
the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Genetically Altered Soil &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Genetically engineered corn has become very popular among
American farmers. About 20 percent of last year's crop was of the
modified variety, which exudes a toxin in the leaves and pollen
that kills caterpillars and other pests that attack the plant above
ground. But what, if anything, happens in the soil?
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at New York University have discovered that the
toxin, known as Bt because the genes that produce it come from a
bacterium, Bacillus thuringiensis, is exuded from the roots of the
corn plant, too. In fact, the researchers found, about the same
amount of Bt toxin enters the soil through the roots as is
introduced from pollen that comes off during tasseling and from the
residue of stalks and leaves left behind after harvesting.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, writing in Nature, note that the toxin
apparently binds with soil and thus persists for long periods of
time _ at least 234 days, the longest time studied. As to whether
the presence of all that pesticide in the soil is good or bad, the
scientists were noncommitting further research is needed to
show whether it helps control harmful pest populations or wipes out
beneficial insects.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
