u a BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      12-06 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; TIMING: On Their Toes Can Be Risky &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No parent shells out the money for ballet class so a child can
turn out a flat-footed dancer, but keeping dancers off their toes
may not be such a bad thing, at least for a while.
</P>
<P>
   A new study suggests that going on point may lead to arthritis
of the ankle in ballet dancers. The research was presented last
week at a conference of the Radiological Society of North America.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers who go on point dance on the tips of their toes with the
aid of a special shoe. They often begin as young as 11 or 12. The
problem, said Dr. David C. Salonen, the Toronto radiologist who
conducted the study, is that the position puts great pressure on
the talonavicular joint, one of the three major joints to make up
the ankle.
</P>
<P>
   When researchers used magnetic resonance imaging to examine the
ankles of 11 female dancers with the National Ballet of Canada,
they found that all were stable and had full range of motion. But
arthritis was detected in many joints, including 18 percent of the
talonavicular ones.
</P>
<P>
   The findings should not deter children from studying dance, said
Salonen, whose own two young daughters study ballet. The message,
he said, is not ``Look out, moms: don't let your kids dance.''
</P>
<P>
   But the findings suggest that parents should hold off allowing
their children to go on point until later in their studies, he
said, and that students and professional dancers should consider
resting longer between performances _ much the way baseball
pitchers are used in rotation. ``There has to be a happy medium,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAFETY: Allaying Health Workers' Worst Fear &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The physical sensation is fleeting, but the emotional trauma can
linger for months. And in the worst cases, the physical harm can be
lifelong, or even fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Health care workers call it the needle stick, and for many it is
their greatest fear on the job, because one small slip could infect
them with HIV, hepatitis or similar causes of disease. Each year,
federal authorities estimate, there are 600,000 to 800,000 such
mistakes among the nation's 8 million health care workers, although
most do not result in infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a terrible ordeal,'' said Dr. Linda Rosenstock, director
of the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health.
</P>
<P>
   For medical workers, the greatest risk comes if they stick
themselves with a needle used on a patient with hepatitis B; the
chance of infection is as high as 30 percent. It is believed to be
much more difficult to acquire infections of AIDS or other forms of
hepatitis through needle sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Now the agency, part of the federal Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention, has issued guidelines meant to reduce the risk of
needle-stick injuries to health workers. Officials say they hope to
extend the success some institutions have already had in reducing
the incidents _ in some cases as much as 88 percent _ in medical
offices across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Although many devices already exist to reduce the risk,
Rosenstock said, they are not in widespread use. Only about 15
percent of hospitals, for example, are reported to use needles with
safety attachments.
</P>
<P>
   The institute is recommending that needles be eliminated
whenever possible. For intravenous treatment, for example, they can
be replaced with connectors that attach to each other with blunt or
valved connectors. When needles cannot be avoided, the agency
recommends using equipment with safety features, like shields.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations are available online, at www.cdc.gov/niosh.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIAGNOSIS: Better Gauge for Carpal Tunnel Problems &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, federal officials said the Clinton administration
might soon issue sweeping new rules for the workplace that could
help protect millions of Americans from repetitive strain injuries,
often associated with the heavy use of computers. Under the new
rules, employers with even a few cases of RSI will be required to
carry out full-scale ergonomic programs.
</P>
<P>
   Now a new study raises questions about the best way to diagnose
one of the best-known RSI diseases, carpal tunnel syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in a recent issue of the journal Muscle and
Nerve, found that variations in the results of the nerve-conduction
studies often used to make a finding of carpal tunnel are so
significant that there should be changes in how they are
interpreted.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Salerno, who conducted the study as an occupational
health student at the University of Michigan, says doctors now use
the nerve tests to give a yes or no answer to whether a patient has
carpal tunnel. It would be more useful, she said, for doctors to
use a system of categories like normal, equivocal, mild or definite
abnormality.
</P>
<P>
   In the conduction tests, doctors give a small jolt of
electricity to nerves in a patient's arm, then measure how long it
takes to reach the muscle. The problem, Salerno said, is that
several factors _ from skin temperature to the placement of the
electrodes that deliver the shock _ can affect the results.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIDE EFFECTS: Better Sex, After the Hysterectomy &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For many women who need to undergo hysterectomies, the anxiety
they feel is not just over the surgery to remove the uterus but
over a widespread belief about the procedure's aftermath: that
their sex lives will never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a study of 1,300 women by the University of Maryland
medical school may put that fear to rest. It reports that most
women said their sex lives were better, not worse, after the
operation, which is performed on 600,000 women in America each
year, mainly those who suffer the benign but painful uterine tumors
called fibroids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't know what to expect,'' said Dr. Kristen
Kjerulff, a professor of epidemiology at the medical school who was
the study's principal investigator.
</P>
<P>
   About 5 percent of the women studied over a two-year period did
report problems with sex after the operation, including pain and
loss of desire. (Some of these problems, Kjerulff said, can be
addressed through medication.) But many of the rest reported
substantial improvements in their sex lives, including increased
desire and stronger, more frequent orgasms.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say the improvement may result from the fact that,
their medical conditions having been treated, the women simply feel
better.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PREVENTION: Fighting Pneumonia, as Easy as Sitting &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the solutions to the most serious medical problems do
not have to be high tech.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a study recently published in The Lancet, the British
medical journal. It suggests that to reduce pneumonia in
intensive-care wards, all doctors need to do is to have the
patients sit up.
</P>
<P>
   The current practice of having patients lie on their backs
appears to contribute to the development of pneumonia, the most
common hospital-acquired infection, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers in Spain studied 86 patients on respirators and had
39 of them moved into semi-recumbent positions. Three of the 39
developed pneumonia, compared with 16 of the 47 who were lying
down.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
