<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     12-06 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Dec. 7. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MONACO-SAFRA (Paris) _ An American nurse who had worked for
Edmond Safra for the last five months has admitted to setting the
fire that killed the billionaire banker as he took refuge in a
bathroom in his luxury penthouse in Monte Carlo last Friday,
according to Monaco's chief prosecutor. The prosecutor said the
nurse, Ted Maher, 41, from Stormville, N.Y., had concocted his
story that the harbor-side apartment was under attack by two-hooded
men with knives and then set fire to a waste paper basket in an
effort to draw attention to himself. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-RELIGION (Gusau, Nigeria) _ Zamfara, the North Dakota of
Nigeria, has suddenly become this West African nation's most famous
state, as well as the biggest challenge to Nigeria's fragile
national unity. In October, the state government announced it would
introduce Sharia, the Islamic social and penal code, raising near
hysteria in a country already divided nearly evenly _ and uneasily
_ between a Muslim north and a Christian south. Outside the state,
Zamfara's actions have caused near panic. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-RUSSIA (Dolinsky, Russia) _ Russian planes dropped
leaflets on Chechnya's besieged capital on Monday, warning
residents and rebels to flee by Saturday before federal forces
launch a massive attack to smash the city, Grozny, into submission.
The Russian military has been raining bombs and artillery on the
city for weeks but has been hesitant to risk storming it, for fear
that street battles would cause the kind of heavy casualties that
Russia suffered in Grozny in the 1994-96 war. (Developing; summary
from wires.) By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-BANKS-HOLOCAUST (Undated) _ A three-year search of Swiss
banks accused of hiding accounts held by Holocaust victims ended on
Monday with a commission of independent auditors announcing it had
found 54,000 accounts that were probably linked to victims of Nazi
persecution, and describing in detail how some of the banks had
issued ``deliberately misleading statements'' for decades to Jews
who had come looking for their family's assets. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-TRADE (Sao Paulo, Brazil) _ As a developing nation
grappling with the social turmoil caused by the economic forces of
globalization, Brazil tends to grow testy when it feels its
problems are misrepresented by an all-powerful United States intent
on handing out lessons. Like other developing states, Brazil had
much to gain from success in Seattle. The liberalization of world
agricultural trade alone could bring an additional $11 billion in
annual export revenue. So its reaction to some of Clinton's remarks
in Seattle was swift and angry. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MIRANDA (Washington) _ The Supreme Court's deeply
familiar, much disputed Miranda decision is headed for its most
important test, as the justices announced Monday that they would
decide whether Congress had effectively overruled the 33-year-old
decision with a law that was enacted for that purpose in 1968 and
ignored almost ever since. The question for the court, in an appeal
by an indicted bank robber who made self-incriminating statements
without having first received his Miranda warnings, is whether
Miranda vs. Arizona itself established a rule of constitutional law
or whether it merely expressed the Warren Court's preferred method
of enforcing the constitutional right against compelled
self-incrimination. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-BENEFITS (Washington) _ The Social Security
Administration is not being optimistic enough about how long
Americans will live in the 21st Century and, as a result, is
underestimating how much it will have to pay out to them, according
to a federal advisory panel's report on the solvency of the Social
Security system. The advisory panel said on Monday that the Clinton
administration had underestimated the financial problems of the
Social Security program because it had understated likely
improvements in the life expectancy of Americans, who will collect
benefits for more years than the government now predicts. By Robert
Pear.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-CRACKDOWN (San Francisco) _ In San Francisco, homeless
people haunt the city: hiding in doorways, pushing overloaded
shopping carts, standing on corners announcing their troubles on
cardboard signs (``Veteran, homeless and hungry''). But San
Francisco is far from alone. At the richest time in the nation's
history, housing that the poor can afford is at an all-time low,
fueling an increase in homelessness, according to the United States
Conference of Mayors. And with complaints about beggars and bag
ladies and mumbling, stumbling vagrants growing as well, cities are
fighting to move homeless people out of public spaces as never
before. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-LANDER (Pasadena, Calif.) _ When the Mars Polar Lander
failed to signal it had arrived on the Red Planet, NASA scientists
hoped it was resting. Now they fear it is dead. Scientists were
preparing what they called their last best chance to contact the
missing lander _ an operation set for midnight local time (3 a.m.
EST). They are seeking a miracle but expecting the worst.
(Developing; summary from wires.) By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERFAITH-DECORATIONS (Undated) _ The December holidays have
long been a source of angst for many duel-faith couples, and the
tug is particularly acute for Christians and Jews whose seasonal
celebrations collide head on with Christmas and Hanukkah. Couples
have often decided to forgo one holiday or simply display the
paraphernalia of both side by side. But many families are now
synthesizing two customs. The commercial marketplace is starting to
respond to this pluralistic view of the holidays by producing what
was once taboo: decorations that merge the symbols of two
observances. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-IVESTER (Undated) _ After a grueling year of product
recalls, falling profits and scuttled acquisition plans,
Coca-Cola's top executive said that he would step down in April. M.
Douglas Ivester, 52, said simply that he wanted to move on to a
different stage of his life. But his decision to retire as chairman
and chief executive at such a young age after a mere two years
stunned shareholders and the business world. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
</TEXT>
