<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0890 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-`MILLIONAIRE'-TEX     12-06 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-`MILLIONAIRE'-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NOW, A NEW GAME: WHO WANTS TO RUIN TV?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Things are shaping up rather nicely for ABC and its game show,
the one that invites ordinary peons like us to be millionaires.
It's a certified ratings phenomenon, a surprise, a shocker, one of
those pieces of mud that networks sling at the wall, hoping
something sticks. This one did, which is terrific because, well,
that's all it takes. One. One hit, and you're off to the races and
everyone is freaking out, inside your corridors, in your
competitors' corridors, in the suites of advertisers and the ad
agencies that serve them.
</P>
<P>
   Now ABC has figured out how to use its new loaded weapon (can't
just keep these things lying around the house, you know), and its
salivating competitors have their faces smashed up against the
window, all disfigured and green with envy, outsiders begging
entry.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Jan. 11, we'll get ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
three times a week: Sunday, Tuesday and Thursday. Don't look
surprised by the trifecta, or what will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Every network and producer and parking attendant with
connections is coming up with game show ideas, from the lame to the
really lame to the really, really lame. Even ABC will try to
duplicate its own British duplication because ``there is room for
more,'' as ABC entertainment co-chairman Lloyd Braun so gleefully
put it in a conference call. After all, television audiences are
demanding yet fickle, and if something sticks, if it's a hit, if it
draws 22 million viewers, as ``Millionaire'' has, you're not an
idiot but idolized.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. But didn't a parent ever lecture you about being careful
with weapons? They can be deadly to the innocent who want no part
of this but will be in the range of fire anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   Such as the average television viewer.
</P>
<P>
   In a teleconference the other day to discuss the just-concluded
sweeps ratings period, NBC officials announced intentions to scale
back big-budget miniseries and specials during future sweeps, to
better safeguard their high-dollar investments.
</P>
<P>
   This is a revelation, as networks, particularly NBC, have
increasingly found ratings success in flashy movies like ``Merlin''
and ``Cinderella,'' developed specifically to attract an optimal
number of viewers at the optimal time. But the way NBC, CBS and Fox
see it, going up against ``Millionaire'' is economic suicide. Why
air your ``best stuff'' when it won't be seen?
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' has changed the economic landscape for the
betterment of ABC and those with Disney stock. But it's also
threatening to unravel the viewing opportunities for the rest of
us, those who don't very much care for game shows of any stripe and
couldn't care less whether ``Millionaire'' returns as a Sunday,
Tuesday and Thursday fixture or a Saturday morning cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the bigger problem: When networks start running scared,
which they are, it results in conservatism and bonehead choices and
series with mush for brains, of which we have plenty already.
There's little incentive to be unique and daring. Good ideas are
left at the door, shaking like rabbits in a lion's den.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we'll have a schedule full of game shows, much the way
we had (and still have, to a point) multiple newsmagazines. And
what a shame, because those costly dramas just now getting off the
endangered list will again be pre-empted for programming that costs
less to produce and therefore has higher returns and smaller risks.
</P>
<P>
   David E. Kelley is reportedly miffed about his ``Snoops''
getting a cancellation notice to make room for ``Millionaire'' _
OK, it wasn't great, and it had only so-so ratings. But if ABC is
willing to tick off its golden-child producer, is there no end to
this game-show cockiness?
</P>
<P>
   The only thing we can hope for at this point _ and it's bound to
happen _ is that game shows dilute the market and lose steam. How
could it not? I believe that cream rises to the top. But airing
three days a week and with other game shows cluttering the
landscape, how long can even ``Millionaire'' keep luring such
sizable audiences?
</P>
<P>
   We're going to have to wait this one out. For the time being,
though, imagine a game show airing every night of the week. I'm all
for variety on television, but game shows over dramas merely dumbs
down TV even more.
</P>
<P>
   TV is about to be turned upside down. And it's all because we
want to be millionaires, to see ordinary people win big money.
</P>
<P>
   I have a better idea. Buy a lottery ticket. The odds are the
same, and you're not dragging the rest of us down with you.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1656EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0891 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BROADWAY-SEASON-TEX     12-06 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-SEASON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY TROTTING OUT THE GLITTERY STAGE SHOWS THEATERGOERS LOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanied by BC-BROADWAY-BEST) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The scene begins in a dance studio, after gawky,
untalented students and a lecherous instructor have just learned a
routine to ``Disco Duck'' and gone home. Young stud Tony spots
wispy Stephanie on the other side of the floor. Earlier, he had
been eying her at the hot nightclub, 2001 Odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   Sure of himself, he struts over to ask her to be his dance
partner in an upcoming competition. Considering herself more
sophisticated than Tony, Stephanie can't be bothered by his
brashness. Still, she shows faint signs of attraction.
</P>
<P>
   You know what happens next. You know she will act on that
attraction. You know she will dance lustily with Tony, break up
with him, and come running back in the end so she and Tony can
dance like it's 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Even never having seen the movie of the same name, you know all
this will happen because ``Saturday Night Fever'' is a big-budget
Broadway musical that needs to appeal to the masses so it can make
lots of money and find worldwide success. And you know it will do
just that, because even if the material is merely skin-deep, it is
accessible, it is fun, it has a beat so you can dance to it. It is
a musical, and, despite critical panning, it is one of numerous
such shows that are continuing the late-'90s Broadway revival.
</P>
<P>
   There has been much discussion during the past few years about
the supposed decline of the American musical. Critics cry out for
the tunes of Stephen Sondheim and the dance steps of Bob Fosse.
</P>
<P>
   The public, however, is unfazed. The musicals of today still
sing to theatergoers who continue to pack houses. The 1998-1999
season was Broadway's biggest moneymaker. Now, halfway into the
1999-2000 season, the League of American Theatres and Producers has
announced a record Thanksgiving-week box office in New York _ $14.3
million _ and predicts that this season's box-office take will top
last year's.
</P>
<P>
   These reports reflect a nationwide boom in performing arts
attendance, which has as much to do with a healthy economy as
anything else. Still, Broadway must be doing something right if
it's seeing record audiences. Folks are still flocking to the Great
White Way to catch staple hits such as ``Phantom of the Opera,''
``Beauty and the Beast'' and ``Les Miserables,'' as well as
significant revivals, such as ``Cabaret'' and ``Annie Get Your
Gun'' (and you can add the recently opened ``Kiss Me Kate'' to this
list).
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, though, the musical still fails to garner respect. Much
of what Broadway has seen in the way of new musicals the last half
of this decade has been adapted from movies, some ill-conceived
(''Footloose,'' ``Big'') and others well-received (''The Lion
King'').
</P>
<P>
   The works that have received mixed reactions from critics and
audiences have been by rising musical composers Jason Robert Brown
(''Parade''), Adam Guettel (''Floyd Collins'') and Michael John
LaChiusa (''Hello Again''). All suffered short runs because of
stark staging and dark themes, and music that is infinitely more
interesting but less accessible than, say, something by Frank
Wildhorn (''Jekyll &AMP; Hyde,'' ``The Scarlet Pimpernel''). LaChiusa's
current musical, the sometimes brilliant ``Marie Christine,'' set
in late-1800s New Orleans and Chicago and based on ``Medea,'' will
likely see a quick demise as well. The only piece in this dark mold
that has met with unanimous success is ``Rent,'' which will likely
go down as the musical of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, audiences want their musical theater full of
spectacle and multimillion-dollar sets. Indeed, if anything is
wrong with the state of the modern musical, it is just ``that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never understand why (producers) spend that much money on a
musical,'' said actor Judd Hirsch, recently in town for the touring
production of the hit play ``Art.'' ``The only real thing on that
stage is the people. When I see a car or an airplane onstage, I
just laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   One young team that has had moderate success is Stephen Flaherty
and Lynn Ahrens, whose ``Ragtime'' will soon close after a
three-year run.
</P>
<P>
   E.L. Doctorow's story was ``an almost impossible book and notion
to put on stage,'' said composer Harvey Schmidt, who with partner
Tom Jones has given us ``The Fantasticks'' and ``100 in the
Shade.'' ``Ragtime'' ``was very accessible, but interesting at the
same time. It was very bold and not ordinary. It had density and
humanity, which is necessary. (Ahrens and Flaherty's) first
musical, `Lucky Stiff,' was good, too. It wasn't ordinary music,
but they did it right. They made every single minute count.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahrens and Flaherty are working on ``The Seussical,'' based on
the books of Dr. Seuss, but that's one of the few bright spots on
the musicals horizon.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to more revivals _ ``Finian's Rainbow,''
``Oklahoma!,'' ``Jesus Christ Superstar'' and ``The Music Man'' _
2000 will see new works by the kings of Broadway box office: Andrew
Lloyd Webber (''Whistle Down the Wind''), Claude-Michel Schonberg
and Alain Boublil (''Martin Guerre'') and Wildhorn (''Havana'').
Not to mention more adaptations of works that wouldn't seem to be
good musical fodder in the first place, such as ``The Witches of
Eastwick,'' ``Blade Runner'' and, believe it or not, ``Batman.''
</P>
<P>
   Pow!
</P>
<P>
   But as long as Broadway is breaking records, why mess with the
formula? It won't stop the dedicated from trying new things.
``There has never been more interest among young people fascinated
with trying to write musicals,'' said Schmidt. ``Sooner or later,
someone's going to break through with a new way of doing them. It
has got to happen to stir things up.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1656EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0893 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BROADWAY-SEASON-TEX     12-06 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-SEASON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY TROTTING OUT THE GLITTERY STAGE SHOWS THEATERGOERS LOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanied by BC-BROADWAY-BEST) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
