   Other than that, audiences want their musical theater full of
spectacle and multimillion-dollar sets. Indeed, if anything is
wrong with the state of the modern musical, it is just ``that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never understand why (producers) spend that much money on a
musical,'' said actor Judd Hirsch, recently in town for the touring
production of the hit play ``Art.'' ``The only real thing on that
stage is the people. When I see a car or an airplane onstage, I
just laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   One young team that has had moderate success is Stephen Flaherty
and Lynn Ahrens, whose ``Ragtime'' will soon close after a
three-year run.
</P>
<P>
   E.L. Doctorow's story was ``an almost impossible book and notion
to put on stage,'' said composer Harvey Schmidt, who with partner
Tom Jones has given us ``The Fantasticks'' and ``100 in the
Shade.'' ``Ragtime'' ``was very accessible, but interesting at the
same time. It was very bold and not ordinary. It had density and
humanity, which is necessary. (Ahrens and Flaherty's) first
musical, `Lucky Stiff,' was good, too. It wasn't ordinary music,
but they did it right. They made every single minute count.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahrens and Flaherty are working on ``The Seussical,'' based on
the books of Dr. Seuss, but that's one of the few bright spots on
the musicals horizon.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to more revivals _ ``Finian's Rainbow,''
``Oklahoma!,'' ``Jesus Christ Superstar'' and ``The Music Man'' _
2000 will see new works by the kings of Broadway box office: Andrew
Lloyd Webber (''Whistle Down the Wind''), Claude-Michel Schonberg
and Alain Boublil (''Martin Guerre'') and Wildhorn (''Havana'').
Not to mention more adaptations of works that wouldn't seem to be
good musical fodder in the first place, such as ``The Witches of
Eastwick,'' ``Blade Runner'' and, believe it or not, ``Batman.''
</P>
<P>
   Pow!
</P>
<P>
   But as long as Broadway is breaking records, why mess with the
formula? It won't stop the dedicated from trying new things.
``There has never been more interest among young people fascinated
with trying to write musicals,'' said Schmidt. ``Sooner or later,
someone's going to break through with a new way of doing them. It
has got to happen to stir things up.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1657EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
