<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0899 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-AGE-COMMUNITY-HNS &LR;      12-06 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGE-COMMUNITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGE-RESTRICTED TEXAS COMMUNITY TELLS WIDOW, 52, TO MOVE OUT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE OLAFSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Linda Bell's husband had been dead two months and
seven days when she got the letter.
</P>
<P>
   It said, in effect, move out of your house within six months or
face legal action.
</P>
<P>
   At Country Place, an age-restricted community in neighboring
Brazoria County near Pearland, just south of Houston, if you're
younger than 55 and your spouse dies, there's a distinct
possibility that you can be thrown out of your house.
</P>
<P>
   That's the position the Country Place board of directors has
taken against Bell and two other women.
</P>
<P>
   After Bell lost her 60-year-old husband to Lou Gehrig's disease
in August, she was told she no longer could claim an exemption to
the minimum age required for homeowners in the master-planned
community of 1,300 people who have left the big-city rat race for
the quieter confines of age-restricted living.
</P>
<P>
   At age 52, Bell is considered too young.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, a secretary to oilman Bud Adams _ owner of the National
Football League's Tennessee Titans _ is fighting mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband lived in my house, he died in my house and they're
telling me I have to leave my house. And they're telling me in a
rude letter before he's even been dead three months. That is
wrong,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other women _ one age 54 and the other 51 _ who lost their
husbands in recent years also have received notice they will face
legal action unless they comply with the community's age
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that it is not necessary for you to relocate your
residence in order to comply with the age restriction provisions,''
said their letters from property manager Dawn Crawford of
Association Management Inc. ``However, if you do not have any other
alternatives, please promptly take steps in this direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Country Place is buzzing over the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   But Roger Lampman, president of the Country Place Master
Community Association, makes no apologies for the treatment of the
women.
</P>
<P>
   The covenants, conditions and restrictions of the community, he
said, require that homeowners under 55 have a spouse above that age
living with them.
</P>
<P>
   The widows, he said, either have to leave or have someone 55 or
older move in with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to enforce what your covenants are. You might feel
it's heartless, I might feel it's heartless, but the covenants are
the covenants,'' said Lampman, 59, a retired General Motors
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the American way,'' Lampman added. ``You abide by the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Country Place's conditions, covenants and restrictions, however,
say nothing about evicting residents younger than 55 after they
lose their spouses. Neither do they specify how long someone
younger than 55 may remain after losing an older spouse.
</P>
<P>
   A volunteer committee is reviewing the rules to suggest changes.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of that committee, Jack Banowsky, said he senses
the retirement community favors an exception being written into the
rules that would allow residents under 55 to stay after their older
spouses die.
</P>
<P>
   Any changes, though, will require an approval vote by 75 percent
of the residents.
</P>
<P>
   And any changes could lead to another set of problems, said
Banowsky, a 70-year-old retired engineer.
</P>
<P>
   What if an under-age resident remarries someone even younger?
</P>
<P>
   What if stepchildren are involved?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you begin to erode the whole concept of a senior
community,'' Banowsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Another restriction prohibits residents under 18. If teen-agers
or pre-teens want to visit relatives, they must limit their stay to
a total of 30 days per year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such restrictions, life in Country Place has a genuine
appeal that reminds some of the 1950s, when everyone on the block
knew each other, fear of crime was an afterthought and boom boxes
had not been invented.
</P>
<P>
   The security of Country Place is invariably cited as a major
plus by residents, who say they are unafraid to take a nighttime
stroll, thanks to security guards posted at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there are dozens of organized groups and activities in
which to participate.
</P>
<P>
   If golfing, swimming or playing bridge don't appeal, there's a
choral group, a 40-member band and a drama troupe that stages such
productions as ``Arsenic and Old Lace`` and ``Harvey.''
</P>
<P>
   More important, perhaps, is an atmosphere in which neighbors
help neighbors, especially when illness strikes.
</P>
<P>
   When cancer spread into the spinal cord of Candy Gillespie's
husband, Wally, their neighbors took care of virtually all the
couple's needs, from grocery shopping to the laundry.
</P>
<P>
   After Gillespie's husband died in 1997 at age 77, she didn't
hear a word from the Country Place board for two years _ until
October.
</P>
<P>
   The letter she received from Association Management Inc. was the
same one Linda Bell had received, threatening that lawyers will be
hired unless she complies with the age rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once an attorney becomes involved, we will seek reimbursement
from you for all attorney fees and cost incurred by Country Place
as a result of your noncompliance,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're saying is, `We don't care if you own the house,
we just don't want you living in it,''' said Gillespie, a
54-year-old bookkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   The third woman who has been told to comply with Country Place's
age restrictions is Myrlene Cox Muddiman, whose first husband died
in June 1994. A month later, she received a letter from the board
of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Two more letters arrived in the ensuing months before the matter
was dropped after she contacted a lawyer for help.
</P>
<P>
   In October, though, she received a fourth letter _ identical to
the ones sent to Gillespie and Bell _ even though she remarried a
57-year-old Country Place resident last March.
</P>
<P>
   Since Muddiman has been through this before in 1994, she
expressed concern more for Gillespie and Bell than for herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the grief this caused me after my first husband
died,'' said Muddiman, a 51-year-old nurse practitioner ``I feel
great anger (that) they have to go through what I went through _
because you have enough to go through after you lose your spouse
without being threatened with being kicked out of your home. This
needs to be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie and Bell haven't sought legal help from an attorney,
but they have asked Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, to find out from the
Department of Housing and Urban Development whether kicking them
out is a violation of the Fair Housing Act.
</P>
<P>
   The department is reviewing the age policy of Country Place at
the request of DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly interested in the question,'' said George
Rodriguez, a HUD senior community builder in the agency's Houston
office.
</P>
<P>
   HUD normally investigates apartment complexes and rental housing
rather than owner-occupied single-family dwellings like Country
Place, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something completely new,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The management company for Country Place has cited the need to
comply with federal legislation called the Housing for Older
Persons Act as the reason the community's age restriction rule must
be enforced against the women.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, that law allows a senior community to have up to 20
percent of its residents younger than 55.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has inflamed the passions of some residents, including
Virginia Ling.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime Country Place resident, Ling said her husband had to
grab her by the arm at a restaurant when she became angry with a
woman dinner companion who voiced support for evicting under-age
widows in the senior community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to punch her lights out,'' said Ling. ``I looked
at her _ and this woman's a widow _ and I said to her, `What about
compassion? Are you crazy?' They don't have an answer for that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
