<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0900 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV12-82     12-06 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV12-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVE THE OFF-LINE LIFE WITH A GOOD BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 12)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics. Double parentheses
should be set as brackets.) 
(Eds: The word SCHWA in parentheses has been used twice instead of
the phonetic symbol _ an upside-down ``e'' _ which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems. If printing this
symbol is a problem, the story can end at the optional trim.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The people who were opposed to that,'' President Clinton said
of his police subsidy, ``they practically  &UR; swole &LR;  up and died when
it was passed.'' In another gibe at Republican budgeteers, he said
they had ``totally  &UR; bumfuzzled &LR; '' American voters.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for followers of Clintonian syntax and vocabulary,
this winter's Christmas book list for word mavens has entries that
help explicate the president's remarks. ( &UR; Explicate &LR;  has a learned
connotation, meaning ``to analyze in detail'';  &UR; elucidate &LR;  means
``to illuminate, especially by an illustration''; the more general
term, which I should have used, is  &UR; explain &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   ``Words and Rules: The Ingredients of Language,'' by Steven
Pinker (Basic Books, $26), offers a deliciously erudite, if
somewhat grainy, glass of Metamucil for the legion of English
speakers troubled by irregular verbs.
</P>
<P>
   In Pinker's world, our brains hold irregular verbs in memory.
The past tense of  &UR; eat &LR;  is not  &UR; eated &LR;  but  &UR; ate &LR; . Gotta remember
that. But all the other past and other tenses we form from regular
verbs ( &UR; walk-walked &LR; ,  &UR; elucidate-elucidated &LR; ) abide by rules of
syntax hard-wired in our heads. From this he constructs a theory of
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irregular forms like  &UR; break-broke &LR;  are memorized,'' he tells
me; ``regular forms like  &UR; smash-smashed &LR;  are generated on the fly
by a rule.'' So here am I, with my swelled head, wondering where
Clinton came up with  &UR; swole &LR;  instead of the regular past tense,
 &UR; swelled &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; Swole &LR;  used to be the past tense of  &UR; swell &LR; ,'' Pinker
explains. ``Many Southern U.S. dialects preserve obsolete irregular
forms like  &UR; drag-drug &LR;  and  &UR; help-holp &LR; .'' But as most other
children forget the memorized irregularities, the verb turns
regular _ and the past tense of  &UR; drag &LR;  is no longer  &UR; drug &LR;  but
 &UR; dragged &LR; , of  &UR; help &LR;  no longer  &UR; holp &LR;  but  &UR; helped &LR;  and of  &UR; swell &LR; 
no longer  &UR; swole &LR;  but  &UR; swelled &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; Swole &LR;  is interesting for another reason,'' Pinker says.
``The stem has survived in Standard English in the participle and
adjective form  &UR; swollen &LR; .'' Curious: As the irregular  &UR; swell &LR;  wore
down to regular, thanks to generations of forgetful children, the
past-tense form lost the vowel change from  &UR; e &LR;  to  &UR; o &LR;  while the
past participle has preserved it ( &UR; swell, swelled, swollen &LR; ). This
insight gets a linguist all puffed up.
</P>
<P>
   For a little help on the presidential  &UR; bumfuzzled &LR; , we turn to
another author: Allan Metcalf, in ``The World in So Many Words''
(Houghton Mifflin, $19). One of the words he explicates is the
related  &UR; bamboozle &LR; , which first appeared on the London stage in
Colley Cibber's 1702 hit, ``She Wou'd, and She Wou'd Not.''
</P>
<P>
   Cibber's character worries about ``Sham proofs, that they
propos'd to  &UR; bamboozle &LR;  me with.'' As Metcalf notes, Jonathan Swift
in The Tatler No. 230 complains about ``certain words invented by
some pretty fellows ... some of which are now struggling for the
vogue,'' like  &UR; phizz &LR;  for physiognomy or face,  &UR; sham &LR; ,  &UR; bubble &LR; ,
 &UR; bully &LR; ,  &UR; banter &LR;  and  &UR; bamboozle &LR; , the last meaning ``to trick, to
confuse.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bumfuzzle &LR;  and its variant  &UR; bumfuddle &LR;  (influenced by
 &UR; befuddle &LR; ) mean the same: ``to confuse deliberately.'' The
Dictionary of American Regional English tracked it to a 1905 Ozarks
usage, which is home country for Clinton; the Random House
Historical Dictionary of American Slang makes the leap to the year
before, in ``The Villagers,'' by Oliver B. Limerick: ``Hezekiah
tumbled to the fact that he had been  &UR; bumfuzzled &LR; .'' Despite Dean
Swift's disapproval, the variant of Cibber's slang term lives on in
today's White House.
</P>
<P>
   Other books that make gifts of gab this holiday season:
</P>
<P>
   Not a language book, but mightily bethumped with words, is
``Shakespeare in Charge: The Bard's Guide to Leading and Succeeding
on the Business Stage,'' by Norman Augustine and Kenneth Adelman
(Talk Miramax Books, which sounds more like an exhortation than the
name of a publisher, $22.95).
</P>
<P>
   This guide to corporate clambering-up draws on the greatest
plays for instruction _ ``None will sweat but for promotion,'' says
Orlando in ``As You Like It'' _ and time spent on a book that
brings executives to iambic pentameter is not out of joint.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Memories of the Great and the Good'' (Pavilion, $24.95),
Alistair Cooke, the literate and impeccably grammatical voice of
America to Britain for the past 50 years, uses a word in his
introduction that exemplifies his prose: ``There is another
prejudice, or  &UR; postjudice &LR;  rather, that may have conditioned my
choice of heroes and heroines.''
</P>
<P>
   This word for the rejection of ``the urge to pry into the
sexuality, preferably kinky,'' of Cooke's subjects was coined by
the critic John Ruskin in 1886. A generation later, G.K. Chesterton
defined  &UR; postjudice &LR;  as ``not the bias before the fair trial, but
the bias that remains after.''
</P>
<P>
   There is much to be learned in reading Cooke's fluid
recollections of the famous people he has covered, from George
Bernard Shaw to Erma Bombeck _ not the least that it is worth the
effort to make one's prose appear effortless.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nuke 'Em
</P>
<P>
   In a generally upbeat review of George W. Bush's maiden
interview on ``Meet the Press,'' I zinged him on his pronunciation
of the word  &UR; nuclear &LR; . A half-dozen times he said
``NU-ky(SCHWA)-ler'' rather than the correct NU-klee-er or
NYOO-klee-er.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he can't pronounce  &UR; nuclear &LR; ,'' writes Joseph Friend
from cyberspace, ``he is a shoe-in in as much as neither can Carter
and Clinton. Must be a requirement of office.''
</P>
<P>
   Lexicographers have noticed this phenomenon. ``Though
disapproved of by many,'' goes a usage note in Merriam-Webster's
10th Collegiate ($24.95), ``pronunciations ending in -ky(SCHWA)-ler
have been found in widespread use among educated speakers including
scientists, lawyers, professors ... and at least one U.S. president
((Eisenhower, Carter)) and vice president ((Mondale, Quayle)).''
Scholarly elucidations of the cause of this mispronunciation will
be welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   Friend's ``shoe-in,'' by the way, is properly spelled  &UR; shoo-in &LR; .
The colloquial verb  &UR; to shoo &LR;  means ``to gently urge in a desired
direction.'' The racetrack term  &UR; shoo-in &LR; , meaning ``certain
winner,'' is rooted in a fraudulent practice of corrupt jockeys:
They agree to bet on one long shot, holding back their own mounts,
and chase in or  &UR; shoo in &LR;  the horse they picked to win.
</P>
<P>
   To mix political racing metaphors:  &UR; Dark horses &LR;  dispute that
the  &UR; front-runner &LR;  is a  &UR; shoo-in &LR; , no matter how he pronounces
 &UR; nuclear &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
