<SLUG> BC-WHITEHOUSE-HOLIDAY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHE'LL BE HOME FOR CHRISTMAS _ BUT WHICH ONE?
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ 'Tis the season for conflicting roles.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton held the first lady's traditional press
preview Monday of a White House bedecked for Christmas, but Topic A
was her untraditional campaign for a New York Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were less interested in Mrs. Clinton's descriptions of
this year's holiday gingerbread houses than when she move into her
new $1.7 million house in Chappaqua, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   (As always, though, the journalistic horde seemed most
interested in the White House buffet tables laden with shrimp, baby
lamb chops, crab cakes, sushi, fruitcake, cookies, pastries and
potent egg nog.)
</P>
<P>
   The annual tour by the first lady opens a season of almost
continuous holiday activities at the White House, but this year
promises to be different.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Mrs. Clinton will miss Wednesday's ceremony to
light the national Christmas tree so that she can attend a New York
event sponsored by an Irish-American magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning at 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue, the first lady
said she is already ``pulling things out of storage'' for her new
house at 15 Old School Lane an affluent New York suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking to begin moving things in later this month,'' Mrs.
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mostly trying to use what I have'' rather than getting new
furniture, she said. ``I may have to buy some things, but I'm
trying to be really clear about what I do have and get those in the
best possible shape.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she said the Clintons will ``certainly'' spend
Christmas in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our favorite time of the year,'' she said. ``There isn't
any more wonderful place to celebrate the holidays than here at the
White House.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's White House decoration theme is ``Holiday
Treasures,'' which has a double meaning, said Mrs. Clinton. First,
the nostalgic ornaments, wreaths, mantelpieces and decorated trees
harken back to the nation's cultural and historic legacy. Second,
they highlight a White House millennium project to save and restore
``enduring symbols of American tradition that define us as a
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the ``American Treasure'' decorative pieces, for example,
are replicas of Ebenezer Baptist Church in Atlanta and the 1973
Bartow County Courthouse in Cartersville, Ga. A model of the 1905
Wright Flyer III from Dayton, Ohio, is another of these treasures.
</P>
<P>
   This year's gingerbread creation is a ``confectionery tribute''
to treasures around the nation's capital. There's a White House,
Mount Vernon, Washington Monument and Jefferson Memorial _ all
constructed of brown gingerbread and held together with a chocolate
mortar. Nearby runs a marzipan Potomac River.
</P>
<P>
   The White House holiday card features the North Portico. The
watercolor painting is by Ray Ellis, an artist from Martha's
Vineyard, Ma., who also did the 1998 card featuring the State
Dining Room.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
