<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ROME-2000-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROME PREPARES FOR ITS JUBILEE YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Dec. 12) 
(jt) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ With its traffic-clogged ancient lanes, Rome is never,
even under the best of circumstances, an easy place to maneuver,
except perhaps on foot.
</P>
<P>
   But the coming Jubilee year _ when Rome and the Vatican expect
millions of visitors to celebrate the start of Christianity's third
millennium _ promises to make mobility even more challenging.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge confronts not only Rome but other parts of Italy
as well. Many of the expected visitors will flow in by bus, car,
train and plane from around Europe, straining highways, airports
and rail systems. The new airport at Malpensa serving Milan,
northern Italy's commercial and business center, continues to
suffer teething problems. An investment program to expand the
capacity of Fiumicino airport in Rome, though well under way, will
not be complete by Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there is lingering highway disruption. Though the
Tauern Tunnel in Austria, on a major north-south route linking
southern Germany and northern Austria with Italy, reopened in
August after extensive repairs made necessary by a tunnel fire in
May, the even more crucial Mont Blanc Tunnel between France and
Italy has been closed since March after dozens of people died in a
fire. It is not expected to reopen before early 2001. That will
force drivers from France and parts of Switzerland to seek
alternative routes, such as the Alpine passes in northern Italy,
which can be impassable in winter. Yet attractive choices exist for
those who come by train, including new high-speed Swiss Cisalpino
trains linking Geneva and Zurich to Milan.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the transportation challenge as great as in Rome
itself. In 1996, the Italian government allocated $1.7 billion,
partly to beautify the city, but mainly to improve public
transport. Some projects, like doubling the size of a tunnel under
the Janiculum Hill, are designed to improve car and bus traffic.
But much of the spending has been aimed at reducing the number of
vehicles in the historic center and increasing public options.
Rome's mayor, Francesco Rutelli, estimated recently that by Jan. 1
roughly 90 percent of the improvements will be complete. Some will
mean little for many visitors. The city vaunts several new cycling
routes for those brave or foolish enough to challenge Rome's
traffic on two wheels, including one near the Villa Borghese. Along
the Via Appia, the ancient Roman road leading out of the city to
the south, the beltway circling Rome known as the Raccordo Anulare,
which once severed the Via Appia like a knife a salami into two
sections, has been put underground in a two-mile tunnel, enabling
hikers along the route to enjoy its antiquities both within and
outside the beltway.
</P>
<P>
   For getting around Rome, there are numerous improvements. The
train line that connects Fiumicino airport with city subway
stations and the main rail terminal at Termini is being beefed up
by the addition of double-decker train cars and more frequent
departures. For motorists, 24 new parking lots marked ``Parcheggi
di Scambio,'' a kind of park-and-ride arrangement, have been built
to enable drivers to switch to public transport. In the center,
several bus lines now feature express as well as local buses that
are marked with a prominent E. On 25 different routes, buses
designated by small owls perched atop the bus-stop signs are being
added that will run, although at less frequent intervals, through
the night. In the historic center, three lines with small electric
buses ferry passengers through some of the narrowest streets.
</P>
<P>
   For easier access to the Vatican museums, travelers can now take
the subway's A Line, which passes Termini station and stops at such
central locations as Piazza Barberini and the Spanish Steps, to
continue on to a new station at the Via Cipro, a five-minute walk
from the museums. One of the most useful offerings is a bus line
called La Linea delle Basiliche, or the Major Basilicas Tour, that
will start at the end of this year. When fully operational, silver
buses marked Major Basilicas Tour will link four important
basilicas _ Santa Maria degli Angeli, or St. Mary of the Angels,
St. John Lateran, St. Peter's and St. Paul Outside the Walls _ that
the church requires Holy Year pilgrims to visit to obtain special
Jubilee indulgences. The buses will make 80 stops along the way,
and the 75-minute trip will cost about $8, at 1,860 lire to $1.
There will be a 20-minute stop at St. John's, St. Peter's and St.
Paul's, and riders will be able to get on and off the bus as often
as they wish within the day.
</P>
<P>
   Among the easiest ways to obtain information on getting around
Rome is to ask at hotels or drop by one of the new dark-green
octagonal information booths sprouting up in town. An
English-language Web site, www.atac.roma.it/trasroma/indexuk.htm,
is now available from Rome's municipal transport authority. It
offers extensive information, including a search feature for
plotting trips anywhere in the city.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
