<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Dec. 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The front that brought rain to areas near the Atlantic seaboard
Monday will shift offshore Tuesday. Rain will gradually end in
northern and eastern Maine during the midday and afternoon. The
precipitation may change to snow before ending in extreme northern
Maine as increasing winds from the north import colder air. In the
wake of the front, most of the East Coast states will be dry and
cooler as high pressure arrives from the Middle West. Clouds will
linger near the northern Appalachians, while areas farther south
have plentiful sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Dry and mild weather will cover the Plains and Mississippi
Valley. Onshore breezes will promote some clouds near the western
Gulf of Mexico while most of the central and southern Plains have
abundant sunshine. Farther north across the Plains and Great Lakes,
sunshine will be dimmed by clouds as the returning mild air is
forced to rise over cooler air in place over these regions.
</P>
<P>
   Chilly air will spread over the Northwest as a cold front moves
into the interior. Moist winds from over the Pacific will continue
to ascend west-facing mountain slopes, resulting in intermittent
snow from the southern Cascades and northern Sierra to the northern
Rockies. Showers will linger near the coast, but clouds will break
across parts of eastern Washington and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, a potent jet stream disturbance will begin to
energize low pressure over southern Utah. As a result, locally
heavy mountain snow will spread from Utah Tuesday to northern
Arizona and western Colorado Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: White Danger
</P>
<P>
   There was a high risk of avalanches above 6,000 feet in the
Cascades Monday. During the weekend, snow that fell in the upper
slopes had relatively low density owing to the chilly conditions
that prevailed. Early Monday, as increasing Pacific winds carried
mild ocean air inland, snow became wetter and mixed with rain in
some areas. The added weight of rain and wet snow put stress on
lighter, underlying snow, heightening the risk that the snow would
give way and slide down the mountains. The danger should ebb
Tuesday as winds abate and colder air returns to the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1724EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
