<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0910 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BROADWAY-BEST-3000(3T     12-06 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-BEST-3000(3TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO SEE ON AND OFF BROADWAY
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies BC-BROADWAY-SEASON) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BROADWAY
</P>
<P>
   ``SATURDAY NIGHT FEVER''
</P>
<P>
   A stage version of the quintessential disco movie sounds like a
bad idea. In many respects, it is. The singing and acting leave
little to recommend. But disco was about dancing, shaking one's
groove thang, and the exciting choreography almost makes up for the
show's shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Almost. With all these songs to fit in, the story doesn't
examine relationships between characters as fully as the movie,
especially the one between Tony Manero (James Carpinello) and his
family.
</P>
<P>
   Carpinello was obviously cast because he wowed the auditioners
with his deadpan impersonation of John Travolta, but he never makes
the character his own. The standout performance is by Orfeh as
Annette, the girl in love with Tony.
</P>
<P>
   Audience members were digging the show, though, probably because
it hits a nostalgia button. The Bee Gees' music actually translates
well to being sung by a chorus. If you want great theater, don't
see ``Saturday Night Fever.'' But if you think ``You Should Be
Dancing,'' go. Its biggest strength is that it doesn't pretend to
be anything more than fun.
</P>
<P>
   (Indefinite run at the Minskoff Theatre, 200 W. 45th St.
$30-$80. Ticketmaster.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``MARIE CHRISTINE''
</P>
<P>
   Michael John LaChiusa's musical about a Creole woman in 1894 who
plays with voodoo and whose passion leads her to unthinkable acts
is one of the best shows playing. Unfortunately, it won't last.
</P>
<P>
   Freely adapted from ``Medea,'' ``Marie'' is dark in almost every
respect. The music is spare and sad, most of the costumes are
black, and the spectacle-free set is bare-bones: a raked area on
one side, bleachers on the other. In an interesting staging
decision, most of the cast members (chorus and minor players) sit
still in the bleachers and watch the action in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   Three-time Tony winner Audra McDonald beautifully captures the
drama and pathos of the title character. Her personal chorus is a
trio of women who, when not on stage, sit in the first row of the
audience. Although all the performances are first rate, Mary Testa
gets a chance to scene-steal as Magdalena. But like ``Parade'' and
other beautifully staged but gloomy works, ``Marie Christine'' is
not going to find itself a hit with audiences who come to New York
looking to be wowed by helicopters or falling chandeliers.
</P>
<P>
   (Indefinite run at Lincoln Center's Vivian Beaumont Theatre, 150
W. 65th St. $40-$75. Telecharge.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``KISS ME, KATE''
</P>
<P>
   The good thing about the plethora of musical revivals is that
producers have been picking from the best and giving them
big-budget star treatment. For proof, see the previous two Tony
winners for best musical revival, ``Cabaret'' and ``Annie Get Your
Gun.'' Both are still thriving.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Cole Porter's ``Kiss Me, Kate'' has not been
produced on Broadway since its 1948 opening. There is much to laud
about the staging and performances in this show, based on
Shakespeare's ``Taming of the Shrew,'' in which actors are actually
performing a musical production of ``Shrew.'' Leads Brian Stokes
Mitchell (Fred/Petruchio) and Marin Mazzie (Lili/Katharine) achieve
intense chemistry. Mazzie's extraordinary vocal talents mirror the
immense range she gives to her character. She's vulnerable in ``So
in Love'' and brilliantly comedic in ``I Hate Men.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also fine performances from supporting cast members
Amy Spranger as the ditzy Lois Lane/Bianca and Michael Berresse as
Bill/Hortensio. The dance numbers are arresting, especially the Act
2 opener, ``Too Darn Hot.'' Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   (Indefinite run at the Martin Beck Theatre, 302 W. 45th St.
$20-$85. Telecharge.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``PUTTING IT TOGETHER''
</P>
<P>
   A revival of sorts, this Stephen Sondheim review played
off-Broadway in 1994. But the first production didn't have Carol
Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   (Notice it's spelled review, not revue, because, as player
Bronson Pinchot explains at the onset: ``Sondheim wants you to
think. If you don't want to think, go see `Cats.' '')
</P>
<P>
   The premise here is that five guests, the Wife (Burnett), the
Husband (George Hearn), the Younger Man (John Barrowman), the
Younger Woman (Ruthie Henshall) and the Observer (Pinchot), are at
a cocktail party. Through 31 Sondheim tunes _ from ``Everyday a
Little Death'' from ``A Little Night Music,'' to ``Sooner or
Later'' from ``Dick Tracy'' _ the characters fight, fall in love,
reminisce and find catharsis. You couldn't have this much drama if
you strung together nothing but ``showstopper'' tunes, a la Andrew
Lloyd Webber.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Laugh In''-esque set is playful, and Burnett is a terrific
entertainer, but with the exception of Henshall, the cast rarely
matches the brilliance, darkness or rich layers of Sondheim's
music. Pinchot finally comes through with a rousing ``Buddy's
Blues'' (from ``Follies''), and the company hits a high note with
``The Ladies Who Lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   See ``Together'' for Burnett's inimitable stage presence, but
skip it if you idolize Sondheim enough to know all the ways it
could be better put together.
</P>
<P>
   (Indefinite run at the Ethel Barrymore Theatre, 243 W. 47th St.
$30-$85. Telecharge.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   ``KAT AND THE KINGS''
</P>
<P>
   Here's an odd one: a musical transplant from Cape Town, South
Africa. David Kramer and Taliep Petersen's show is about a singing
and dancing group that, against an apartheid backdrop, thirsts for
fame.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Hector plays Kat Diamond, now retired from the biz and
narrating as he looks back at his younger self (played by Jody J.
Abrahams) and his partners, three male and one female. Set in the
1950s, the original music is a mirror of American rock 'n' roll,
with the troupe performing routines that echo Ritchie Valens, The
Platters and Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   The performers distinguish themselves as dancers and singers,
but the acting will come across as over-the-top and sometimes
melodramatic to American audiences. You'll likely walk away feeling
thoroughly entertained, but not moved.
</P>
<P>
   (Indefinite run at the Cort Theatre, 138 W. 48th St. $45-$75.
Telecharge.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``THE RAINMAKER''
</P>
<P>
   Musicals aren't the only stage shows that are revived. Broadway
mounted Eugene O'Neill's ``The Iceman Cometh'' and Arthur Miller's
``Death of a Salesman'' this year; Miller's ``The Price'' is
currently running. Coming soon are revisits to Peter Shaffer's
``Amadeus,'' Anton Chekhov's ``Uncle Vanya'' and O'Neill's ``A Moon
for the Misbegotten.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rainmaker'' is N. Richard Nash's 1954 play about a scam
artist (Woody Harrelson, in his first starring role on Broadway)
who comes to a drought-stricken Midwestern town in 1936. Director
Scott Ellis gets fine turns from the actors, especially Jayne
Atkinson as the woman who thinks she will never marry because she
is plain-looking. The weak spot is, sadly, Harrelson. There's a
good reason he's a screen actor _ he doesn't have much stage
presence. And yes, his character, Bill Starbuck, initially promises
what he knows he can't provide _ rain _ but Harrelson doesn't give
him much heart. Throughout, he's too much like a snake-oil
salesman, never reaching the necessary catharsis of Nash's script.
</P>
<P>
   (Through Feb. 6 at the Brooks Atkinson Theatre, 256 W. 47th St.
$40-$65. Ticketmaster.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``DAME EDNA: THE ROYAL TOUR''
</P>
<P>
   Australian Barry Humphries brings his longtime alter ego, Dame
Edna Everage, for her first appearance on Broadway. Go see this for
nonstop laughs, but if you're sitting within her eyesight (meaning
the first 15 or so rows), beware. This partially improvised,
hilarious show is constructed around picking on audience members.
She remembers not only the names of all those she has singled out
and where they are sitting, but also the names of their children,
baby sitters, spouses, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Among her/his pranks: bringing a couple on stage to eat a meal
of pasta while she continues talking to the audience, and putting
in a surprise phone call to someone a theatergoer knows. At our
performance, she called the 19-year-old baby sitter of a mother in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   (Indefinite run at the Booth Theatre, 222 W. 45th St. $45-$65.
Telecharge.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``MORNING, NOON AND NIGHT''
</P>
<P>
   Writer and monologuist Spalding Gray's career has been almost as
colorful as Dame Edna's. In previous performance pieces such as
``It's a Slippery Slope,'' ``Monster in a Box,'' ``Swimming to
Cambodia'' and ``Gray's Anatomy,'' he exposed every aspect of his
often-untamed lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   But now, he has settled down a bit. Married again and with a
young child _ his third _ he has moved the family from Manhattan to
a Victorian house in a bucolic Long Island town. Gray fans might be
a little disappointed in his newfound love of family life, but his
razor-sharp wit and knack for storytelling have not waned.
</P>
<P>
   (Through Jan. 10 at Lincoln Center's Vivian Beaumont Theatre,
150 W. 65th St. $25-$45. Runs Sunday and Monday nights only.
Telecharge.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   OFF-BROADWAY
</P>
<P>
   ``GIVE ME YOUR ANSWER, DO!''
</P>
<P>
   Another trend in New York theater has been the frequent staging
of acclaimed new plays by Irish playwrights such as Martin
McDonough (''The Beauty Queen of Leenane'') and Conor McPherson
(''The Weir,'' ``The Lime-Tree Bower'').
</P>
<P>
   Brian Friel has been around for a while, penning strong scripts
such as ``Translations,'' ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' and
``Philadelphia, Here I Come.'' His latest, ``Give Me Your Answer,
Do!,'' just might be his best.
</P>
<P>
   Like all great playwrights, Friel leans toward in-depth
character study over plot or environment. ``Answer'' concerns an
acclaimed writer whose archives of early work, memoirs and letters
are sought after by a special collection of Irish writers at a
Texas university. In the midst of dealing with this, he has to
worry about money problems and a teen-age daughter who has been
hospitalized with an unnamed illness since childhood. His life
parallels that of a peer _ another writer who will end up in the
collection _ and his father-in-law, a retired blues musician.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about this production is first-rate, and boosted by a
dream cast that includes the brilliant Kate Burton (''The Beauty
Queen of Leenane'') John Glover (Tony-winner for his role as twin
brothers in Terrence McNally's ``Love! Valour! Compassion!''), and
multiple Tony-winner Joel Grey (''Cabaret,'' ``Chicago'').
</P>
<P>
   The local theater company that gets rights to this first _ and
it will happen soon _ will have a major coup on its hands.
</P>
<P>
   (Through Jan. 2 at the Gramercy Theatre, 127 E. 23rd St. $55.
(212) 719-1300 or (212) 777-4900.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright Marsha Norman ('''Night,
Mother'') has been absent from the stage, but has kept busy through
screenwriting _ she penned the recent TV movie ``Audrey Hepburn.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her playwriting return comes with ``Trudy Blue,'' a noble effort
that might be compared to ``The Secret Life of Walter Mitty.''
Polly Draper (the TV show ``thirtysomething'') plays novelist
Ginger, who seeks refuge from her lung cancer and marital problems
through the heroine of her writings, Trudy Blue (Sarah Knowlton).
The performances are mostly vigorous, but several elements of the
production need to be fine-tuned. (Norman's nonlinear script, for
one.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The performance seen for this review was given a day before the
opening. When the kinks get worked out, look for regional companies
to snatch this script up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Runs through Dec. 18 at the MCC Theatre, 120 W. 28th St.
$25-$30. Phone Tix.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``AN EXPERIMENT WITH AN AIR PUMP'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This show was the most intriguing seen this trip. Shelagh
Stephenson's tight script is reminiscent of Tom Stoppard's
``Arcadia.'' It follows two families, one in 1799, the other in
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The title comes from Joseph Wright's 1797 painting ``An
Experiment on a Bird in the Air Pump,'' which depicts a scientist
trying to prove that life cannot exist in a vacuum. He places a
bird in a glass air pump, slowly withdrawing the air and then, when
the bird is near death, revives it by reinserting air. This
symbolizes several themes dealt with in the play, including the
predominant one, science vs. human emotion. Well-acted and nicely
staged, ``Air Pump'' is worth the admission price. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Runs through Dec. 12 at Manhattan Theatre Club, Stage 1, 131 W.
55th St. $50. City Tix.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``LAST TRAIN TO NIBROC'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This new play by Arlene Hutton has nothing new to say, but it's
endearing nonetheless. Raleigh (Benim Foster) is a young writer
leaving his military duties in the Midwest in 1940. On a train, he
meets May (Alexandra Geis), a naive but sweet girl. During this and
the subsequent two scenes, they fall in love and plan marriage. It
offers a typical feel-good ending, laudable performances and a
minimal set. But not much more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Through Dec. 31 at Douglas Fairbanks Theatre, 432 W. 42nd St.
$45. Telecharge.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Ticket info
</P>
<P>
   Telecharge: (212) 239-6200, outside New York (800) 432-7250 or
www.telecharge.com
</P>
<P>
   Ticketmaster: (212) 307-4100, outside New York (800) 755-4000 or
www.ticketmaster.com
</P>
<P>
   Phone Tix: (212) 719-1300
</P>
<P>
   City Tix: (212) 581-1212
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
