<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0916 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT07-COX     12-06 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT EVADED ANTITRUST LAWS, GOVERNMENT CONTENDS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government, responding to a federal judge's
findings in a landmark antirust lawsuit, Monday called Microsoft
Corp. a ``classical example'' of a rogue monopolist that should be
punished under the antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Justice Department prosecutors
continued to meet with the software giant's legal team in Chicago
in an all-out drive to settle the case.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson found Nov. 5
that Microsoft had abused its monopoly power, causing harm to
consumers, competitors and other companies. Monday's filing by the
government argued that these ``findings of fact'' could lead to no
other conclusion than that the company committed wholesale
violations of the nation's 110-year-old antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson concurs with the government view, as seems likely,
and if no settlement is reached, then a new phase of the trial
would deal with specific remedies to be imposed, including the
possible breakup of the world's most highly valued company.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Jackson has named Richard Posner, the chief judge of
the U.S. Court of Appeals of the Chicago-based Seventh Circuit, as
a private mediator. In a series of meetings at Chicago's plush
Standard Club since Nov. 30, Posner has been searching for ways for
the parties to reach an accord, so far to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   The government contended Monday that Jackson's findings
established beyond a doubt that Microsoft committed ``multiple
violations'' of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
</P>
<P>
   The 1890 law, the brief noted, ``prohibits a firm with monopoly
power from maintaining that monopoly power through means that go
beyond competition on the merits.''
</P>
<P>
   As the government put it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Under those settled principles of monopolization law,
Microsoft's multiple actions to repel promising efforts to lower
the critical barrier to entry into its monopoly market constitute
unlawful maintenance of a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a classic example of a case in which a defendant's
possession of substantial market power, combined with his
exclusionary or anticompetitive behavior, threatens to defeat or
forestall the corrective forces of competition and thereby sustain
or extend the defendant's agglomeration of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the schedule set by Jackson, Microsoft is due to file its
written reply to the government brief on Jan. 17. After two further
written rebuttal exchanges, on Jan. 24 and Jan. 31, Jackson will
hear oral arguments on Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
