A0932 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     12-06 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV08-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAY UP NORTH IN FLORIDA
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Wednesday, Dec. 8)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first so-called ``cold'' front of the season moved through
Southwest Florida recently, setting off the kind of panic one
normally associates with soccer riots or a 2-point dip in the
Nasdaq index.
</P>
<P>
   The local TV stations, dedicated as they are to responsible
journalism, did everything they could to fuel the hysteria. One
forecaster warned viewers that the area was about to be ``gripped''
by the worst cold weather of the year, making it sound as though we
were embarking upon a new Ice Age and woolly mammoths would soon be
seen strolling down Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   Another forecaster, whose somber expression reminded me of
Walter Cronkite at the peak of the Cuban missile crisis, warned
viewers that temperatures would ``plummet'' during the night,
leading some of the more easily frightened citizens to conclude
that they would wake up to a world that more closely resembled the
dark side of Pluto than the semitropics.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the forecaster got around to saying that daytime
highs would only ``inch up'' into the mid-60s, most viewers were
ready to chop up their furniture for firewood and strap snow-chains
onto their tires.
</P>
<P>
   I understand that this is a highly competitive business and that
ratings would probably suffer if the forecasters avoided words like
``gripped,'' ``plummet'' and ``frosty'' to describe weather
conditions that most people could compensate for with a light
sweater and a baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   (The same philosophy, of course, spills over onto the
blood-splattered news coverage that makes our retirement
communities and mobile-home parks seem as dangerous as East Timor.
Ratings would undoubtedly suffer if the lead story consisted of a
shuffleboard outbreak in Golf Lakes Estates.)
</P>
<P>
   People who visit our area from ``Up North,'' which means any
place north of Tallahassee, think we're nuts, and understandably
so. I moved here 23 years ago from Baltimore County, which is north
of Tallahassee but still not exactly polar-bear country. All it
took was an inch of snow to close schools and most of the major
roads, which was definitely a wise move given the snow-driving
skills of your average Baltimorean.
</P>
<P>
   But even a borderline Northerner like myself was unprepared for
the panic that sets in here during the two or three weeks of the
year that are not bathing-suit weather. For the first few years I
was here, it was all I could do not to shake people by the lapels
and yell, ``It's not that cold! I've gone skinny-dipping in the
ocean in colder weather than this! Of course, I came down with a
terrible respiratory ailment! And a 104-degree fever! Which
eventually deteriorated into pneumonia and landed me in the
hospital! But at least I wasn't a pathetic whiner like you are!
Because I was knocked out on sedatives the whole time! So buck up,
will ya!''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, this tactic did little to dissuade my new
neighbors and colleagues from acting like big babies every time the
mercury dipped below 60.
</P>
<P>
   But it's OK now, because over the course of 23 years, you learn
to adjust to these things.
</P>
<P>
   Which reminds me: The temperature is supposed to plummet into
the mid-50s tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Better check the fuel in the emergency generator and dig out the
thermal underwear.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be a frosty one.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1743EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0934 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MUSICAL-RIGHTS-ART-11     12-06 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICAL-RIGHTS-ART-1120(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUARDIANS WATCH OVER NEW ``KISS ME, KATE'' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The name of the playwright John Guare is nowhere to
be found in the program for the revival of ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' which
returned last month, to critical fireworks, for its first
full-scale Broadway production in more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Guare, author of ``Six Degrees of Separation,'' played an
important role in revising parts of the musical's book, updating
the character of Harrison Howell, adding a song for the leading
lady in the second act and writing banter at the top of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Before reaching the stage, these changes had to be approved by
Lois and Arthur Elias. The couple, who live in Manhattan, were
entrusted with ``Kiss Me, Kate'' by their close friend Bella
Spewack, who wrote the musical's book with her husband, Sam, in
1948 and died at 90 in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade the Eliases have been fiercely protective
of this Cole Porter musical based on Shakespeare's ``Taming of the
Shrew,'' insisting that hardly a word be changed and that no writer
_ not even Wendy Wasserstein or Christopher Durang _ take any
credit for the script away from the Spewacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had fought for years about the script _ everybody wanted to
rewrite it completely _ and we felt, not only out of loyalty to
Bella and Sam but because it's a good script, that it shouldn't be
rewritten,'' Ms. Elias said. ``I can't tell you how many producers
and writers we have dealt with.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it has taken all this time for ``Kiss Me, Kate'' _
which originally opened on Dec. 30, 1948 _ to make its way back to
Broadway as the first major hit of this season.
</P>
<P>
   And at a time when revivals are all the rage, the story of the
musical's hesitant return raises the curtain on an obscure, insular
world of rights organizations, estates and family members, all
jealously holding the keys to some of the musical theater's most
valuable treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these holders of rights are widows like Jo Sullivan
Loesser, whose husband, Frank Loesser, wrote ``Guys and Dolls,''
and Rosemary Willson, who guards ``The Music Man,'' which is by her
husband, Meredith Willson, and is due to be revived on Broadway
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Some are appointed executors, like Harry Kraut for the Leonard
Bernstein estate and Robert Montgomery for Porter's. The work of
Rodgers and Hammerstein and Irving Berlin is overseen by the
Rodgers and Hammerstein Organization. The licensing of many theater
properties is handled by Music Theater International, while
Tams-Whitmark Music Library is the agent for several estates,
including the Spewacks'.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to granting the rights to ``first-class''
productions _ meaning shows in large, established theaters _ these
rights holders say they are diligent in making sure the work lands
in safe hands.
</P>
<P>
   And while they cannot see every stock and amateur production _
in churches, summer camps or community theaters _ these
organizations say they find out when licenses have been abused.
Like the time an Atlanta troupe set ``Oklahoma!'' in a 1941
rehearsal room and added scenes about Pearl Harbor. Or the time an
off-Broadway production set ``South Pacific'' in a rehabilitation
ward for Vietnam veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's three performances in a high school or six weeks
in a dinner theater,'' said Bert Fink, a spokesman for the Rodgers
and Hammerstein Organization, ``we take it seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Several noted that ``Kiss Me, Kate'' was being celebrated for
having been revived largely intact, unlike new interpretations such
as Sam Mendes' gritty ``Cabaret'' or Nicholas Hytner's dark
``Carousel.'' In choreographing the current ``Kate,'' Kathleen
Marshall said she drew on her experience as the artistic director
of the Encores series, which presents concert versions of classic
musicals at City Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned to trust the material,'' Ms. Marshall said. ``To
first say, `Let's use what was there and deviate when necessary.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bella Spewack willed all of her intellectual property to Arthur
Elias, now 74, a painter, and Ms. Elias, 73, whom the Spewacks met
on a trip to France in 1961. ``Bella had no children,'' Ms. Elias
said. ``For many, many years, we were her children.''
</P>
<P>
   For the current ``Kate,'' Ms. Elias, who used to work in public
relations, regularly sat in on rehearsals, comparing the original
book with what she saw coming to life onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the cast and the creative team say they wondered
what she was thinking, whether she approved. ``It always made me a
little nervous,'' said Lee Wilkof, who plays one of the gangsters
in the revival. ``I wanted a little reassurance from her, because
she was so familiar with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Elias had reason to be initially watchful. She and her
husband had rejected several proposals in the past, feeling they
went too far.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Elias said that one writer whom he would not name rewrote
the book so much that the two gangsters _ whose portrayal received
rave reviews earlier this month _ were taken out. ``We would not
sign a contract where major modifications were made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spurned ``Kate'' writers have included Ms. Wasserstein, Durang
and James Lapine, who in addition to revising the book would have
directed the musical, to have been produced by Fran and Barry
Weissler. Lapine said his production fell apart because he couldn't
find a cast before the rights ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wasserstein said her proposal some years ago _ which also
had Michael Blakemore, who staged the current revival, attached as
director _ broke down because of the Eliases. ``They were concerned
that I would take credit,'' Ms. Wasserstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Had she moved ahead, Ms. Wasserstein said, one issue she would
have addressed is why the leading lady, Lilli Vanessi, returns in
the end to Fred Graham, the leading man and her former husband,
having left to marry Harrison Howell.
</P>
<P>
   Durang was brought in to work on the script in 1994 by the New
York Shakespeare Festival, which planned to revive the show in
Central Park and then on Broadway, featuring Kevin Kline and Mary
Elizabeth Mastrantonio.
</P>
<P>
   The project unraveled, Durang said, because the timing was too
rushed and the Eliases did not feel they had the assurances they
needed. Had he moved forward, Durang said, he planned in part to
flesh out what happened to the production's show within the show
when Lilli quits before intermission. Did she have an understudy,
for example? ``I was sorry our version didn't come together,''
Durang said.
</P>
<P>
   The Eliases said they were not trying to be obstructionist,
merely responsible. ``We had great difficulty over this business of
saying no, because if you say no, there is no production,'' Ms.
Elias said. ``But it has to be the right team.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While revivals are often stymied by casting problems _ the
character of Fred in ``Kiss Me, Kate'' is considered particularly
tough to fill _ rights holders say the book generally proves to be
the greatest stumbling block, particularly with those star-driven
productions of the 1920s and '30s, before the plot-driven musical
defined by ``Oklahoma!'' in 1943 had fully evolved.
</P>
<P>
   Several rights holders talked about producers who have proposed
wholesale changes that make old chestnuts seem downright
avant-garde. ``Sometimes I think we should encourage them to write
their own shows,'' said Kraut of the Bernstein estate.
</P>
<P>
   When a Japanese producer wanted to set ``West Side Story'' in
Tokyo and make the conflict between Koreans and Japanese, Kraut
said, he asked what the producer intended to do with the song
``America.'' ``I never heard back from him,'' Kraut said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Kim Kowalke, president of the Kurt Weill
Foundation for Music, said he was practically begging producers to
rethink that German composer's work in contemporary terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had the problem of producers' coming with creative
ideas,'' Kowalke said. One should not attempt to duplicate Weill's
work, he added, ``because you've got a whole different culture
outside the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The obstacle to reviving Weill, Kowalke said, is not only that
his musicals tended to be centered on issues specific to the 1940s
but that audiences today are likely to find Weill strange. ``In the
'40s Broadway was big enough to accommodate about four or five
different strands,'' Kowalke said. ``Nowadays Broadway's much more
homogenized, and it doesn't seem to have those different
audiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it was noted mostly for its updated approach to
American Indians, Peter Stone's revision of Irving Berlin's ``Annie
Get Your Gun'' for Broadway last year also included several
significant structural changes.
</P>
<P>
   Stone is currently revising ``Finian's Rainbow'' and said he
found himself having to ratchet up the story's racial tensions to
make them as shocking as they were when the show was first produced
in 1947. Stone called it ``politically incorrecting something.''
</P>
<P>
   Why should playwrights like Guare, Stone or Durang get involved
in a revival at all? ``The fact of having a musical to play with
was an irresistible joy,'' Guare said. ``There's always that
fantasy of saying, `I know how to fix that show.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of Roger Berlind, the producer who initiated the
project, Guare said he was direct with the Eliases about the things
in ``Kate'' that he felt had to be addressed. But Guare also
declined credit and told them he did not want to mess with a good
thing. ``All we wanted to do was let the piece speak for itself,''
he said, ``just invigorating it, not rethinking it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Eliases those were the magic words. ``Arthur and I felt
when we met with him that this was a writer who really valued
another writer's work,'' Ms. Elias said. ``He had no need to
promote himself.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Guare got the green light and, with Blakemore, went to
work. Their main contribution was to enliven the character of
Harrison Howell, Lilli's fiance, changing him from a dull senator
originally modeled on the presidential adviser Bernard Baruch to a
blustery Gen. MacArthur type. The collaborators also added Porter's
song ``From This Moment On,'' for Harrison and Lilli, which was
part of the 1953 MGM movie version of ``Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   They also had to wrestle with the sexism in the play, given that
Kate gets spanked and ends the show with the song ``I Am Ashamed
That Women Are So Simple.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we say that in 1999 without having every woman in the
audience rise up?'' Guare asked. In adjusting it, he said, he and
Blakemore structured the musical's final moments as a ``coming to
sanity, not a giving up of her being.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps most significantly, they added a crucial stage
direction: Lilli winks. ``We wanted to make it a very fair battle
between two lovers,'' Guare said.
</P>
<P>
   The Eliases said their main directive was that Lilli and Fred
clearly adore each other. ``They can't get enough of one another,''
Ms. Elias said. ``If you don't have that, you don't have `Kiss Me,
Kate.''' Her husband added, ``They're both humbled and equalized by
love.''
</P>
<P>
   On opening night, after watching a Harrison Howell scene, Ms.
Elias said she turned to Guare, seated a few rows back, and gave
him a thumbs-up. (Guare said she blew him a kiss.)
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in their tranquil living room a few days later, the
Eliases had nothing but praise for Guare and Blakemore, saying they
could not be happier with how the whole experience turned out. The
show's prospects as a blockbuster seemed almost irrelevant to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been a big success but it was wrong in terms of what
Bella and Sam Spewack wrote,'' Ms. Elias said, ``we would feel as
though we had not been good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   As for how Guare feels about being the invisible hand behind the
hit, he said he had been enjoying his rapidly diminishing
anonymity. He particularly gets a kick when friends rave to him
about the revival, completely unaware of his association with it.
``They say, `We saw the best show last night,''' Guare said. ```You
must see it.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
