<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAHAM: COLOMBIA'S ECONOMIC, DRUG PROBLEMS THREAT TO REGION'S
STABILITY
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Colombia, the oldest democracy in South America, is
facing a dual crisis of rising violence and a declining economy,
Sen. Bob Graham warned Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in violence comes from a new alliance between the
entrenched guerrilla movements and a restructured narcotics
industry, Graham said in a telephone conference with reporters
after a four-day trip that included stops in Haiti, Colombia and
Panama.
</P>
<P>
   The three-term Florida Democrat said illicit drug money pumped
into the guerrilla movements has allowed them to stockpile
armaments and beef up communications making them more deadly than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the once-flourishing Colombian economy has fallen
into a depression with unemployment around 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The result: A surge in the number of Colombians seeking to leave
the country.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials in Bogota told Graham that the number of
Colombians expected to come to the United States this year could be
as high as 350,000, compared to 200,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the cooperation between Colombia's drug cartels and
guerrillas has also spurred the country's military to become
involved in fighting narco-traffickers, Graham said. That job
previously had been left primarily to the undermanned Colombian
police forces.
</P>
<P>
   And Colombian President Andres Pastrana has proposed a $7.5
billion economic redevelopment plan for his country. Half of that
money would come from the international community, including $1.5
billion from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said Pastrana told him during a breakfast last week that
he has been assured President Clinton would place the aid request
before Congress early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Aiding Colombia is in the United States' vital interest, Graham
said, noting that ``its destabilization has the potential of
affecting the other countries around it,'' particularly Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to visiting Colombia, Graham spent a day in Haiti, which
he described as ``a nation in limbo politically and economically.''
</P>
<P>
   The result of parliamentary elections early next year, Graham
predicted, ``will determine whether it begins to move forward ...
or continues the slide that it has experienced in the last two or
three years.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
