<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another look at Nat Turner's rebellion
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tony Horwitz, whose award-winning book ``Confederates in the
Attic'' examined the lingering obsession with the Civil War,
revisits the controversy surrounding Nat Turner and his slave
rebellion in a compelling article in this week's New Yorker ($3).
</P>
<P>
   Turner's rebellion in 1831 in Southampton County, Va., was one
of the bloodiest in history. Armed with broadaxes and other farm
tools, Turner and 60 other slaves slaughtered 57 men, women and
children. Dismissed as a God-crazed madman by some historians,
Turner was the subject of ``The Confessions of Nat Turner,'' a
fiercely debated 1967 novel by William Styron.
</P>
<P>
   Published at the height of the black power movement, Styron's
Pulitzer Prize-winning novel was attacked by black leaders. Now,
Horwitz writes, the mood has changed, and Spike Lee is interested
in filming the book to show a more complete portrait of Turner.
Some of the violence, however, may be hard to stomach, Lee notes.
``We're not going to have Nat Turner Happy Meals at McDonald's.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Images of a generation: In an impressive 256-page issue,
Rolling Stone ($4.95) presents a fascinating collection of some of
the greatest images of music and culture from the past
half-century. Many photographs will be familiar, but others have
never been published. Among the most memorable pictures are Barron
Wolman's 1967 shot of the Grateful Dead on the front porch of its
Ashbury Street residence in San Francisco after a drug raid; Janis
Joplin slumped on a couch with a bottle of Southern Comfort
backstage at Winterland in San Francisco; B.B. King, John Lee
Hooker and the late Willie Dixon relaxing at the pool at the Sunset
Marquis Hotel in Los Angeles in 1991; and Annie Leibovitz's 1972
shot of Tom Wolfe _ before he began wearing his traditional white
suit _ posing at Cape Kennedy while researching ``The Right
Stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best list: In a special year-end issue, Spin ($2.99) names
Atlanta rap group TLC's ``No Scrubs'' as single of the year. Album
of the year goes to Nine Inch Nails for ``The Fragile,'' and Rage
Against the Machine takes top honors as band of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wireless wonders: According to a U.S. News &AMP; World Report
($3.50) poll, many Americans are frustrated with their computers.
Millions of PCs apparently are stashed away in closets or in dusty
corners because their owners consider them too complicated. What
consumers are looking for, the magazine reports, are easier ways to
tap into the Internet and communicate with each other. This trend
is already evident in Finland, where technology guru Mato Valtonen
(former lead singer of the Leningrad Cowboys) has developed WapIT,
a new system that allows mobile phones to tap into the Internet.
Users can check sports results and the latest musical releases and
even download the joke of the day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Battle of Seattle: Newsweek ($3.50) reflects on the protests
in Seattle over the World Trade Organization meeting and predicts
more demonstrations from this odd coalition of environmentalists,
labor activists and '60s liberals, all organized via the Internet.
Weighing in on the issue in Time ($3.50), columnist Charles
Krauthammer criticizes the protesters as kooks. These are some of
the same people who opposed military intervention in El Salvador
and Nicaragua because they insisted the problem was one of poverty.
``Well,'' Krauthammer writes, ``it turns out that the best cure for
the poverty the left so agonized about then is precisely what the
left is demonstrating against today _ capitalism and trade.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Media notes: Atlanta-based Jezebel magazine has joined forces
with radio executives Lew and John Dickey in a new media venture
that is yet to be named. Jezebel founders Joshua Goodhart and Adam
Capes said the new company will be a platform for additional
publishing ventures in Atlanta and throughout the country. Jezebel,
a celebrity- and fashion-oriented magazine, was launched three
years ago and has a circulation of 50,000, Goodhart said. The
Dickeys, officers in Cumulus Media, own Kiss 104.7 (WALR-FM),
WCNN-AM (680) and WFOM-AM (1230) in Atlanta and other stations in
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
