<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KORBEL-RUNS-DRY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE END IS NEAR: KORBEL SAYS IT'S ALL OUT OF CHAMPAGNE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PEG MELNIK   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Korbel Champagne Cellars, trademarked ``The
Official Champagne of the Millennium,'' has a Y2K complication:
It's out of champagne.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true,'' said Gary Heck, president and chairman of the
Russian River winery. ``We're sold out. We could not sell one more
bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   Korbel has lots of champagne for future years. But Heck sold his
last available bottle of champagne on Nov. 15, running through 1.59
million cases. While plenty of Korbel bottles remain on store
shelves, the winery has no more bottles to sell to distributors and
retailers this year, Heck said.
</P>
<P>
   With less than four weeks to go until the century's last New
Year's Eve, the much-hyped champagne shortage appears to be part
fact, part fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers may have trouble buying high-end French Champagnes and
small-lot California sparkling wines for the millennium, according
to a survey of local vintners and sommeliers. Aside from that,
there will be plenty to uncork.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out at the winery. We believe it will be in the
retailers. What we can't guarantee is the price,'' said Kristie
Nackord, spokeswoman for Domaine Chandon, a sparkling wine producer
in Yountville.
</P>
<P>
   While its reserve wines were snapped up long ago, Domaine
Chandon's mass market brands are in ample supply, Nackord said.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Ferrer Champagne Caves in Sonoma still has wine left to
sell in its tasting room, but has allocated all of its dwindling
inventory in the warehouse to distributors, spokeswoman Eva Bertran
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all wanted more, but we just couldn't supply it,''
Bertran said. ``It's pretty crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although distributors still have some Korbel products, it is
unclear whether they have enough champagne to keep store shelves
stocked through the year's end, said Ryan Barella, a Northern
California marketing manager with Brown-Forman, Korbel's marketing
and sales partner.
</P>
<P>
   Korbel and other champagne producers sell 70 percent of their
product in November and December. However, most typically have some
inventory left after New Year's Day to carry them until the new
vintage is released.
</P>
<P>
   Distributors in some states are running short on Korbel product
and requesting more, Heck said, citing sales reports from
Brown-Forman.
</P>
<P>
   Although Korbel has promoted itself as the official champagne of
the millennium, Heck said he wasn't embarrassed by a potential
shortage. ``We produced 30 percent more champagne than we ever had
in the history of Korbel and we produced as much as we possibly
could with our facility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Korbel produced 350,000 more cases than it did in 1998 in
anticipation of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   A shortage of champagne is good news and bad news for Korbel.
Like all businesses, wineries try to sell everything they make. But
if Korbel sells out too soon, it faces an agonizing decision:
Should it delve into next year's supply of bubbly to meet demand or
allow retailers to run out of champagne and risk losing shelf space
to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to lose shelf space,'' Heck said. ``It's a
difficult task to regain, but hopefully that won't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Korbel could see its territory on store shelves filled by
cheaper champagnes that can be produced in 30 days, Heck said.
Korbel champagnes require 18 months to produce because they are
made in the traditional French process called methode champenoise.
</P>
<P>
   Korbel, which spent about $25 million in promotions this year,
has tried to tightly associate its 11 styles of champagne with the
upcoming millennium celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Korbel is the first official worldwide sponsor of the Times
Square 2000 celebration in New York City. In 1997, Korbel signed a
10-year sponsorship with The Times Square Business Improvement
District, which stages the New Year's Eve party watched around the
world on TV. Korbel paid ``in the millions'' for this agreement,
spokeswoman Margie Healy said.
</P>
<P>
   Korbel also has trademarked ``The Official Champagne of the
Millennium'' for use in packaging, advertising and promotion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
