<HEADLINE>
AFTER 70 YEARS, A SMOOTHER TRIP TO THE SOUTH POLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
repeating to add art note (ART ADV: Photos NYT 24-25 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seventy years ago last week, Adm. Richard E. Byrd became the
first person to fly over the South Pole, in a Ford tri-motor
aircraft that had a cruising speed of about 90 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd had to navigate by sighting the sun, because the effects of
the magnetic pole made his compasses useless.
</P>
<P>
   And because his plane could not land at the pole, he simply
dropped an American flag to prove he had made it to 90 degrees
south latitude.
</P>
<P>
   On the anniversary of Byrd's flight, a crew from the New York
Air National Guard flew a ski-equipped LC-130 aircraft on a supply
mission to the pole. The New York Guard is the only military
organization that flies ski-equipped aircraft. But its planes can
fly at 250 mph, 26,000 feet up, and carry computers, satellite
links, radar and a gyroscope.
</P>
<P>
   When the crew members landed, they could stay in the buildings
of the Amundsen-Scott South Pole base, where the galley has won
renown for having ``the best food on the continent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
