<P>
   AIRTRAN-SABRETECH _ Verdict in AirTran-SabreTech case. (Palm
Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   IVESTER RETIRES
</P>
<P>
   COKE-IVESTER _ ATLANTA _ Douglas Ivester retires unexpectedly as
chairman of Coca-Cola. In a recent interview with The
Journal-Constitition, Ivester was upbeat about Coca-Cola's
prospects. Earnings, which have been in the tank, were expected to
see a turnaround for the fourth quarter and Ivester expected the
company to double its business in the next eight to 12 months. He
recently restructured his management lineup to streamline
decisionmaking. And the stock was back on its way up after a dismal
performance this year. Given the outlook, it came as a shock to
many when he announced his planned retirement in April 2000,
especially since the 52-year-old would be shy of retirement age,
which is 56 at the company. A look at what may have prompted the
decision, including Ivester's style of management. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   w/COKE_BOARD _ ATLANTA _ All along Coca-Cola's board, including
James Williams and Warren Buffett, have expressed confidence that
Doug Ivester was the man to lead take the company forward. Was
there a concerted effort to get him to change his mind and stay, or
did the board simply thank him his service. A look at board
reaction to the resignation. (Saporta, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COKE-DAFT _ ATLANTA _ While Douglas Daft may not be a name
familiar to many outside Coca-Cola, the native Australian has been
with the company for 30 years. He will be chosen by the Coke board
to replace Ivester as chairman and chief executive officer. In the
interim he will be president and chief operating officer. Ivester
says Daft is ``perfectly suited to lead this company in its
continuing efforts to build value for all its share owners.'' A
look at Daft's background and what may, or may not, make him suited
for the job. (Kempner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COKE-WALLSTREET _Coca-Cola's stock, which had reached a low of
$47 in recent months but had climbed into the high 60s recently,
took a hit after Ivester's announcement. The stock remained down at
midday, and at least one analyst downgraded the stock from ``buy''
to ``neutral.'' A look at Wall Street's reaction to the
announcement. (Luke, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING-AT&AMP;T DEAL
</P>
<P>
   ATT-MINDSPRING _ Where's the Earthlink in MindSpring'd deal with
AT&AMP;T to provide high speed Internet access? How does this deal,
which lays the groundwork for other ISPs to offer cable Internet
access, impact the industry? 15.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ATT-EXCITE _ Excite, the ISP for cable operators, has an
exclusive contract with AT&AMP;T and other cable operators including
Cox Communications until mid 2002. How does AT&AMP;T's about face on
open access of its cable for competiting Internet service
providers, affect the future of Excite Home. We ask analysts and
cable operators. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   ATT-BELLSOUTH _ Almost two decades after its phone monopoly was
broken, AT&AMP;T appears to be ready to shake its massive head and
assume a leadership role in the lucrative world of
telecommunications and digital access. What does this portend for
BellSouth and other competitors. (Holsendolph, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   HDEPOT-CANADA _ Home Depot's Canadian competition is heating up
as the retailer extends its national reach. Revy Home Centres, the
second-largest home improvement retailer in Canada, plans a major
expansion in Toronto and Quebec. That would combat recent growth
plans by Atlanta-based Home Depot in those markets. (Bond, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is available now. Art includes four color photographs, 1
photo illustration.
</P>
