<HEADER>
A0954 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-GREED-COX     12-06 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GREED-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   4-hour version of silent film a winner
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Eyman
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When director Erich von Stroheim was a
newly arrived immigrant to America, one of the first books he read
was Frank Norris' fascinating 1899 novel ``McTeague.'' It's the
story of an amiable lug from Placer County, Calif., who becomes a
dentist in turn-of-the-century San Francisco, then begins a long,
slow slide into lethargy and degradation that culminates in him
murdering his miserly wife and dying a hunted fugitive in Death
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it's not a laugh riot. But it is a virtuoso piece of
naturalism, a shock to the system of the then-prevalent Victorian
style, and a book that can still be read with pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   As his directorial career heated up in the early '20s, Stroheim
was determined to make ``McTeague'' his dream project _ a literal,
exhaustively detailed adaptation of Norris' novel, shot in the
actual locations described in the book, including Death Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Six months after Stroheim started shooting, he had a movie _ a
very long movie. Stroheim's initial cut was eight hours, which he
knew was out of the question. He was trying to get it down to four
hours _ still basically out of the question _ when he was trampled
by stampeding events.
</P>
<P>
   The Goldwyn company, which had originally financed the movie,
merged into Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer, headed by Irving Thalberg, who had
already fired Stroheim once, from Universal's ``Foolish Wives.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess what happened?
</P>
<P>
   Under Thalberg's supervision, ``Greed'' _ the movie's new title
_ was edited down to slightly more than two hours in a respectable
job. Stroheim's uncut version, shown just once for an invited
preview audience, has been the cinema's Holy Grail for 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Schmidlin, fresh from his restoration of Orson Welles'
Touch of Evil, has embarked on a similar project for Stroheim's
masterpiece. Schmidlin's version premiered on the invaluable Turner
Classic Movies.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidlin didn't have any more actual film footage to work with,
but he did have over 600 stills from the complete cut of the film,
and he intersperses those with the pre-existing version of
Stroheim's film.
</P>
<P>
   He has also taken the trouble to color a number of images that
Stroheim indicated were to be tinted, usually gold _ coins, a large
gold tooth that McTeague hangs outside his office on Polk Street
(the building is still there, by the way.)
</P>
<P>
   Using stills to paper over missing footage has never worked well
in the past. In the restored versions of films such as ``Lost
Horizon'' or the 1954 ``A Star is Born,'' there's a palpable
disequilibrium. The soundtrack grinds on while you suddenly shift
from watching a movie to watching a photo album.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the stills don't get in the way with a silent
film nearly as much as with a talkie. Mostly, I would guess this is
because of the more abstract, dream-like nature of silent films.
They're inherently unrealistic anyway _ physically, the art form
they most resemble is ballet, but with the emotions of opera.
</P>
<P>
   What Schmidlin has wrought is a four-hour version of the film,
something approaching Stroheim's intentions, with a new,
serviceable musical score composed by Robert Israel.
</P>
<P>
   What is gained? A strong sense of Stroheim's vast, over-arching
composition: Zola-esque, determinist, class-oriented (Norris was
clearly close to Jack London's brand of socialism), a beautifully
detailed panoply of life's underachievers undone by a malevolent
fate and their own bubbling anger.
</P>
<P>
   What is lost? Mostly, dramatic compression. When the time came
to cut the film down, MGM excised all of Norris' subplots to
concentrate on McTeague and his wife Trina. A story about an
obsessive junk dealer and his doomed wife, which MGM cut almost
completely, plays as slightly redundant; it's essentially the same
story as Mac and Trina, with different faces.
</P>
<P>
   Another story, about an elderly couple who gently court each
other in the same boarding house, seems like a pleasant but
inessential appendage, calculated relief from the rest of the grim
goings-on.
</P>
<P>
   What leaps out at you in the new version is Stroheim's audacity;
nothing like ``Greed'' had ever been attempted, and nothing like it
would be for another 40 years, until movies like ``Rocco and his
Brothers,'' or, later, ``Jean de Florette'' and ``Manon of the
Spring.'' Needless to say, those were all European in origin.
</P>
<P>
   Stroheim's style was classical and quite beautiful; the camera
rarely moves, is invariably in the right place, and he uses some
startlingly innovative deep-focus shots, years before cameraman
Gregg Toland and Orson Welles nabbed the credit by shooting all of
``Citizen Kane'' in that style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greed'' has always been a must-see for buffs, but Schmidlin
has placed it in its proper dramatic context. This year, Christmas
comes early.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Eyman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
