<HEADER>
A0955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MEDICAL-MISTAKES-COX     12-06 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-MISTAKES-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Medical mistakes: A prescription for danger
</P>
<P>
   By Diane Lore
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sabrina Gibbs picked baby animals for her nursery's
theme, painting the walls a light lavender and building a wooden
palm tree for tiny stuffed monkeys to swing.
</P>
<P>
   At night, she would sit in the nursery, more than eight months
pregnant, and sing:
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you, Norman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   You are my first born, brand-new
</P>
<P>
   Oh Norman, we love you.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gibbs also had gestational diabetes. And she needed a weekly
test to make sure neither she nor her fetus were in distress.
Unknown to her and her physician, however, the medical assistant
failed to schedule the test as ordered. And then failed to notify
anyone she hadn't done it.
</P>
<P>
   That cascaded into a series of medical miscommunications. A
second doctor assumed the test had been done because of the first
doctor's orders. So he didn't ask Gibbs about it and didn't
re-order the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on a Sunday, she stopped feeling the baby move. That
morning, she assumed it was because the baby was just sleeping. But
that night, she and her husband, Norman, rushed to the emergency
room. There they learned Norman Jr. was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was simply devastating,'' said Gibbs, who last year won a
$1.5 million jury verdict against Kaiser Foundation Health Plan of
Georgia Inc., which contracted the practice for services.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do everything you can _ I was giving myself insulin
injections three times a day _ and then you learn you lost your
baby because of something that was totally preventable,'' she said.
``You can't fathom the pain of it .''
</P>
<P>
   A new report issued by the National Academy of Sciences finds
medical mistakes like the one that claimed Gibbs' son occur far too
frequently, killing between 44,000 and 98,000 patients a year. And
although more than half of the mistakes don't result in serious
complications, experts say the study's findings emphasize that
consumers must check and re-check the care they receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still this myth of perfection,'' said Dr. Richard
Kaine, director of Quality Management Resources Limited in Buford,
a national consulting firm that evaluates hospitals' operations and
quality. ``People in health care are typically very dedicated, very
bright and very competent. But that's resulted in a system that
always assumes they'll get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   In real life, health care workers are still mere mortals. And
when coupled with increased scientific complexity and financial
pressure to do more with less, there's more opportunity to get it
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription errors top the list for medical mistakes. More than
2.5 billion prescriptions are written each year, solving everything
from anxiety to impotence. And each month, the average hospital
fills more than 15,000 doses a month.
</P>
<P>
   More than 7,000 patients died in 1993 from errors related to
prescriptions, according to the academy's report. And experts say
that figure is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's three things that happen with prescriptions: You get
the wrong medication, you get the wrong dosage of medication or you
take the medication at the wrong time,'' said Charles Inlander,
executive director of the People's Medical Society, a non-profit
health care consumer group in Allentown, Penn. ``In any case, it's
not going to help you get well.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is consumers can protect themselves by taking
several simple steps. When the doctor orders a prescription, a
patient should not rely on the handwritten prescription. Instead,
consumers should ask for the name of the drug, and what it is
supposed to do. The physician should print the prescription, if the
order is not being filed electronically.
</P>
<P>
   When at a hospital, the patient or a family member should
double-check the basics with the nurse _ the patient's name, the
type of medicine and the dosage _ every time a pill or I.V.
medication is given. And if you're picking up a prescription at a
drug store, take two minutes to verify the medication with the
pharmacist. That's especially important in today's drug stores
where some pharmacists are filling more than 400 orders a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to trust health care professionals. But we are
nowhere near perfect and mistakes can be made,'' said William W.
Smith, a pharmacist at Kings' Drugs on Peachtree Road.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, mistakes are not dramatic - the removal of the
wrong leg or organ of a patient - but are the result of obvious
breaches of good common sense or failure to pay attention to
details. ``Most often, it is a case of a patient simply falling
through the cracks,'' said Tom Sampson, an Atlanta medical
malpractice attorney with Thomas Kennedy, Sampson and Patterson.
``It's a case of someone not doing the follow-up that's needed.''
</P>
<P>
   And experts say medical mistakes occur more frequently than the
figures reported because so much of the medical system operates
outside the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get more information about the CIA than about
hospitals,'' Inlander said. ``The medical system really is the last
bastion of non-consumerism.'' Consumers can compare the energy
rating of refrigerators, but can't compare the infection rates of
Atlanta hospitals. He or she can check the Internet to see how a
car performs, but not how his or her heart surgeon performs.
</P>
<P>
   And if a hospital worker makes a mistake, the description of the
error is not recorded in the patient chart, but in a separate
incident report. The premise is that hospitals should have the
right to correct problems without constant fear of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates say these practices are outdated and
sometimes used as a way to dodge accountability.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the number of medical mistakes, some facilities are
taking steps to improve safety.
</P>
<P>
   At Emory Hospitals, for example, an automated robotic dispensing
system is now used to administer prescriptions, eliminating the
possibility of human error, said spokeswoman Rashel Stephenson. And
nationwide, hospitals are instituting programs that allow doctors
to enter their orders through computer systems, narrowing the
possibility that orders for tests and drugs fall through the
cracks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many medical facilities are instituting best
practice guidelines, which provide a standard directive for care in
certain situations - something experts say will reduce errors.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a airline pilot is required to run through a check
list every time he flies . It's not that he doesn't know how to fly
the plane, Kaine said, but because it's one final chance to make
sure everything is in order.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons, on the other hand, have no such checklists.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I bet if they had to hop on the table next to you, they
sure would,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs, 35, is convinced such consistency is the reason that her
two other pregnancies in the past five years went smoothly.
Although she had gestational diabetes with both children, now 4 and
2 years old, her new doctor kept everything on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like night and day,'' Gibbs said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, experts say consumers need to take matters into
their own hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of putting all your trust in Marcus Welby are long
over,'' said Sampson. ``Because even though a lot of people in
medicine are well-intentioned, no one cares about your health like
you do. Be proactive and protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
