<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SEAJET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Skimming the surface: JetFoil struts its stuff
 &HT;    (EDS: Runs with TRAVEL-FREEPORT, TRAVEL-FREESHOP.)
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREEPORT, Bahamas _ Last month, I flew over to the Bahamas. But
without the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   I took the SeaJet Kara, a 250-passenger Boeing JetFoil, one of
only two operating in U.S. waters. The SeaJet, a hydrofoil, flew
from West Palm Beach, Fla., to Freeport going 50 mph and riding 14
to 16 feet above the water.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is 80 percent aviation and 20 percent maritime,
says SeaJet CEO George Bradley. ``We say it's a vessel that
flies.''
</P>
<P>
   The boat left the Port of Palm Beach with its hull in the water,
but once we were past the inlet, it rose out of the ocean on two
18-foot-long struts. On the end of the front strut is a small
airplane-type wing with flaps that help steer, and on the wide
strut on the back is a long airplane-type wing.
</P>
<P>
   There are no propellers. The boat's water-propulsion system is
powered by two 8,200-hp Allison gas turbines, pushing 48,000
gallons per minute.
</P>
<P>
   It took 99 minutes of flying time and two hours dock to dock to
get to Freeport. Fishermen, freighter crews and tourists at both
harbors snapped photos of this weird jet-boat as it flew across the
water.
</P>
<P>
   The SeaJets were designed by Boeing and built in Seattle in
1982. Kara and a sister SeaJet, Kristen, which also offers service
between West Palm Beach and Freeport, both operated in the English
Channel before that company went out of business when the English
Channel Tunnel was finished.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 40 Boeing SeaJets working worldwide, all owned by
German businessman Sven Paulsen, operate in Hong Kong and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Kara's interior resembles a very wide-bodied jet, with fold-down
tray tables on the seat backs. Complimentary coffee, soft drinks
and cookies were handed out by flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   The motion of the boat was similar to the slight side-to-side
swaying of a train. On the flight out, unusually high seas made it
difficult to drink out of a coffee cup as we crossed the Gulf
Stream, but it wasn't the rolling motion that causes seasickness.
On the return trip, the movement was as smooth as a new Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers should count on three hours or so of travel, including
time to get through Customs at both ends.
</P>
<P>
   For those who hate to fly the small planes to Freeport and who
don't want to ride the waves to get there, the SeaJet might be the
perfect alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Rates are $99 round-trip from West Palm Beach, Fla., for adults;
$49, kids ages 3 to 16. There's also a $25 arrival/departure tax.
Ask about hotel-SeaJet packages. Call (561) 844-3383 or visit
www.SeaJets.com. The SeaJet leaves from the Port of Palm Beach
twice daily, at 9 a.m. and 4:30 p.m. Thursday through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Blackerby writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
