<HEADER>
A0963 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-RHODA-COX     12-06 1418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHODA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life after ``Rhoda'' good for Harper
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ What could a man-hungry, anxiety-riddled
sitcom sidekick from the Bronx and a Nobel Prize-winning
missionary's daughter who opened our eyes to China through her
novels and human rights activism possibly have in common?
</P>
<P>
   Fictional Rhoda Morgenstern and the very real Pearl S. Buck are
separated by only one degree through Valerie Harper, the former
Broadway hoofer turned television icon who is back onstage at the
Royal Poinciana Playhouse beginning Tuesday with her one-woman show
about Buck, ``All Under Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how long she portrays the author of ``The Good Earth''
and some 70 other books _ and the 59-year-old Harper hopes it's
long after the gray wig she dons nightly is superfluous _ she will
always be linked in the public's mind with Morgenstern. After all,
she played her from 1970-74 on ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' and
another four years on the spinoff series ``Rhoda,'' walking off
with a quartet of Emmys for her brassy, kvetchy comic efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Even when she prepared to face audiences as Buck last year
off-Broadway, Harper worried that they were really looking for
glimpses of Rhoda. ``It had been a fear before we started, but the
audience is just darling in their willingness to suspend
disbelief,'' she says, without a trace of Morgenstern's telltale
New Yawk accent. ``We didn't know whether it would work. Not only
the disbelief that it's Valerie, but that it's not Rhoda and that
it is Pearl, a woman that's going to be 80 and has cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper was acclaimed in New York for her recreation of Buck,
even impressing critics who considered her a mere television
actress. ``Yeah, they lie in wait. It's just that if you come from
television, any television person has to prove herself,'' she
concedes. ``I did too, even though I spent most of my life in
theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet just when Harper has proven there is life and career after
Rhoda, she is heading back to the comfort of her most familiar
role. Prior to coming to South Florida for a mini-road tour of
``All Under Heaven,'' she filmed a made-for-TV movie called ``Mary
and Rhoda.'' Scheduled to air on ABC at the end of February's
ratings sweeps month, it showcases Rhoda and Mary Richards 20 years
later, as they deal with the comic challenges of being single
mothers of college-age daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a reunion show, in that it's all about going
forward,'' Harper is quick to explain. ``The whole point of the
movie (is) where have they been, where are they now and where are
they going.'' If it pulls in the viewers she and producer-husband
Tony Cacciotti hope for, chances are it could become a weekly
series.
</P>
<P>
   Harper no longer frets over being associated with Rhoda, as if
that were possible. ``I don't know how more saturated we could
be,'' she says, noting the continued exposure of ``The Mary Tyler
Moore Show'' and ``Rhoda'' in syndication. ``I used to be worried
about it, but I feel like I owe the fans big time. So I got my
Bronx accent out again, polished it up. It was great. Mary and I,
we're like an old vaudeville team that knows each other so well.''
</P>
<P>
   At this moment, however, this vaudevillian is performing solo.
For years, she and Cacciotti had talked about creating a stage show
for her _ a ``Mark Twain Tonight!'' _ something to take on tour
between television and film projects. If they could find the right
historical subject, she says, ``we knew that we would make money on
the road, that we would have it for the rest of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, the choice of Buck is a tribute to Harper's mother.
``My mother loved her,'' she says. ``She had her books around the
house forever.'' And an assist goes to Dom DeLuise's wife, Carol,
who sent Harper a Christmas card each year. In it would be a note
that a donation had been made in her name to the Pearl S. Buck
Foundation, which works worldwide on behalf of needy children,
particularly those of American servicemen and Asian mothers. It was
enough to pique Harper's curiosity, so she hit the books, working
her way through the Buck canon, and now proudly announces that she
is up to 68 of the author's works.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it took three-and-a-half years before Harper had a play
ready to open in New York, having first gone through a couple of
directors, a writer and a completely different script. Eventually,
Harper cowrote ``All Under Heaven'' with Oakland playwright Dyke
Garrison, piecing together a portrait of Buck at 79 _ a year before
her death in 1973 _ seen in her Vermont farmhouse, preparing to
return to China, now under a Communist rule that she had been so
critical of.
</P>
<P>
   Using her background in Second City improvisational comedy and
an offshoot called Story Theatre, they fashioned a play in which
Harper becomes some 18 characters from Buck's past, ranging from
Buck's impersonation of Richard Nixon to a Chinese dowager queen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was what I really worked hard on,'' she says. ``Every
time an Asian character enters the play, making them each a
particular figure. I mean we all remember Mickey Rooney, God love
his soul, in ``Breakfast at Tiffany's.'' I remember at the time
thinking, `What's he doing with the buck teeth and the accent?' So
that was the furthest thing from what we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Among her achievements, Buck was able to give the world a more
accurate view of Asia, counteracting the Hollywood stereotypes.
``She wrote of Asians as human beings,'' says Harper. ``We thought
that they were so mysterious, unknowable. The inscrutable East, the
Dragon Lady with long fingernails. Pearl opened up China and she
wrote with Chinese eyes. She did more than anyone for race
relations and opening up the global village.''
</P>
<P>
   Although much of ``All Under Heaven'' will be new information
about Buck for most audiences, Harper and Cacciotti were determined
that it not come across as academic. ``He kept saying, 'Valerie, we
do not want a history lesson. The theater is not about lessoning.
It's about moving people to laughter, to tears, to thoughts. It's
got to be emotional,' '' Harper recalls. ``And just her point of
view, sometimes her archness, is cause for comedy. Sometimes you're
laughing with her, sometimes you're laughing at her, but that's
good theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater is where Suffern, N.Y.-born, Hunter College-educated
Harper began, first in the Radio City Music Hall corps de ballet at
the age of 16, followed by the chorus of such Broadway shows as
``Li'l Abner'' and ``Wildcat.'' Soon after her five years with
Second City, she was discovered by television and became nationally
known on ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show.''
</P>
<P>
   After her fast-track ascent, the '80s and '90s have been rockier
for Harper. In 1986, a series called ``Valerie'' was built around
her, but it led to a contentious contract dispute with NBC and
producer Lorimar. It was settled out-of-court, but Harper gained a
reputation as a troublemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did two short-lived series this decade _ ``City'' and ``The
Office'' _ do much for her career. She has her theories about why
they didn't work, centering on network incompetence, yet Harper
remains philosophical. ``I guess I was lucky in my life to get five
shows on the air. Period,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is evident that she would love another shot at
television success. In May, Harper shot a pilot for a sitcom with
Ron Leibman about a mixed marriage (``I'm Jewish, he's Italian'')
of empty nesters whose grown children return home. She thought it
was ``hilarious,'' but the networks must have disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   She is juggling several other projects, including a new show for
Broadway and a line of green tea-based skin care products being
hawked on the Home Shopping Network. According to Cacciotti, public
and cable television executives are flying in to see ``All Under
Heaven'' in Palm Beach, Fla., for a potential two-hour special of
it, to be shot in China.
</P>
<P>
   But all of this could be put on hold if ``Mary and Rhoda''
clicks. ``We might get great numbers, through the ceiling, and they
might say, `Great movie,' and that's it,'' says Harper. ``It may
fall flat, reviewers may not like it. I don't know. But as Mary
said to me, `Val, we're going to kick ourselves if we don't try.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Hap Erstein writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: haperstein(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
