<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUND-SCIENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sound enhancer fails test
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The SoundScience Universal Audio Dynamic Sound
Improvement Processor promises to ``enhance reproduction for
fuller, cleaner, undiluted sound with sharp mid-tones, crisp
trebles and powerful base'' from your CD player, television,
computer, DVD player, radio, cassette player, satellite receiver
and video game consoles.
</P>
<P>
   But the big question is what does ``enhance'' mean? The
promotional material the company provided was a little vague, so
the Dayton Daily News asked for a sample unit to see for ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   I tried out the unit on my middle-of-the-road quality home
stereo to get the layman's opinion and turned it over to Dayton
Daily News audio columnist Don Loose for a professional
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Both of us came to the same conclusion: The SoundScience device,
called by its initials DSIP, seems to boost base and treble tones
dramatically, but the results sounded distorted. It might be a good
product to attach to an inexpensive stereo or boombox to jack up
the bass response, but it's probably not for true high fidelity
sound lovers.
</P>
<P>
   The DSIP is a silver plastic box about six inches across powered
by an AC adapter. It came with RCA-type plugs to connect it to
stereo components.
</P>
<P>
   To test the DSIP, Loose said he placed it in the tape loop of a
hi-fi system known for its transparency. He played two CDs with
which he was very familiar. The first was a Holly Cole CD featuring
female vocal, acoustic bass, acoustic piano, and a string section.
The second was the recently released Columbus Jazz Orchestra 25th
anniversary CD, Band At Work, which he recorded and engineered
himself in live concert settings.
</P>
<P>
   Loose didn't care for the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, in one Holly Cole take, the string bass plays in
unison with low piano notes, and you can clearly hear the two
timbres in unison,'' Loose said. ``The DSIP obliterates the
separate timbres into a single muddy bass line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The treble fared no better. The first thing to jump out were
distorted sibilants in Holly's voice which weren't there when the
DSIP was out of the system. The Columbus Jazz Orchestra sounded
really tinny _ not like the sound of real brass or woodwinds.''
</P>
<P>
   I connected the DSIP to my video recorder and played a battle
scene passage from Star Trek II: The Wrath of Kahn. The first thing
I noticed was an immediate increase in rumbling bass tones
associated with explosions.
</P>
<P>
   But I also noticed an unpleasant buzzy, tinny undertone as
characters spoke. And high-pitched laser blasts had an effect like
scraping fingernails across a chalkboard.
</P>
<P>
   SoundScience sells the Universal Audio DSIP for $90 online at
its Web site at www.soundscience.com. You can also order by phone
by calling (201) 767-3297.
</P>
<P>
   Other products in the SoundScience's line include less expensive
units for travel and for television only.
</P>
<P>
   James Cummings writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: jamescummings(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1801EST &QL; 
