<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0965 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-STAGE-MUSICALS-COX     12-06 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-MUSICALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New musicals carve their territories on Broadway
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the end of a century in which Broadway became
synonymous with commercial theater, its prime indigenous product _
the stage musical _ is busy looking nostalgically backward and
warily ahead. The former is represented by a vibrant, tuneful
revival of ``Kiss Me Kate,'' while the latter can be seen in a
dramatically powerful, but melodically stingy new work called
``Marie Christine.''
</P>
<P>
   Both are loosely based on classic plays, ``Kiss Me Kate''
puckishly springing from Shakespeare's ``The Taming of the Shrew''
and ``Marie Christine'' rooted in Euripides' tragic ``Medea.'' Both
productions contain juicy, larger-than-life leading roles, expertly
performed by stars likely to dominate Broadway for years to come.
But once you get beyond those superficial similarities, the two
shows are as different as possible, representing opposite extremes
of the musical theater spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiss Me Kate,'' which hails from 1948, is both a musical
``Shrew'' and the comic tempests of a pair of divorced theater
legends trying to get through the show's out-of-town opening night.
Along the way, they discover they are still in love with each
other. Fifty-one years ago, it was a recognizable send-up of the
famously egotistical Alfred Lunt and Lynn Fontanne, but the show
has outlived its satirical targets.
</P>
<P>
   The icing on the ``Kate'' cake is certainly the Cole Porter
score, as urbane, romantic and whimsical as any he ever wrote. Both
within and outside the play-within-a-play there are such lovely
ballads as ``So In Love'' and ``Were Thine That Special Face.'' And
when Porter starts punning on play titles in ``Brush Up Your
Shakespeare'' (''If she says your behavior is heinous/Kick her
right in the Coriolanus''), it is enough to make a grown man groan.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other hit shows of that era (''Annie Get Your Gun,''
``Finian's Rainbow'') being revived with wholesale script
adjustments, Kate has a quite playable book by Sam and Bella
Spewack. It cleverly interweaves its plots with Elizabethan
resonances, plus the added comic peril of bookie's goons who
mistakenly lean on lothario and director Fred Graham (Brian Stokes
Mitchell) and, to keep close tabs, end up onstage mid-Shrew.
</P>
<P>
   Minor tinkering, including the insertion of the previously cut
``From This Moment On'' and the invention of a MacArthur-like
suitor (Ron Holgate) for diva Lili Vanessi (Marin Mazzie), was
reportedly done by an uncredited John Guare. Attempts at revision
in the name of political correctness _ which ``Taming of the
Shrew'' may never qualify for _ have wisely been avoided.
</P>
<P>
   If the reason Kiss Me Kate had never returned to Broadway
previously is a lack of lead performers who could do justice to
both the Shakespearean verse and the Porter score, that has
certainly been solved by Mitchell and Mazzie. It comes as no
surprise that these stars of ``Ragtime'' know their way around a
love song, but it is their broad comic abilities in frequent
nose-to-nose confrontations that make them so winning.
</P>
<P>
   Like Shakespeare, Porter and the Spewacks wrote a secondary
romance for Kate's sister Bianca and her suitor Lucentio, to be
played by nightclub cutie Lois Lane (Amy Spanger) and Broadway
hoofer Bill Calhoun (Michael Berresse). She vamps her way
alluringly through ``Always True to You (In My Fashion)'' and he
climbs athletically over Robin Wagner's three-level backstage set
while warbling ``Bianca.'' Choreographer Kathleen Marshall comes up
with some smashing steamy steps, but never better than the second
act opener for the ensemble, ``Too Darn Hot.'' Michael Blakemore
(''City of Angels'') directs it all with a deft farcical touch and
an evident affection for show business lore.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever it is noted that they don't write 'em like they used
to, ``Kiss Me Kate'' is the sort of hit-song-stocked show referred
to. ``Marie Christine'' is the prototypical modern show that, alas,
prompts the remark. High-minded and serious, as you might expect a
version of ``Medea'' to be, it tells its story largely through a
rarefied score of art songs by Michael John La Chuisa which lean
toward contemporary opera.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say there aren't some beautiful, dramatically
charged numbers here. Marie's aria of feminist philosophy, ``Way
Back to Paradise,'' and her duet with her corrupt, duplicitious
lover Dante, ``We're Gonna Go to Chicago,'' remain vivid after an
initial hearing. But unlike Porter's easy way with a melody, La
Chuisa's structural complexities require work on the audience's
part and ultimately turn this gut-wrenching tale into a cerebral
head trip, which could not have been the goal.
</P>
<P>
   What La Chuisa has managed is to transpose the story of a
spurned sorceress who takes revenge by murdering her sons to that
of a black woman with voodoo powers in 1899 New Orleans and
Chicago. As she becomes involved with charismatic sea captain and
political climber Dante (intense Anthony Crivello), who pushes her
aside for the daughter of a ward boss, we begin to see a believable
situation for Marie to commit the unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly what La Chuisa and director-choreographer Graciela
Daniele have done is create a stunning showcase for Audra McDonald,
the three-time Tony Award winner (after only three Broadway
appearances). Her classically trained soprano gets a workout
negotiating through the music's treacherous rises and falls, yet
she handles its demands with power and control. The result is a
``Medea'' that is all-too-rational and, thus, all the more
frightening. If she does not win a fourth Tony, it will be because
the show fails to find an audience, not for any fault in her
towering performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marie Christine'' is an admirable attempt to push the musical
theater forward, one that is clearly linked to Lincoln Center
Theatre's effort last season, ``Parade,'' which was so worthy yet
so critically and popularly dismissed. For those who believe that
the musical can be more than easy, instantly accessible
entertainment, ``Marie Christine'' is likely to intrigue. But do
they exist in sufficient numbers? Fortunately, star power has
always driven the Broadway theater, and in McDonald this demanding,
yet rewarding production has a gleaming, genuine star.
</P>
<P>
   KISS ME, KATE
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Martin Beck Theatre, 302 W. 45th St., New York
</P>
<P>
   _ When: Continuing indefinitely
</P>
<P>
   _ Tickets: $25-$80. Call: (800) 432-7250.
</P>
<P>
   _ The verdict: A merry, knockabout revival with a pair of
buoyant stars, a great, tuneful Porter score and dance worth
kicking your heels over.
</P>
<P>
   MARIE CHRISTINE
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Vivian Beaumont Theatre, Lincoln Center, 150 West 65th
St., New York
</P>
<P>
   _ When: Through Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tickets: $40-$75. Call: (212) 239-6200.
</P>
<P>
   _ The verdict: Serious music fans are the target audience for
this contemporary operatic Medea, but everyone should see the
towering performance of McDonald in the title role.
</P>
<P>
   Hap Erstein writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: haperstein(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
