<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICINE-MEDIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    READ OF THE WEEK: PILL BOOKS
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim and M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you tried an over-the-counter allergy or cold medication
lately? Do you have a new prescription for an antibiotic?
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're taking an over-the-counter or prescription drug,
you should be aware of what you're taking and of any possible side
effects or drug interactions it might have.
</P>
<P>
   The venerable ``Physicians' Desk Reference'' (Medical Economics
Data, 1998, $79.95 hardback), now in its 53rd edition, is the most
inclusive and exhaustive drug reference, but neither the handiest
nor the simplest to understand. Most people probably will get more
out of a pill book geared toward laypersons, such as one of these:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Pill Book'' (Bantam, 1998, $6.99 paper-back)
</P>
<P>
   This guide covers the most frequently prescribed prescription
drugs and has a companion volume, ``The Pill Book Guide to
Over-the-Counter Medications.'' Both have easy-to-use indexes and
color illustrations of the most common pills _ extremely useful if
you're trying to identify a mystery pill in your medicine cabinet.
The guides list warnings, possible side effects and food and drug
interactions for each medicine. They also alert pregnant or
breast-feeding women and elderly people to special concerns.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Complete Drug Reference,'' 2000 (Consumer Reports, 1999,
$44.95 hard-
</P>
<P>
   back)
</P>
<P>
   Dictionary-sized, but worth the extra weight. It comes with
color illustrations of the most common pills and extremely detailed
information. The entry for aspirin, for example, is more than four
pages long. Like Consumer Reports magazine itself, this reference
is easy to read and jargon-free.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Worst Pills, Best Pills'' (Pocket Books, 1999, $16
paperback)
</P>
<P>
   The first page of this book cuts right to the chase with a list
of 14 pairs of drugs that, if taken together, can cause possibly
fatal reactions. The inside cover lists 10 rules for safer drug
use. (Rule 4 is ``Make sure drug therapy is really needed for your
medical condition.'') The book warns strongly against numerous
drugs but includes the sensible warning that people should talk to
their doctor before stopping any medication.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Complete Guide to Prescription and Nonprescription
Drugs'' (Perigee, 1999, $16.95 paperback)
</P>
<P>
   This guide provides basic information in an at-a-glance format.
The lack of illustrations is a drawback, especially considering the
price, but the book includes useful features such as a glossary of
terms.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET SITE OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Here's the problem with health information on the Internet: It's
hard to know the motives behind the creation of the site you're
looking at, and without that knowledge, it's hard to trust the data
the site presents. Sites may have an ulterior motive, they may be
disguised advertising, or they may, as several studies have
recently documented, simply be getting the facts wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A completely trustworthy health site _ with the added benefits
of excellent design, simple navigation and a nonjudgmental tone _
is Go Ask Alice! (www.goaskalice.columbia.edu). Run by the health
education program at Columbia University in New York, Alice!
accepts questions about health and sexuality through an anonymous
server, answers them frankly and archives the answers for easy
access.
</P>
<P>
   The site has been running since 1993 and gets about 1,000
questions a week. According to the site administrators, survey
responses show that the questioners are parents and teachers as
well as college and high school students. Common questions include
``Can I ask my girlfriend not to drink at college?'', ``My
13-year-old brother has severe depression and my parents won't
listen to me about it'' and ``Can HIV be passed by kissing?''
</P>
<P>
   (Despite its name, the site has no connection to the 1970s
anti-drug book ``Go Ask Alice,'' written by ``Anonymous.'')
</P>
<P>
   ARE YOU AWARE ...
</P>
<P>
   This month is National Drunk and Drugged Driving Prevention
Month. For information, contact Mothers Against Drunk Driving at
1-800-438-6233 or 404-233-3331 or visit www.madd.org.Lillian Lee
Kim and M.A.J. McKenna write for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
