<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FREEPORT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surprises to be had in Freeport
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREEPORT, Bahamas _ Late-season Hurricane Lenny churned in the
Caribbean, forcing two huge cruise ships to dock in Freeport.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers groaned about the unexpected change in course to a
backwater port no one knew anything about. But once on land, they
were far from irate. They roamed the duty-free shops of the
International Bazaar and Lucayan Market, found their own private
spots on more than 120 miles of white sand beaches, and gambled at
the Moroccan-style Princess Resort.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest surprise was the high style of the new Lucayan
Reef Village Hotel. These day guests were awed by the wild shapes
of the Alice-in-Wonderland furniture _ sofas with backs high enough
to accommodate Shaquille O'Neal, club chairs sporting exaggerated
curves and wind-surfer sails attached to the ceiling _ and a
two-story restaurant with chairs and wall paintings in colliding
tropical colors.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, it was just as impressive _ a replica of aqueduct ruins
running the length of three pools and a sugar mill surrounded by
water.
</P>
<P>
   The most common refrain as the cruise passengers filed through
the lobby: ``This looks like South Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   A fashionable couple from New York compared the interior design
and furniture to Miami Beach's chicest hotel, the Delano. High
praise for an island known more for day-trip gamblers wearing gold
chains and polyester than for sophisticated visitors who know an
artistic achievement when they see one.
</P>
<P>
   And this is only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The Lucayan Reef Village, which opened April 1, is the first
phase of a $300 million resort that, by the end of next year, will
include two more hotels, Lighthouse Pointe and Breakers Cay. The
sprawling resort will have 1,350 rooms and suites, 14 restaurants
and bars, a championship 18-hole golf course designed by Robert
Trent Jones and another 18-hole course that is open, a tennis
complex, spa and fitness center, a movie theater, marine
educational program and casino.
</P>
<P>
   The complex will be called The Lucayan, and guests at all three
hotels will register at the Manor House, a new building in the
center of the complex that will also house a convention center and
fitness center.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone familiar with the old Freeport won't recognize the Port
Lucaya area. The Lucayan Reef Village used to be the Radisson
Hotel, which had well-worn public rooms and faded decor.
</P>
<P>
   Next door was the Clarion, which was bulldozed, and farther down
the beach was the Lucayan, which is being transformed into luxury
villas.
</P>
<P>
   The new hotels face a gorgeous white beach and are across the
street from Port Lucaya, which has 85 duty-free stores and 28 bars
and restaurants, including the Illusions Jazz and Comedy Club, all
next to the scenic Bell Channel Bay.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lucayan is not the only hotel on this quiet island known
more for its natural beauty and tacky day tourists than man-made
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark Bahamas Princess Resort includes the Moroccan-style
Princess Tower and the Princess Country Club, which has two 18-hole
championship golf courses, six tennis courts and seven restaurants.
This is the place for gamblers and shoppers. The Tower has a casino
and is next door to the International Bazaar, a labyrinth of shady
lanes with more than 100 duty-free and other shops, and 14
restaurants and bars.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the 3-year-old Pelican Bay, a 48-room inn that
looks like a collection of colorful Bahamian houses. The balconies
of the rooms overlook the channel and Port Lucaya market. And next
to the market and channel is the Port Lucaya Resort and Yacht Club,
a small resort with pool, Jacuzzi and marina. This is the place to
stay if you bring your yacht. The beach is just across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Old Bahama Bay, a luxury beach resort, is expected to open this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Bahama Island, only 50 miles from West Palm Beach, is
undergoing a renaissance on the order of Atlantis on Paradise
Island. The owner of the Lucayan resort development is Harbour
Plaza Hotel Management Limited, a Hong Kong-based company that
operates four hotels in Hong Kong and mainland China, including the
Harbour Plaza Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   This sleepy island appears to be waking up.
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   _ HOTELS: Room rates at The Lucayan are $115 until Dec. 23,
single or double occupancy. Call a travel agent or (800) 582-2926
or (242) 373-1333 for reservations. Camp Lucaya is open for kids up
to 12 years old. Camp costs $20 a day per child.
</P>
<P>
   _ INFORMATION: For more information about Grand Bahama Island
and the Bahamas, call (800) 4-Bahama (800-422-4262).
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Blackerby writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: cherylblackerby(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
