<HEADER>
A0974 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MRSCLINTON-BOOK-REVIE     12-06 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-BOOK-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HILLARY'S CHOICE': AS SHEEHY SEES IT, HILLARY IS ADDICTED TO THE
PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In her new book, ``Hillary's Choice,'' Gail Sheehy puts the
first lady on the shrink's couch. In the course of the book Ms.
Sheehy ends up sounding a lot like Dr. Joyce Brothers while her
subject comes across as an Oprah guest: a woman who loves too much
and plays Wendy to her husband's Peter Pan.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheehy's assessment: that Hillary Rodham Clinton is addicted
to her husband, Bill, that ``he is her only rebellion, the one
thing she can't logically explain,'' that she sought in him the
approval her withholding father never gave her but found herself
``living out the same dynamic'' with another ``emotionally
unavailable'' man. ``When her accomplishments overshadowed
Clinton's,'' the author of ``Passages'' writes, ``he would punish
her in his own way _ by philandering.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, however, steadfastly stood by her man because, Ms.
Sheehy contends, she was practiced in the art of denial and had
decided long ago to hold on to her ``life strategy in service of a
larger agenda.'' That strategy, in Ms. Sheehy's words, was ``to
take the raw material of this brilliant, emotionally battered child
with a good heart and a desperate ambition and shape him into a
political star to which she could hitch her wagon full of dreams
for changing the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a Hillary to raise a president,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from such pseudo-psychoanalytic musings and some new
tidbits of gossip (an interview with a college boyfriend who
implies that the young Miss Rodham might have smoked marijuana; the
suggestion that in 1989 Bill Clinton had ``fallen in love'' with a
tall blonde named Marilyn Jo Denton Jenkins), ``Hillary's Choice''
simply rehashes the now familiar story of the Clintons' marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Sheehy did more than 400 interviews for this book,
relying particularly heavily, it would seem, on the consultant Dick
Morris and a former Clinton aide, Betsey Wright, her narrative
remains deeply indebted to earlier studies of the Clintons and the
Clinton presidency, most notably, George Stephanopoulos' ``All Too
Human,'' and David Maraniss' two books, ``First in His Class'' and
``The Clinton Enigma.'' Many of the firsthand observations of Mrs.
Clinton in this book come from interviews Ms. Sheehy conducted with
her for a 1992 profile in Vanity Fair magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary's Choice'' paints a now familiar portrait of an
administration riven by internal conflict, a narcissistic president
unable to control his impulsive behavior, and a first lady given to
stonewalling and an us-vs.-them mentality. Mrs. Clinton, we are
told once again, is smart, tough, ambitious and self-righteous, a
perfectionist who would rather fight than compromise. Her husband,
we are reminded, is a conciliator who takes a relativistic approach
to policy and the truth and likes to play the role of victim.
</P>
<P>
   She is the cerebral, analytic strategist; he is the charming
retail politician. She is an absolutist; he is `` Situational
Ethics.'' He is ``the eternal boy,'' stuck ``in an adolescent
orientation toward life''; she is the ``den mother'' and chief
``enabler,'' ``the Valkyrie who was always ready to lift her
wounded barefoot boy from the battlefield and fly him to
Valhalla.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that Hillary the Wife suffered but steeled
herself when Bill betrayed her,'' Ms. Sheehy writes. ``She had to
put on her Hillary the Partner hat to defend and deny and sweep up
behind him; she was a high-status abused wife. But it became
increasingly apparent in their White House years that when Bill
misbehaved sexually, it could be a win-win situation for both
Hillary the Wife and Hillary the Partner. She is elevated to the
iconic status of a secular saint and Bill looks like the
troublemaker.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Sheehy's telling, Hillary the Wife gets an added bonus
whenever her husband is in trouble: ``Every time he gets caught,''
she writes, ``Clinton concentrates his sexual magnetism on his wife
for a change. Still insecure about her feminine attraction, she is
once again courted and seduced. He promises (lies) whatever is
necessary to get out of the doghouse. Whatever the exact words and
body language he uses, they give credibility to her fantasy that
everything will be different in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Ms. Sheehy's opinion that Clinton did not come clean to
his wife about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky until
days before his grand jury testimony and that for months he had
sent Hillary ``out into the world to lie for him, to risk her own
reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Going beyond conventional explanations of the president's
ability to ``compartmentalize'' his life, Ms. Sheehy quotes an
anonymous ``mental health professional'' who suggests that the
president may suffer from ``dissociative identities,'' a disorder
also known as ``multiple personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   In another passage that appears to be pure speculation,
buttressed with no supporting quotes or sourcing, Ms. Sheehy adds:
``Hillary was wretched. She could no longer reconcile her view of
herself as a devout Christian with her complicity in this debauched
marriage. Something would have to change. Drastically. For all
Clinton's protestations of repentance, she could not count on him
to change: she had heard it all before. No, this time the change
would have to be in her.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 12, 1999, the day the Senate voted on the impeachment
charges, Mrs. Clinton met with her husband's former political
strategist, Harold M. Ickes, to discuss her possible run for a U.S.
Senate seat from New York. Ms. Sheehy quotes Ickes as saying,
``This is a race for redemption''; winning the seat would ``permit
her supporters to say there was a lot more here than anybody
thought.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a Senate seat would help erase memories of
Whitewater, Filegate, Travelgate, Mrs. Clinton's failed health care
initiative and her anti-feminist role as a long-suffering wife in
the Lewinsky melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Sheehy, Hillary Clinton's decision to step out from
behind her husband's shadow fits perfectly into a ``Passages''
paradigm: It meant she had ``come through the little death of
midlife'' and ``stood up against shame and scorn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clintons were also entering a new and natural
developmental stage in the lives of couples _ what I call the
`Couple Crossover' at middle life,'' Ms. Sheehy writes. ``As women
age, they become more independent, aggressive and political. It is
natural for couples to experience a switch of polarities.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the reader quickly wearies of Ms. Sheehy's penchant for
perky psychobabble jargon, it somehow seems fitting that the
Clintons with their protean identities should be the politicians
subjected to her armchair psychoanalysis. Bill Clinton, after all,
once remarked that character ``is a journey, not a destination''
and he has repeatedly bailed himself out of trouble by invoking the
recovery movement belief that mistakes and transgressions are pit
stops on the road to redemption.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As for Hillary Rodham Clinton, she has tried on and discarded
personas almost as frequently as she has changed hairdos, shedding
and retrieving her maiden name and trying on the roles of health
care maven, Vogue cover girl, non-cookie-baking policy wonk,
cuckolded martyr and now, would-be senator with varying degrees of
aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   In college, Ms. Sheehy reports, Hillary Rodham similarly toyed
with a variety of identities: ``educational and social reformer,
alienated academic, involved pseudo-hippie,'' and ``compassionate
misanthrope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder who is me,'' she wrote a friend in 1968. ``I wonder
if I'll ever meet her. If I did, I think we'd get along famously.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HILLARY'S CHOICE'
</P>
<P>
   By Gail Sheehy
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 389 pages. Random House. $23.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
