<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CENSORSHIP-NOTEBOOK-N     12-06 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSORSHIP-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CENSORED!' IS SUITABLE FOR BLUENOSES, FANCY PANTS, BREWERS,
WHATEVER 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for evidence that vintage sex and violence along with
scenes of whiskey and drug binges and assorted naughtiness used to
be a lot more fun than much of what is cluttering the screen these
days? Look no further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Censored!'' on American Movie Classics is an hour's worth of
drug fiends and vamps (that's Theda Bara writhing seductively on
the floor), pratfalls and barroom brawls and batterings, belly
dances and smoochings from the silent-movie era. Anybody this side
of Gary Bauer ought to get a laugh out of them.
</P>
<P>
   The clips, which incited protests from the censoriously inclined
circa 1898 to 1922, have turned into treasures for movie buffs.
Unfortunately, sound is added Tuesday night in the form of a
narration that for no discernible reason uses two commentators _
the director Oliver Stone and the actor William Baldwin _ who
deliver the same simple message in much the same way: Censorship is
bad.
</P>
<P>
   That is an easy message to agree with, but the script doesn't
dig very strenuously into the conflicting pressures over a tough
issue. It settles in part for a jejune Marxism, as the narrators (I
couldn't tell one from the other) argue that censorship has been a
tool of the exploiting class to shield the moviegoing public from
unpleasant realities of American life, war, political finaglings,
labor relations and sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   There is some truth here; bluenoses have often tried to keep the
masses from the crude pleasures and rude truths of popular
entertainments. And yes, agitation over movies about drug and
alcohol addiction did tend to focus on the underclass _ immigrants,
blacks and slum dwellers in general _ while upper-class addiction
was ignored. Still, brewers came to the defense of the less
privileged boozers by protesting that the portrayal of drunks in
movies (there's Charlie Chaplin flopping gracefully around) were
giving saloons a bad name. Who were the true exploiters, the saloon
keepers or the Prohibitionists?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, America's main exercise in movie censorship, the Hays
Code, a k a the Breen Office, which began in the 1930s and lasted
for a couple of decades, originated not in corporate boardrooms but
among Roman Catholic parishioners obedient to their hierarchy's
call for a boycott of disapproved material. If we are searching for
class categories, this was a remarkably successful populist
insurrection against the Hollywood moguls.
</P>
<P>
   The anticensorship forces have, over time, won most of the legal
wars. But in a society that puts a high premium on unfettered
expression yet is chronically concerned over the impact of what is
expressed, this running controversy cannot be readily reduced to a
class struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful have been known to use their powers to suppress
their enemies when they can get away with it, but matters like
changing standards, divergent tastes, commercial interests and the
unsettled, perhaps unsettleable relationship between mass
entertainment and personal behavior go beyond class. Silent-screen
movie villains, after all, were often takeoffs on the fancy-pants
set; see the way they twirled their mustaches. (Speaking of the
impact on personal behavior, one of the perils of the early movies,
some reformers held, was the ``movie masher,'' the fellow who took
the opportunity in the darkened theater to emulate what was
happening on the screen.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Censored!'' is on strongest ground in dealing with official
restrictions on news coverage in World War I and the apparent ban
on the spread of information about birth control among poor women
that kept Margaret Sanger's ideas off the screen for a half
century. (A Pennsylvania official opined that it ``would be
criminal to undeceive kids who believed in storks.'') But changes
stirred by the women's movement and by movie fashions cut across
class lines. Upper-class women were prominent in promoting birth
control among the less privileged, and moviegoers of all ilks
seemed willing to settle for ``Traffic in Souls,'' a hit when white
slavery was a popular topic.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Censored!'' reaches ``The Birth of a Nation'' (1915), its
class compass is of no use at all. Here is an acknowledged
masterpiece that is also an acknowledged exercise in anti-black
propaganda. It may be the most banned movie in history. So how are
the producers of ``Censored,'' opposed equally to racism and to
censorship, to handle it?
</P>
<P>
   The program settles for the line that Stone has used as a refuge
from criticisms of some of his own work. Having been pummeled for
distorting or inventing history in ``J.F.K.,'' his fantasy about
the John F. Kennedy assassination, he uses ``art'' as his defense.
Given D.W. Griffith's status in movie history, the artistic
argument for ``The Birth of a Nation'' is more forceful than
anything Stone can advance on his own behalf as a propagandist.
</P>
<P>
   The art defense, popular though it understandably is among
enemies of censorship, might be more useful for opening a
discussion than for censoring one before it fairly gets started. If
a connection can be made, say, between crime and certain movies or
between fatherless children and certain music, must society just
bear it? Does artistic expression or aspiration or pretension trump
every social calamity?
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion offered Tuesday tonight, that art, if great
enough, needs no excuses or that art, of the right sort, can
inspire the right kind of change, or that Griffith's epic
``Intolerance'' somehow compensates for ``The Birth of a Nation,''
or any implication that a Stone can shelter under the genius of a
Griffith seems merely evasive.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Censored!'' finally gives up on justification by art and
settles for the easy conclusion that ``We create the marketplace''
and ``If you really don't want it, don't buy it!'' Choosing allies
when it comes to censorship can be uncomfortable, and this sounds
like a copout by the masters and minions of Hollywood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
