<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0985 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-DOCTORS-TRAINING-HNS &LR;      12-06 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-TRAINING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIST SAYS CONGRESS WILL FIND WAYS TO FINANCE MEDICAL TRAINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By JUDY HOLLAND   
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Bill Frist, the only physician in the Senate
and a key force in crafting health-care policy for Republicans,
predicted Monday that Congress will find new ways to pay for
training medical residents at U.S. teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Cuts in Medicare funding have squeezed federal reimbursements to
the nation's 400 teaching hospitals at the same time that managed
health-care plans have cut back their payments to the hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Frist, a Republican from Tennessee and a transplant surgeon
before he became active in politics, said senators are looking for
new ways to help struggling teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are reaching out to establish a much broader payment
source,'' Frist said, speaking at a Capitol Hill forum on who
should pay for educating physicians. The panel was sponsored by the
Alliance for Health Reform, a nonpartisan education group. Frist is
vice chairman and Sen. John D. Rockefeller, D.W-Va., is chairman of
the group. The Commonwealth Fund, a philanthropy that focuses on
health issues, also underwrote the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Frist, who chairs the public health panel of the Senate Health,
Education, Labor and Pensions Committee, said many members of
Congress believe the hospitals may need funding beyond the $7
billion a year they receive in Medicare payments.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and the Clinton administration last month approved a
federal budget that will restore about $1 billion in Medicare money
to teaching hospitals. Congress cut that funding in 1997 when it
balanced the federal budget. Teaching hospitals hailed the
``give-back'' as a major victory, which would bolster their
institutions for two years, but said they need more funding to
survive beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., has introduced legislation
that would create a trust fund to finance medical residents'
training through a fee on health insurance premiums of managed care
providers, private insurers and large employers. Such a fund would
also include existing Medicare and Medicaid money earmarked to pay
for resident training.
</P>
<P>
   Frist indicated he preferred a different approach under which
Congress would vote specific appropriations for teaching hospitals
for several years at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Helms, an economist at the American Enterprise Institute,
a conservative Washington think tank, said the federal government
shouldn't have a permanent entitlement fund to pay for the training
of physicians, ``who turn out to be some of the wealthiest members
of our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Helms said, the institutions should have to go to
battle every year in the appropriations process in which Congress
decides which programs should get federal money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be appropriate to return this to an appropriations
process,'' Helms said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Blumenthal, a Harvard Medical School professor, said
the country's resident training system is ``becoming unglued''
because of funding problems.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal told the panel that it costs about 30 percent more to
care for a patient in a teaching hospital than it does elsewhere
because of extra costs related to training medical residents,
conducting clinical research and caring for a larger load of sicker
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said the extra services offered at teaching hospitals
``are public goods that have value but aren't marketable,'' adding
that a ``reliable and predictable'' source of money is needed to
keep them afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Murray Ross, executive director of the Medicare Payment Advisory
Commission, a nonpartisan agency that advises Congress on Medicare
issues, said teaching hospitals need special financial help to pay
for the extra quality they provide.
</P>
<P>
   Ross expressed concern that the current system of federal
reimbursement is based on the number of residents per hospital with
the result that teaching hospitals train more residents than they
need, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to get the payment formula away from the number
of residents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
</P>
<P>
   Judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
