   SATURDAY, Dec. 25
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-MILLENNIUM-$ADV25 _ ROME _ About 30 million pilgrims are
expected to converge upon this delicate old city for the Roman
Catholic Holy Year 2000. The preparations have been sometimes
comic, and other times impressive. Developing. (Freeman).
</P>
<P>
   With Photos.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, Dec. 26
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL-$ADV25 _ PANAMA CITY _ After 85 years, the U.S.
hands over the Panama Canal at noon on Dec. 31 in a ceremony sure
to kick up a new round of debate among worried conservatives.
Critics have never been comfortable with the deal brokered 23 years
ago by then U.S. President Jimmy Carter, fearing the Panamanians
will overcharge ships using the canal and possibly hamstring the
U.S. military. Lately, they've been outraged at a deal cut by the
Panamanians to let a Hong Kong company run the busy ports at either
end of the 50-mile-long canal, saying the company is a front for
the Chinese military. Meanwhile Panamanians plan elaborate
ceremonies for an event they believe will showcase their emergence
on the world stage and symbolize their autonomy after decades of
U.S. domination. Worried that the millennium will overshadow their
moment of glory, the government will hold ceremonies Dec. 13 and
14. It isn't yet clear who will represent the U.S., as Pres.
Clinton seems shy of showing up for a giveaway that might hamper Al
Gore's campaign. (Williams).
</P>
<P>
   With CANAL-SIDE-$ADV26 _ PANAMA CITY _ How vital is the canal to
the United States, and does the hand-over harm us militarily or
economicallly? (Williams).
</P>
<P>
   (Tentative). With CANAL-CARTER-$ADV26 _ A sidebar on Jimmy
Carter, who negotiated the canal's return to Panama. How will
history treat the controversial treaty? Is it the sign of a world
power secure enough in its position to give up control of a vital
trade link, or does it symbolize a waning of U.S. dominance?
(Williams).
</P>
<P>
   CANAL-IMPACT-$ADV26 _ PANAMA CITY _ What does the turn-over mean
to average Panamanians? Thousands who have lived and worked for
decades in the canal zone at U.S. military bases have lost their
jobs as the bases have closed, while dozens of businesses with
contracts to provide services at the bases now have no employer.
Bars and restaurants that once catered to free-spending G.I.'s will
have to find new customers, while the Panamanian government must
find uses for several large tracts of land once occupied by the
U.S. While the
</P>
<P>
   turnover is a point of national pride for Panama, many average
citizens may regret the U.S. pull-out. (Williams).
</P>
<P>
   With Photos.
</P>
<P>
   With info-graphic showing the canal's location, with bullets on
history, dimensions, etc.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both International/Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ODD _ WASHINGTON - Adviser Naomi Wolf suggested that Vice
President Al Gore let his ``oddness'' shine through his formal
nature. She explained that Gore was the kind of visionary person
who could see around corners. But Gore has always been viewed as a
little too New Age-ish, from the ``shuttle method'' for choosing
the sex of children to relying on get-in-touch-with-your-feelings
facilitators. Is Al Gore just too weird to be president? (Shepard).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   (Scratched) TECH-FUTURE.
</P>
