<HEADER>
A0987 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-EDUCATION-AUDIT07-COX     12-06 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-AUDIT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDUCATION DEPARTMENT TO REPLACE BAD SOFTWARE
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The flawed computer software that lost track of
billions of dollars at the Education Department will be replaced by
2001, department officials told Congress on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Procedures and personnel changes already adopted within the
department will also help avoid a repetition of the fiscal fiasco
revealed last month by the department's outside auditors, said
Marshall Smith, acting deputy secretary of education. It is even
possible that the next audit will show the books are accurate, he
maintained.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the glass as one-half full, but I see it as
three-fourths empty,'' responded Rep. Peter Hoekstra, R-Mich.,
chairman of the House subcommittee for education investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Hoekstra said the proposed fixes will have to be implemented by
a department that has a ``pretty sorry'' record. Among other
things, fiscal experts testified that the department spent more
than $5 million on accounting software that doesn't work, failed to
reconcile its balances until the end of the year and either failed
to supply or was months late in applying information to its outside
auditors.
</P>
<P>
   During the three-hour hearing , Smith had one consolation: All
the fiscal experts who testified said they hadn't found any signs
that the bookkeeping mess was caused by stealing or illegal misuse
of funds.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they found that the department had a ``competency
challenge,'' said Rep. Harold Ford Jr., D-Tenn., who accepted
Smith's explanations.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rep. Bob Schaffer, R-Colo., said he remained convinced
that some of the discrepancies uncovered by the outside auditors
must have been due to ``waste, fraud or abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, more than eight months after its audit report for
the 1998 fiscal year was due, the accounting firm of Ernst &AMP; Young
announced it would not express any opinion at all on the accuracy
of the department's books.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights of the report in which Ernst &AMP; Young
justified its decision:
</P>
<P>
   _ Department officials never could explain one $6 billion
discrepancy between two of its internal accounting systems.
</P>
<P>
   _ After a great deal of effort, the department finally learned
that a $1 billion difference between its records and those in the
Treasury Department came about when a transfer of half a billion
dollars was entered backwards by the Education Department.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than one-fifth of the more than $500 million in one
account should have been kept in a separate account. The department
couldn't explain the source or purposes of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lax security procedures and features left the department's
centralized accounting records open to interference by insiders or
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lampley, the partner who directed the Ernst &AMP; Young
audit team, said most of the problems seemed to be caused by the
bad software, loss of experienced workers in the department's
financial office, and the department's attempts to cope with two
new government-wide reporting requirements while repairing the
flawed software.
</P>
<P>
   When the company that made the software was sold to another firm
that wasn't interested in that kind of business, it became hard to
get help with the software's problems, several witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
