<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1001 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ATT-BELLSOUTH-COX     12-06 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-BELLSOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giving credit where credit's due: MindSpring outlasts
competition
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AT&AMP;T, which was one of the world's biggest monopolies
until its breakup in 1984, seemed to be headed that way anew.
</P>
<P>
   By buying about half the cable franchises, serving 27 percent of
the subscribers, AT&AMP;T seemed poised to dominate a huge sector of
the communications market, using high-speed Internet access as a
major lure.
</P>
<P>
   Government leaders, from mayors to county commissioners, joined
hands with consumer groups to protest that the communications giant
was about to acquire a choke hold on the hottest and fastest
growing area of telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was especially acute in Atlanta because AT&AMP;T is on the
verge of acquiring MediaOne, a national player that happens to be
Atlanta's major cable provider.
</P>
<P>
   By offering its customers a package of communications services
at an attractive price, AT&AMP;T seemed poised to grab a huge share of
the market with a combination of video, Internet access, and
several phone lines to each house _ not to speak of a nice
long-distance tie-in. At the same time it would exclude individual
businesses like MindSpring from offering a competitive option or
having any share of that business through that broad, high-speed
pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T was about to become Ma Bell all over again, or so it
seemed.
</P>
<P>
   But over the weekend AT&AMP;T changed course. And adopted a new
theme song. The company said it might be better off, really, by
allowing MindSpring and other service providers to drum up
business, boost marketing and bring their own customers to the AT&AMP;T
cable party.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened _ did AT&AMP;T revisit economics? Or did management
read the history books on how AT&AMP;T bought like blazes in the 1970's
to keep other companies off their telephone network only to lose in
the end with the breakup of the company?
</P>
<P>
   The latter possibility seems more persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission, including Chairman
William E. Kennard, has endorsed the principle of competition but
have said they expect the marketplace to work out the terms. As it
happens, the commission and the Justice Department are reviewing
the bid by AT&AMP;T to acquire MediaOne to see if it is
anti-competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Localities like Portland, Oregon, have taken on AT&AMP;T's cable
operations, suing for open access. Portland won a decision favoring
open access, but it is under appeal.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, BellSouth and other telephone companies are
proceeding with their own appealing solution to high speed Internet
access, called Digital Subscriber Line, or DSL. The quickened pace
of DSL development looms as a considerable competitor with cable
technology, especially since phone companies have more live direct
connections to homes than the cable companies.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is so concerned about that logistical advantage that it now
plans to develop high-speed wireless Internet systems to businesses
and homes, to cover places they may not reach with their cable
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   And so now, for whatever reason, AT&AMP;T says it will allow all
Internet service providers to come in and work out deals to offer
their service by way of cable.
</P>
<P>
   This all bears watching, however. The devil is in the details _
and competition will come only if AT&AMP;T offers workable and
acceptable terms for opening its pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that AT&AMP;T stands to benefit from a smoother,
faster transition into its new business as a cable company and
telecommunications company all rolled into one. Hitting the ground
running appears to be a higher priority now than fighting for a
protected preserve.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring, which stayed at the bargaining table with AT&AMP;T when
others lost the faith or doubted the outcome, is due plenty of
credit for successfully arguing the case for open access.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
