<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1004 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-MARS-LANDER-NYT &LR;      12-06 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-LANDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARS-MISSION SCIENTISTS MOURN YEARS OF APPARENTLY LOST WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Next attempt to listen for signals is 3:30 a.m. ET; Story
should stand.) (mk) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Just about now, if things had gone
differently, Wayne Zimmerman would have been waiting expectantly
and nervously for the Mars Polar Lander's mechanical arm to start
digging in the planet's cold ground, searching for evidence of
water ice. He was the lead engineer for electronics on the team
that developed and tested the 6.5-foot arm.
</P>
<P>
   As the grim reality of the lander's apparent loss settled in on
Monday, Zimmerman paid a visit to the ``Mars yard'' here at the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory. There, on a bed of simulated red Mars soil,
stood a mock-up of the vehicle that has been assembled to head out
in 2001 for the next landing attempt. Its robot arm was almost
identical to the one on the ill-starred polar lander.
</P>
<P>
   The visit was an occasion for mourning and reflection and also
worry that the $165-million mission's failure could prompt public
and congressional criticism of the entire Mars exploration program,
including possible calls for severe cutbacks. The gloom was doubly
thick because in September the lander's companion craft, Mars
Climate Orbiter, was lost as it approached the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all just crestfallen,'' Zimmerman said. ``Man, it's
tough when you put that much work for years into designing,
building and testing, it's hard to lose it all. Not to have an
opportunity to do that science is pretty depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with each passing hour, little hope remained that flight
controllers would somehow establish radio contact with the missing
polar lander. A listening opportunity early Monday morning, the
sixth since the spacecraft's landing attempt on Friday, again
produced nothing but silence. Another effort, perhaps the last on
which controllers are pinning much hope, would be made early
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're nearing the point where we've used up our final silver
bullets,'' Richard Cook, the project manager, said after the latest
attempt to pick up radio signals from the polar lander.
</P>
<P>
   Mission officials said that they had also abandoned much hope of
receiving any transmissions from the two small probes that were
supposed to penetrate the Martian ground at about the same time of
the lander's arrival. They were designed to examine the subsurface
for signs of water ice.
</P>
<P>
   The search for water by both the probes and the lander was an
effort to answer the consuming question about Mars: Could life have
arisen there in the past? Water is considered essential for life,
and other research has shown that some water ice and vapor exist on
Mars and may have been more abundant and in liquid form at an
earlier period.
</P>
<P>
   The mission's apparent failure has been acutely painful for
others, like Zimmerman, who have invested years, sometimes decades
of their careers, on Mars exploration. Dr. Richard Zurek, the chief
scientist for the project, found himself a three-time loser. He was
also chief scientist for the lost climate orbiter and an
investigator on the $1-billion Mars Observer, which disappeared
mysteriously in 1993 as it arrived at the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Paige, one of the leading mission scientists from the
University of California at Los Angeles, had now lost years of work
and millions of dollars in instruments on three separate failed
missions to Mars over the last decade. He had been hoping to follow
in the footsteps of his father as a polar explorer. David Paige
Sr., the scientist son said, was an artist who accompanied Adm.
Richard Byrd to Antarctica in 1933. The lander was making the first
attempt to reach the polar region of another world.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce Murray, a planetary geologist at the California
Institute of Technology, felt time running out on him. Nearly three
decades ago, he predicted that volumes of water were probably
frozen in the Martian polar regions and beneath the surface. This
was his first chance, at the age of 68, to learn more about the
abundance and behavior of water on Mars, now and possibly in the
past. And there is no follow-up polar mission in future plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very special time,'' Murray had said the day before
the polar lander's scheduled arrival, meaning for science and for
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Mission officials have so far deflected questions about the
implications of the lander's failure for future Mars exploration as
premature. But Zimmerman, standing in the Mars yard, said he feared
a public reaction that might cripple the program. ``People must
understand how difficult these things are,'' he said. ``It's like a
contact sport and your playing field is the whole solar system and
its full of hazards and unknowns.''
</P>
<P>
   In a strategy developed last year, NASA laid plans for two
missions to Mars at each launching opportunity, which comes every
26 months, for the net decade. The 2001 missions are to be an
orbiter and lander similar in design and capabilities to the failed
missions this fall. But the next lander would set down near the
equator and would carry a roving vehicle much like the one on Mars
Pathfinder in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Following that, in 2003, will be the beginning of missions aimed
at returning soil and rock samples from Mars, conducted with the
help of European space agencies. A rover dispatched that year would
collect samples and rocket them into a Mars orbit. Two years later,
another rover would gather more samples into a container and send
them into orbit. An American-French spacecraft in 2005 would
retrieve the two sample containers and bring them to Earth by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Unspoken by the polar lander mission officials so far, but on
the minds of their colleagues, is the question about an underlying
premise of this exploration strategy. To reduce costs and risks of
a single failure undermining the whole effort, Daniel Goldin, the
NASA administrator, instituted a ``faster, cheaper, better'' policy
for planetary exploration. The question is whether the policy has
forced engineers to sacrifice reliability by cutting corners to
stay within tight budgets.
</P>
<P>
   As Zimmerman reflected on the loss of a mission and spoke of
these concerns for the future, he switched on power to the
mechanical arm designed for the next planned landing on Mars. He
commanded the arm to scoop up soil and lift it to the top of the
spacecraft mockup. He was back being an engineer worrying about an
exploring machine, not the politics of planetary exploration.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I have another chance,'' he said. ``I'm working on a
rover and this robot arm for Mars '01.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
