<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1007 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ATT-EXCITE-COX     12-06 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-EXCITE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Excite At Home prepared for competition
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even for Excite At Home, an Internet start-up
accustomed to the pirouette of the online industry, Monday was a
wild ride.
</P>
<P>
   First the company announced it had hit a milestone, signing up 1
million customers for its online service. It is one of two networks
that use digital cable TV networks rather than telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time AT&AMP;T, its largest shareholder, announced it
would permit online competitor MindSpring to use its lines to offer
high-speed access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short run, this isn't important to Excite At Home,''
says Bruce Leichtman, a media analyst at industry consultant Yankee
Group. ``But long term it means a new competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Excite At Home is no stranger to competition. The Silicon
Valley-based company has waged an uphill battle to persuade online
users to try its service during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Excite At Home and Road Runner, the second major network of that
kind, offer online access through digital cable networks. These
networks provide a connection up to 100 times faster than is
possible with conventional telephone lines. That enables
lightning-fast viewing and downloading of such things as movie
clips and songs.
</P>
<P>
   Even with this advantage, Excite At Home and Road Runner have
had a hard time signing up customers. One reason is that only a
small percentage of all cable networks have been rebuilt with the
fiber-optic lines necessary to carry digital traffic such as
Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts are predicting, at best, a total of 2 million
cable TV Internet customers by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   While an underdog compared with online giant America Online,
Excite At Home has been gaining momentum. Today the service is in
more than 100 markets. Its largest markets include much of New
Jersey, Baltimore, Dallas-Forth Worth, San Diego, the San Francisco
Bay area and Orange County, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Excite At Home typically enters a market through an exclusive
contract with one of three big cable TV operators: Atlanta-based
Cox Communications, Comcast and AT&AMP;T, which bought cable operator
Tele-Communications Inc. last year.
</P>
<P>
   These cable operators initially invested in Excite At Home to
help its online technology become the country's standard for
Internet connections in the future. Cox Communications and Comcast
each own 12 percent of Excite At Home while AT&AMP;T owns 71 percent.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has differed with Cox Communications and Comcast about the
future of Excite At Home. It wants the online service to be a dumb
pipeline and not a provider of content. AT&AMP;T has also said it will
not renew its exclusive contract, which expires in 2002, with
Excite At Home.
</P>
<P>
   That has freed AT&AMP;T to sign up other services such as MindSpring
to use the company's digital networks to access the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While Excite At Home executives could not be reached for
comment, observers of the company don't believe the MindSpring deal
will hurt Excite At Home.
</P>
<P>
   Says Leichtman, ``What counts long term is that Excite At Home
establishes itself as a competitor, and it should be strong enough
to stand on its own by 2002.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
