<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Tuesday, Dec. 7. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
PYSCHE (Washington) - More than a dozen psychiatric evaluations of
Arizona Sen. John McCain reveal a driven man. He was driven to
escape the shadow of his father, a Navy admiral, and when he was
released from his Vietnam captivity, he was determined to overcome
his problems without the aid of psychiatric counseling, even though
he had twice made feeble attempts to kill himself while he was a
prisoner. He has an `overdeveloped super-ego,'' according a
psychological assessment and an `unrealistically high need for
achievement.'' ''He may tend to expect too much of himself, and
take it hard when/if things don't go as planned,'' said one MD in a
psychological assessment. In self-evaluations, when asked what
others may not like about him, McCain wrote, `Quick temper.'' By
JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) - The reporter from Atlanta wanted to know
what the problem was between Arizona Sen. John McCain and ``The
Arizona Republic.`` He said McCain's campaign people told him not
to talk to anyone in the Arizona press. They're smart, I told him.
I were them, I'd say the same thing. It's like this: Every reporter
outside of Arizona wants to date John McCain. We're married to him.
By E.J. MONTINI. Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K''
categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
KUWAIT-EDIT (Phoenix) - You might remember Kuwait as that tiny,
oil-rich nation for which the United States went to war.
</P>
<P>
   You paid the price to liberate the Kuwaiti maiden-in-distress.
And probably felt pretty good about it. After all, liberation is so
satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   But you ought to ask for your money back.
</P>
<P>
   You paid for a flawed product.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait remains only half-liberated. By its own choice. Story
moved in the ``K'' category. &QL; 
