<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-WARD-BOS </SLUG>
  
 MINNIE WARD, 114, EX-TEACHER; BELIEVED OLDEST BOSTON RESIDENT
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   BOSTON _ Minnie B. (Smith) Ward, a former teacher who was
reputed to be the oldest resident of Boston, died Thursday in
Sherrill House in Boston. She was 114.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Ward was born on her father's farm in Brownsville, Texas,
on Nov. 19, 1885, the year of President Ulysses S. Grant's death.
</P>
<P>
   She graduated from Roger Williams College in Nashville, Tenn.,
in 1903, the year Wilbur and Orville Wright built their first
airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Early in life she was a teacher of English history and
dressmaking in the schoolhouse her father founded in Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   She married the Rev. Cassius Ward in 1911, when she was 26 years
old. At the time a Model T Ford cost $850 and the first skyscraper,
the 47-story Singer building, had just been built in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after their wedding, her husband was assigned to
Ebenezer Baptist Church in Boston. ``It was very different for
me,'' Mrs. Ward said in a story published in the Globe on Jan. 15,
1998, ``because my hometown was a small town and Boston, of course,
was not. Back home people were still using horses and buggies, and
riding on horseback. It was quite a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1928, she and her family moved to Pittsburgh, where Ward had
taken a pastorate. They lived there for nine years. After her
husband died of a heart problem in 1937, Mrs. Ward and her children
moved back to Boston, and she took a job as a cook at Boston
University.
</P>
<P>
   After her retirement from Boston University she became involved
in affairs for the elderly, and was a founding member of the Boston
Council of Elders.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, she was honored by Mayor Thomas M. Menino as the city's
oldest resident at a ceremony held in her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep on keepin' on. I feel quite present. It's hard to think
of it all sometimes. It's been such a long, long time,'' said Mrs.
Ward in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   She leaves a daughter, Hertha W. Taylor of Indianapolis; two
sons, Cassius A. of Detroit and John A. of Boston; 15
grandchildren; and 15 great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
