<HEADLINE>
ZIFF-DAVIS SELLS MAJOR PUBLICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trade publishing giant Ziff-Davis continues to disassemble its
media empire, selling off major publications including PC Week in
an effort to salvage its sagging stock price, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal, the private investment firm Willis Stein &AMP; Partners
agreed to pay $780 million in cash for Ziff-Davis' widely acclaimed
publishing unit _ which includes PC Magazine, the world's No. 1
computer trade magazine, and PC Computing, the nation's No. 2
computer consumer monthly. It also includes Interactive Week, an
Internet weekly magazine, and Yahoo! Internet Life, a popular
Internet consumer magazine title.
</P>
<P>
   The magazines have been considered bibles for computer buyers
everywhere, although ad sales have languished some in recent years
as the high-tech frontier has shifted from personal computers to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But the main reason for the sale, company executives said
Monday, was Ziff-Davis' depressed stock price, which had been
weighed down by staggering corporate debt and a ``balance sheet
that didn't make sense to anybody on Wall Street,'' a company
executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Ziff-Davis last summer hired Morgan Stanley Dean Witter to help
find ways to get its stock price up. And in August, the company
sold ZD Market Intelligence, its market research unit, to direct
marketing company Harte-Hanks Inc. for $106 million. The company
expects to close the sale of its ZD Education and its interest in
ZDTV before the end of the first quarter of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major step toward our goal of unlocking value for
our shareholders,'' Eric Hippeau, Ziff-Davis chairman and chief
executive, said of Monday's sale.
</P>
<P>
   Ziff-Davis said it would retain the publications Computer
Shopper and its ownership interest in Red Herring, a Silicon Valley
venture capital magazine. It will also keep its Internet
properties, traded under the separate tracking stock of ZDNet. The
deal includes an arrangement in which ZDNet will pay royalties to
use Ziff-Davis Publishing content on line for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Ziff-Davis fell 1 3/16 to 17 1/16 on the New York
Stock Exchange. ZDNet shares fell 1 1/2 to 21 3/8, also on the
NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   PC Week _ a highly successful news and buying guide for
corporate computer administrators published in Medford, Mass. _
isn't expected to be immediately effected by the sale.
</P>
<P>
   A business plan to ``grow'' the magazine over the next five to
seven years, presented to magazine editors by Willis Stein &AMP;
Partners in a conference call was well received, an editor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seemed enthusiastic and have a good plan in mind,'' the
editor said.
</P>
<P>
   Willis Stein said it named James Dunning Jr. as chairman and
chief executive of the publishing group. Dunning formerly ran
Petersen, the largest US publisher of special interest magazines.
He was executive vice president at Ziff-Davis predecessor Ziff
Communications, from 1984 to 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The publishing unit transaction is expected to close in the
first quarter of 2000 and is subject to financing and other
conditions, the company said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
