<SLUG> BC-COURT-WARNING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TO REVIEW MIRANDA WARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By MARK HELM   c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide whether
federal agents are required to read criminal suspects the so-called
Miranda warning telling them that they have a right to remain
silent.
</P>
<P>
   The warning has become familiar through movies and television:
You have a right to remain silent and to have a lawyer even if you
can't afford one, and anything you say may be held against you in
court.
</P>
<P>
   In taking a case involving a Maryland man who made
self-incriminating statements to the FBI, the justices agreed to
decide if the comments can be used as evidence in his bank-robbery
trial even if the agents did not first read him the warning.
</P>
<P>
   At stake are more than three decades of court precedent aimed at
overcoming police abuses and coerced admissions that courts over
the years said violated a fundamental tenet the Constitution's the
right against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The high court is being asked to agree with a lower court that
said the 1966 Miranda vs. Arizona ruling that led to the warning
has been invalidated in federal cases by a 1968 law passed by
Congress. If the justices agree, then states presumably could
decide to abolish the warnings in state and local police cases.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966 the Supreme Court overturned the conviction of Ernesto
Miranda, 23 and a poor, eighth-grade dropout who was found guilty
after confessing that he had raped an 18-year-old woman. The court
said he should be have been told of his rights to remain silent and
consult an attorney before he talked to the police.
</P>
<P>
   In the Maryland case, the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Richmond, Va., ruled in February 1998 that the Miranda decision had
been superseded by Section 3501 of Congress' 1968 crime bill _
passed at a time of urban riots and high street crime.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, that section has been largely ignored until the
circuit court's surprising ruling last year.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court's decision stemmed from a $876 bank robbery in
Alexandria, Va., on Jan. 24, 1997. During the robbery, a witness
took down the license plate number of the getaway car, a white
Oldsmobile. Three days later, FBI agents showed up at the Takoma
Park, Md., apartment of the car's registered owner, an unemployed
man named Charles Dickerson. The Oldsmobile was out front.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson says the agents busted in; they say he opened the
door. Nevertheless, he agreed to accompany them to an FBI office.
He refused, however, to let them search his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Agent Christopher Lawlor later testified that he had noticed
a wad of cash on the bed as Dickerson picked up his coat. During
Dickerson's questioning at the FBI office, Lawlor left the room,
called a magistrate and got permission to search the suspect's
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Lawlor returned to the interview room and told Dickerson he had
obtained a search warrant. Dickerson then confessed to driving his
car in a series of robberies.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson's lawyers sought to suppress the evidence, claiming
their client was not given Miranda warnings before confessing. The
FBI denied the claim, but a U.S. District Court accepted
Dickerson's contention and threw out the confession and the
evidence found in the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth Circuit court, citing Section 3501 of the 1968 crime
law, said mere ``technical violations'' of Miranda should no longer
negate all confessions.
</P>
<P>
   By an 8-5 vote, the appeals court said that 3501 means that
failing to issue Miranda warnings is just one of several factors
courts should consider in deciding whether statements to police
were made voluntarily. The law says judges may look at whether any
warnings were given, at the time that elapsed between a suspect's
being taken into custody and confessing, and at whether the
defendant knew for sure that he could remain silent or request an
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The circuit judges quoted a recent comment of Supreme Court
Justice Antonin Scalia, who said failure to use Section 3501 ``may
have produced ... the non-prosecution of many dangerous felons.''
The judges said Dickerson ``is just such a case.''
</P>
<P>
   In a friend-of-the-court brief to the Fourth Circuit court,
University of Utah law professor Paul Cassell, who will defend
Section 3501 before the Supreme Court, argued that the 1968 law
allowed use of Dickerson's statements regardless of any Miranda
violation. Cassell, who represents the conservative Washington
Legal Foundation, contended that Miranda has had a ``devastating
effect on law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court agreed, saying Miranda warnings were created
simply to safeguard the Fifth Amendment's right to silence. In
addition, it said, the Miranda decision invited states and Congress
to ``develop their own safeguards.'' If the states are free to
initiate their own rules, the Fourth Circuit said, then the Miranda
warnings cannot possibly be a constitutional standard.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief supporting the Miranda rule, Attorney General Janet
Reno argued that the 1968 law cannot be enforced because the
Miranda decision ``is of constitutional dimension'' and ``cannot be
superseded merely by legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   She urged the court to overrule the Dickerson decision and
predicted serious repercussions otherwise. Miranda ``has come to
play a unique and important role in the nation's conception of our
criminal justice system,'' the brief said. ``It promotes public
confidence that the criminal justice system is fair.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
