<SLUG> BC-CABLE-ATT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T OPEN-ACCESS PLAN CRITICIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Advocates of open access to fast Internet cable modems slammed
AT&AMP;T Monday for overhyping an agreement in principle to make its
services available to the nation's second-biggest Internet
provider, calling the deal too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of smoke; it's a lot of mirrors, and when you find
your way through it there is not much there,'' said Stephen Allen,
spokesman for a group organizing a November 2000 Massachusetts
ballot question demanding open access statewide. ``Our campaign is
still very much on.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Federal Communications chairman William E.
Kennard, cosigned by AT&AMP;T and MindSpring, the country's number two
Internet service provider, the phone giant said it will allow cable
modem customers to choose any ISP they want once AT&AMP;T's exclusive
contract with Excite AtHome expires in mid-2002 and once
unspecified ``technical issues are addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, people who subscribe to high-speed cable modems from
AT&AMP;T or MediaOne go to the home page of affiliated ISPs such as
Excite AtHome and RoadRunner, unless they pay more and reconfigure
their computer to go to a different ISP.
</P>
<P>
   Rival ISPs contend that as a public monopoly, cable franchises
should be required to sell them wholesale access to the cable lines
so they can enroll subscribers offering the same high-speed access
that Excite AtHome and RoadRunner can offer.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T supporters called the MindSpring pact _ essentially, an
agreement to negotiate access terms _ a landmark deal that proves
that government action is unnecessary to open access through fast
cable modems to ISPs, and that such moves should be left to
business-to-business negotiations in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AT&AMP;T/MindSpring agreement strongly reinforces our view
that private sector negotiations are much more likely to produce
benefits to consumers than any set of government-imposed
regulations,'' said Robert Sachs, president of the National Cable
Television Association.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard called the agreement a ``good first step toward
providing consumers with a choice of Internet service providers
without paying twice,'' adding that he continues to think imposing
government regulations mandating such access ``would only slow down
broadband deployment.''
</P>
<P>
   But open access advocates said in several ways, there was far
less to the AT&AMP;T-MindSpring pact than the companies claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the fact that it covers only one of the hundreds of
ISPs, it would not take effect until June 2002 at the soonest, when
the deal expires under which AT&AMP;T makes Excite AtHome the exclusive
affiliated home page with its cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the letter to the FCC is little more than a plan spelling
out a version of open access AT&AMP;T would support and a promise to
negotiate terms with MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   Even a top MindSpring executive, David N. Baker, said, ``We
applaud AT&AMP;T for moving in the right direction . . . (but) there
are still major issues to be resolved. We see no reason for them to
have to wait around for another 2 1/2 years.''
</P>
<P>
   America Online said it will continue to lobby for a nationwide
open access policy, calling the MindSpring deal nothing more than a
good start.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's group, the Massachusetts Coalition for Consumer Choice
and Competition on the Internet, last week filed 70,000 voter
signatures as a first step toward a proposed November 2000 ballot
question requiring MediaOne and other cable franchises to open
access on their systems to all ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an illusion, it's not the solution,'' Allen said. By
offering the possibility of MindSpring as an equal-cost, same-speed
alternative to Excite AtHome, Allen said, ``They're saying you can
have either A or B, but we want to offer you the choice from A to
Z.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T general counsel Jim Cicconi said the company ``has already
begun negotiations with a number of ISPs'' in hopes of reaching
agreements similar to the MindSpring pact. However, company
officials said they see no way to back out of the exclusive
contract with Excite AtHome, in which AT&AMP;T holds a controlling
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Excite AtHome chief technology officer Milo Medin warned
that providing shared access with MindSpring could require two
years to develop and install technical changes. ``The technology to
do what we're talking about in that letter doesn't exist today,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
