<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, Dec. 7. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-MIRANDA (Washington) _ The Miranda decision, a
33-year-old landmark of the Warren Court's criminal procedure
revolution, headed Monday for its most important test, as the
justices announced that they would decide whether Congress had
effectively overruled it with a law that was enacted for that
purpose in 1968 and then was ignored almost ever since. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With MIRANDA-HISTORY.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-LANDER (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Just about now, if things
had gone differently, Wayne Zimmerman would have been waiting
expectantly and nervously for the Mars Polar Lander's mechanical
arm to start digging in the planet's cold ground, searching for
evidence of water ice. Instead, the engineer and others are worried
that the $165-million mission's failure could prompt public and
congressional criticism of the entire Mars exploration program,
including possible calls for severe cutbacks. By John Noble
Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MONACO-SAFRA (Paris) _ An American nurse employed by Edmond
Safra admitted Monday that he set the fire that killed the
billionaire banker in his luxury penthouse in Monte Carlo last
Friday, Monaco's chief prosecutor said. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: An early version has moved in `i' news file; it will be
updated.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-RUSSIA (Znamenskoye, Chechnya) _ The Russian military
dropped thousands of leaflets over Grozny on Monday, warning
residents of the besieged city to get out by Saturday or risk
death. Those who fail to leave will be considered terrorists and
bandits and will be eliminated by aviation and artillery, the
leaflet warned. By Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-CRACKDOWN (San Francisco) _ In San Francisco, homeless
people haunt the city: hiding in doorways, pushing overloaded
shopping carts, standing on corners announcing their troubles on
cardboard signs (``Veteran, homeless and hungry''). But San
Francisco is far from alone. At the richest time in the nation's
history, housing that the poor can afford is at an all-time low,
fueling an increase in homelessness, according to the United States
Conference of Mayors. And with complaints about beggars and bag
ladies and mumbling, stumbling vagrants growing as well, cities are
fighting to move homeless people out of public spaces as never
before. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT26-28.
</P>
<P>
   INTERFAITH-DECORATIONS (Undated) _ The December holidays have
long been a source of angst for many duel-faith couples, and the
tug is particularly acute for Christians and Jews whose seasonal
celebrations collide head on with Christmas and Hanukkah. Couples
have often decided to forgo one holiday or simply display the
paraphernalia of both side by side. But many families are now
synthesizing two customs. The commercial marketplace is starting to
respond to this pluralistic view of the holidays by producing what
was once taboo: decorations that merge the symbols of two
observances. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT29.
</P>
<P>
   Two column reefer:
</P>
<P>
   VALUJET-SABRETECH (Miami) _ SabreTech, the aircraft maintenance
company that safety investigators concluded had improperly packaged
the oxygen generators linked to the 1996 crash of ValuJet Flight
592, was found guilty in a subdued federal courtroom of improperly
handling the hazardous materials. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE:
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-BANKS-HOLOCAUST (Undated) _ A three-year search of Swiss
banks accused of hiding accounts held by Holocaust victims ended on
Monday with a commission of independent auditors announcing it had
found 54,000 accounts that were probably linked to victims of Nazi
persecution, and describing in detail how some of the banks had
issued ``deliberately misleading statements'' for decades to Jews
who had come looking for their family's assets. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-IVESTER (Undated) _ After a grueling year of product
recalls, falling profits and scuttled acquisition plans,
Coca-Cola's top executive said that he would step down in April. M.
Douglas Ivester, 52, said simply that he wanted to move on to a
different stage of his life. But his decision to retire as chairman
and chief executive at such a young age after a mere two years
stunned shareholders and the business world. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   With NYT10.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SCHIZOPHRENIA-RESEARCH (Undated) _ Researchers are
beginning, in a systematic way, to investigate the earliest stages
of schizophrenia, attempting to find signs that could predict its
onset. But some of that research has become controversial,
particularly the aspect of treating people with drugs for a
condition they do not yet have. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-SERIAL-MURDER (Lahore, Pakistan) _ Since Thursday
morning, people, some of them from hundreds of miles away, have
come to look for evidence that their missing sons were slain by a
man who says he sexually molested and killed 100 young boys and
then dissolved their flesh and bones in vats of chemicals. So far,
the parents have claimed 69 of the victims, most of them boys
between ages 12 and 15. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
