A1037 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-CANCERDIARY07-COX     12-06 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CANCERDIARY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reporter's `Diary' takes clear-eyed view of cancer
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's become the new morning in America: healthy one day, cancer
the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family, there was like no illness, and then my brother got
leukemia and my mother got breast cancer and I got lymphoma, all in
the course of five years,'' Rebecca Perl says as she journeys from
her Maryland home to a Nebraska hospital for a bone marrow
transplant. ``It's just so weird, all this cancer in our family,
all of a sudden.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the next things we see in this often frankly funny yet
desperately frank Cinemax documentary, ``Scenes From a Transplant:
A Cancer Diary,'' is Perl giving herself an injection in a locked
Waffle House restroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``At home, I'd do it at like 7:25, right before `Seinfeld,'''
Perl explains as she shoots a prescribed drug into her thigh. ``If
it took me more than five minutes to do it, I'd miss `Seinfeld,' so
I'd hurry myself along.''
</P>
<P>
   Perl, who survived the transplant, is a science correspondent
for National Public Radio in Washington. She was diagnosed with
non-Hodgkins lymphoma six months after the birth of her son.
</P>
<P>
   A year of chemotherapy failed to destroy the cancerous tumor in
her chest. A bone marrow transplant was her last chance. ``A Cancer
Diary,'' co-produced and directed by Dan Collison and Perl's
longtime companion, Tom Jennings, chronicles her months-long
transplant ordeal. Told that she can go home after what appears to
be a successful transplant, with nurses patting her and cheering
her on, Perl comments afterward about her reaction, ``I felt like a
contestant on a game show. Like I was supposed to jump up and
down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't?'' she's asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. ... I feigned a little excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about this whole process that's overly
optimistic to me,'' she adds later. ``I have to be very cautious. I
don't really know what the deal is.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal here is nothing fancy _ Perl was teetering between life
and death _ and neither is this documentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question we're kind of avoiding is the cancer
itself,'' Jennings says. ``We're so encumbered with the daily
routine, we're not really thinking about the final goal at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is that diarylike attention to the banal and unpretty
that ultimately makes this chronicle so profound. There are times
when ``Scenes'' can seem almost too clear-eyed; there's a sense
that Perl is both the reporter and the reported upon, and that
she's speaking at a slightly cool remove from what's happening to
her.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a huge, hard story that overwhelms any smallish
shortcomings. By the end, as she's leaving the Nebraska hospital in
the dead of winter, you want to fling your own hat along with the
tiny, baby-birdlike Perl, as she does a half-baked imitation of
Mary Tyler Moore (``You're gonna make it after all!'') from the old
TV show.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, Perl has taught us to be cautious, too. The end is
full of both hope and heartache: another morning in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scenes From
</P>
<P>
   a Transplant:
</P>
<P>
   A Cancer Diary''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight at 6:30 on Cinemax
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
