<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-DELEGATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH LEADER WANTS A REAL PEACE DIVIDEND: U.S. INVESTMENT IN
NORTHERN IRELAND  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Britain's senior minister for Northern Ireland
called on the Clinton administration Thursday to work with American
businesses to step up investment in Northern Ireland to support the
peace agreement by ending ``the very real poverty and deprivation''
found there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to see an early dividend from the peace that
has been created,'' said Peter Mandelson, the Northern Ireland
secretary, after meeting at the White House with administration
officials to brief them on the accord that has brought home rule in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he was promoting investment to cement the peace,
Mandelson acknowledged that the negotiations that have ended
decades of violence in Northern Ireland could be set back ``to
square one'' without continued cooperation between pro-British
unionists and pro-Irish republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties now realize that they need each other,'' he told
reporters. ``This is the essence of the accommodation that has been
struck.'' But, he said, ``we still have to go the final mile.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, London transferred local government authority for
Northern Ireland to a new power-sharing assembly drawn from the
Protestant and Catholic parties. Last weekend, the outlawed Irish
Republican Army sent an emissary to meet with an international
disarmament committee to discuss the turnover of its weapons, which
is required under the peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson said that as a result of the peace process, Northern
Ireland had undergone a ``transformation'' that should have obvious
appeal to American business executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a completely different place _ no roadchecks, no
roadblocks, people going about their day's business, their normal
lives, as anywhere else in the United Kingdom,'' he said, adding
that he wanted ``to bring home to the American business community
the huge return from their investment in Northern Ireland, if they
were to commit to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States is already the largest single foreign investor
in Northern Ireland. According to British government figure,
American companies have invested about $1.9 billion there over the
last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year two-thirds of all first-time investment in Northern
Ireland was made by American companies, including several
electronics firms seeking to take advantage of its well-educated,
relatively low-cost work force. American companies employ about 10
percent of the nearly 140,000 people who work in manufacturing jobs
in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have good people, good skills,'' said Mandelson, a close
political ally of Prime Minister Tony Blair who was named to the
Northern Ireland post in October.
</P>
<P>
   The mood of the talks Monday between the British delegation led
by Mandelson and Clinton administration officials was that of a
mutual admiration society.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson repeatedly praised President Clinton and former Sen.
George Mitchell of Maine, who oversaw the negotiations that led to
home rule in Northern Ireland, for their involvement in the peace
process. He said that Clinton had made use of the ``the persuasive
skills for which he is famous'' in the peace negotiations and that
``he has not spared any effort, any ounce of energy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1927EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1040 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ATT-MINDSPRING-COX     12-06 1586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-MINDSPRING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT&AMP;T sets new path for high-speed future
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AT&AMP;T on Monday moved to bolster its sagging reputation
on Wall Street, announcing a new strategy for giving rivals access
to its high-speed cable network and sweeping changes to its
management structure.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced the creation of a special tracking
stock for its wireless unit and $1 billion construction of a
fiber-optic network linking 30 metropolitan areas, including
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The news includes a shake-up among top executives jostling to
succeed Chief Executive Officer Michael Armstrong, whose bold but
risky strategic gambles have at least raised the specter of a
premature departure. Armstrong is 61 and the mandatory retirement
age is 65.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, flying high in early 1999, has seen a slow slide in its
stock price as doubts mounted concerning its ability to pull off
the seismic shift from lumbering long-distance company to agile
high-speed telecommunications provider. That bet rides in part on a
pending $62 billion purchase of MediaOne, in the midst of continued
bumpiness of AT&AMP;T's $70 billion acquisition of Tele-Communications
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   After months of resisting the notion of providing access to
competing Internet service providers over its cable lines, AT&AMP;T
signed a deal with Atlanta-based MindSpring Enterprises setting out
principles for this. That deal would give AT&AMP;T customers a choice
in their ISP _ but not until 2002, when the company's current
arrangement with ISP Excite At Home expires.
</P>
<P>
   While the deal was endorsed by Kenneth Fellman, chairman of an
advisory board to the Federal Communications Commission _ any final
arrangement would need FCC approval.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea drew fire from several who had been part of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   One who dropped out was Andrew Schwartzman, president of the
Media Access Project, a law firm representing citizen interests at
the FCC. Another was a representative of Mayor Bill Campbell.
Campbell was asked to participate by FCC Chairman William Kennard
in his capacity as head of the national mayors council.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Campbell's city is home to both MindSpring and a
franchise of MediaOne, which has about 610,900 customers in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, having won AT&AMP;T's big concession for open access,
MindSpring almost immediately began campaigning for more. In a
letter to the FCC, Dave Baker, MindSpring vice president, wrote
that the deal would allow AT&AMP;T to retain the power to control how
video streaming, telephone use and other services would be
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   He called on the FCC to pry still more concessions from AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise, today's agreement will not benefit consumers for
years to come _ if even then,'' Baker said. ``While this commitment
is an important step in the right direction, it is only a first
step.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has about 10,000 employees in more than 20 locations
throughout metro Atlanta, including the Midtown offices that serve
as headquarters for the Southeast. The company also has one of its
three network control centers in Conyers, which handles close to
100 million calls each day, and its data processing and financial
centers in Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the executive changes nor the creation of a tracking
stock announced Monday is expected to have any impact on Atlanta or
the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T plans a $1 billion fiber-optic network that will link 30
metropolitan areas, including Atlanta. Those areas, which already
have AT&AMP;T fiber, will account for about 80 percent of the demand
for high-speed services, according to Frank Ianna, president of
AT&AMP;T Network Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project will allow us to quickly and economically
increase bandwidth whenever necessary,'' Ianna said.
</P>
<P>
   Bandwidth _ the capacity of a line to transmit huge amounts of
data quickly _ is key to many new services, like video via the
Internet. But AT&AMP;T's local fiber did not connect directly to
consumers _ which is why the company went on an unprecedented
buying spree, hoping to forge detours around local phone companies
that have direct connections to consumer homes.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong went to Wall Street and persuaded investors and
analysts that by spending more than $100 billion on acquisitions,
AT&AMP;T would hold a significant if not commanding piece of future
communications.
</P>
<P>
   Computer data, e-mail, phone, video, digital television and
high-speed Internet access would all flow through one wire _ owned
by AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   But the luster of that vision has dimmed. TCI, a largely rural
system, has been slow to convert to high-speed networks, and
MediaOne, too, will be tough to upgrade and integrate into AT&AMP;T's
system.
</P>
<P>
   At best, it will years before AT&AMP;T's plan bears fruit. At worst,
it will be mired in costly upgrades and outpaced by other
telecommunication systems _ especially the high-speed digital
subscriber lines offered by phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T stock crested in February at more than $63 a share before
starting its long slide. After one resurgence in May, AT&AMP;T fell
steadily, reaching a low of $41.75 a share on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, pre-Armstrong, AT&AMP;T seemingly couldn't do
anything right, and last year, post-Armstrong, they seemingly
couldn't do anything wrong,'' said Jeff Kagan, Atlanta-based
telecommunications analyst. ``Even though AT&AMP;T is making the right
kinds of moves to prepare for the future, we are just starting to
realize how massive a task transforming AT&AMP;T really is.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, AT&AMP;T began talking about ``unlocking the value'' of
its successful wireless business.
</P>
<P>
   The idea had been used with wild success by Sprint. Sprint PCS,
the wireless tracking stock created last year by Sprint, has
already quintupled in value.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless was seen as a high-growth, high-profit business that
could quickly achieve dramatically higher valuations than the old-
line long-distance business or the cable services in which AT&AMP;T
cable service was committed to sinking billions of dollars for
years. Tracking stocks provide no ownership, but instead promise
investors quick growth and often dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking stock can pump up a company's buying power. As the
tracking stock price rises, the company _ which retains most of the
shares _ has ever more currency to make deals.
</P>
<P>
   Acquisitions ``are one of the reasons to do a wireless tracker _
to get the currency,'' analyst Guy Woodlief of Prudential
Securities told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   The louder the AT&AMP;T secret was whispered, the more the stock
rose. In late November, AT&AMP;T hit $60 a share for the first time
since early July. AT&AMP;T closed Monday at $56.93 3/4, down 6.25 cents
a share.
</P>
<P>
   As if to highlight AT&AMP;T's challenges, the former chief of AT&AMP;T's
broadband and Internet unit picked Monday to announce that he had
taken a similar slot at Global Crossing, the ambitious company run
by another former AT&AMP;T executive.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Hindery, who left AT&AMP;T after repeated clashes with
Armstrong, will now report to Global Crossing CEO Robert
Annunziata, former CEO of Teleport Communications before it was
purchased by AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing, like Qwest Communications _ another company led
by an AT&AMP;T expatriates _ touts itself as the network of the future,
a high-speed, low-overhead outfit that will run rings around the
behemoths like AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong has been nothing if not bold.
</P>
<P>
   The tracking stock announced Monday will sell a 19 percent stake
in the unit, which has had sales growth of about 40 percent. The
offering, which is expected to raise up to $10 billion, created the
AT&AMP;T Wireless Group.
</P>
<P>
   John Zeglis, president of AT&AMP;T, was named chairman and chief
executive of the new unit.
</P>
<P>
   Zeglis, often mentioned as a candidate for the top job, was
among a host of executives emerging Monday with a new role in the
key units of Internet, wireless and cable.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes was the naming of Daniel Somers, who is chief
financial officer, as president and chief executive of AT&AMP;T
Broadband and Internet Services, responsible for cable television
and its upgrade to high-speed data. Somers is already unofficially
in that job, the position left empty by Hindery's departure.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Hesse will remain president and CEO of AT&AMP;T Wireless and
will become executive VP of the AT&AMP;T Wireless Group.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Keith, currently president of AT&AMP;T Business Services,
will join AT&AMP;T Wireless Group as executive vice president. Keith,
based in Atlanta for several years in the early 1990s as vice
president for sales in the Southeast, will now will be responsible
for launching a ``fixed wireless'' service that can offer
high-speed access where AT&AMP;T will not own cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   A report released Monday by the Strategis Group says the ascent
of wireless technology is close at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless broadband revenues, most of it coming from local
telephone service and Internet use, will grow at a 418 percent clip
during the next five years, according to Strategis, a
telecommunications consulting group. Wireless broadband revenues
will reach $3.4 billion in 2003, compared to 1999 revenues of $11.2
million, said John Zahurancik, vice president of Strategis Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 2003, we forecast that no less than 34 percent of U.S.
households and 45 percent of U.S. businesses will be serviceable by
broadband wireless networks.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
