<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-HOLBROOKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLBROOKE TAKES CAMPAIGN AGAINST CONGO CONFLICT TO SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRETORIA, South Africa _ Richard Holbrooke, the chief American
delegate to the United Nations, called on the warring parties in
Congo on Monday to live up to the peace accord they signed several
months ago, adding that other nations will help but not before they
see signs of sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech here to foreign affairs experts and journalists,
Holbrooke praised the framework of the agreement signed in July and
August in the Zambian capital, Lusaka. He said that until steps
were taken to carry out the agreement, the United States would not
support sending peacekeepers to Congo, the sprawling central
African nation formerly called Zaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peacekeeping requires far more than just words, more than
paper agreements,'' he said. ``The parties to the Lusaka agreement
must respect their commitments if peace is to return to the Congo.
The international community cannot simply impose peace.''
</P>
<P>
   He has said that there will be no American troops for an African
peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who is visiting leaders of all the countries involved
in the conflict, expressed concern about recent battles between
rebels and government forces in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The renewed fighting in the Congo, which is a direct violation
of the Lusaka agreement, threatens to leave this important
agreement in tatters,'' he said. ``If the parties in Congo truly
want the international community's involvement and support, such
violations are simply unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's message will be repeated often over the next few
days. His tour of Africa has already taken him to Angola and
Namibia, both supporters of the Congolese government. After his
speech here in South Africa's administrative capital, Holbrooke's
agenda included visits to Zimbabwe and Zambia, which have also
backed the Congolese government.
</P>
<P>
   From Zambia he will go to Congo, to meet with President Laurent
Kabila, and to Uganda and Rwanda, both of which have been backing
the rebels in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila led a rebellion from eastern Congo that succeeded, in May
1997, in taking power from the longtime dictator, Mobutu Sese Seko.
A year later, a rebel movement began against his government, and
the neighboring countries have provided support to one side or the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke hopes he can push the parties toward finally
appointing a mediator, as called for in the Lusaka agreement, to
guide the early stages of carrying it out. It would be a simple but
very significant step, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's efforts to address the conflict in Congo come as the
United States is preparing to assume the presidency of the U.N.
Security Council next month. Holbrooke said on Sunday that he
intends to the use the position to focus attention on Africa and in
particular the conflicts in Congo and Angola, where a long-running
civil war has started again.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has authorized a force of 500 military
observers as a prelude to a peacekeeping force in Congo. But the
renewed fighting has prevented the observers from beginning their
work and would make a peacekeeping effort a waste at this point,
Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot expect that alone, outside peacekeepers will deliver
a peace that is lasting and just,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Holbrooke made it clear that he did not expect
his visits to solve the Congo conflict, but that he hoped they
might push the process forward a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Regional leaders and experts say that the United States has an
important role to play but that ultimately the responsibility rests
closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the U.S. going to directly affect this? No, not in any
way,'' said Jakkie Potgieter, a researcher at the Institute for
Security Studies in South Africa and an expert on military conflict
in Africa. ``But it is important. It reassures the region around
the conflict, countries like South Africa that are working very
hard trying to resolve this, that the U.S. supports what they are
doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
