<HEADER>
A1043 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-WALLSTREET-COX     12-06 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-WALLSTREET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fall in stock price reflects abrupt change in leadership
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Reflecting the uncertainties of a shift in management,
shares of Coca-Cola fell as much as 8.3 percent Monday on three
times average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   The shares tumbled to as low as $62.62 1/2 before finishing at
$63.93 3/4, down $4.37 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   More than 13.2 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and analysts were divided on the near-term prospects
for the stock, which fell to a 52-week low of $47.31 1/4 about two
months ago before rebounding on several recent ``buy''
recommendations from brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   The expectation was that Coca-Cola's profits would recover next
year as prices and sales volumes rise and overseas markets pick up.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Coca-Cola reported volume trends during October and
November are tracking ahead of growth from the third quarter of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the trends reflect improving economic
conditions in many parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The volume trend figures exclude those Cadbury Schweppes
beverage brands that Coke acquired in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola also has been raising prices, hoping to boost profit.
</P>
<P>
   But the management change unsettled some investors, leading to
the sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's concern out there that even though Coke has given
indications volume is beginning to turn around, the change in
leadership could disrupt that process,'' explained analyst Tim
Drake of Banc One Investment Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Those concerns might be misplaced, said money manager Phillip M.
Larkins of Atlanta-based Legacy South, which owns 200,000 Coca-Cola
shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would view the change as an effort to mend fences
internationally, particularly in Europe, with a non-American CEO,''
said Larkins, noting that Douglas N. Daft, who will succeed current
chairman and chief executive, M. Douglas Ivester next April, is an
Australian.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent the stock-price decline doesn't reflect renewed
earnings worries, I think it's a buying opportunity. It's not every
day a stock drops 8 percent or so.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Larkins noted that even at Monday's price,
Coca-Cola's shares still trade at a hefty premium to that of the
benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, of which it is a
member.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's shares now trade at 51.6 times trailing 12-month
earnings; and 49.5 times estimated 1999 earnings of $1.29 a share.
The S&AMP;P 500 is trading at 31.5 times earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you're nervous about the stock market, you don't
buy,'' Larkins said. ``But if you were looking to buy the stock,
you might at least begin to take an initial position. If you were
contemplating buying 1,000 shares, you might want to go ahead and
buy 500 shares.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkins said that based on the company's improving fundamentals,
he doesn't believe the stock will fall back to October's lows.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts that recently recommend the shares continued to
do so Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Douglas Lane of Merrill Lynch, who kept his
``buy'' rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock has sold off on the news because it was sudden and
unexpected, but we believe that Coke has a very deep bench, and
that fundamentals continue to improve at the company,'' Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   The management change signals ``a close to a very difficult
chapter in the company's history'' and a change in management
style, Lane added.
</P>
<P>
   But several other analysts removed their ``buy''
recommendations, including Andrew J. Conway of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. He downgraded the stock to ``neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   K. Timothy Swanson of A.G. Edwards lowered his rating to
``maintain position'' from ``buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some investors have noted that, under Ivester, Coca-Cola's stock
has risen just 11 percent, trailing the 48 percent rise in the S&AMP;P
500.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the first time in two decades, the stock's price is on
track for an annual decline.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, investors apparently weren't concerned about the
company's prospects last year, when they bid up the stock price to
as high as $87.93 3/4 on July 14. At that price, the stock was
trading at about 58 times trailing 12-month earnings, showing its
biggest P/E expansion in decades.
</P>
<P>
   To compare, the stock traded as low as eight times earnings in
January 1982, before the current bull market began.
</P>
<P>
   About half of Coca-Cola's shares are held by individuals, with
the other half owned by institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Luke writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Bloomberg News contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
