<HEADER>
A1045 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-POLIO-VACCINE-BOS &LR;      12-06 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLIO-VACCINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDIATRICIANS URGE USE OF SAFER POLIO VIRUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics recommended Monday that
doctors should stop using the oral polio vaccine, made from a
weakened live virus, and switch over to injections, which contain
the dead polio virus.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the routine childhood immunization schedule, all
infants get the vaccine for polio, the highly contagious intestinal
infection that can spread quickly to the brain and spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been controversy about the oral vaccine because,
although indigenous polio has been eradicated from the United
States since 1979, a few people get polio each year from the
vaccine designed to prevent the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The academy's new policy, to go into effect Jan. 1, is published
in the December issue of Pediatrics, the academy's journal.
</P>
<P>
   The oral vaccine was used for so long because it had a public
health benefit that the killed virus does not. When polio outbreaks
were common, people who received the killed vaccine in the
injectible form could still carry the indigenous virus in their
intestines and infect those who were not vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the inactivated vaccine only provided specific
immunity to the child receiving the vaccine. With the oral vaccine,
the child could also pass on immunity to those who didn't receive
the vaccine, doctors said, calling that an important advantage in
communities of unvaccinated individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Even though natural polio has been officially eradicated in the
United States since 1979, there were five cases of polio from
people entering the country with the disease between 1980 and 1986.
Because all children still must get their polio vaccine before
starting school, the disease didn't spread with those ``imported''
cases.
</P>
<P>
   But between 1992 and 1993, an ``imported'' virus in the
Netherlands resulted in 70 cases of polio in a community whose
members refused vaccination for religious reasons. Of those, two
died and 59 became paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   The AAP has suggested doctors could use up their remaining
supplies of oral vaccine for the third and fourth doses in the
series of four that children receive, but they should not buy more.
There has not been a case of vaccine-caused polio when the first
two doses are injected and the last two oral, said the AAP.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Duplease of North Haven, Conn. is critical of the academy
for allowing a grace period so remaining supplies of the oral
vaccine could be used. Her six-year-old daughter, Alexis
Duplease-Landolfi, has to wear a leg brace on her right leg because
she got polio from the vaccine after the first dose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like how the academy has told the doctors that they
need to go to an all-injectible schedule and then give them another
chance to use up their leftover vaccines. Another parent should not
have to go through what I have,'' Duplease said.
</P>
<P>
   The company that has produced the oral vaccine, Wyeth-Lederle
Vaccines, no longer sells or produces it, said a company
spokeswoman. Physicians are able to obtain a full refund or credit
for the unused oral vaccines, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Georges Peter, a professor of pediatrics at Brown University
School of Medicine and member of the Committee of Infectious
Diseases of the AAP, said the transitional period was allowed
because there was no guarantee that the manufacturer would take
back the product.
</P>
<P>
   ``The six-month period is only to provide a time limit. I don't
think there will be much use of the oral vaccine after the first
one or two months,'' Peter said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said the oral vaccine should be used only when there is
a polio outbreak or when previously unvaccinated children will be
traveling in less than four weeks to polio-endemic areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were in a country that still had polio, it would be a
mistake to recommend the inactivated vaccine,'' Peter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
