<HEADER>
A1046 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-MEXICO-KILLINGS-COX     12-06 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-KILLINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latest bad news in Juarez casts pall on economy, life
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIUDAD JUAREZ, Chihuahua _ Francisco Alcanter's eyes searched
for tourists coming over the international bridge from El Paso.
``Taxi?'' he asked, jockeying with other cab drivers for business.
</P>
<P>
   Alcanter has seen the news about Mexican and U.S. officials
digging for bodies at two ranches near Juarez, where they believe
victims of the city's long-running drug war are buried. The latest
headlines bother Alcanter, who remains skeptical of reports of mass
graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The publicity, unfortunately, hurts a lot of families,'' he
said. ``The tourists listen to the news, and they're afraid to come
here.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, Juarez, a blue-collar factory city of
almost 2 million people, has been the scene of more than any city's
share of bad news.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 women have been slain in Juarez since 1993, many
of them young factory workers abducted as they returned home from
jobs in one of the city's 330 maquiladoras, the U.S.-owned plants
where Mexican workers assemble products for the American market.
</P>
<P>
   The string of killings, which many Juarez residents suspect are
the work of one or more serial killers, ha-- attracted worldwide
attention.
</P>
<P>
   When drug kingpin Amado Carrillo Fuentes, who ran the powerful
Juarez cartel for years, died in July 1997 after undergoing plastic
surgery and liposuction, a bloody war for control of his empire
broke out in Juarez's streets. Gunmen massacred people in
restaurants. Bodies turned up all over the city. And people began
vanishing.
</P>
<P>
   All over Juarez, the violence has bred fear, and fear has
changed how many people live.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go from home to work and from work to home,'' said Eduardo
Lopez, a Juarez resident who works as a bricklayer in El Paso.
Lopez said he and his wife have two children, ages 4 and 8, and
``we don't let them go out, only to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Estrada, who has lived in Juarez for 42 years, said she
doesn't think the city's law-abiding citizens can do much to change
things. The drug traffickers have too much money and too much
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police don't do anything,'' Estrada said. ``They're
connected to all that (drug activity).''
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Hervella, president of an El Paso group called the
Association of Relatives and Friends of Disappeared Persons, said
his group has counted 196 missing people in Juarez and El Paso.
Families in Juarez have reported loved ones dragged from their
homes by armed, uniformed men in vans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Mexican authorities, aided by 65 FBI agents, began
excavating what may be the graves of people who have disappeared
during the past four years. Authorities have reported finding six
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   In Juarez and El Paso, two cities linked by history, economics
and blood ties, images of masked Mexican soldiers guarding the
grave sites made residents shudder and businesspeople worry.
</P>
<P>
   For El Paso resident Javier Arias, the latest grim news just
reinforced his anxiety about crossing into Juarez.
</P>
<P>
   Arias, a Chihuahua native who lived in Juarez for 16 years
before moving to the U.S. side of the river, said he frequently
visits family in Juarez _ but only during the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go at night,'' he said. ``Juarez is beautiful, but
it's not like before. It's dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   On Juarez Avenue, the main strip leading from one of the
international bridges downtown, the pharmacies and gift shops
lining the crowded street live or die on tourist dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby discos, which under Mexican law can serve alcohol to
anyone over 18, draw U.S. high school and college students with
thumping music and cheap drinks.
</P>
<P>
   El Pasoans routinely cross the border to dine, shop and visit
family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   News of the graves is likely to hurt businesses on both sides of
the Rio Grande, at least temporarily, said Tom Fullerton, an
economist at the University of Texas at El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has no data to show how highly publicized crime
affects border businesses, Fullerton said businesspeople in both
cities have reported slowdowns after past news flurries.
</P>
<P>
   Juarez's merchants will ride out this latest wave of unwanted
international attention, as they have for years, said Felipe
Sorcia, who runs Mexico Lindo Curios on Juarez Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't affect us much,'' Sorcia said. ``Crisis is a
permanent condition in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Aguilar, 20, a Juarez native who is studying microbiology
at UTEP, said the restaurant shootings didn't stop students from
flowing into Juarez's entertainment district, and neither will the
latest news.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the discos are full of people from El Paso,'' he said.
``My friends here go regularly.''
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Maese, a 22-year-old El Pasoan, said, ``I still go over
there. I'm not scared. It's good food; it's a good atmosphere. It's
cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Maese's 31-year-old friend shook his head, saying he hasn't been
to Juarez in a year. The man, who refused to give his name _ ``You
can't be too careful around here,'' he explained _ said one of his
friends, a 25-year-old UTEP student named Carlos Valmana, died in
1997 when gunmen sprayed Geronimo's Bar and Grill in Juarez with
automatic rifle fire. Valmana, a bystander, was among three killed
in what police called a drug-related hit.
</P>
<P>
   The attack came a month after six people died in similar fashion
at the Max-Fin restaurant, next door to Geronimo's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss Juarez,'' said Maese's friend, an El Paso native. ``But
you don't want to be a statistic. You never know what's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
