<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-HONDURAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students help bring gifts to Honduras
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hoping to balm still-raw memories from a shooting last
May at Heritage High School that left six of their classmates
wounded, two Conyers, Ga., teenagers left Monday for Honduras to
help evangelist Franklin Graham deliver small Christmas gifts to
destitute and dying children.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said senior Tracie Watkins, 18, and junior Cary Sanders,
16, were chosen to take part in this year's ``Operation Christmas
Child'' program because their brush with tragedy will help them
empathize with some of the poorest people on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   While their modest gifts will ``bring great joy'' to the
Honduran children, who have nothing, it also will prove cathartic
for the Heritage teens, who in comparison, have practically
everything, Graham said in an interview. Meeting the poor Honduran
kids will make Conyers teens realize even more how lucky they are,
Graham said, though their memories of that bloody day last May will
never go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also thought this would be a wonderful way to show the good
that's in the schools where tragedies have occurred,'' said Graham,
47, son of evangelist Billy Graham and his already-anointed
successor. ``This will help the girls see how fortunate they are,
even though they have gone through tragic circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Honduras has always been among the poorest nations. And last
fall, Hurricane Mitch slammed into the Central American country,
killing 13,000 people _ a horrific tragedy in a republic of less
than 6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, head of Samaritan's Purse, a $100 million-a-year
nonprofit relief organization in Boone, N.C., piloted a twin-engine
Sabreliner to Honduras after a news conference Monday morning with
Watkins and Sanders. They spoke near a cargo hangar, where 70,000
brightly-colored shoe boxes stuffed with toys packed by children in
Georgia and Alabama were loaded aboard a gigantic Russian-made
freight plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can touch the heart of even a single child, this project
will be an amazing success, Sanders told a crowd of several hundred
well-wishers.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, Graham and his organization have delivered shoe box
gifts to almost 6 million underprivileged children in dozens of
war- and crisis-torn countries. This year, Graham said, 3 million
shoe box gifts will be delivered in 60 such countries.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
