<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON MAY BE ENJOYING HER LAST WHITE HOUSE CHRISTMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As visitors awaiting the arrival of First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton inspected the decorations adorning the
official White House Christmas tree _ one for each state and the
District of Columbia -- one of them asked, ``Where's New York?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Prominently displayed somewhere,'' quipped White House Social
Secretary Capricia Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   With Mrs. Clinton planning to move soon to New York to run for
the US Senate, even her traditional announcement of the White House
holiday theme pivots to her future as a Senate candidate from New
York and whether this will be her last Christmas in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, whose role as first lady is epitomized during the
holiday season when the White House is decked out in Christmas
decorations and becomes a revolving door of holiday parties, said
Monday she has begun packing and will move to New York as soon as
the Secret Service finishes securing the $1.7 million house she and
the president bought last summer in Chappaqua, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Secret Service is moving forward, and making the changes
that they have to make,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``I'm pulling things
out of storage and deciding what has to be recovered, or
reupholstered.'' She said she is ``looking to begin moving things
in later this month, I hope.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether this will be the last year she will be
available to host such Christmas receptions at the White House, she
demurred. ``We'll certainly be here for Christmas and we're looking
forward to having our entire family and guests and friends here for
the Christmas holidays,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Mrs. Clinton said she plans to step back from her
role as first lady after Jan. 1 so she can devote a majority of her
time to campaigning for the Senate seat from New York.
</P>
<P>
   But the moving date hasn't been set, and neither has she bought
any furniture. ``I'm mostly trying to use what I have. I may have
to buy some things, but I'm trying to be really clear about what I
do have and get those in the best possible shape.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, however, the demands of moving to New York are
giving way to the demands of her duties as first lady, which often
intensify during the holiday season. She will play host to some
eight holiday receptions, along with playing a central role in
millennium festivities in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This year's theme, ``Holiday Treasures at the White House,''
drips with nostalgia and is a compendium of Mrs. Clinton's
interests in historical and cultural sites as honorary chair of the
Saving America's Treasures program.
</P>
<P>
   In the East Foyer, the entire Christmas tree features replicas
of places Mrs. Clinton visited on her tour, including Eleanor
Roosevelt's Val-Kill Cottage in Hyde Park, N.Y.; Benedict Arnold's
Revolutionary War Gunboat in Vergennes, Vt.; and Ventfort Hall in
Stockbridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The official White House tree, an 18 1/2-foot Noble fir from
Washington state that adorns the Blue Room, is decorated with
11,911 scenes and objects as well as 80 handmade dolls featuring
aviator Amelia Earhart, scientist Albert Einstein, civil rights
activist Rosa Parks and three dolls of the abolitionist Harriet
Tubman.
</P>
<P>
   The mantels and pier tables in the Green Room, the Red Room, and
other areas of the White House also feature hand-crafted
reproductions of historic buildings across the country. The main
foyer is decorated with reproduction fruit in the style of Colonial
Williamsburg. White House pastry chefs created a 220-pound
gingerbread sculpture of the White House, the Jefferson Memorial,
the Washington Monument and Mount Vernon, with chocolate trees
lining the bank of the Potomac River.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton also unveiled this year's White House greeting
card, an impressionist painting of the North Portico, which Mrs.
Clinton described as one of her favorite views of the White House.
The artist, Ray Ellis of Martha's Vineyard, Mass., also did last
year's greeting card.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
