<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRANDA-HISTORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRANDA VS. ARIZONA: THE CASE THAT SPLIT THE COURT AND THE
COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., N.Y., Calif., Mo.)   (With SCOTUS-MIRANDA)  
(DW) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Miranda vs. Arizona, announced by the Supreme Court
on June 13, 1966, was the name for a decision that resolved four
separate criminal appeals, all raising the same question of what
the Fifth Amendment's right against compelled self-incrimination
meant in the context of an interrogation by the police of a suspect
in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Because his was the lead case of the group, Ernesto Miranda
became by far the most famous of the four. Described in Chief
Justice Earl Warren's opinion as an ``indigent Mexican'' and a
``seriously disturbed individual with pronounced sexual
fantasies,'' Miranda had been convicted by an Arizona jury of
kidnapping and rape on the basis of a signed confession he gave to
the Phoenix police officers who had questioned him for two hours
without a lawyer present, in Interrogation Room No. 2 of the
detective bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants in the other cases, from New York, California,
and Missouri, shared similar encounters with their police
interrogators. The California Supreme Court had overturned the
murder conviction of one, Roy Allen Stewart, because there was no
evidence that he had been advised of his right to counsel and his
right to remain silent. The justices affirmed the California
court's ruling and reversed the convictions of Miranda and the
other two defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The case split the court, 5-4, and split the country as well,
unleashing a furious debate over whether the Warren Court, which
had been significantly expanding the rights of criminal defendants,
had finally gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   In his majority opinion, Warren said the case had raised
questions ``which go to the roots of our concepts of American
criminal jurisprudence: the restraints society must observe
consistent with the federal Constitution in prosecuting individuals
for crime.''
</P>
<P>
   He summarized the court's holding in this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless other fully effective means are devised to inform
accused persons of their right of silence and to assure a
continuous opportunity to exercise it, the following measures are
required. Prior to any questioning, the person must be warned that
he has a right to remain silent, that any statement he does make
may be used as evidence against him, and that he has a right to the
presence of an attorney, either retained or appointed. The
defendant may waive effectuation of these rights, provided the
waiver is made voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently. If,
however, he indicates in any manner and at any stage of the process
that he wishes to consult with an attorney before speaking, there
can be no questioning.''
</P>
<P>
   The four dissenters objected that the new rules would exact too
high a price on the criminal justice system by letting guilty
people, even those who had confessed their guilt, go free.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Byron R. White wrote in dissent, ``In some unknown
number of cases the court's rule will return a killer, a rapist, or
other criminal to the streets and to the environment which produced
him, to repeat his crime whenever it pleases him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1946EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1060 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-06 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE ANOTHER LOOK AT ORRIN HATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Betcha don't know that Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch is a
very funny fellow. Not odd funny. Ha-ha funny.
</P>
<P>
   Who suspected? His image as a Republican presidential candidate
is so stodgy and stiff that he has the support of only 1 percent of
those surveyed in two recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at a dinner Saturday of an organization here called the
Gridiron Club he was such a hilarious stand-up comic that the
journalists who make up the group informally crowned him the
funniest speaker in the club's recent history. Clearly, there's
more to the oh-so-serious chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee than first meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Joking can be dangerous on the campaign trail, which may have
something to do with why Hatch doesn't loosen up in front of
cameras. The 1996 GOP presidential nominee, Bob Dole, held the
Washington championship for biting wit for decades, but his humor
on the hustings came across as too sardonic and it cost him votes.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes was recently burned by an attempt at humor that
wasn't even funny. He took a mocking swipe at Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, saying, ``When I was young and irresponsible, I was young and
irresponsible, and unlike some, I grew away from that initial
position and clearly some others are still stuck in it.''
</P>
<P>
   After he was criticized as an attack dog, Forbes contended the
remark was a ``throw-away line'' merely meant to be humorous.
</P>
<P>
   But a little more campaign levity from Hatch might project a
warmer personality and boost his ratings. He has a better sense of
proportion than Dole and he's a heck of a lot funnier than Forbes.
And while he poked fun at his rivals, he didn't spare himself.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch didn't necessarily make political buddies of the Gridiron
Club cynics, who are primarily Washington newspaper chain bureau
chiefs, columnists and White House correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   But he certainly got their attention. And attention is something
his limping candidacy really needs. He had such a good time
laughing at his own jokes that tears came to his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that his good friend, Sen. Edward Kennedy, knows
New Hampshire in the winter well. (Kennedy really is a friend;
Hatch has been criticized by fellow conservatives for consorting
with an ideological enemy.) So he gave Hatch his campaign flask.
``I really appreciated it, because it's so hard to get my warm milk
in a motel at night,'' Hatch deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch proceeded to run down the names of the world leaders that
Bush fumbled in a pop quiz recently and ended with the spelling of
potato, which Vice President Dan Quayle once missed in a famous
classroom episode. Then the senator sailed on to other candidates.
Democratic challenger Bill Bradley, he noted, said he was too cool
to play that foreign-leaders-name game and would rather ``try to
prove, yet again, that sleep can be induced without medication.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, Hatch continued, issued a press release saying he not
only knew all the answers but could spell the names of several
other world leaders, beginning with Great Britain's Tony Blair,
B-L-A-R-E.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, a Mormon, said he thought such pop quizzes were unfair,
unless they asked ``general interest'' questions such as ``who
founded the Mormon Church?'' Or ``what kind of a name is Orrin?''
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed out, tongue in cheek, how much progress his own
presidential campaign was making. ``I've been clawing, scratching
my way to the top,'' he joshed. When he started he was 10th out of
10 candidates. Then he moved up to 9, 8, 7 and now 6. ``Some point
to the fact Lamar (Alexander), Dan (Quayle), Liddy (Dole) and Pat
(Buchanan) quit,'' he laughed, ``but I see a trend ... I have moved
up four places just standing still.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Hatch came to President Clinton. He predicted that when
Clinton went to a mall to Christmas shop and Santa asked the big
question, Clinton would respond, ``It depends on what you mean by
`good.'''
</P>
<P>
   And he mused gleefully that as he sat on a stool looking at his
fellow GOP candidates during the New Hampshire debate last week he
couldn't help thinking, ``Washington, Adams, Jefferson, Madison _
how the heck did we come to this?''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch delightfully described himself as ``just a wacky kid from
Utah trying to get ahead in this crazy, mixed-up world.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of Hatch as wacky is hilarious in itself. Maybe you had
to be there. But it does suggest that Hatch is a more complicated
creature than his public demeanor would indicate. A second look at
his candidacy might be worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 1949EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-OBITUARY-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      12-06 0235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICHOLAS HOTTON III; WAS SMITHSONIAN CURATOR; AT 78 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nicholas Hotton III, retired curator of fossil reptiles at the
Museum of Natural History at the Smithsonian Institution in
Washington, D.C., died of colon cancer Nov. 29 in his home in
Takoma Park, Md. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   A specialist on the extinct reptiles that preceded mammals, Mr.
Hotton was the author of two books, ``Dinosaurs'' and ``The
Evidence of Evolution,'' as well as dozens of scientific papers.
</P>
<P>
   He spent nearly every spring collecting fossils at sites in West
Texas and did field research in South Africa, Antarctica, and
Wyoming, where he conducted educational dinosaur digs.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Sault Ste. Marie, Mich. He graduated from the
University of Chicago, where he laterearned a doctorate in biology.
</P>
<P>
   He served in the Army in the Philippines and Okinawa during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his museum work, he taught at the University of
Kansas and George Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   His wife of 43 years, Ruth Olmstead Hotton, who assisted in his
field work, died in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves two sons, Albert T. of Silver Spring, Md., and
Nicholas IV of Antwerp, N.Y.; a daughter, Carol L. of Takoma Park;
a brother, Peter of Weymouth, Mass.; a sister, Cynthia Rampone of
Portland, Ore.; and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
