<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-SERIAL-MURDE     12-06 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-SERIAL-MURDER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN READS A MONSTROUS CONFESSION: `I HAVE KILLED 100
CHILDREN...'  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAHORE, Pakistan _ Rashida Bibi had returned once more, wailing
with grief, rocking side to side like the clapper of a bell. She
was pleading. Wouldn't they let her hold her dead son's clothes
again? Or touch his sandals?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there are bones somewhere,'' she cried out. ``There must
be something. I need to have something!''
</P>
<P>
   Others rushed to calm her, this slight woman sheathed in a black
shawl. But the soothing was useless. She shrieked and wept.
</P>
<P>
   Three days before, Mrs. Bibi, like hundreds of others, crowded
into the courtyard of the Ravi Road police station, a yellow brick
building in the faded elegance of historic Lahore.
</P>
<P>
   Mounds of soiled clothes, rows of old shoes and piles of color
photos were on display there _ all taunting clues left by a man who
says he sexually molested and killed 100 young boys and then
dissolved their flesh and bones in vats of chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have killed 100 children, all boys, and placed their bodies
in acid-filled drums,'' Javed Iqbal, 38, a wealthy, tormented man,
wrote in a boastful confession to the police. ``In terms of
expense, including the acid, it cost me 120 rupees ($2.40) to erase
each victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Thursday morning, people, some of them from hundreds of
miles away, have come to look for evidence that their missing sons
are among the slain. So far, they have claimed 69 of the victims,
most of them boys between ages 12 and 15.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bibi recognized the clothes of her 14-year-old son, Zaheer
Abbas. Monday, Qari Shabbir Ahmad, 32, found the photo of his
brother, a 10-year-old. He muttered the boy's name, ``Bashir,
Bashir!'' Then he howled, ``He has been missing four months, and
now he is dead, dead, dead!''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan is in the midst of something monstrous: serial killings
that far more than the military coup of Oct. 12 have made this
religious society flinch. The name Javed Iqbal is gouging at the
nation's soul. He has forced the nation to think of raped boys and
lunacy and cities that teem with impoverished runaways who are
drawn to anyone with money.
</P>
<P>
   In his confessional and hauntingly bizarre letters sent last
week to the police and to an Urdu-language newspaper, Iqbal
remorselessly explained himself as a wronged citizen who was merely
answering abomination with abomination.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote that he had been badly beaten up by two of his servants
in September 1998. His skull was cracked, his jaw fractured. He
went to the police, but they ignored him. The intolerable
frustration, he wrote, pushed him toward suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I prayed that if I left the world, I would leave it with
dozens of others. My prayer was accepted by God, and friends became
angels for me, and then a blood-curdling drama began. Now 100
mothers will die mourning the deaths of their children.''
</P>
<P>
   After killing 43 boys, Iqbal said, he bought a camera to improve
his methodical record keeping. He wanted the documentation of color
snapshots. So his final victims were photographed, their faces
eerily captured while they were alive and smiling.
</P>
<P>
   He also provided a carefully annotated list of the dead, perhaps
because he intended to leave little else of them, except what was
flushed into the city sewers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he wrote: ``Victim 87 is Mohammad Imran, age 15,
son of Talib Hussain, district Bahawalnager, house located next to
animal hospital. Father makes wooden cots. Color whitish to fair.
Health very good. Face beautiful. Cheeks full. Killed on November
11, 1999. 7 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Iqbal made these homicidal unburdenings seem the prelude to his
own premeditated death. ``I am on my way to drown myself in the
River Ravi,'' he wrote. ``I have planned to tie a heavy rock to
myself so that I can die quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   But the police have dragged the shallow waters of the Ravi and
found no body. ``I am quite sure he is alive,'' said Malik Muhammad
Iqbal, the regional head of police. ``He is a very clever man. He
is enjoying his fame. He is reading the newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   The police say they have arrested three men who admit to being
employees of Iqbal and his accomplices in the killings, using
chains to help choke the victims. ``And we will catch the main
culprit too,'' said Inspector Ashiq Marth, who runs the Ravi Road
police station, where crowds continue to gather. ``If I catch him
personally, I will commit against him what the law would call a
sin.''
</P>
<P>
   Lahore, perhaps Pakistan's greatest cultural center, is a city
enriched by centuries-old monuments built by Mughal rulers and
stately Victorian buildings left by the British. It is where
Kipling begins the novel ``Kim,'' the main character a young boy on
his own in a ``stealthy prowl through the dark gullies and lanes''
of the mysterious walled city.
</P>
<P>
   Iqbal rented a $40-a-month, three-room apartment in a narrow
alley off busy Ravi Road, just a few miles from where Kipling's
story takes shape.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood is still a magnet for young boys in search of
independence. Some become pickpockets, some prostitutes, some drug
addicts. Some merely hang out around the Data Ganj Baksh, a giant
shrine named for an 11th-century Sufi saint. The police say that
Iqbal and his confederates found much of their prey beneath the
shadow of the great minarets and enticed the youngsters with offers
of good food and lively music.
</P>
<P>
   The photos show most of the boys bare-chested, standing before a
wooden window of the decrepit apartment. When the police finally
entered _ invited as they were by Iqbal's revelatory mailing _ they
found handwritten placards on the walls to serve as a guide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The five sacks lying in the corner of this room contain the
clothes of 100 victims while the remaining three contain 85 pairs
of shoes belonging to them,'' one read.
</P>
<P>
   Barrels of chemicals were stored in the V-shaped room farthest
from the front door. ``Today, dated Nov. 25, 1999, I have decided
to commit suicide,'' read another poster. ``Yesterday, I killed my
employee, Sajid, and incinerated his body in the container so that
he could be punished for theft and for disturbing me again and
again.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past week, police have questioned dozens of people
who have been part of Iqbal's life, including two former wives, a
son and a daughter, and a variety of relatives who say they had
been estranged from him. ``His family was angry with him because of
his bad habits,'' said Marth, a huge man capable of an occasional
understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Local newspapers, piecing together scraps of Iqbal's past,
report that he was caught committing sodomy against young boys as
far back as 1985. Back then, neighbors humbled rather than
reporting him _ demanding that he go door-to-door admitting his
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Iqbal was later arrested several times for child molesting, but
he managed to avoid prison by failing to show up in court or by
buying his freedom. He inherited a share of his father's
scrap-metal business in the early 1990s, converting his portion
into about $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   Critics here say better police work might have prevented Iqbal's
mortal binge. Even after receiving the killer's well-substantiated
confession, the police were slow to investigate. Reporters preceded
policemen to the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the victims had been reported missing to the authorities.
Some parents who did make reports said they had been thrashed by
constables for being bothersome. ``The poor have no friends in a
police station,'' said one father.
</P>
<P>
   Grieving parents blamed themselves as well, however. In the
courtyard of the Ravi Road station, as people searched through the
heaps of clothes under a peepul tree, many said their sons had run
away because of harsh discipline or simple neglect.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son ran off because I made him work,'' said Hassan Ahmed.
</P>
<P>
   Rashida Bibi, desperate to again hold anything that had belonged
to her 14-year-old son, rued her own lack of concern at his
disappearance. Once before, he had gone away for a month and then
come back. She thought this time would be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she now found herself begging the police to bring out
his belongings, which they had removed from the heap and stored.
``I want to smell the clothes of my son,'' the weeping mother said.
``What else is there to do? Nothing else of him is left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
