<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1068 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-IVESTER-COX     12-06 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-IVESTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke's CEO shocks business world with retirement announcement
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a surprise announcement Monday that sent shock
waves from Atlanta's North Avenue to New York's Wall Street,
Coca-Cola Co. said M. Douglas Ivester will retire as chairman and
chief executive officer in April.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, who oversaw a tumultuous two years at the helm of the
world's largest soft-drink company, will be replaced by Douglas
Daft, a 30-year company veteran who oversaw operations in the
Middle East, Far East and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Daft, 56, immediately became president and chief operating
officer _ a position that has been vacant since October 1997, when
Ivester left that No. 2 job to head the company following the death
of Roberto C. Goizueta.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, some industry analysts and company observers believe
Ivester is retiring after resisting pressure from the board of
directors to appoint a No. 2 executive.
</P>
<P>
   The company, however, declined to comment on that issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``After much soul-searching, I have come to believe our company
will now be best served by fresh leadership that will bring its own
energy to bear _ and I believe Doug Daft is the person to provide
that leadership,'' Ivester, 52, said in a message to all company
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The development took Wall Street by complete surprise, sending
the stock tumbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a startling development,'' said Andrew Conway, an analyst
with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``I think it's a loss. Doug
Ivester is the most experienced executive Coca-Cola has.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was more of a surprise than the 49ers losing eight games
in a row,'' added Manny Goldman, global beverage analyst for
Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester made his decision last week and informed a few board
members of it at the end of the week, said company spokesman Robert
Baskin.
</P>
<P>
   The board then held a special meeting Sunday to ``reluctantly''
accept Ivester's decision and to name Daft president. Some board
members attended the hastily-called meeting, while others
participated by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The board also indicated it intends to elect Daft, who Ivester
recommended, as chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe board recently has been turning up the
heat on Ivester to appoint a No. 2 executive to help him run the
company in the wake of several well-publicized problems:
</P>
<P>
   _ The biggest recall in the company's 113-year history, which
occurred in Belgium in June after Coca-Cola products were blamed
for sickening nearly 250 consumers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trouble consummating strategic purchases, especially in
Europe, where government regulators have had the company under an
antitrust microscope.
</P>
<P>
   _ A depressed stock price caused by disappointing earnings,
which were in large part the result of faltering economies in parts
of Asia, Latin America, Russia and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   _ A racial discrimination suit filed by four employees who want
to expand it into a class-action case. Coca-Cola denies the
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Ivester described the past 15 months as
the worst period for the company in the last 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ivester was bullish about the future in a recent
interview with The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have been through is a temporary blip in the long-term
scheme,'' Ivester said. But, he quickly added, ``The future is as
bright as the past,'' referring to Coke's glory days when many of
the company's investors earned huge profits.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the company recently announced a reorganization
that reduced the number of executives reporting to Ivester to six,
from 16.
</P>
<P>
   While the board agreed with that decision, announced on Oct. 29,
observers said some board members still wanted him to take the next
step and appoint a president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   But Ivester wanted to give the recent reorganization _ the first
major one in his tenure as chief _ a chance to work. Observers said
Ivester resigned after tension developed between him and the board.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, Ivester has received a good bit of
criticism in some industry circles for not appointing a No. 2
person. The belief among those critics is that some of the
company's problems could have been better contained had Ivester not
been flying solo.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester also may have grown weary of constantly being a
lightning rod for criticism in the media _ especially when compared
with Goizueta, who had been held in such high esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Some people familiar with the company said Ivester was in a
``no-win situation,'' comparing him to a football coach following
in the footsteps of Paul ``Bear'' Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   After two grueling years, the company's problems may have
combined with the unrelenting criticism to lead him to the decision
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug Ivester is a human being,'' said John Sicher, editor and
publisher of Beverage Digest. ``He must have felt under a lot of
pressure. ... He decided it was time to pass the torch.''
</P>
<P>
   What's hard to understand is the timing of the torch's passing.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, the board and industry analysts all have been expecting
a turnaround during the next few quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wouldn't he enjoy the fruits?'' Conway asked rhetorically.
``It must have been just a personal decision to step aside.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said Ivester's decision to retire was his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not forced out,'' said Baskin, the company spokesman.
``He wanted the company to focus on the positive, not on the
challenges of the recent past or on him, but on the opportunities
that lie ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We accepted his resignation reluctantly,'' said James B.
Williams, a Coca-Cola director and retired SunTrust CEO. ``He
resigned for personal reasons. I've always supported Doug.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, known for his financial acumen, will be replaced by
Daft, whose background is in company operations.
</P>
<P>
   Daft, who joined the company in 1969, just received his second
major promotion in less than two months.
</P>
<P>
   In the October reorganization, he was given responsibility for
overseeing operations in the Middle East, Far East and Africa, as
well as the company's recently created Schweppes beverages
division. Before that he was responsible for the Middle and Far
East. He also has held important company positions overseeing
operations in Japan, China, Indonesia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daft has spent decades building the company's business,
primarily in Asia,'' Sicher said. ``He is experienced in building
operations in international markets and is well regarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, meanwhile, is credited with a number of accomplishments
during his 20-year tenure at Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the key architects of the company's ``anchor
bottler'' system, which has resulted in the consolidation and
improved long-term financial performance of the company and its
bottlers on a global basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a major driver of the company's lucrative share
repurchase program over the years, which benefited stockholders,''
said Goldman, the analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made a tremendous contribution over the years,''
Goldman said. ``But things don't always work out as planned in life
or in business.''
</P>
<P>
   In his memo to employees, Ivester said he will maintain a North
Avenue office until May 2001 and will remain a consultant to the
company ``for a number of years. I will do everything I can to
ensure that the transition is a flawless one.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
