<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-SETBACK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECREASE IN PUBLIC SPENDING HURTS JAPAN'S RECOVERY, AGENCY
REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan's tentative recovery from its worst recession
since World War II suffered a setback last quarter as economic
growth fell at an unexpectedly steep rate, hurt by depleted
spending on public works projects, the nation's Economic Planning
Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said that the gross domestic product fell 1 percent
in the July through September period. Although economists said the
data did not suggest that Japan might slip back into recession
after two quarters of expansion, it still illustrated the country's
dependence on public-spending projects to stimulate growth.
</P>
<P>
   The data also re-established the two-steps-forward,
one-step-back pattern that has characterized Japan's economic
activity.
</P>
<P>
   All measures of domestic demand _ which account for more than
half of the country's economic growth and which the government has
been trying so hard to stimulate _ turned negative in the quarter.
Consumer spending slipped three-tenths of 1 percent, corporate
capital expenditures fell 2.1 percent and housing investment,
previously strengthened by tax incentives, fell 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By far the biggest factor in the economy's retreat was a plunge
in public spending, which fell 8.5 percent as the government
exhausted its last supplemental budget.
</P>
<P>
   Hiroyuki Inoue, senior economist at the Japan Center for
Economic Research, said, ``Although we have seen some recovery and
expect a moderate recovery going forward, we cannot forget the fact
that it was pushed ahead by special economic policies such as
enormous public spending, historically low interest rates and
massive credit guarantees for small and mid-sized businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Exports were the only major area of growth, rising 4.7 percent,
a trend that may not last because of the increased strength of the
yen, which has made Japanese products more expensive overseas. The
yen has been rising to nearly four-year highs against the dollar,
settling in New York Monday at 103.03 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saving grace in the quarter was a substantial rise in the
trade surplus,'' said Richard Katz, senior editor of The Oriental
Economist, a newsletter. ``Without that rise, GDP would have fallen
1.3 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Parliament is expected to approve another supplemental
budget this month, which could inject $61 billion into the economy,
but the effects of that spending will not be noticeable until some
time next spring or early summer. ost economists expect the economy
to flounder until then, though some think the government's forecast
of six-tenths of 1 percent growth for this year to be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Officials had taken great pains to dampen expectations. The
Japanese central bank, in particular, has been reluctant to
describe the growth of the first two quarters of 1999 as a
recovery. Taichi Sakaiya, the head of the Economic Planning Agency,
warned economists and investors that a prediction of 1.4 percent
Japanese growth made last month by the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development, a group of affluent industrial
nations, was overly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumption is down and will probably stay depressed,'' said
Robert Alan Feldman, chief economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
in Tokyo. ``There's weakness in the public works component, and
exports are likely to become flat-to-negative because of the
stronger yen. This is not the environment for strong GDP growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the stock market here seemed to shrug off the bad
news, with the benchmark Nikkei index of 225 issues continuing to
rise, up three-quarters of a percent to 18,507.20. Other indexes
were up more sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The figures released Monday were in some ways difficult to
interpret because of revisions to the previous two quarters'
statistics. The Economic Planning Agency increased its figures for
economic growth in the April-June quarter to 1 percent from
one-tenth of a percent, which aroused some skepticism among
economists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the upward revision in the second quarter looks
questionable to me,'' Feldman said. He noted that the figures for
public investment had sharply reversed, going from a 4 percent drop
in the initial announcement to a 2.8 percent gain in the revised
data, an unusually sharp adjustment. Other economists noted that
capital expenditures for the fiscal year from April 1, 1998 through
March 31, 1999 had been revised upward by 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are bound to cause confusion because of all the
revisions we've had,'' said Brian Rose of Warburg Dillon Read here.
``As an economist, one of the basic things you'd like to know is
the size of capital expenditures, and that's just changed, which
means forecasts and models have to change, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose noted that the latest quarterly data still showed that the
economy grew by nine-tenths of a percent compared with the quarter
a year earlier. ``The economy won't be great,'' he said, ``but the
supplemental budget will kick in early next fiscal year and that
should keep the economy going next year. But if you were relying on
the economy to go into a strong recovery, you should be worried.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
