<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1074 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-06 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GROUNDED FOR 2000 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here we are, just 24 shopping days until the turn of the
millennium, and what I want to know is, what happened to the flying
cars?
</P>
<P>
   We're about to become Americans of the 21st century. People have
been predicting what we'd be like for more than 100 years, and our
accouterments don't entirely live up to expectations. No airborne
automobiles. No spaceliners to extraterrestrial vacation spots _ we
can't even deliver that mechanical thing to Mars in working order.
No housecleaning robots. No moving sidewalks, except those deeply
unsatisfactory ones in airports.
</P>
<P>
   Our failure to produce flying cars seems like a particular
betrayal, since it was so central to our image. A century ago, a
French novelty company produced a series of trading cards depicting
life in the year 2000. People had hardly figured out how to make
cars move on the ground at that point, but the cards showed
citizens of the future _ us _ soaring into air cafes for a cup of
coffee or setting down on floating stores that bobbed in the
English Channel. Movies about the 21st century almost always
featured flying cars. There was a Hollywood musical from 1930
called ``Just Imagine'' that imagined them all over New York City
by 1980.
</P>
<P>
   I actually did look into the flying car failure a while back,
and an expert in the internal design department at Ford explained
very gently that although building a flying car was certainly
conceivable, it would cost $10 million and sound like a Boeing 747.
And actually, it's just as well. If they were easy to produce, we'd
be walking around wearing helmets to protect us from the detritus
of flying car crashes.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the popular prognosticators of the past never
got us right is because they tended to envision our lives as filled
with the same things they already had, only better. They didn't
conceive of computers or faxes; they thought about pneumatic tubes
going really, really fast. They predicted something approaching
radio _ on those 100-year-old trading cards, we're pictured
listening to a news broadcast on what looks like a Victrola
attached to a small electric power plant. But they never figured
out television, possibly because they couldn't stretch their minds
around what having a perpetual entertainment machine in every
living room would do to family life.
</P>
<P>
   John Elfreth Watkins, who wrote a really first-rate set of
predictions for Ladies' Home Journal at the turn of the last
century, managed to anticipate air-conditioning, international
long-distance telephone service, school lunch programs, the rise of
the suburbs, color photography and frozen dinners. But he was,
unfortunately for us, overoptimistic in matters such as the
extermination of all roaches, houseflies and mosquitoes, and
physical fitness. ``A man or woman unable to walk ten miles at a
stretch will be regarded as a weakling,'' he decreed. Neither he
nor anyone else seemed to consider the possibility that the newer,
faster, transportation vehicles of the future would get in each
other's way. ``The trip from suburban home to office will require a
few minutes only,'' Watkins predicted.
</P>
<P>
   One of the nicest things about our failure to acquire the
21st-century life style our great-grandparents expected is the
degree to which we've stubbornly clung to the impractical. The
forecasters of the past always presumed that once automobile travel
became universal, horses would become extinct. Nobody realized that
we'd keep them around simply because we like them. In 1950, Popular
Mechanics magazine announced that in another half-century people
would be living in plastic houses with waterproof furniture. ``The
housewife of 2000 can do her daily cleaning with the garden hose,''
the magazine predicted, and would wash her meltable plastic dishes
down the drain after every meal. The guys at Popular Mechanics,
enamored of utility, presumed we'd all want drip-dry living rooms
as soon as they were available. They never imagined that after
acquiring the microwave, houseproud men and women would embrace
Martha Stewart and welcome in the new century by cooking holiday
puddings that would have been too time-consuming for Victorians.
</P>
<P>
   So we march into the millennium, gravity-bound, traffic-clogged
and roach-infested as ever, less efficient, but maybe more human,
than anybody anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
