u f BC-AT&AMP;T-NYT &LR;      12-06 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T PLANS WIRELESS TELEPHONE AND INTERNET SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a series of far-reaching announcements Monday spanning the
realms of finance, management and regulation, AT&AMP;T fleshed out its
plans for going after the regional Bell companies' markets across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the long-distance communications company announced
a change in its financial structure, a broad new wireless
communications initiative, sweeping changes in its top executive
ranks and a deal to open its cable television systems to outside
Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Unveiled at a meeting with hundreds of analysts in New York
City, the panoply of initiatives was meant to convince Wall Street
and regulators in Washington that AT&AMP;T is serious about providing
better returns to investors and new choices for consumers in local
phone service and high-speed Internet access. More important, the
announcements are meant to convey that the company has the
wherewithal to make those things happen.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, AT&AMP;T announced plans to issue a tracking stock for
its fast-growing wireless unit that would trade separately from
AT&AMP;T's common stock, which is among the most widely held in the
nation. AT&AMP;T also said that it would deploy a new ``fixed
wireless'' technology to provide local phone service and
lightning-quick Internet access to millions of United States homes.
</P>
<P>
   However, wireless will not provide AT&AMP;T's main foray into the
local communications business, which the company had to give up
when it split under court supervision in 1984. AT&AMP;T has invested
more than $100 billion to become the nation's No. 1 cable
television provider, planning to use cable to deliver high-speed
Internet access and local phone service.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's cable strategy, however, has run into a wall of criticism
because in acquiring Tele-Communications Inc., it inherited a
contract giving the Excite(at)Home cable modem venture exclusive
rights to provide high-speed Internet service until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet providers, led by America Online Inc., say that
the arrangement is unfair and that AT&AMP;T should open its cable
systems to other Internet providers.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has continued to stand by its exclusive deal with
Excite(AT)Home, of which it is the largest shareholder but has
tried hard to convince regulators and the Internet industry that it
will happily strike deals with other ISPs after 2002.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, AT&AMP;T Monday announced a broad, if somewhat vague,
agreement with Mindspring, a big Internet provider, and with the
chairman of a Federal Communications Commission advisory group
regarding the principles that AT&AMP;T will embrace as it deals with
Internet providers.
</P>
<P>
   Those principles include an agreement by AT&AMP;T to provide its
customers with a choice of Internet providers; to allow users to
customize their ``start page'' on the Web, often considered
valuable advertising territory; and to allow users unfettered
access to all Web content without additional charges from AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, outlined in a public letter to William E.
Kennard, chairman of the FCC, is clearly meant to forestall any
regulatory attempts to force AT&AMP;T to open its cable systems.
Municipalities including Portland, Ore., which must approve the
transfer of cable licenses from TCI to AT&AMP;T, are attempting to pry
open AT&AMP;T's systems, though Kennard has said the federal
government, not states or cities, has jurisdiction over any such
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying the strategic and financial moves were
announcements of sweeping management changes to implement them.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, John D. Zeglis, AT&AMP;T's president, was named
chairman of the newly independent wireless unit. Daniel E. Somers,
the chief financial officer, was named chairman of the cable unit,
succeeding Leo Hindery, who left the company in October (and Monday
was named to head a division of Global Crossing). Richard R.
Roscitt, head of the AT&AMP;T unit that runs the networks of big
business customers, was named chief of AT&AMP;T's overall
business-services division.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to AT&AMP;T said the company was still negotiating
with Charles H. Noski, the No. 2 executive at General Motors'
Hughes Electronics operation, to succeed Somers as AT&AMP;T's chief
financial officer. The executives said a deal with Noski could be
announced soon. Kathleen Earley, who previously ran the company's
Internet operation, was named to a new post overseeing all AT&AMP;T's
disparate data communications offerings for business customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
