<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1079 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-DAFT-COX     12-06 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-DAFT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daft named Ivester's successor
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola's next chief executive is a former
schoolteacher who washes his own cars. And he's got a listed number
in the phone book, if you need to give him a call.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and neighbors say Douglas N. Daft is a friendly,
down-to-earth guy who knows how to make people feel comfortable.
And that, analysts say, should help him as he faces foreign
government officials who have been increasingly hostile to the idea
of allowing a powerful American company overwhelm more overseas
beverage markets.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-year-old Daft may have something else going for him
internationally: He's not an American.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Australia. And while he has lived in Atlanta since
1991, he is not a U.S. citizen.
</P>
<P>
   That will be a first for Atlanta-based Coca-Cola's chief
executive ranks. Retiring Chairman and Chief Executive Officer M.
Douglas Ivester is from New Holland, Ga. His predecessor, Roberto
C. Goizueta, was born in Cuba but became a naturalized U.S.
citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very tactful move,'' says Schroder &AMP; Co. analyst
Caroline Levy. ''It's possible that was part of the decision-making
process'' in the selection of Daft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I clearly think that having a very American leader hasn't seem
to have been as successful,'' Levy says.
</P>
<P>
   Daft ``is more international in flavor'' than Ivester, and in
that way more like Goizueta, she says. ``He's got the statesmanship
that you need to run a company that operates in 200 countries.''
</P>
<P>
   He has also been in the thick of some of Coca-Cola's worst
troubles as Asian economies have struggled over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, Daft has headed Coca-Cola's Middle and Far East
Group, a position that made him responsible for operations from
Morocco in North Africa to India, China, Japan, Australia and
everything in-between. In a reorganization in October, Daft's turf
expanded to include the rest of Africa. The combined area accounts
for nearly one out of every four drinks Coca-Cola sells.
</P>
<P>
   Daft was also given responsibility for the Schweppes Beverage
Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's well-liked both inside the company and by the bottlers,''
says John Sicher, who is editor and publisher of Beverage Digest.
``He is a very hands-on executive in terms of really knowing the
business at the marketplace level.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's Asian operations cover vast and immensely diverse
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has been one of Coca-Cola's biggest and most profitable
markets. But consumer preferences there change quickly, and Daft
has proven nimble enough to keep ahead, says Merrill Lynch global
beverage analyst Manny Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Daft's responsibilities included China, where
Coca-Cola was one of the first and most successful American
companies to expand.
</P>
<P>
   In India, the company is in the midst of a consolidation of
bottlers and layoffs of employees.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Middle East, Daft has tried to build up brands in
countries where the company had had little or no operations until
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The job demands almost constant travel, which is why neighbors
say they only rarely see Daft at his home near the Atlanta History
Center and only a short walk from Atlanta's nightlife. He lives in
a small, walled complex of upscale townhouses and detached homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a wonderful guy,'' says neighbor Homer Deakins. ``His
biggest problem is he doesn't play enough golf. He's never
around.''
</P>
<P>
   When he is, Deakins says, Daft is in the neighborhood courtyard
with a Mercedes sports utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see him out in his yard, washing his cars. That's not
something you would expect somebody of his stature to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Daft started out small.
</P>
<P>
   He got his bachelor's degree in mathematics at the University of
New England near Sydney and a post-graduate degree in business
administration at the University of New South Wales.
</P>
<P>
   He worked as a school science teacher for a year or two. Then he
joined Coca-Cola as a planning officer, watching market trends for
the company in Sydney. It was the beginning of what has been a
30-year career steadily moving up Coca-Cola's ranks.
</P>
<P>
   When he isn't working or washing cars, Daft likes to fly fish
and snow ski. He has a wife, Delphine, and two grown children.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kempner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
