<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-WARNING (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to decide
whether federal agents are required to read criminal suspects the
so-called Miranda warning telling them that they have a right to
remain silent. The warning has become familiar through movies and
television: You have a right to remain silent and to have a lawyer
even if you can't afford one, and anything you say may be held
against you in court. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-PRISONS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to decide
whether Congress can limit the authority of judges to oversee
troubled state prison systems. The case stems from a lawsuit filed
by Indiana prison inmates. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTOR-TRAINING (Washington) _ Sen. Bill Frist, the only
physician in the Senate and a key force in crafting health-care
policy for Republicans, predicts that Congress will find new ways
to pay for training medical residents at teaching hospitals. Cuts
in Medicare funding have squeezed federal reimbursements to the
nation's 400 teaching hospitals at the same time that managed
health-care plans have cut back their payments to the hospitals. By
JUDY HOLLAND. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-DEBATE (Phoenix) _ The Republican presidential hopefuls meet
in a nationally televised debate tonight, the third such forum but
the second for the apparent front-runner, Texas Gov. George W.
Bush. By CRAGG HINES and R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NASA-MARS (Pasadena, Calif.) _ The Mars Polar Lander will not be
declared lost for some time but hope has all but run out for
finding the vehicle, raising some serious questions inside and
outside NASA about how the Mars program is being run. By MARK
CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   AGE-COMMUNITY (Houston) _ Linda Bell's husband had been dead two
months and seven days when she got the letter telling her that she
must move out of her house within six months or face legal action.
At Country Place, an age-restricted community south of south of
Houston, residents who are younger than 55 who have just lost an
older spouse may be forced to move. By STEVE OLAFSON. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PENNY-FUTURE (Albany, N.Y.) _ There are 114 billion pennies in
circulation, yet last summer the nation still managed to suffer one
of the biggest penny shortages in recent memory _ mainly because so
many people kept taking them home and dumping them in jars or giant
water-cooler bottles. Is the penny pooped as currency, or will it
continue to survive in an era of credit cards? By ALAN WECHSLER.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS-RICE (Cincinnati) _ Jerry Rice, a star wide receiver,
says he intends to return to the struggling San Francisco 49ers
next year for his 16th season. Since returning from two major
operations on his left knee in 1997, Rice has fought to regain his
form, but showed promise in Sunday's game against the Cincinnati
Bengals. By JOHN CRUMPACKER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington _ Bet you didn't know that Utah Sen.
Orrin Hatch is a very funny fellow. Not odd funny. Ha-ha funny. Who
suspected? His image during his Republican presidential campaign
has been so stodgy and stiff that he is stuck in the back of the
pack. But at a press club's dinner Saturday he was informally
crowned the funniest speaker in the club's history. There's more to
Hatch than first meets the eye. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Republican presidential hopeful
George W. Bush and other avowed tax-fighters may be missing the
boat with many voters. Most people would like to see their taxes
reduced, to be sure, but taxes apparently aren't as burning an
issue with most voters as they seemingly are with the candidates,
at least not this year. By CLAY ROBISON. (Already filed.)
</P>
