<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONACO-SAFRA-735&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.) 
AMERICAN NURSE ADMITS TO SETTING FIRE THAT KILLED BILLIONAIRE
BANKER
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ An American nurse who had worked for Edmond Safra for
the last five months has admitted to setting the fire that killed
the billionaire banker as he took refuge in a bathroom in his
luxury penthouse in Monte Carlo last Friday, Monaco's chief
prosecutor said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor said the nurse, Ted Maher, 41, of Stormville,
N.Y., had told the police that he had not intended to kill anyone,
but had fabricated his story that the apartment was under attack by
two hooded men with knives and had set fire to a wastepaper basket
in an effort ``to draw attention to himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Daniel Serdet, said that Maher, was ``jealous''
of Safra's seven other nurses, one of whom died with Safra in the
bathroom. In claiming to have fought off the attackers, Maher hoped
to win approval, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to be a hero,'' Serdet said.
</P>
<P>
   The reported confession came after days of speculation over the
events that took place in the predawn hours atop one of the
principality's most secure buildings, home to three different bank
offices.
</P>
<P>
   Safra's death had stunned the rarified world of international
investment he had been part of for decades and triggered numerous
theories about why he might have been a target of attack.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers around the world speculated that the Lebanese-born
Safra _ who without formal education built an international banking
empire _ might have been killed because of his many business
dealings, including those with Russian investors.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of his death was also particularly poignant. Safra,
who suffered from Parkinson's disease, was on the verge of
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   A deal to sell his businesses, including the Republic National
Bank of New York, which would have brought him about $2.65 billion,
is in its final stages.
</P>
<P>
   But French investigators said on Monday that there was no
complicated intrigue: Maher acted alone, they said, in part because
of a dispute with another nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Serdet said that, after starting the fire and slashing himself
twice with his own switchblade _ once in the thigh, and once in the
stomach _ Maher went downstairs to get the concierge to call the
police and firefighters to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Serdet said that Maher had not expected to kill anyone. Indeed,
investigating officials said on Saturday that Safra and his nurse,
Vivienne Torrent, could have escaped. But Safra, terrified that
assailants were after him, refused to leave the bathroom even when
the police and firefighters arrived on the scene, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials had said that Safra spoke twice by cell phone
with his wife, Lily, who tried to coax him out. However, The
Associated Press reported that a source involved in the case said
that this was not true, but that Safra had called the police twice
from the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Both Safra and Ms. Torrent, a 52-year-old American, died of
asphyxiation.
</P>
<P>
   Serdet said Maher would be charged with arson without intent to
kill, a charge that could bring him a life sentence. But the
prosecutor said also that Maher would be examined by psychiatrists
first to see that he was competent to stand trial. He said Maher
was apparently highly agitated and taking medication at the time of
the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was psychologically fragile and under the influence of
medication,'' Serdet said.
</P>
<P>
   Maher, who was born in Maine, is a 1989 graduate of Dutchess
Community College in Dutchess County, N.Y., and received his New
York nurse's license in 1990. He had been a full-time pediatric
nurse at Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center in New York City for
nine years before taking an unpaid leave of absence earlier this
year, a hospital spokeswoman said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, he and his wife, Heidi, who also worked as a
non-staff nurse at Columbia-Presbyterian, and their three children
have lived in a ranch house in Stormville, 70 miles north of New
York City. He had been in Monaco only for the past six weeks,
officials there said.
</P>
<P>
   Monaco police announced Maher's confession on the day of Safra's
funeral in Geneva, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 mourners attended the ceremony at the Hekhal Haness
synagogue, including the Nobel Peace laureate, Eli Wiesel; Israel's
foreign minister, David Levy; Prince Sadruddin Aga Khan and the
former U.N. secretary general, Javier Perez de Cuellar. Safra's
body was then taken for burial to a Jewish cemetery the village of
Veyrier, just south of Geneva.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At first, the authorities, basing their accounts on Maher's
initial testimony, said that two men wearing hoods and brandishing
knives had burst into an infirmary on the penthouse level, which
had recently been built for Safra.
</P>
<P>
   The pink stucco building sits along one of Monaco's most
gracious avenues, with views of a yacht-filled harbor and the
palace of Monaco's royal family. Safra, who shunned publicity, had
homes in New York, Paris, Geneva and a villa nearby on the French
Riviera in Villefranche-sur-Mer.
</P>
<P>
   But he spent a lot of time in Monaco, which offers the very rich
a income-tax-free haven. He apparently felt so safe here that he
did not have his bodyguards stay the night with him, when he slept
in Monaco.
</P>
<P>
   But repeated questioning of Maher, who had been taken to
Princess Grace hospital in Monaco to be treated for his knife
wounds produced vague and conflicting accounts of the events, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday, police officials said that they had no evidence to
corroborate Maher's story about a break-in or of the two masked
men. They continued to say they were unsure how anyone could have
gained access to the highly secured building.
</P>
<P>
   Late on Sunday night, the police formally took Maher into
custody.
</P>
<P>
   Serdet said that Maher confessed to setting the fire on Monday
morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
