<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-IVESTER-ART-1050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIGNATION OF COCA-COLA CHIEF SURPRISES BUSINESS WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also COKEDAFT) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a grueling year of falling profits, scuttled acquisitions
and the biggest product recall in company history, Coca-Cola's top
executive said Monday that he would step down in April.
</P>
<P>
   The outgoing executive, M. Douglas Ivester, 52, said only that
he wanted to ``move on to the next stage of my life.'' But his
decision to retire so young after barely two years as chairman and
chief executive, a job in which he took delight, stunned
shareholders and the business world.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Daft, a senior vice president who oversees operations in
Asia and the Middle East, was named president and chief operating
officer immediately and will assume the top role next year,
Coca-Cola said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester presided over one of the worst patches in the company's
performance since World War II, and that may have exhausted him or
led the board to believe it was time to look for someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester's rocky path looks even more so next to the smooth
machine that was Coke under the legendary Roberto Goizueta, the
chairman who oversaw a soaring stock price and global sales growth
for 16 years until his death from cancer. Ivester, a one-time
accountant who designed the interlocking Coca-Cola system with its
bottlers, had the misfortune to take over from him in 1997 shortly
after the Asian financial crisis erupted.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the company has been buffeted by disappointing sales
and a raft of other problems, including a racial-discrimination
lawsuit, government challenges to its acquisition plans and a
product contamination scare in Europe this summer, all of which
have caused it to slip from its perch as one of the most admired
companies in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Though board members had publicly restated their confidence in
Ivester's leadership, he had been increasingly criticized by some
investors and company insiders as arrogant and insensitive, most
notably in failing to quickly relieve consumer concerns in Europe.
In addition, his refusal to name a No. 2 was a sore point with Wall
Street and possibly some of Coke's directors. Ivester was fond of
jetting around the world to visit with Coke employees and with
customers, but seemed to lack the diplomatic skills to deal
effectively with European regulators and others whose agendas were
at odds with his own.
</P>
<P>
   In a time of soaring stock prices, executives with poor stock
performance can find themselves under extraordinary pressure from
impatient investors who will take their money elsewhere. Over time,
concerns about Ivester's management style and slowing sales in the
United States and abroad had knocked billions of dollars off his
company's value. Coke's share price, which exceeded $87 in
mid-1998, plunged to $48 in October before rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester's resignation, which followed a special board meeting on
Sunday, punished the company's stock once more. One stock analyst,
Andrew Conway of Morgan Stanley, downgraded Coke for the first time
in five years. ``It's the equivalent of a major earthquake in
Atlanta,'' he said. The stock closed at $64.601, down $3.719. That
price represents an 11 percent increase during Ivester's tenure,
compared with a 50 percent rise in the broad market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke used to be all about consistency from an investor
perspective, in terms of earnings results and volume results,''
said Jennifer Solomon, a beverage analyst for Salomon Smith Barney.
``We've had nothing but inconsistency the last couple of years, and
this just adds to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the confusion Monday was the release of Coca-Cola's
volume numbers for the fourth quarter. The company estimated that
sales were ahead of those for the third quarter, suggesting that
the tide is turning in Coke's favor. That led many to wonder why
Ivester would make his decision now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug has informed the board of his desire to retire as
chairman and chief executive officer in April, a decision the board
has reluctantly accepted,'' the company said in a statement
attributed to James Williams, a board member who is also a major
shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   A Coca-Cola spokesman, Rob Baskin, reiterated that it was
Ivester's decision. ``He decided at the end of last week that it
was time for fresh leadership at the Coca-Cola Co.,'' Baskin said.
``He had some conversations with a few board members, they called a
special meeting, and they reluctantly accepted his notice of
retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the board's 12 members are Warren Buffett, the value
investor who leads Berskhire Hathaway; Herb Allen, chairman of
Allen &AMP; Co.; former U.N. ambassador Donald McHenry, and James
Robinson, former chairman of American Express. Efforts to reach
board members for comment were unsuccessful Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the board, there has been underlying unhappiness with
the sequence of negative events,'' said Emanuel Goldman, a global
consumer-products analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``It's been one after
another after another. No single one would necessarily be a
determinant, but it's the sum total that probably resulted in
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock analysts scrambled to hold conference calls with their
investor clients Monday, but came up short on details. ``The
explanation for his departure at this point in time for the reasons
I've been offered seems incomplete,'' said Marc Cohen, an analyst
for Goldman Sachs. ``It strikes me as odd timing, if indeed the
business has been repaired and is heading in a positive
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivester publicly delighted in the challenges of running
Coca-Cola, where he was known to put in long hours, seven days a
week, with few interests outside the office. ``Even on a bad day,
it's still the best job in the world,'' he told a group of analysts
and money managers in July.
</P>
<P>
   Bottlers also seemed perplexed. ``I don't understand any of
it,'' said J. Bruce Llewellyn, the chief executive of Coca-Cola
Philadelphia Bottling Co., who said he learned of the announcement
while watching television. ``I've known Doug Ivester for a long,
long time, and I thought he was very good and very knowledegable
about this business. It's his troops and his plan that are in place
for the globalization of Coke.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is completely out of character for a Coke executive to
step down early, leading some stock analysts to speculate that
Ivester had been pushed out by the board.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In October, Coke hinted that a succession issue was rising. In a
sweeping management change, it gave additional power to three
executives, including Daft, setting up an apparent race for the top
spot. A 30-year veteran of Coke, Daft was passed over for the top
spot after Goizueta's death.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, who the company said chose Daft as his successor, may
be leaving after weathering some of the worst problems abroad.
Economic crises in Russia, Japan, parts of Latin America and Europe
have curbed volume growth over the last 15 months, with currency
changes eroding earnings as well. Coca-Cola derives about 75
percent of its profits abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to expand the company abroad through acquisitions
stumbled over regulatory issues. A $1.8 billion purchase of the
Cadbury Schweppes brands in most of the world had to be scaled back
to exclude much of Europe, after objections from the European
Commission, and a two-year effort to buy the Orangina brand from
Pernod Ricard SA collapsed last month after the French government
blocked it.
</P>
<P>
   In June Coca-Cola had its biggest product recall ever after
hundreds of Belgians said they became ill with nausea and other
symptoms after drinking Coca-Cola and Fanta, another Coke brand.
The incidents prompted a 10-day ban on Coca-Cola products in
Belgium, the shutdown of two bottling plants in Belgium and France,
and an estimated $200 million in costs to Coca-Cola in Belgium and
beyond, as fears spread across the region. Its bottler in Belgium,
Coca-Cola Enterprises, took a $103 million charge to earnings from
the recall, in which 17 million cases of Coke were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola spent heavily on damage control, giving away Cokes to
individuals and stores. Ivester appeared in a television
commercial, apologizing to the Belgian people and assuring them
that Coke was safe to drink. He also apologized in full-page
newspaper ads across the country. Still, the company was widely
criticized for responding slowly to the crisis; those apologies
came a week after the first reports of symptoms. Four
schoolchildren said last week that they had still not fully
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Coke is also contending with a racial-discrimination lawsuit
filed by four employees who say they were denied pay increases and
other promotions because of their race. And the management shuffle
in October reassigned the highest-ranking black executive, Carl
Ware, who resigned days later as senior vice president. His
departure was a source of concern for some in Atlanta's civil
rights community.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Coke's 29,000 employees were sent an e-mail Monday
telling them of Ivester's decision. Baskin said Ivester has no
health problems that influenced his decision. Goizueta died at age
65, a few months after being diagnosed with lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Now the focus shifts to Daft, who will have a chance to
influence a planned relaunch of Coca-Cola Classic early next year
and a strategic change at the company to raise prices even if it
means slowing case sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there are significant strategic issues that Doug
Daft will face, and the resignation of Doug Ivester will mark a
historic transition,'' said Bill Pecoriello, an analyst for Sanford
C. Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in Atlanta last year, Daft described the driving
force behind Coke's sales abroad. ``We all see Coke as being way
past a soft drink,'' he said. ``It can represent a way of life to
people. It can represent a change. You drink a Coke and it makes
you able to cope with an environment that isn't all that fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
