<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUES-TIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Advice on fighting the blues
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are tips from experts on how to help lift the winter
blues:
</P>
<P>
   If you're feeling overwhelmed:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make time to spend with friends.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make time for fun.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Smile. Really. It releases pleasurable brain chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Find out if your more demanding family traditions are
essential to the rest of the family. Maybe they can be replaced by
easier ones.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Get outdoors each day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Drink at least eight glasses of water a day to flush out
toxins, facilitate digestion and keep the skin from drying.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sugar, alcohol and caffeine can bring on feelings of stress
and depression in any month, so go easy on all of them.
</P>
<P>
   If your expectations might be unrealistically high:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't forget: Things go wrong in every month. Why should
December be an exception?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Enjoy the holidays moment by moment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Families have disagreements. Don't let them ruin your day, and
don't provoke them by bringing up weightier issues that can wait
till next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stick to a reasonable budget. Driving around past Christmas
decorations is cheap entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Follow your heart. ``So many times we rely on external
pressures to make a decision or evaluate a situation, when we
really have the answer inside of us the whole time,'' says licensed
counselor Scott Hall.
</P>
<P>
   If you have persistent symptoms of sadness, fatigue, disinterest
or changes in eating or sleeping patterns, see a mental health
professional. Those symptoms could indicate clinical depression and
seasonal affective disorder (SAD) _ both medical conditions that
can be treated.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
