<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1104 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WINTER-BLUES-COX     12-06 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTER-BLUES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Milestone year could take holiday anxiety to new heights
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Winter blues start showing their gloomy faces
around the first week of every December, counselors say, as
inevitably as Christmas music on the radio and advertising inserts
in the newspaper. But this year, with the odometer on our lives
turning over to three zeroes, the blues could be more prevalent
than normal as anyone old enough to remember the first moon landing
stops to wonder where all the years have gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's going to be a massive outbreak of the blues,''
Centerville psychologist Kathy Platoni said last week, ``especially
as people face the new millennium and realize how their lives are
not how they wanted them to be at this amazing crossroad. I'm
surprised we haven't seen more of it yet, but I think the warm
weather has been a delaying factor.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, December brings a dismal convergence of the unrealized
goals of New Year's, the unyielding grayness of winter and the
unattainable purity of Christmas cheer. They don't suffer from
clinical depression, seasonal affective disorder (SAD) or other
serious, medically treatable illnesses that dampen moods. They're
just blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do something about it,'' says Scott Hall, a licensed
clinical counselor and assistant professor of counseling education
at the University of Dayton. As Hall and Platoni advise, people can
brighten their blues at least to a shimmering teal by trying to
keep their expectations and ambitions realistic and by reaching out
to others.
</P>
<P>
   People often cultivate their sadness with one of two thought
processes, Hall says.
</P>
<P>
   Then as Christmas approaches, either they are disappointed that
nothing in their lives resembles riding on a horse-drawn carriage
to the tune of ``I'll Be Home for Christmas,'' or they're
overwhelmed by the feeling that a team of Clydesdales is bearing
down on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holiday demands tend to create over-the-top everyday stress
levels that begin to feel normal,'' says Susie Mantell, a
stress-relief expert whose relaxation audio tape is titled ``Your
Present: A Half-Hour of Peace.'' Don't try to do more than you can,
she says. Be a little selfish, or else you're no good to anyone
else. ``When in doubt, ask yourself, `Does this enhance my life?'
``
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the family could get along fine with fewer cookies,
decorations, outings and side dishes, Hall suggests. ``Doing
something a little differently this year doesn't mean that you are
shattering traditions or rituals.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the overwhelmed and the disappointed can make things worse
for themselves by picturing life to be like those eye-moistening
movies and TV commercials ``where it's snowy and everyone is
home,'' he says. ``Those images plant a seed of how it should be,
and that's where we get in trouble. It puts an absolute on our
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the real world, things don't turn out perfectly. It helps
to accept the certainty that the holidays won't meet such lofty
expectations, Hall says. The gift might not bring whoops of joy,
the bean-and-mushroom-soup casserole might burn or the
sisters-in-law might start fighting. ``We expect certain outcomes
and if they don't happen, we can be shattered,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Unrealistic expectations also are a reason that New Year's
resolutions can be problematic even in years that don't end with
two or three zeroes, Hall says. The TOPS (Take Off Pounds Sensibly)
Club weight-loss organization released a survey last month saying
48 percent of Americans will make resolutions to lose weight or
change their eating habits, but only 14 percent will keep the
pledge all year. The average person will give it up around Feb. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned that many resolutions this year will
include crash diets, overexercising and overall unhealthy
practices,'' says Howard Rankin, TOPS' psychological advisor.
``Ideally, resolutions for improved health should stick _ long past
Feb. 23.''
</P>
<P>
   Re-evaluating life and anticipating needed changes aren't bad
things, Hall says, but ``Unfortunately, we tend to wait until the
end of the year and put all these things into one grand, huge goal.
It would be better to take things in little steps throughout the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall expects millennial blues to peak after Jan. 1. The simple
act of writing a check will remind us that even the 1 and 9 at the
front of the year is no longer a familiar constant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a major issue,'' he says, particularly for
seniors and baby boomers. ``Going into a new century makes it a
more vivid reminder that life is passing us by.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jan. 1 will bring a sense of relief to many, Dr. James
Lomax of Baylor College of Medicine in Houston says it will bring
embarrassment to others. Their apocalyptic fears will be proven
wrong, the psychiatrist says, and some will have fallen prey to
``people who will exploit a person's financial fears in ways that
could be very costly.''
</P>
<P>
   But we can't stop the milestone from passing. Nobody is rich
enough or insignificant enough or determined enough to avoid it.
``I think it's important to acknowledge that,'' says Platoni.
</P>
<P>
   Make preparations, she says. ``If you feel you need to do
something, keep that bottled water available and a couple hundred
bucks of cash.'' She's buying Coleman lanterns for Christmas gifts.
But beyond that, she says, ``it's important to realize it's just
the passage of another day.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking about millennial feelings can help, she says. Platoni
suggests friends, ministers, trusted family members. She also says
volunteer work for a church or charity often benefits the helper
even more than the needy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do something for somebody else that's meaningful,'' she says.
``Spend a day working at a shelter. Do something for needy
children, or for food relief. Get out there and generate some
positive feelings by giving of yourself from your heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find your humanity within yourself. I have found that that is
more meaningful than anything else in terms of celebrating the
Christmas spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contact Relax Intuit about Susie Mantell's and other
stress-relief techniques toll-free at (888) 669-7352 (NOW-RELAX) or
www.relaxintuit.com, or order Mantell's tape at bookstores or
888-322-6657.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  National Foundation for Depressive Illness (NAFDI) toll-free
at (800) 248-4344.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com
</P>
