<SLUG> BC-SWISS-BANKS-REACT-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT RELIEVES SWISS, BUT QUESTIONS REMAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SWISS-BANKS-HOLOCAUST) 
(lb) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZURICH, Switzerland _ As the international panel released its
findings Monday on the assets of Holocaust victims in Switzerland,
the relief was palpable not only among bankers but also among other
Swiss.
</P>
<P>
   Accusations that Swiss bankers had hoarded the accounts of Jews
from Germany and other Axis-occupied countries who had tried to
secure their assets in secure Swiss vaults had battered the
country's long-held beliefs that only wartime neutrality and valor
saved it from coming under Hitler's boot.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that while the actions of some individual
banks had been misleading, there had not been a conspiracy or
organized discrimination to deprive survivors of Nazi Germany of
their funds.
</P>
<P>
   Relieved banking officials, politicians and the public seemed to
embrace those conclusions, even though the report described some
egregious incidents of duplicitous and unprofessional conduct by
banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the exercise was fair,'' said a prominent Zurich
banker, Hans Baer, who served as an alternate on the commission
appointed by the Swiss Bankers' Association and American Jewish
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest relief was that the report did not recommend
overturning the $1.25 billion settlement by Swiss banks in August
1998 to settle outstanding claims. Swiss banking officials had been
so fearful on that point that they had written about their concerns
to the commission chairman, Paul Volcker.
</P>
<P>
   The banking officials said the nearly 54,000 dormant, or
inactive, accounts that the panel said might belong to Holocaust
victims would present a payout so vast that it would exceed the
settlement amount.
</P>
<P>
   Although he agreed that claims could be covered under the global
settlement, Israel Singer, secretary-general of the World Jewish
Congress, said that the ``whole story is what we didn't find,''
referring to 2 million accounts from 1933-1945 that did not have
any documentation, so they could not be researched.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened here today is a worldwide mea culpa,'' said
Singer, who was also a commission alternate. American Jewish groups
have long protested that there was considerably more money in
Switzerland than the $32 million in 775 Holocaust-linked accounts
that Swiss banks disclosed from their last search in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The report's conclusions were praised by Swiss political
parties, although the Socialist Party noted that it was
``absolutely unacceptable and a shame'' that it took 50 years to
reach a result.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland's governing Federal Council released a statement
saying that the banks' cooperation and payment of the $200 million
search costs testified ``to their sincere determination to
establish the truth regarding the existence and extent of dormant
assets in Switzerland dating from World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement, however, noted the report's findings that there
had been a ``lack of sensitivity and at times a scantly cooperative
attitude'' toward people seeking their assets in the postwar years
_ incidents documented in the report that have drawn little comment
thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Swiss Bankers' Association chairman, Georg Krayer, said
he regretted the insensitivity to claimants. ``I should like to
apologize for all the disappointments and hurt feelings this
inadequacy may have caused,'' he said. But he insisted that except
for a few ``isolated cases,'' the banks had acted correctly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of the cases documented in the report describes how an
account holder who found refuge in Chile asked the bank to release
funds to pay for a food package for his wife who was interned at a
concentration camp. The bank refused, citing government directives.
Later, however, the bank sent money to a Berlin bank on the
instruction of Nazi trustees of the account.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude here is that since it was not systematic robbery,
since it wasn't planned, then it was a mistake, so people feel
relief,'' said Rolf Bloch, president of the Swiss Federation of
Jewish Communities, speaking from Bern.
</P>
<P>
   The key remaining question is whether Swiss banking regulators
will agree to publish 25,000 names from accounts that may be linked
to the Holocaust. Baer and others predicted that bankers would do
so in the end to bring the dormant-accounts saga to an end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
