<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SOCSEC-BENEFITS-ART-N     12-06 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-BENEFITS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL SAYS SOCIAL SECURITY NEEDS ARE UNDERESTIMATED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Social Security Administration is not being
optimistic enough about how long Americans will live in the 21st
century, and as a result it has underestimated how much their
benefits will cost, a federal advisory panel said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration underestimated the financial problems
of the Social Security program because it had understated likely
improvements in the life expectancy of Americans, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials already assume that Americans will live longer
in the next century. But the expert panel said that the
government's assumptions were too conservative, and that life
expectancy would probably continue improving in coming decades,
just as it has through the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-member panel said the decline in mortality rates had
financial implications: ``Longer lives imply more years of Social
Security benefits,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel reviewed the economic, demographic and other technical
assumptions used by the trustees of the Social Security program,
including the secretaries of the Treasury, Labor, and Health and
Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's report was commissioned and issued by the Social
Security Advisory Board, an independent bipartisan body created by
Congress and appointed by the president and congressional leaders.
The trustees may incorporate the panel's suggestions in their own
annual report. But Social Security tax rates, the formula for
computing benefits and the standard retirement age can be altered
only by changes in federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy at birth increased to 76.7 in 1998 from 63.6
years in 1940. The Social Security Administration predicts that it
will rise to 79.3 in 2030 and to 81.5 in 2070. The expert panel
said these numbers are likely to be higher; it predicted that life
expectancy would probably reach 81 in 2030 and 85.2 in 2070.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think life expectancy will increase more rapidly than the
actuaries have estimated in the past,'' said Richard Lee, a
professor of demography and economics at the University of
California at Berkeley and a panel member.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has often described this type of situation as
``a high-class problem,'' because it reflects improvements in the
well-being of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, led by Eugene Steuerle, an economist at the Urban
Institute, also said that wages and productivity would rise a
little faster than the government had assumed, and also suggested
other changes for the trustees' report.
</P>
<P>
   Taking these changes together, the panel concluded that Social
Security's long-term financial problems were about 25 percent
greater than the official government estimates indicated. To cover
the shortfall by raising taxes, the panel said, annual payroll
taxes would have to be increased by 2.6 percentage points above
current levels _ not just by 2.07 percentage points, as would be
required under the Clinton administration's assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   For a worker earning $30,000 a year, that means the payroll tax
would have to rise by $780 a year, rather than the increase of $621
needed under the assumptions now used by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The panel said that Social Security officials had made the
pessimistic and implausible assumption that life expectancy in the
United States would continue to lag far behind that of other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it said, Social Security actuaries assume that
American women will have to wait until 2033 before they achieve the
life expectancy already achieved by French women in 1995 (about 82
years). Likewise, it said, the actuaries assume that American men
will have to wait until 2029 before they achieve the life
expectancy recorded by Japanese men in 1995 (77 years).
</P>
<P>
   The experience of other countries shows that ``U.S. mortality
can fall a long way without encountering biomedical limits,'' the
panel said.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Ross, deputy commissioner of Social Security, said the
panel's recommendations would be ``carefully considered'' as her
agency prepares future annual reports on the program's financial
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Goss, deputy chief actuary of Social Security, said:
``Everybody agrees that mortality will continue to improve in the
future. The point of debate is how fast that improvement will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
