<SLUG> BC-POLIO-VACCINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS URGE POLIO SHOTS TO REPLACE ORAL VACCINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The oral polio vaccine, used routinely in the United States
since the 1960s, should be replaced by old-fashioned polio shots,
the American Academy of Pediatrics said in a statement issued on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation is the final step in phasing out the oral
vaccine, which began in 1997 when health officials recommended that
the first two doses of polio vaccine be given by injection and the
last two by mouth, instead of all four being given by mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the change is that the oral vaccine, which
contains a live but weakened form of the polio virus, can in rare
instances cause polio, either in the child receiving the vaccine or
in an unvaccinated adult who comes into contact with the child.
About eight such cases occur each year in the United States, one
for every 2.4 million oral doses given.
</P>
<P>
   The injected vaccine, which is just as effective as the oral
one, cannot cause polio, because it uses an inactivated form of the
virus. The injected vaccine used today is an updated, stronger
version of the original vaccine that was developed by Dr. Jonas
Salk and introduced to the public in 1953. The Salk vaccine
injections were later replaced by Dr. Albert Sabin's oral vaccine
because the oral version was more effective and better able to stop
outbreaks in areas where many cases occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The academy's new recommendation is nearly identical to one made
in June by the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention,
which said that after Jan. 1, 2000, all four doses of the vaccine
should be injected, rather than given by mouth. The doses are to be
given when children are 2 months, 4 months, 6 to 18 months and 4 to
6 years old.
</P>
<P>
   But the academy's recommendation differed from that of the
federal centers in one respect: instead of recommending, as the
centers did, that doctors stop using the oral vaccine altogether in
January, the academy said that during the first few months of 2000
doctors could use up their leftover oral vaccine by giving it as
the third or fourth dose to children who had already had two or
three injections of polio vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   An advocacy group representing families whose children had
contracted polio from the oral vaccine strongly objected to the
idea of allowing doctors to continue to use it, suggesting that it
might cause more cases of polio. John Salamone, president of
Informed Parents Against VAPP (vaccine-associated paralytic polio),
issued a statement saying that members were ``deeply troubled'' by
continued use of the vaccine, especially since doctors could return
it the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the manufacturer, Wyeth Lederle Vaccines, a
division of American Home Products, confirmed that the company
would take the oral vaccine back and give doctors refunds or
credits.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Georges Peter, a professor of pediatrics at Brown
University and chairman of the National Vaccine Advisory Committee,
who helped develop the academy's recommendations, said that no
cases of polio had ever been linked to the oral vaccine when it was
used as a third or fourth dose in children who had already had two
or three injected doses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean in any way to belittle the parents' concerns, but
I think the risk from the academy's policy is minimal to
nonexistent,'' Peter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
