<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTAH-CAMP-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTAH WILDERNESS SEARCHED FOR LAST OF 8 YOUTHS WHO ASSAULTED
COUNSELORS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR CITY, Utah _ For a second day, searchers combed a rugged
desert region west of here Monday, looking for the last of eight
teenaged boys from a program for troubled youth who assaulted their
counselors on Saturday and escaped into the wilderness of southwest
Utah.
</P>
<P>
   One boy was found by authorities on Saturday after he became
ill; five others turned up Monday, the authorities here in Iron
County said. One surrendered at a farm near Milford, Utah, and
another was taken into custody in Ely, Nev., after hitchhiking a
ride with a truck driver. The boy found in Nevada told
investigators they would find three other boys in a remote area
between Ely and Garrison, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   But with search efforts on the ground and in the air so far
unsuccessful, the authorities and program officials said they were
worried that the other two boys' could not endure the severe
nighttime cold in the area. Typically, this time of year,
temperatures in southwest Utah can fall below 10 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary concern right now is for the health and safety of
the remaining boys,'' Steve Peterson, one of the founders of the
program, the Redcliff Ascent Wilderness Therapy Program, said in a
statement. `'The boys are not outfitted for extended periods in
this type of weather and in this type of terrain.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the ages of the boys, 14 to 16, their identities were
not released by the authorities. Officials said only that are from
New York, Connecticut, Pennsylvania and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what happened on Saturday is known through interviews of
the first boy found by the Iron County sheriff's department. Now in
custody at a juvenile detention center on charges of aggravated
assault and theft, the boy told investigators that the group
overwhelmed the counselors _ Kirk Stock, 23, and Sunshine Fuller,
22 _ by beating them with sticks. The authorities said Stock was
knocked unconscious and bound with duct tape, and Ms. Fuller was
left tied to a tree.
</P>
<P>
   But Peterson said in his statement, ``Reports that one counselor
was rendered unconscious were erroneous. Both instructors freed
themselves and hiked to a neighboring group about two hours away to
call for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said the remaining seven boys in the group fled on foot
after their attack, taking some food, water and radios that use
only frequencies dedicated to Redcliff. He said efforts have been
made to contact the youth using the radios, and aircraft have been
dispatched to search for fires in the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third time this year that the authorities in
southwest Utah have been summoned to search for missing teenagers
from the Redcliff program. In separate incidents in April,
investigators found a 14-year-old girl and a 13-year-old boy who
had wandered off from their therapy groups.
</P>
<P>
   But even with periodic problems of missing youth, Peterson and
other Redcliff officials defended the wilderness program as an
effective tool for troubled and at-risk youth.
</P>
<P>
   He said the assault is the first incident of its kind since
Redcliff began operations six years ago, a period in which he said
the program has helped more than 1,500 youth from around the
country, using techniques that build self-esteem and teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the popularity of programs like Redcliff have grown in
recent years as an increasing number of families, many of them
high-income, turn to unusual alternatives to confront a child who
has exhibited signs of behavioral problems, emotional needs or
substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the programs are located in southern Utah, where the
rugged terrain plays a major role in rehabilitation. By design,
groups of teenagers are led by counselors into mountains and desert
for several days at a time, where the vagaries of nature are used
to teach responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Nadauld, director of admissions for Redcliff, said several
hundred teenagers are enrolled each year in its wilderness therapy
program of 30 or 60 days, and groups generally consist of six to
nine people with three staff counselors and a support team that
includes a therapist and other administrative personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the parental decision to send their children to programs
like this reflects a last-resort approach after mounting
frustrations of unsuccessful discipline through more conventional
methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, at their best, these programs can be very powerful,
efficacious and impactful experiences,'' said Bill Zimmerman,
accreditation coordinator for the Association of Experiental
Education in Boulder, Colo., a company that monitors professional
wilderness camps and adventure training programs in the United
States and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons these businesses are flourishing is because
they have had such profound changes on the participants in terms of
those individuals self-concept or self-esteem,'' he added. `'It's
an environment where things get really simple _ making adequate
shelter, making sure they don't get hurt _ and they have to rely on
communication so they can achieve their goals. Gradually they
realize they that if they want to achieve something really
difficult, they have to develop those skills.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1117 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RITE-AID-MARKETPLACE-     12-06 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RITE-AID-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SO, WHAT REALLY HAPPENED AT THE RITE AID MEETING? 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the financial position of Rite Aid Corp. unraveled this year,
the most intriguing single meeting seems to have taken place on
June 30. There are diametrically different versions of what was
said at that meeting _ differences that raise questions about the
performance of Rite Aid's board and its auditors.
</P>
<P>
   Rite Aid says that at that June 30 meeting of the audit
committee, auditors from KPMG International failed to mention that
they no longer trusted the company's chief financial officer. Nor,
said the company, did KPMG make it clear that its doubts about the
quality of the company's financial controls were so great that the
auditing firm would not issue quarterly reports on the company's
financials.
</P>
<P>
   KPMG says that it did discuss both points, which Rite Aid agrees
the auditor had made in earlier conversations with the company's
management. Two weeks later, the company issued a quarterly
financial report that gave no hint of the auditor's belief that the
company's financial controls could not be relied upon.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the chief executive, Martin Grass, was forced out of
the company, and Rite Aid said it would have to restate its results
for the last three years. It expects to reduce reported profits by
$500 million. In November, KPMG resigned as the company's auditor.
</P>
<P>
   A new management team took over Rite Aid Monday, voicing
optimism but saying the pace of growth will be slowed. In a
conference call with analysts, Robert G. Miller, the new chief
executive, said financial controls ``must be strengthened, and they
will be.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he believed ``most of the writeoffs are behind
us'' but said final numbers will await completion of an
investigation of the company's accounting practices by Swidler
Berlin Shereff Friedman, a New York and Washington law firm, and an
audit by Deloitte &AMP; Touche, the company's new auditors.
</P>
<P>
   The June 30 meeting came after a difficult period in the
relationship of Rite Aid and KPMG. The company had been forced by
auditors to take the humiliating step of making major changes in
its financial statements for the fiscal year that had ended in
February. The profits had been substantially higher in the news
release issued in March than they were in the report filed on June
1 with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of June, Rite Aid's stock price was about $25, half
the peak it had reached in January but far above the low of $4.50
it fell to after the bad news came out in November. Monday, the
price rose $3.625, to $11.875, as investors reacted to the new
management team.
</P>
<P>
   On June 23, KPMG notified Rite Aid that it felt it could no
longer rely on representations made by Frank Bergonzi, the
company's chief financial officer, and that because the company's
accounting controls were so bad, it would not be able to issue
reports on the company's quarterly financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   That is confirmed by Rite Aid, but the company would not say to
whom that message was given. And a spokeswoman said it was not
passed on to the audit committee.
</P>
<P>
   KPMG, in a filing with the SECMonday, said that its personnel
who attended the June 30 audit committee meeting remember
discussing the lack of confidence in Bergonzi and KPMG's refusal to
issue quarterly reports. But Rite Aid says the subject neverarose
at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In its own filing with the SEC, Rite Aid said its version of
what transpired is supported by the three members of the audit
committee, as well as by another director, who was not identified,
who attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the audit committee are Preston Robert Tisch, the
co-chairman of Loews Corp. and the part owner of the New York
Giants football team; Nancy Lieberman, a partner at Skadden, Arps,
Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom, the New York law firm, and William Bratton,
the former New York City police commissioner. Of the three, only
Bratton returned a telephone call, and he said he could not discuss
the situation.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rite Aid directors' recollections are accurate, it must
have been an extraordinary meeting. Everyone agrees that KPMG
delivered a letter to the audit committee saying that financial
controls were so bad that Rite Aid could not ``accumulate and
reconcile information necessary to properly record and analyze
transactions on a timely basis.''
</P>
<P>
   But the company says that meeting did not get into KPMG's
conclusion that it could not perform quarterly reviews, which are
less extensive than audits but offer some assurance for companies
before quarterly statements are issued.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for KPMG said the firm would not discuss the
situation beyond what is contained in the filings. Bergonzi, who
left Rite Aid two weeks after the June 30 meeting, in what the
company called a retirement, also declined to comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the S EC,
rules have been proposed and are now being considered by various
regulatory bodies, to strengthen the role of corporate audit
committees. Among them is a rule that would require audit
committees to discuss with auditors the quality of the corporate
financial statements, not just whether they meet the minimal
requirements of generally accepted accounting principles.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules would also require companies to say whether
any information had come to the attention of audit committee
members that caused them to believe financial statements contained
materially misleading statements.
</P>
<P>
   That proposal has run into resistance from some companies, which
have told the SEC that they fear it would increase the legal
liability of audit committee members. The SEC is considering
whether to relax that requirement.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rite Aid case makes clear that it is possible for a
difference of opinion to arise regarding what was said about the
very question that is at the heart of the reason for creating an
audit committee: Can investors be confident that a company's
financial reports are accurate?
</P>
<P>
   Rite Aid's audit committee says it didn't know what was going
on, and KPMG says it did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
