<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AIRTRAN-SABRETECH-COX     12-06 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-SABRETECH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SabreTech held liable for actions leading to ValuJet crash
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (a) General news and (f) Financial categories.)
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A federal jury on Monday convicted the SabreTech
maintenance firm of eight criminal counts of recklessness and one
count of improper training in the deadly May 1996 ValuJet crash,
but cleared the company and two maintenance workers of 14 other
charges.
</P>
<P>
   In what was believed to be the first criminal conviction in an
accidental air crash, both prosecutors and SabreTech declared
victory. But Gwendolyn Marks of Miami, who lost her son Philmore in
the crash, called the verdict ``a dagger in the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Crash investigators believe a horrific fire sent Flight 592
slamming into the Everglades, killing all 110 aboard. Investigators
have concluded that 144 outdated oxygen generator canisters _
removed from another plane, listed as ``empty'' by SabreTech and
loaded by ValuJet in Miami for return to ValuJet's Atlanta
headquarters _ activated in the DC-9's cargo hold, sparking the
fire.
</P>
<P>
   The crash is the deadliest in Florida history and may have been
one of the most preventable anywhere. The National Transportation
Safety Board has said the crash reflected complacency, rushing and
a bottom-line mentality on the part of both the airline industry
and its overseer, the Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, which began Nov. 17, is believed to be the first ever
criminal case in an accidental plane crash in U.S. history. The
12-member jury began discussing the case late Thursday, spent all
day Friday in discussion and deliberated for a little more than six
hours Monday before announcing its verdict about 3:15 p.m. Jurors
left without comment.
</P>
<P>
   SabreTech still faces 110 state felony murder counts and another
110 manslaughter charges in the case. Miami-Dade County prosecutors
allege the deaths stemmed from the illegal transportation of
hazardous materials. No one would go to prison, but the company
could be fined up to $10,000 per count if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The federal jury Monday ruled that SabreTech recklessly allowed
hazardous materials _ the oxygen generators _ to be transported and
failed to properly train its employees. It also concluded SabreTech
improperly trained employees in handling hazardous materials.
</P>
<P>
   It faces up to $500,000 in fines per count plus unspecified
restitution to the victims' families. U.S. District Judge James
Lawrence King did not set a sentencing date.
</P>
<P>
   SabreTech and employees Daniel Gonzalez and Eugene Florence were
acquitted of charges of conspiracy and lying on repair records. The
company also was cleared of additional hazardous materials charges.
</P>
<P>
   A third defendant, Chilean native Mauro Valenzuela, jumped bail
and has been declared a federal fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez and Florence hugged in the court, then stood with their
lawyers on the steps of U.S. District Court, but declined repeated
calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Florence had signed a work card saying he fitted the generators
with plastic caps designed to prevent them from activating, but
admitted days after the crash that he never did. Gonzalez is
accused of pressing Florence and other mechanics to sign false
paperwork. He also was charged with falsely signing off on work
never done on another plane in 1995; prosecutors have said that
shows SabreTech had a history of sacrificing care for profits.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has said the workers made unintentional mistakes but
committed no crimes.
</P>
<P>
   If he had been convicted, Florence would have faced up to 15
years in prison, Gonzalez up to 10 years. Last week, King dropped
eight of 11 charges against Florence.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors accentuated the positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly it sends a strong message . . . that there will be
serious _ I repeat, serious _ criminal consequences,'' assistant
U.S. Attorney Guy Lewis said. ``The good news is that the flying
public can sleep well tonight.'' The SabreTech corporation, which
lost $37 million after the crash, is out of business. Its parent
company, St. Louis-based Sabreliner, would be liable for any fines
and restitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never should have gone through this nightmare,'' Sabreliner
spokesman Kenneth Quinn said. ``We may never know what happened on
that fateful flight, (but) the search for a scapegoat for the
terrible ValuJet tragedy is plain wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ValuJet, which has changed its name to AirTran, and SabreTech
have settled most lawsuits brought by victims' families, but a few
are set for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Sawyer of southern Miami-Dade County, whose grandparents,
Conway and Anna Laurie Hamilton of Coral Gables, died on the plane,
let out a long sigh in the courtroom after the verdicts were
announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got off on a lot of charges,'' she said later outside.
``It's a shame but it's a good first step and it shows America you
can't put the almighty buck ahead of peoples' safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Kleinberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: eliotkleinberg(at)pbpost.com
</P>
