<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1121 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-FIRE-WORCESTER-BOS     12-06 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-FIRE-WORCESTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTERS STRUGGLE WITH EMOTIONS DURING DELAY IN SEARCH FOR FIVE
VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. -- Anguish turned to frustration as weary
firefighters were forced Monday to halt for eight hours their
efforts to find five fallen comrades inside a burned-out warehouse
because of fears that an unstable firewall might collapse on top of
search crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing on earth we want to do is hurt someone,'' said
Worcester Fire Department District Chief Walter Giard, as dozens of
firefighters milled outside what one fire official dubbed ``the
building from hell.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for the remaining five firefighters resumed after a
large crane had dismantled part of the unsteady fire wall.
</P>
<P>
   The delay added to the emotional pain of exhausted firefighters
and family members of the six men who died Friday night battling
the blaze that still continued to smolder at the Worcester Cold
Storage and Warehouse Co. building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually have to hold people back'' from entering the
building under unsafe conditions, District Chief Ron Fritz said.
``The frustration is really overwhelming. Words really can't
explain what we're going through right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowds of dejected firefighters had nothing to do during the day
but stand by, watching front-end loaders sort rubble into piles _
piles of blackened, twisted metal piping, piles of crumbled brick
and piles of ashes. Family members huddled in blankets nearby as
smoke hung in the air and a light rain fell. So far, investigators
have no leads on what caused the massive fire on the edge of
downtown that reduced the sprawling, vacant building to charred
rubble. Investigators said they did not know if the empty building
had been boarded up or secured in anyway to keep out trespassers.
</P>
<P>
   District Chief Michael McNamee, who commanded the first unit to
arrive at the scene of Friday's fire, provided new insight Monday
into how the fire spread and why it so quickly engulfed the
warehouse in thick black smoke.
</P>
<P>
   When 25 to 30 firefigthers first entered the burning building to
look for homeless people reported to be inside the area was so
clear and conditions so unthreatening that the men were not wearing
face masks, McNamee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But within four seconds the building filled compltely with
black, hot billowing smoke,'' said McNamee.
</P>
<P>
   And that, he added, was because of the building's original
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was built to hold in the cold, so it could hold the heat
in, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thick brick walls were padded with cork and in many of the
maze-like storage areas sheet rock had been padded with
polyurethane foam, a petroleum product, McNamee said.
</P>
<P>
   The wave of heavy, black smoke that disoriented the firefighters
probably erupted just as the blaze reached the polyurethane, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I refer to it as the building from hell,'' said McNamee.
</P>
<P>
   After firefighters were ordered to retreat, two members of
Rescue Company No. 1 failed to show up for a headcount _ Paul
Brotherton, 41, of Auburn, and Jeremiah Lucey, 38, of Leicester.
</P>
<P>
   Four men who went in to search for them and never returned -
Lieutenant Thomas Spencer, 42, of Worcester, Timothy Jackson, 51,
of Hopedale, James Lyons, 34, of Worcester, and Jospeh McGuirk, 38,
of Leicester.
</P>
<P>
   There were no homless people believed to be inside the building
when the fire started.
</P>
<P>
   While the warehouse had once been part of a bustling commercial
neighborhood, city officials who had visited the building in recent
years described it as a windowless, claustrophobic maze of hallways
with ceilings no higher than seven or eight feet high.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no electricity, no water, no heat and the sprinkler
system was busted,'' said the city's commercial assessor, Ed
Hostrander, who visited the building in 1994. ``I remember thinking
that I would not have wanted to be a firefighter in there. I was
just afraid I would never find my way out.''
</P>
<P>
   After removing Jackson's body Sunday, investigators found his
badge Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on, hopes faded among the 300 people working
outside the warehouse that the other five men would be quickly
located and their remains turned over to anxious relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Officials Monday refused to discuss in any detail their
investigation into the fire and stepped back from previous comments
that the blaze may have been set because it was burning in two
places when firefighters first arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call it suspicious, but suspicious doesn't mean
anything,'' said District Chief James Callery. ``We wouldn't be
investigating if it weren't suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire Chief Dennis Budd Monday set up a board of inquiry that
will begin meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters Monday were facing the possibility that the bodies
of the five dead firefighters might not be retrieved in time for
Thursday's memorial at the Worcester Centrum, which is expected to
draw 15,000 to 20,000 firefighters from across the country and
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only just now getting a handle on the scale this
operation is going to be,'' Callery said with a note of tired
resignation in his voice. ``It's going to be long and difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the family members gathered Monday at the warehouse ruins
was Timothy Jackson, Jr., 32.
</P>
<P>
   Even though his father's body had been found and taken away,
Jackson said he came back because there was still unfinished
business among the close-knit community of firefighters who
repeatedly refer to each other as ``family'' and ``brother.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be coming back here until the last fireman is out,''
Jackson said. ``I don't think I should sit home while my father's
brothers are still in there.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the recovery effort, the Boston Fire Department
brought in a high-tech fiberoptic imaging device with a 26-foot
range and 180 degree rotation that can snake into crevices too
small for humans to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   But the most useful tool Monday was the 130-foot crane brought
from out-of-state to dismantle, bit-by-bit, about 20 feeet of the
warehouse's internal firewall to prevent the possibility that it
would collapse during the recovery effort.
</P>
<P>
   As the hours of work accumulated, many firefighters had received
little or no sleep since Friday night, going home only when ordered
by superiors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is that keeps us going, but whatever it
is, we should all bottle it and sell it,'' said Donald Courtney,
vice-president of the local firefighter's union.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's devastating fire has elicited a tremendous outpouring
of support from people in this central Massachusetts city of
170,000.
</P>
<P>
   A firetruck-turned-memorial was virtually hidden behind piles of
flower bouquets left as condolences by strangers, along with toy
firetrucks, paper hearts, photographs, and handmade signs.
``Firefighters saved my baby. I will always remember,'' read one
card, which was signed: ``a grateful mother.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, families continued to reflect on the fathers,
sons, husbands and brothers they lost.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Jr., recalled that his 10-year-old son, Joshua, has a
firefighters' calender in his room and wanted to follow in his
grandfather's footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father and he had a bond where he was supposed to teach his
grandson to be a firefighter,'' Jackson said. ``Now Joshua just
sits and holds his grandfather's picture.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff reporter Jordana Hart contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
