<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1123 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-VALUJET-SABRETECH-NYT     12-06 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALUJET-SABRETECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRACTOR FOUND GUILTY IN TRIAL ON VALUJET CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ SabreTech Inc., the aircraft maintenance company that
safety investigators concluded had improperly packaged the oxygen
generators linked to the 1996 crash of ValuJet Airlines Flight 592,
was found guilty Monday in a subdued federal courtroom of
improperly handling the hazardous materials.
</P>
<P>
   As the court clerk read the verdict here Monday afternoon, there
were no shouts of victory or even words of satisfaction from
relatives of the crash's 110 victims. There was only a quiet
sadness.
</P>
<P>
   Gwendolyn Marks, the mother of Philmore Marks, a 23-year-old
victim of the disaster, sat in her seat, her eyes pooling with
tears: ``If Philmore were here, he would shake his head, and say,
`Nothing ever works out like you want it to.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although SabreTech the company was found guilty on eight counts
of causing the transportation of hazardous materials, no top
executives were charged in the crash. A fine to be set by Judge
James Lawrence King of U.S. District Court will be the only
punishment. And the two company employees who did go on trial here
with SabreTech, Daniel Gonzalez, chief of hangar operations, and
Eugene Florence, a mechanic, were acquitted on charges that they
lied on repair records.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors had argued that SabreTech and the two
employees _ a third worker is believed to have fled the country _
sacrificed caution for expediency to complete contracted work on
time, then lied on work forms, causing the crash of ValuJet Flight
592.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Heck Miller, assistant U.S. attorney, said SabreTech
workers did not install safety caps on oxygen generators that
heated up in the plane's cargo hold but said on paperwork that they
had. The generators caused a fire in the cargo hold of Flight 592,
which then crashed just after takeoff from Miami International
Airport on May 11, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big business, getting away with murder,'' said Laura Sawyer,
whose grandparents, Conway and Anna Laurie Hamilton, died in the
crash.
</P>
<P>
   SabreTech is out of business; following post-crash publicity,
its business dried up. But it is not bankrupt, and will, its
lawyers say, continue to fight legal challenges against it,
including unrelated state charges of murder. The fine for the
federal conviction could run as high as $2.25 million. Meanwhile,
ValuJet is still flying, under a new name, AirTran.
</P>
<P>
   If anything good came from the federal charges, said relatives
of its victims, it is that the ValuJet crash may become a
cautionary tale. ``I just hope the airlines will learn a lesson
from all this,'' Mrs. Marks said. ``That they will be safe, because
it's the law. That people who do their jobs do it well.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers, who had described the crash as an accident, not
a crime, claimed some victories in the verdict. ``My client felt
that no one committed a criminal act,'' said Jane Moscowitz, a
lawyer for Florence. ``He's sorry that the accident happened. It
was a tragedy. It wasn't a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   SabreTech had been charged with one count of conspiracy, but the
jury found the company not guilty of that count and of five counts
of making false statements. But it did find SabreTech guilty on one
count of failing to provide training in handling hazardous
materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pretty good vindication of the company,'' said Ken Quinn, a
lawyer for SabreTech. ``We are very pleased with the not guilty
verdicts for our former SabreTech mechanics. We are also pleased
that the jury dismissed almost two-thirds of the charges against
the company, including the government's outlandish conspiracy and
terrorist counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn said the company would appeal. He and other lawyers for
SabreTech had argued that no one at the company intended for anyone
to be hurt, and that, although mistakes were made, the company's
actions never amounted to a crime. Instead, company lawyers said,
the crash was probably caused by the condition of the 27-year-old
DC-9, which had mechanical and electric problems.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, disappointed that the two SabreTech employees were
not convicted, said the jury's verdict ``validated the government's
case.'' Guy Lewis, acting U.S. attorney for the Southern District
of Florida, said that Gonzalez and Florence were not ``the most
culpable party in this horrific tragedy.'' The company itself was,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government's charges stemmed from what prosecutors said was
``pencil-whipping'' by Gonzalez, who, they said, pressed Florence
and other workers to sign the paperwork even though the actual work
had not been completed.
</P>
<P>
   Florence, prosecutors said, signed a work card stating that he
had installed shipping caps on the volatile generators _ caps that
would have prevented them from heating up in the cargo hold and
causing the 2,200-degree fire.
</P>
<P>
   ValuJet and SabreTech have settled most of the lawsuits brought
by relatives of the victims, but some are still pending.
</P>
<P>
   In the Miami courtroom, relatives of the victims walked away
from the three-week trial feeling empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone always talks about the 110 victims,'' said Ms.
Sawyer, whose grandparents perished in the crash. ``But there are
so many more victims than the people who died on that plane. There
are thousands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
