<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1124 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PHILLY-CRIME-ART-NYT &LR;      12-06 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-CRIME-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSELL BYERS, TABLOID COLUMNIST, DIES RESISTING ROBBER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ In grief and alarm, residents from all corners of
this city expressed shock Monday at the death of one of their most
outspoken newspaper writers in a street stabbing in the unlikely
bastion of affluent Chestnut Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a matter of principle with him, not a manhood thing,''
said Jude Bruno of the sudden, violent death of W. Russell G.
Byers, a columnist with the Philadelphia Daily News who resisted a
robber Saturday night near the hamlet's picturesque main street and
was stabbed in the heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russell Byers was very opinionated and made it clear in his
columns that he stood against urban crime,'' said Bruno, manager of
Caruso's Market in Chestnut Hill where Byers shopped and, his
neighbors said, held forth on city issues more avidly as a
committed resident than a professional pundit. ``He just couldn't
give in.''
</P>
<P>
   After an intense citywide search, the police announced the
arrest Monday of a murder suspect, identified as 20-year-old Javier
Goode, who reportedly was recorded on a surveillance television
tape at the neighborhood Wawa convenience store where Byers bled to
death after being assaulted in the adjacent parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tried to get the guy away from me and into the light,''
Byers' wife, Laurada, told the Daily News. She described how the
assailant emerged from the nighttime shadows outside the store
after they had stopped for ice cream in the heart of what police
say is statistically one of the safest areas of the city.
</P>
<P>
   From the city's political establishment to the cobble-stoned
streets of his home neighborhood, Byers was mourned as a writer of
popular, sharp-edged civic commentary and as a man who transcended
his roots in old-line wealth to reach a tabloid readership with
solidly researched views on government problems.
</P>
<P>
   Byers' great-grandfather was W.R. Grace, the 19th-century
industrialist who amassed a fortune and became the first Catholic
elected mayor of New York City. He was twice married to and
divorced from Connie Mellon, a daughter of the Pittsburgh society
family, and for all his upper-class credentials mourners stressed
Byers passion for the give and take of street-level politics and
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russell was a man who had a tangible love for the city of
Philadelphia,'' said Mayor-elect John F. Street, a politician who
crossed swords with Byers in the past, notably in a libel suit that
the columnist won.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Katz, a close friend and Republican businessman who narrowly
lost to Street in last month's election, said the city was left
with ``a huge, huge void.'' ``He was an amazing guy with a
tremendous sense of optimism,'' Katz said as city residents
expressed amazement at the very idea of murder in Chestnut Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never ever had a killing like this,'' said Marie Jones,
editor of the Chestnut Hill Local, the community weekly. ``The
neighborhood is terribly shaken,'' she said in her office off
Germantown Avenue, the main street of small shops and galleries
that was aglow with holiday lights.
</P>
<P>
   The police reported only eight incidents of violent crime in the
neighborhood since June, and these typically involved such property
crimes as purse snatchings and car break-ins. ``We feel so safe
here leave our car doors unlocked,'' said Mickey Valinis at the
local visitors bureau. ``We're totally amazed this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno at Caruso's said some merchants feel that a more visible
police presence was needed. But as attractive as the neighborhood
might be to passing thieves, residents emphasized that Byers and
other local voters heartily endorsed remaining a part of
Philadelphia a decade ago when they rejected a secession proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Chestnut Hill's problem or Philadelphia's problem;
the fact is we live in a violent society,'' said John Ingersoll at
the Chestnut Hill Cheese Shop, who knew Byers as a friend and
regular Saturday morning customer and conversationalist. ``He was
always full of good ideas, sort of like a good coach,'' said
Ingersoll, noting the Byers held the most eclectic Christmas
parties with the guest list ranging from ranking politicians to
local tradesmen.
</P>
<P>
   The 59-year-old Byers was senior editor at the News. He came to
newspapering a decade ago after a career in politics and government
that included service with Vice President Nelson Rockefeller and
executive jobs with the Department of Health, Education and
Welfare. In roaming the city, he built a reputation for budget
delving and blunt writing, with his last columns urging the new
mayor to ``read the riot act'' to ``what is now Your
Establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   An impromptu memorial of flowers and candles _ including a pack
of the Lucky Strike cigarettes Byers smoked as he paced his office
and composed his columns _ was placed by friends outside the store
where he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing to remember,'' said Zachery Stalberg, a
close friend who is editor of the News, ``is that Russell was
really not a journalist first. He was really a citizen first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
