<HEADER>
A1126 &Cx1f; tad-z
b a BC-DEATHROW-BRITS-COX     12-06 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATHROW-BRITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    British barristers to bargain with U.S. courts in Florida murder
case
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A team of proper British barristers
appearing (SET ITALICS)amicus curiae (END ITALICS) on behalf of a
countryman condemned to die more than a decade ago for the grisly
murders of a father and son in a Miami hotel penthouse may appear
curious indeed when they argue before the Florida Supreme Court
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The barristers, trying to help overturn the conviction of
Krishna Maharaj, plan to appear in horse hair wigs and flowing
black robes. One may even sport silk stockings.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys believe American courts unfairly handled Maharaj's
case after his trial judge was arrested in Miami on bribery
charges. They also contend prosecutors withheld evidence and
Maharaj's defense attorney performed ineptly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, Kris got screwed over, and it's shocking they haven't
done something before now,'' said Clive Stafford Smith, a
British-born attorney in Louisiana representing Maharaj. ``I told
them to send the damn gun boat and just shell Washington until we
beat them into submission and they reminded me those times had
passed.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the British barristers have taken a more diplomatic
tack in their ``friend of the court'' arguments:
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of capital punishment in Great Britain and the
United States is littered with tragic examples of justice
miscarrying with fatal effect,'' barrister Julian B. Knowles
pleaded in his brief. ``(We) would respectfully urge the Court to
act now to prevent the possibility of another case being added to
this list.''
</P>
<P>
   It is rare, though not unheard of, for bewigged barristers from
the British Empire to appear in American courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles, representing 104 members of the House of Commons, will
be accompanied by attorneys for 128 members of the House of Lords
(England's highest court), the European Parliament, the Human
Rights Committee of the Bar of England and Wales, and Queen's
Counsel Phillip Sapsford, he of the silk stockings.
</P>
<P>
   While international intervention in death sentences has rarely
persuaded American courts, it does bring attention to a
controversial law abandoned by all but a few Western countries,
said Richard Dieter, director of the Washington-based Death Penalty
Information Center.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the European Parliament called for a
moratorium and the United Nations Commission on Human Rights asked
countries to suspend death sentences while it examines the issue.
The Catholic Church has long opposed capital punishment and this
year the pope succeeded in persuading the governor of Missouri to
grant clemency to a Death Row inmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly an important case whenever any foreign national
is on Death Row because of reciprocity, . . . just as if we wanted
to send over our lawyers if someone was going to be caned in
Singapore,'' Dieter said. ``It's no secret Florida is going before
the U.S. Supreme Court on the issue of the electric chair . . . and
all of that heightens the focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Maharaj, 60, once a millionaire with a fleet of Rolls-Royces and
a stable of thoroughbreds, was convicted in October 1987 of killing
a business partner and his son in the two-story penthouse suite of
the Dupont Plaza Hotel in downtown Miami a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Maharaj, a British subject born in Trinidad, had moved to the
U.S. in 1985 after building a fortune importing bananas and fruit
to England, said Smith. Maharaj lived large: He owned the second
largest string of racing ponies in Britain at one time, and a
prized horse beat the Queen Mother's entry at Royal Ascot. He also
paid the law school tuition for his brother, who is now the
attorney general for Trinidad and coincidentally helped shepherd an
unprecedented string of executions in that country recently.
</P>
<P>
   When Maharaj's English business started declining, he decided to
invest in Florida real estate and in1986 hired neighbors Derrick
Moo Young, 53, and his son, Duane, 23 to manage property. (In 1981
Maharaj purchased undeveloped land in Royal Palm Beach for $3.75
million, but it fell victim to foreclosure a year later when he
failed to make payments.)
</P>
<P>
   The partnership soured when Maharaj blamed the Moo Youngs for
blowing a business deal and sued. Police say Maharaj lured the Moo
Youngs to the hotel to confront them and shot first the father,
then the son.
</P>
<P>
   But defense attorneys say that Maharaj was framed and that the
prosecution's eyewitness failed a lie detector test. The Moo
Youngs, they say, were linked to a $5 billion dollar money
laundering conspiracy and had many enemies. In addition, the judge
was arrested four days into the trial on bribery charges and
Maharaj's attorney, Eric Hendon, failed to ask for a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   Hendon declined to comment on the case Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On appeal, Maharaj's case was returned to the trial court for a
new hearing in October 1997, but defense attorneys complained that
they were given no money to help try the case and Maharaj was
broke.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami-Dade circuit judge upheld Maharaj's conviction, but set
aside his sentencing which will go back to a jury. At that point,
interest in England grew and the government took an interest,
Stafford Smith said. Prosecutors will again seek the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big problem we've had in motivating people is I think Kris
suffers from color of skin on both sides of the Atlantic,'' he
said. ``Basically, the bottom line is this guy is patently not
guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Staletovich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: jennystaletovich(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
