<SLUG> BC-EXXON-MOBIL-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXXON REVOKES BENEFITS FOR PARTNERS OF GAY WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil Corp., which was created last week after Exxon
completed its acquisition of Mobil, has revoked a Mobil policy that
provided health-care coverage to the partners of newly hired gay
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The move outraged gay rights advocates, who said the reversal is
a step back for gay employees and goes against the recent trend of
companies, and municipal governments, extending benefits to gay
couples.
</P>
<P>
   Under the policy, partners of Mobil employees who had already
been receiving coverage are ``grandfathered'' and will continue to
get benefits. But partners of employees hired after November will
not be able to receive the benefits, and long-serving gay employees
of Mobil who take a partner in the future will not be able to
obtain benefits for that partner.
</P>
<P>
   The trend of companies extending ``domestic partner'' benefits
to gay couples began in the technology industry, but lately it has
been extended to other industries, including the airlines and some
oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, BP Amoco PLC, which was formed by the merger of
British Petroleum and Amoco, will offer domestic-partner benefits
to all U.S. employees as of April 1. Previously, Amoco had offered
the benefits but BP had not. Gay rights groups say about 15 percent
of the United States' largest companies now offer domestic-partner
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The new Exxon Mobil policy became effective Nov. 30 _ the day
the acquisition closed _ and tracks Exxon's existing policy, which
did not extend domestic-partner benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal of the Mobil policy was attacked Monday by the
Human Rights Campaign, a gay rights group in Washington, which said
it learned of the change after being contacted by several angered
Exxon Mobil employees.
</P>
<P>
   The group issued a statement condemning the action as only the
second major U.S. employer to take such steps, following the
decision last year by the chairman of Perot Systems, Ross Perot, to
not offer benefits to the partners of newly hired gay employees.
That policy remains effective today, a Perot Systems spokeswoman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cirigliano, an Exxon Mobil spokesman, said the new policy
states that benefits will be offered to anyone in a ``legally
valid'' marriage or common-law marriage to an Exxon Mobil employee.
``It's our opinion that basing benefits coverage on a legally
recognized relationship eliminates the need for the company to
establish criteria of its own for which to assess the legitimacy of
any relationship, whether it's straight or gay,'' Cirigliano said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he did not know how many gay Mobil employees
currently have benefits for their partners, and he said he did not
know how long the Mobil policy had been in place.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights advocates were quick to note that no state currently
recognizes same-sex marriages, although they said court cases may
change that in a few states.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's smoke,'' said David M. Smith, the Human Rights Campaign's
communications director. ``They're basically trying to justify what
they have done. The fact is, no jurisdiction recognizes marriages
between same-sex couples. These benefits have proliferated
throughout corporate America as a way for companies to offer equal
pay for equal work.'' He said 74 of the Fortune 500 companies now
offer domestic-partner benefits to same-sex couples.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kevin Cathcart, executive director of the Lambda Legal Defense
and Education fund, a gay rights groups in New York, said,
``They're taking a giant step backward that is out of step with
where the public and industry is going. It's not clear to me what
they gain from this. They will save some small amount of money, but
it hardly seems worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathcart said the trend toward more companies offering
domestic-partner benefits had been helped by ordinances in some
cities restricting the ability of companies to do business with
municipalities unless they offer domestic-partner benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights advocates on Monday attacked Exxon Mobil's decision
to adopt a policy that does not specifically name sexual
orientation as a category of forbidden discrimination, as Mobil's
policy had done.
</P>
<P>
   Cirigliano said Exxon Mobil's anti-discrimination policy simply
lists the same categories that the federal government does. And he
added that language has appeared in Exxon's securities filings _
and in speeches by company executives _ making plain that
discrimination based on sexual orientation will not be tolerated.
</P>
</TEXT>
