<SLUG> BC-GM-HUGHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES OF GM AND HUGHES JUMP ON HOPES OF A STAKE SALE
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER and LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speculation that General Motors Corp. might spin off part of its
stake in Hughes Electronics, or even become the target of a
takeover bid, led to heavy trading Monday in GM shares and GM's
tracking stock in Hughes. But a meeting of GM's board adjourned
Monday afternoon with only an announcement of a factory investment.
</P>
<P>
   After rising sharply on Friday, GM shares closed at $76.50, up
75 cents Monday, on volume nearly double the daily average. The GM
class H shares, which track its stake in Hughes, soared $5, to
$94.6875. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A tracking stock lets companies highlight the financial value of
a business unit without relinquishing ownership. Investors can buy
and sell tracking stock like regular shares, but the stock does not
represent an actual separate ownership stake in the business it
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   After the close of trading, GM said only that its board had
approved investing another $700 million in a pickup factory in
Shreveport, La.
</P>
<P>
   Harry J. Pearce, GM's vice chairman, had told analysts earlier
this fall that the board would hear its annual report Monday on the
performance of Hughes, in which GM owns a 68 percent stake. Pearce
warned that this did not mean that GM planned to change its
relationship with Hughes, but his comment prompted speculation that
the board might decide to spin off a piece of GM's Hughes stake to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have urged such a move, contending it would
temporarily raise the value of GM stock. Hughes is valuable because
its DirecTV unit has become the nation's leading provider of
satellite TV.
</P>
<P>
   GM officials have resisted a spinoff, contending that Hughes has
strategic value to the automaker. GM has tapped Hughes' expertise
in satellite communications and electronics in developing its
OnStar auto navigation system. GM said last month that it planned
to add e-mail and other services to OnStar.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in October, Pearce indicated that any changes at
Hughes might not happen quickly. ``We don't do major restructurings
in any circumstances on a whim overnight,'' he said. ``There are
tax and organizational ramifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at credit-rating agencies have also said they were
counting on GM to retain a sizable stake in Hughes. That means if
GM shed a large part or all of Hughes, GM's borrowing costs would
rise when it finances car loans and leases for customers.
</P>
<P>
   While there was some speculation Monday that GM might be a
takeover candidate _ speculation reported this weekend by Barron's
_ several investment bankers and traders were skeptical. ``Why
would an industrial buyer walk into the reality of owning a
manufacturing business and expose themselves to all the risks, like
GM's union situation?'' one investment banker asked. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
