<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PRISONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES TACKLE TROUBLED STATE PRISON SYSTEMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday agreed to decide
whether the Constitution permits Congress to limit the authority of
judges to oversee troubled state prison systems.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, concerned that judges were asserting too much control
over states, enacted legislation in 1995 that essentially requires
federal judges to respond within 90 days to a state's request that
they withdraw their oversight of prisons. If the judge fails to
answer within that time, the court's prison supervision ends
automatically.
</P>
<P>
   But inmates at an Indiana prison have successfully challenged
the law as a violation of the Constitution's call for a separation
of powers between federal lawmakers and judges.
</P>
<P>
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in May that Congress
unconstitutionally encroached on judicial oversight of prisons. The
court called the 90-day response deadline ``a direct legislative
suspension of a court order.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has joined the state of Indiana in
urging the high court to reverse the 7th Circuit and rule the
Prison Litigation Reform Act constitutional. Federal and state
lawyers said the law does not violate the Constitution because
judges retain their oversight authority if they respond to the
state in time.
</P>
<P>
   But the prisoners' attorney countered that the law violates the
unencumbered authority of judges to ensure constitutionally safe
conditions at prisons.
</P>
<P>
   The high court is expected to render its decision by July.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, inmates at the Indiana Reformatory sued the state,
claiming conditions at the prison were unconstitutionally
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, a federal judge called for drastic changes in prison
operations, including a cap on population and improved standards
for medical care and food preparation. The judge also ordered a
reduction in the use of physical restraints and improvements in
vocational training and substance-abuse and mental-health programs
at the prison, now named the Pendleton Correctional Facility.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Indiana moved to terminate the court's oversight of the
prison, 15 years after the judge asserted control.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, judicial oversight of a prison system can be
suspended if the judge fails to respond within 30 days to a state's
request that supervision end. The law allows a judge to postpone
that deadline for 60 more days if there is ``good cause'' for the
failure to respond.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Judge S. Hugh Dillin of Indianapolis, who is
overseeing the Indiana prison, ruled the statute an
unconstitutional infringement on the separation of powers. The 7th
Circuit agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In successfully urging the justices to hear Indiana's appeal,
state Attorney General Jeffrey Modisett called the law a valid
attempt to prevent zealous judges from overriding, for years at a
time, the well-established authority of states to regulate their
prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 7th Circuit's decision struck down a vital provision of a
congressional enactment designed to preclude federal courts from
intruding unduly on state prison administration,'' Modisett wrote
in a legal brief to the justices. ``The overriding purpose of the
invalidated statute is to motivate prompt judicial action, and the
7th Circuit's decision foils congressional intent.''
</P>
<P>
   But the inmates' attorney, Kenneth Falk of Indianapolis,
countered that the law unconstitutionally makes a federal judge a
congressional ``clerk'' subject to a statutory order that he or she
stop overseeing prisons at the request of state officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
