<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IT'S TIME FOR A CHANGE BY SPREWELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It wouldn't have to be much more than a pat on the
sleeve of the coach's sports coat. A wink or a nod, while lining up
for the center jump. A pointed finger, after establishing eye
contact.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, forget the finger. Temptation is the last
thing Latrell Sprewell ever needs.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't owe P.J. Carlesimo a modest show of conciliation
Tuesday night when the Golden State Warriors play the Knicks again,
two weeks after Sprewell was a profane spectacle out West. He owes
it to himself because, some day, sooner than he thinks, Sprewell
won't be able to explain away his dearth of accountability, his
lack of compassion, with 30 well-timed points.
</P>
<P>
   This is not about saying ``I'm sorry,'' which Sprewell already
said two years ago after choking Carlesimo during a Warriors
practice. It is about growth, about recognizing another human
being's suffering, primarily because of him. If Sprewell truly
can't see this, I'm not one of those who believes he is getting
away with a thing. I just pity him.
</P>
<P>
   I have known Carlesimo since the mid-1970s, when he coached at
Wagner College, when he made his first splash by taking the small
Staten Island school to the National Invitation Tournament.
Twenty-five years ago, when Bobby Knight was a young coach's role
model, Carlesimo screamed at his players until everyone's ears
ached. I would imagine that three or four years of it had to be
wearing, yet lost in Sprewell's revisionist spin is that he went
for Carlesimo's throat after less than eight weeks. And that his
rationale was fueled, as usual, by his sense of entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted a trade, and it wasn't happening fast enough to suit
him. What has he learned? This year, he wanted a contract and blew
off training camp to underscore that it better come fast enough to
suit him.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Carlesimo would never have been a very good professional
coach. Sprewell sure made certain that, at Golden State, he
wouldn't get the chance. Carlesimo lost his best player that first
season, and then the Warriors traded the dynamic Sprewell to the
Knicks for players old and flawed. While Sprewell has moved on to
get all he wanted and more than he could hope for, Carlesimo comes
to Madison Square Garden Tuesday night with a nine-game losing
streak, without much chance of getting past Christmas still
employed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, last time, he was the one who made a move to shake hands
with Sprewell, who made believe he didn't see Carlesimo coming.
What's wrong with that picture? With all the good that's happened
to him in the past 10 months, Sprewell somehow managed to be out on
the court for more than two hours, and not for five seconds feel a
pang of sympathy for a man whose principal offense was a grating
workplace personality. That is scary, or an indication that the
whole thing was an act.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, I thought the news media's portrayal of Sprewell
bordered on racial typecasting; it was as if all photos and footage
of him without a scowl had suddenly been lost. Keyshawn Johnson of
the Jets is right when he says that race plays a role in the way
people respond to his immature outbursts. Whereas black athletes
are too easily portrayed as angry and disloyal, whites _ including
temperamental coaches like Bill Parcells _ are just being
aggressive and fiery.
</P>
<P>
   At Golden State a couple of weeks ago, Sprewell was none of the
above. He was just a self-aggrandizing boor, playing for a coach
who was terrified to wind up in the same place as Carlesimo.
``Spree handled it badly _ I would have told him it wouldn't have
been selling out to go shake P.J.'s hand,'' Doc Rivers said when he
was in New York coaching Orlando on Thanksgiving weekend, offering
the conscience Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy has conveniently
misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy would never have quietly suffered a similar display
from John Starks. But then, Van Gundy always understood that Starks
had the ability to demonstrate regret, beyond being able to say
``I'm sorry.'' Every response to one of Starks' outbursts, every
ruling, did not become another baseless attack against the martyred
player. That is why Starks could finally understand the Knicks'
thinking in trading him, why bitterness is not obstructing Tuesday
night's Garden homecoming, for which he has promised to kiss the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   If people in the Knicks organization could ever again be honest,
they would admit that Sprewell's continuous defensive lapses, among
other fundamental mistakes, have much to do with his being a player
who is still making up his own rules. Poor Carlesimo. He is still
trying to coach by them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
