<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AS HOLIDAY CUSTOMS MERGE, THEIR SYMBOLS DO AS WELL
</P>
<P>
   The December holidays have long been a source of angst for many
couples who observe different faiths, and the tug is particularly
acute for Christians and Jews whose seasonal celebrations collide
head on with Christmas and Hanukkah. But many families are now
synthesizing two sets of customs. The marketplace is starting to
respond to this pluralistic view by producing what was once taboo:
decorations that merge the symbols of two observances.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Argues Case Against Microsoft
</P>
<P>
   The government argued forcefully in a court filing that a
judge's findings in the Microsoft case point inevitably to the
legal conclusion that the big software maker repeatedly violated
the nation's antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   A PIVOTAL MEETING FOR RITE AID
</P>
<P>
   As the financial position of Rite Aid unraveled this year, the
most intriguing single meeting seems to have taken place on June
30. Rite Aid says that at that meeting, auditors from KPMG failed
to mention that they no longer trusted the company's chief
financial officer or had doubts about the quality of the company's
financial controls. KPMG, which resigned in November, says that it
did discuss both points.
</P>
<P>
   DOW FALLS; NASDAQ POSTS A RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended mixed as the Nasdaq composite index rose to another
record. The Dow Jones industrial average finished with a loss of
61.17 points, to 11,225.01. The Nasdaq ended up 25.38 points, to
3,546.01. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 9.97 points,
to 1,423.33.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T ANNOUNCES SWEEPING CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T announced a change in its financial structure, a new
wireless communications initiative, sweeping changes in its
executive ranks and a deal to open its cable systems to other
Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic and Vodafone AirTouch won conditional approval to
combine United States wireless operations but will have to get rid
of billions of dollars worth of systems.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL CROSSING HIRES EXECUTIVE
</P>
<P>
   Leo J. Hindery Jr., a former executive of Tele-Communications
Inc. who essentially kept his job as the head of AT&AMP;T's new cable
unit after TCI was acquired by AT&AMP;T, was named chairman of a Global
Crossing unit that maintains Web sites for corporate customers. He
said Global Crossing intended to announce plans early next year to
spin off the Web unit that he will run as a separately traded
company.
</P>
<P>
   NURSE SAID TO CONFESS TO SAFRA FIRE
</P>
<P>
   A nurse who had worked for the last five months for Edmond
Safra, the founder of the Republic National Bank of New York, has
admitted to setting the fire that killed the banker, a prosecutor
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1137 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-N     12-06 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DEPICTS MICROSOFT'S ACTIONS AS PART OF AN ILLEGAL PATTERN 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government argued forcefully Monday that the court's
findings in the Microsoft case point inevitably to the legal
conclusion that the big software maker repeatedly violated the
nation's antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   In a 70-page court filing, the justice department and the 19
states suing the Microsoft Corp. enumerated more than a dozen acts
by the company to defend its monopoly in the personal computer
operating systems and to try to extend its dominance into the
market for Internet software.
</P>
<P>
   But the court filing also makes the more ambitious assertion
that the sum of Microsoft's acts should add up to an even greater
legal liability than the individual transgressions one by one.
After noting that ``each of these actions is itself sufficient'' to
be a violation, the government added that ``each exacerbated the
effects of the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust experts found the legal bundling of Microsoft's
purported acts of anticompetitive behavior particularly intriguing
_ especially since the legal brief was filed on the same day that
the two sides gathered in Chicago for a second round of settlement
talks with Richard A. Posner, a federal appellate judge serving as
a mediator.
</P>
<P>
   ``By making this pattern of practices argument, the government
is saying that Microsoft is a fundamentally dangerous company and
strongly suggesting that severe sanctions are required,'' said
William Kovacic, a professor at the George Washington University
law school.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions against Microsoft can be imposed by the court, if the
company is found to have violated the law, or by agreement in an
out-of-court settlement. The remedies under consideration by the
justice department and states have ranged broadly from mild ones
like prohibiting Microsoft from imposing certain contract
restrictions to harsh ones like breaking the company up or forcing
it to license its Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side will discuss details of the settlement talks.
</P>
<P>
   The legal brief filed on Monday by the government and states is
their view of what legal conclusions are justified by Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson's findings of fact, which he issued on Nov. 5.
Jackson gave the government a lot to work with in his findings,
saying that Microsoft was a monopoly whose tactics stifled
competition and innovation. The company will get its chance to
respond on Jan. 17, followed by additional briefs from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The justice department and the states cited four categories of
legal claims, but the broadest focused on the many steps Microsoft
took to defend its monopoly. Indeed, many of the major business
decisions Microsoft made during 1995 to 1998 amounted to illegal
acts to protect its monopoly in personal computer operating
systems, according to the government.
</P>
<P>
   In the monopoly protection section of its brief, the government
enumerates 14 anticompetitive acts by Microsoft, especially citing
its contracts and meetings with everyone from Windows-based PC
makers to Apple to Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, such claims became easier for the government to make
because Judge Jackson found Microsoft last month to be a monopoly.
Being a monopoly is not illegal, but the legal standard of
corporate behavior for a monopolist is more circumscribed than for
other companies.
</P>
<P>
   A monopolist, for example, is not supposed to enter into
contracts that ``unreasonably disadvantage a competitor'' _ with
the courts and legal precedent as the guide to just what conduct
crosses that line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you have a monopoly finding, which you do here, the legal
threshold for a violation becomes much easier for the government to
achieve,'' said Richard M. Steuer, a partner in the antitrust
practice at Kaye Scholer Fierman Hays &AMP; Handler, a New York law
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust experts also said the government had deftly tried to
package certain allegations for which the legal standard is more
difficult _ like predatory pricing _ in its monopoly defense claim.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft chose to meld its Internet browser with its Windows
operating system and give the browser away. But recent legal cases
have tended not to find price cutting to be illegal unless it can
be shown that the company plans to increase prices later, after a
rival has been driven from the market.
</P>
<P>
   In its brief, the government repeatedly described Microsoft's
free distribution of browsing software as a ``predatory'' tactic to
harm its main rival in that market, the Netscape Communications
Corp. But Microsoft's predatory campaign, ``for its anticompetitive
effect,'' did not require ``an ability to raise the price of
Internet Explorer in the future,'' the government asserted. ``It
achieved its anticompetitive effect simply by perpetuating
Microsoft's monopoly in the market for another product, the Windows
operating system.''
</P>
<P>
   Deft legal argument, antitrust experts say, but such reasoning
will certainly be challenged when Microsoft files its own suggested
conclusions of law next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
