<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1138 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-MIRANDA-HNS &LR;      12-06 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-MIRANDA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT TO WEIGH IF '68 STATUTE STAYS SILENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court will decide whether an obscure
federal law blunts its 33-year-old admonition that police warn
suspects of their right to remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the case is the continued vitality of the court's
``Miranda warning,'' which has become a staple of law enforcement
agencies and has been made familiar by television crime dramas. The
justices, in a 1966 decision, called for police to tell those they
arrest of the right to remain silent and that anything they say can
and will be used in a court of law.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the justices' ruling, lower courts have often
refused to admit into evidence incriminating statements by criminal
defendants because they were not advised of their constitutional
right not to talk to police. But that general refusal could change
if the justices decide that a little-known 1968 law supersedes the
Miranda warning.
</P>
<P>
   That statute, passed by a law-and-order Congress, was meant to
obviate the need for the warning and allow courts to hear
incriminating statements so long as the defendant spoke voluntarily
and with knowledge of their Fifth Amendment right to remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and other opponents of the law argue
that, if upheld, the statute would lead to the admission of
confessions and other incriminating statements from defendants who
did not fully understand their right not to speak to police.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to render their decision in the case,
Dickerson vs. United States, by July.
</P>
<P>
   Bank-robbery suspect Charles Dickerson says police declined to
give him a Miranda warning before he told them that he was driving
the getaway car. Dickerson said fellow suspect, Jimmy Rochester,
gave him a gun, which he put in his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Police then searched Dickerson's home, where they found the gun
and money allegedly taken from the First Virginia Bank in
Alexandria, Va. Dickerson was then charged with bank robbery,
conspiracy and using a firearm during the January 1997 theft.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson, through his attorney, sought to have his statements
to the police prohibited from being used at trial, saying he had
not been told of his right to remain silent. The District Court for
Eastern Virginia agreed, ruling that the statements could not be
used against Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   But the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed the decision
in February, citing the federal law and saying that Dickerson knew
his rights and made his statements to the police voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   The 4th Circuit added that the Miranda warning was not required
under the Constitution but was merely an example the justices gave
of a warning that would pass constitutional muster.
</P>
<P>
   The 4th Circuit's reliance on the law was surprising because
U.S. prosecutors had not referred to the statute in urging the
court to allow the gun and money to be used as evidence against
Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, no Justice Department, from President Lyndon Johnson to
President Clinton, had relied on the federal statute to get a court
to accept into evidence a defendant's incriminating statement given
without a warning. Federal prosecutors have consistently held that
the Miranda warning is a constitutional requirement from which
police and courts are not permitted to deviate.
</P>
<P>
   Even Clinton's Justice Department, although urging the justices
to allow Dickerson's prosecution to proceed, is pressing the high
court to state clearly that the Constitution requires police to
provide Miranda warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Such a ruling in Miranda's favor would render the federal
statute unconstitutional because Congress has no authority to pass
laws that contradict or relax constitutional mandates.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, in its legal brief to the justices, said
that requiring police to warn people of their rights is a
constitutional requirement that has the unfortunate result of
``reliable evidence'' sometimes being suppressed. But such
suppression is an acceptable cost for ensuring that defendants
receive a fair trial, the department said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overruling Miranda _ at this juncture, more than three decades
after it was announced and after law enforcement has accommodated
to its basic requirements _ would ... tend to undermine public
confidence in the fairness of (the criminal justice) system,'' U.S.
Solicitor General Seth Waxman wrote on behalf of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law enforcement system depends on citizen cooperation and
support in myriad ways,'' he said. ``Steps that may damage that
confidence should not be taken lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, despite its call for upholding Miranda,
said prosecutors should still be able to use as evidence at trial
the gun and money they found in Dickerson's apartment. The police
officers had a valid warrant to search for these items, based on
their reasonable suspicion that Dickerson was involved in the bank
robbery, the department argued.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson's attorney, James Hundley of Fairfax, Va., countered
that neither the statements nor physical evidence may be admitted.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution, as interpreted by the high court, requires
that the Miranda warning be given to all arrestees, Hundley argued.
The police officers' failure to warn Dickerson rendered his
statements regarding the gun inadmissible, and the police were
barred from relying on those comments in searching his apartment,
the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley also disputed the 4th Circuit's conclusion that the
Supreme Court intended Miranda to be only an example of a warning
that police must give arrestees, rather than a constitutional
mandate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, the high court ruled in Miranda vs. Arizona that police
have a duty to ensure that the people they arrest know they have
the constitutional right not to say anything to law enforcement.
The justices, in that decision, provided guidance for what has
become widely known as the Miranda warning: ``You have the right to
remain silent. If you choose to waive this right, anything you say
can and will be used against you in a court of law.''
</P>
<P>
   The warning quickly became a fixture among law enforcement
agencies and in the media. Failure by police to provide a warning
has compelled courts to refuse to admit incriminating statements
into evidence, ruling that the testimonials were given by people
who thought they had no choice but to talk to law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, in the wake of the Miranda decision, passed the
controversial statute. The law allows courts to accept into
evidence ``voluntary'' statements made by arrestees, even if no
warning was given, provided they knew of their right to remain
silent.
</P>
<P>
   Houston criminal defense lawyer Edward Mallett said he hopes the
Supreme Court rules that the Miranda warning is constitutionally
required.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lived with Miranda for a generation now,'' said Mallett,
president-elect of the National Association of Criminal Defense
Lawyers. ``The American people believe that Miranda not only is
consistent with the Constitution but is a good rule.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
