<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1140 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CHINA-CHINA_SFCHRON &LR;      12-06 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CHINA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Tech Industry Benefits From WTO Problems  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Technology industry leaders put on a brave face yesterday in
analyzing the outcome of the Seattle summit of the World Trade
Organization.
<P>
   But the bottom line was that they, as with just about everybody
except the guys in ski masks who smashed up shop windows, came away
from the meeting with precious little to show for their months of
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been nice to reach agreement last week in
Seattle,'' said Tim Bennett, senior vice president of the American
Electronics Association, which represents about 3,000 high-tech
heavyweights. ``But it's certainly not the end of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bennett believes the 11th-hour eleventh-hour &LR;   &LR; collapse
of WTO negotiations worked in the tech industry's favor.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was beginning to look on Friday as though many of the
key issues on the industry's agenda were going to be left out of
the guiding declaration issued by the WTO's negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very concerned,'' Bennett said. ``Now we've got
another bite at the apple.''
</P>
<P>
   The WTO talks are slated to resume in coming months in Geneva. A
so-called ministerial declaration will emerge from those
discussions, outlining the main points to be addressed in
subsequent trade meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The tech industry hopes this declaration will prominently
feature a continued moratorium on e-commerce taxation. Industry
leaders also hope to expand the range of high-tech products covered
by a separate treaty on tariffs, and to accelerate the speed with
which many of these tariffs are reduced.
</P>
<P>
   The e-commerce tax question is now up in the air. Some say that
the past moratorium expired with the collapse of the Seattle talks
and that any nation is now free to implement its own  &LR; taxes on
electronic retailing.
</P>
<P>
   Others insist that the moratorium remains in effect because,
well, nobody has yet to say otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is that it's very hard to tax e-commerce, so we're not
going to see governments popping up with tax plans in the next 24
hours,'' said Michael Maibach, vice president of government affairs
for Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, most tech-industry insiders say WTO haggling will
take a back seat to the political slugfest expected to break out on
Capitol Hill over granting China permanent ``normal trade
relations'' status _ a precondition for China becoming a WTO
member.
</P>
<P>
   ``China remains the most important issue for us,'' said Dave
McCurdy, president of the Electronic Industries Alliance, a
confederation of tech and telecom trade groups. ``By far.''
</P>
<P>
   There was little official talk of China in Seattle because last
month's landmark trade accord between Washington and Beijing came
too late for the WTO to take up the matter of China joining the
135-member global trade body.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing first must cut separate deals with the European Union,
Canada and about 20 other nations. And each of these deals then
must be ratified by the concerned countries before the WTO can
weigh in on China's membership.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the United States, the AFL-CIO and other labor
groups, including the California Labor Federation, have said they
will fight hard to prevent China from receiving permanent
most-favored trade status. They cite Beijing's dubious track record
for human rights as well as the threat of increased competition
from low-paid Chinese workers.
</P>
<P>
   At a seminar in San Francisco yesterday on investing in China,
Jiang Bo, director of U.S. affairs for Beijing's Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, stressed that things are
changing quickly on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese people don't just want to make shoes and provide
toys,'' he said. ``We want to get into high technology.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, he said Beijing will continue providing tax breaks and
other incentives to attract overseas tech and telecom companies.
But Jiang emphasized that such companies must be prepared to
compete aggressively for Chinese customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, it was very easy to do business in China
because there was no competition,'' he observed. ``Now, American
companies and European companies and other companies are all there.
You must now bring your best products to China. Just investing is
not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
