r f BC-ATT-ATT_SFCHRON &LR;      12-06 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-ATT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 AT&AMP;T Set to Open Its Cables  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
AT&AMP;T yesterday confirmed that it will let other companies market
high-speed Internet access over its cable-video network, but its
vaguely worded statement left critics demanding a clearer
commitment and faster transition to open competition.
<P>
   The communications giant has fought for more than a year to
retain exclusive rights to sell the speedy service to consumers.
But yesterday it said it is prepared to negotiate agreements with
multiple Internet service providers that would let them market
similar services under their own brands. AT&AMP;T pledged not to impose
surcharges that would price competitors out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, however, would not take effect until 2002. Until then,
Internet access over the AT&AMP;T network, the nation's largest, will
be available only through ExciteAtHome, a Redwood City company that
is 58-percent owned by AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do they say it's the right thing to do and then ask
everybody to wait two years?'' asked Greg Simon, co-director of the
openNET cq &LR;  Coalition, a year-old organization that represents more
than 900 ISPs and technology companies, including America Online,
MCI, GTE, US West and Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's apparent change of policy came in a letter to William
Kennard, chairman of the Federal Communications Commission, signed
by representatives of AT&AMP;T and MindSpring, a large ISP based in
Atlanta. The move came at Kennard's behest, and he applauded it as
``a good first step.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for AOL, by far the nation's largest ISP, also
called yesterday's letter ``a positive first step,'' but noted that
``the devil is in the details.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released from its Washington, D.C., headquarters,
the openNET Coalition pointed out some of the issues the AT&AMP;T
declaration left unresolved, such as whether the company would
treat all ISPs equally and whether it would impose restrictions on
the kinds of services and content ISPs could deliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without persuasive answers to these questions, this is just a
speech, not a change of policy,'' said Rich Bond, the trade
organization's other co-director.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Nothhaft, CEO of Concentric Networks, a San Jose ISP,
dismissed the AT&AMP;T letter as ``a clever PR move to blunt the
criticism they've been getting from the industry, the public and
even some parts of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a step in the right direction, but a lot more needs
to be done,'' he added. ``The FCC should step in to ensure a level
playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   Even MindSpring, which co-signed the AT&AMP;T letter, asked the FCC
to step in. In a separate letter to the FCC's Kennard, it said,
``only clear and unambiguous federal policy can make the promise of
this first step real, enforceable and timely.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T became the largest cable provider in the nation and in the
Bay Area when it acquired the former Tele-Communications Inc. last
year. By itself, AT&AMP;T controls less than 25 percent of the cable
market. Yesterday's announcements shed no light on whether the 22
other cable companies that also provide Internet services through
ExciteAtHome, such as Comcast and Cox Communications, will follow
AT&AMP;T's lead.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these companies have exclusive contracts with
ExciteAtHome that remain in effect until as late as 2006, according
to David Pine, vice president and general counsel of ExciteAtHome.
</P>
<P>
   That company yesterday announced signing its millionth
one-millionth  &LR; subscriber.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to providing Web content specially tailored to user
with high-speed access, ExciteAtHome owns and manages the equipment
linking the cable networks to the Internet, including 21 regional
data centers and servers at cable company offices.
</P>
<P>
   How much of this infrastructure competitors would have to
duplicate is ``a great question,'' Pine said, acknowledging that
``the details have not been fleshed out.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that having each ISP provide its own
equipment would be ``hopelessly complex.'' In the end, he
predicted, competing ISPs will probably pay a fee to his company to
use its infrastructure, as well as one to AT&AMP;T and other cable
providers for the right to transmit data over ``the last mile,''
the cables that go to homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
