<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SOC-WORLD-CUP-2TAKES-     12-06 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-CUP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV-RIGHTS TALKS FOR 2002 WORLD CUP RAISE ETHICS ISSUES IN JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ When Shinji Ono, a star Japanese midfielder, pulls the
first sheet from a drum on Tuesday to kick off the preliminary draw
for soccer's World Cup in 2002, it will be a crowning moment for
Japan's involvement in international sports.
</P>
<P>
   The country has played host to the Olympics three times, and the
fanfare surrounding the draw is intended to set the stage in
glittering fashion for Japan's joint hosting, together with South
Korea, of what is often called the world's most popular sporting
event.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of the painstaking efforts to insure that the event
goes off without a hitch, there is one important element that even
at this relatively late date has not been settled: the rights for
the television broadcast of the games here in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual recriminations have been flying among the Japanese
broadcast companies seeking to buy rights to the games. From their
descriptions of the way the negotiations have been handled, as well
as from documents obtained by The New York Times, a picture emerges
of possible conflicts of interest, noncompetitive deal-making and
deep suspicions of betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   The suspicions and accusations hardly form the face that FIFA,
soccer's international governing body, would have chosen for its
quadrennial showcase.
</P>
<P>
   But taken together, the accounts of participants in the struggle
over television rights in the host country seem to wed the murky
and sometimes secretive relationships that marked past Olympic
bidding scandals with the kinds of collusive commercial practices
that Japan has often been accused of by its trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   At its essence, the breakdown in talks over television rights
here is a dispute over price. Japanese broadcast officials say they
were shocked by initial proposals from ISL Worldwide, the
international sports marketing company that bought global
television rights for the World Cup from FIFA, for 54 billion yen,
or more than $500 million. The price was later reduced to about
$250 million, some broadcast executives say, which would still
represent about a fortyfold increase over the price that Japan's
national public broadcaster, NHK, paid for the rights to broadcast
the 1998 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Some Japanese network executives now say in private that they
would like to negotiate on their own for the rights to the 2002
World Cup, but Japan's major broadcasters responded to ISL's
opening bid by forging a united front last April. Known officially
as the Japan Consortium, the broadcasting group includes the public
broadcasting network, the country's five private television
networks and nearly 200 local stations.
</P>
<P>
   A Japanese television executive said the consortium had ``grown
out of friendships over a long period.'' But the articles of
association, which were obtained by The New York Times, often read
more like an underworld pact than a conventional commercial
agreement. Members pledge in the document to restrict broadcasting
rights to consortium partners, to jointly set acquisition fees for
the games, to relinquish the right to make individual bids for
television rights and to adhere to strict confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, any member that wants to withdraw from the consortium,
the document says, ``must report its intention to the executive
body, and must have its consent.''
</P>
<P>
   According to consortium members, ISL met once with the group,
noticed that none of its members would offer competing bids or even
speak out of turn, decided that the consortium was essentially a
cartel and refused to negotiate any further.
</P>
<P>
   ISL declined repeated requests for comment on the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But Seiji Urushido, an executive of Japan's BS Nippon Co., a TV
network, and an officer of the consortium, defended its tactics.
``I know that this is unthinkable in the States,'' he said. ``Three
networks there competed fiercely for the rights to the Olympic
Games. As a result, NBC paid an exorbitant fee, which led to
soaring broadcast rights fees all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Economically,'' he added, ``Japan doesn't have the luxury to
pay these kinds of prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Accounts of what happened next vary widely according to the
participants, but in all versions, Dentsu, the powerful Japanese
advertising agency that has been described as the world's largest,
soon began to play the role of a go-between among Japan's
broadcasters and ISL.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Dentsu presented itself in the Japanese news media
as the agent of the Japan Consortium, and Dentsu officials say that
they succeeded in talking down the asking price for TV rights to
the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But many Japanese television executives say that Dentsu's
participation in the negotiations represents a remarkable conflict
of interest. Dentsu owns a 10 percent equity stake in ISL, Dentsu
officials acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Dentsu is said to control one-third of all the advertising on
Japanese television and to enjoy a virtual monopoly on the sale of
ads during prime time, according to ``The Enigma of Japanese
Power'' (Vintage Books), by the Dutch journalist Karel van
Wolferen, a highly regarded recent exploration of contemporary
Japanese society.
</P>
<P>
   The clout that Dentsu exercises over commercial television in
Japan ``is quite unlike any kind of social control through the mass
media anywhere in the world,'' van Wolferen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ISL became concerned enough about the conflict to produce a news
release in September stating that ``in the specific case of the
sale of the television rights of the FIFA World Cup, Dentsu is not
the official representative of ISL.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, as questions about the openness and perhaps even
the legality of the bidding process have been raised, the Japan
Consortium has sought to distance itself from Dentsu. In an
interview, Katsuji Ebisawa, the president of the national public
network, NHK, denied that Dentsu had been officially authorized to
negotiate on behalf of Japan's broadcasting consortium.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   None of this has discouraged Dentsu in its attempts to remain a
central player in the sale of the broadcasting rights, however.
Haruyuki Takahashi, a senior Dentsu executive who has been involved
in the negotiations, said in an interview last week that his
company would continue trying to restart the stalled negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to support both sides, because Dentsu is doing
business with both sides _ with the consortium and with ISL,''
Takahashi said. ``It seems very complicated, because Dentsu has two
faces.''
</P>
<P>
   While these relationships appear to present a conflict of
interest, a Japanese legal expert said that the country's laws on
such conflicts are less stringent than those in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether any laws have been broken depends on a number of
details: whether Dentsu was earning a fee for its work, whether
Dentsu has disclosed its role to both sides in negotiation and
whether it has committed any fraudulent act,'' said the lawyer, who
spoke only on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, things have become even more complicated.
Although Dentsu has strongly denied it, many Japanese broadcasting
executives say they are afraid that Dentsu has concluded a secret
deal for the purchase of broadcasting rights for the World Cup
games _ apparently without informing the Japanese broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   Some broadcast executives now say that the bidding process
should be thrown open and conducted according to international
standards of competition and fairness. Few will say so publicly,
though, because they are sworn to silence by their consortium
agreement and fear retribution from Dentsu and the rest of the
industry if they go it alone.
</P>
<P>
   The president of FIFA, Joseph S. Blatter, said in an interview
in Tokyo on Saturday that Japan was the only region of the world in
which the soccer organization still faced broadcasters who form
cartel-like associations, which he called unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The price of soccer broadcasts has increased dramatically but
reasonably, he contended, because of an explosion of interest in
the sport and the proliferation of television stations and cable
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Told that Dentsu had represented itself as a negotiator on
behalf of Japanese television broadcasters, Blatter said, ``There
is something wrong there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is most unusual, and not acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Urushido, the BS Nippon executive who is a member of the
consortium, scoffed at the notion that excessive coercion was at
work. ``The normal definition of a cartel is to keep a price high
and to inflict damage on the consumer,'' Urushido said. ``What we
are doing has the opposite purpose, so I don't think it is right to
call us a cartel. It would be misleading to focus on the punitive
elements here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
