<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1145 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     12-06 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS  &HT;     Nasdaq-100 Trust a Wise Choice 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
I am advising my cousin on his investment portfolio and would like
some help. He plans to retire in 10 years, and much of his
retirement income will come from defined-benefit pension plans. I
have urged him to jazz up his portfolio by investing a small amount
of money in the Nasdaq 100 index and to hold on forever. But what
is the best way to do this while minimizing taxes? We are looking
at two investment choices: the Rydex OTC mutual fund and the
Nasdaq-100 Trust.
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Rydex OTC, a mutual fund managed by Padco Advisors Inc., and the
Nasdaq-100 Trust, which trades as a stock on the American Stock
Exchange (symbol: QQQ), should produce virtually identical
investment performances, because both track the Nasdaq 100 index.
</P>
<P>
   The index is composed of 100 of the largest over-the-counter
stocks, with about 70 percent of its value in high technology. Tech
stocks have been white-hot lately, and the index carved out a
fantastic 62 percent gain through the first 11 months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   But notwithstanding its strong upward bias, the Nasdaq 100 has
its bad days. Single-day drops of 2 percent to 4 percent are all
too common. Make sure your cousin can live with that kind of
volatility before he takes the plunge. Also, remind him that the
Nasdaq 100's upward march could end someday _ but don't ask me
when.
</P>
<P>
   Rydex OTC is a no-load fund _ meaning that you can buy shares in
it without paying a sales commission. However, according to
Morningstar Inc., which provides information on financial services,
the Rydex fund charges its shareholders management fees and
expenses equal to 1.15 percent of their assets per year. That is on
the high side for index funds, which are passively managed.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq-100 Trust charges a substantially smaller management
fee _ less than 0.2 percent of assets per year. However, you have
to pay a brokerage commission to buy the stock. If you use a
discount broker who charges $10 per trade, the commission will
amount to 1 percent on a $1,000 purchase, or 0.1 percent on a
$10,000 purchase.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, the lower management fee, year after year, seems to
give the Nasdaq-100 Trust an edge over the mutual fund, even though
you must pay that modest, one-time commission to buy the trust
shares.
</P>
<P>
   As for taxes, here, too, the Nasdaq-100 Trust has an edge. If
vast numbers of Rydex OTC shareholders were to sell back their
shares, the mutual fund might be forced to liquidate some of its
holdings to meet the demand for cash. This could happen, for
example, after a market crash or during a prolonged market
downturn.
</P>
<P>
   If it did happen, the fund would be required to distribute
capital gains generated by these sales to the remaining
shareholders. Those shareholders would then have to pay
capital-gains taxes on the money they receive.
</P>
<P>
   This won't happen with the Nasdaq-100 Trust, because it is
structured like a closed-end fund. When shareholders want to bail
out, they simply sell their stock to other investors through the
Amex, rather than redeeming them through the trust itself. Even if
every current shareholder sold at the same time, there would be no
liquidation of assets by the trust.
</P>
<P>
   So, if your cousin were to ``hold on forever,'' he wouldn't pay
taxes on any gains in the value of his Nasdaq-100 Trust holdings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Oracle Spin-Off
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read an article about a new company tied to Oracle Corp.,
called Network Computing, which plans to sell a network computer
for $199. I would like to learn more about the company but can't
find any further information. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: You must be referring to a former Oracle subsidiary called
Network Computer, which was spun off last July as a separate,
publicly held company with a new name _ Liberate Technologies. The
name change explains why you are finding it tough to do the
research.
</P>
<P>
   Liberate is based in San Carlos, and its stock (Nasdaq symbol:
LBRT) recently was trading around $170 per share _ more than 10
times the initial public offering price! It boasts a total market
value of more than $7 billion. All this despite the fact that the
company has never turned a profit. It lost more than $10 million in
the latest quarter on piddling revenues of slightly more than $5
million.
</P>
<P>
   One crucial fact you should know: The company has shifted away
from network computers, which are not turning out to be the hot
product envisioned by Oracle chief executive Larry Ellison. Its new
emphasis is Internet-access appliances. It produces software for
telephones, TV set-top boxes, game consoles and the like.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still interested, you can research Liberate as you
would any other publicly held company. For a start, take a look at
its Web site: www.liberate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Window on a Portfolio
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a free Web site where I can enter a list of my
mutual funds and the portfolio will be analyzed by sector and/or
market capitalization?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   The best I know of is the ``Portfolio Monitor'' provided by
Morningstar (www.morningstar.com). Morningstar specializes in the
analysis of mutual funds, but also invites you to enter information
about stocks you own.
</P>
<P>
   You can then analyze your portfolio in various useful ways,
including by asset class (U.S. stocks, foreign stocks, bonds,
cash), price-earnings ratio, ratio of price to book value, and _
yes _ sector (also known as industry) and market cap.
</P>
<P>
   All this analysis is provided free, although you have to
register on the Web site, disclosing your name, ZIP code and e-mail
address. Morningstar also offers a premium portfolio service,
allowing you to analyze more deeply. But that will cost you $9.95
per month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
