 _ SF CHRON  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Tuesday, December 7, on the New York
Times wire. For questions, please call Georgie Dennison at
415-777-6055 or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business
stories running in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; DOW36000 &LR;  _ Go to your local bookstore and you will see it
prominently displayed: ``Dow 36,000,'' a recently published book
with a flashy gold, black and white cover. With the Dow Jones
industrial average trading around 11,000, you have to feel
energized by that title if you own stocks. But if you look around a
bit more, you will find another new book (with a still-flashier
green, purple, black and white cover) that bears an even more
exhilarating title _ ``Dow 100,000: Fact or Fiction.'' Talk about
one-upmanship! This is 64,000-upmanship! If you are a wild-eyed
optimist, you might be tempted to buy the Dow 100,000 book and
spurn the Dow 36,000 book.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its electrifying title, ``Dow 100,000'' is an
unsurprising, run-of-the-mill investment treatise. The ``Dow
36,000'' book is by far the more radical _ and fascinating _
because its authors _ James K. Glassman and Kevin A. Hassett _
insist that 36,000 is where the blue-chip indicator should be now.
That's right: They think it has the potential to more than triple
overnight. By Arthur M. Louis
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; MONEYBAG &LR;  _ Why Nasdaq-100 trust is a wise choice. By Arthur M.
Louis
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; ATT  &LR; _ AT&AMP;T yesterday confirmed that it will let other companies
market high-speed Internet access over its cable-video network, but
its vaguely worded statement left critics demanding a clearer
commitment and faster transition to open competition. By Henry Norr
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; AVIGEN  &LR; _ A biotech firm in Alameda gave the embattled field of
gene therapy a boost yesterday, by reporting that it had restored
partial blood clotting ability in three hemophiliacs, by injecting
them with an experimental drug containing the short length of DNA
they were born without. Although Avigen Inc. said it was far too
early to proclaim its treatment a cure, the results it reported at
a scientific meeting in New Orleans were hailed as the first
success in more than 10 years and 300 experiments. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; CHINA  &LR; _ Technology industry leaders put on a brave face yesterday
in analyzing the outcome of the Seattle summit of the World Trade
Organization. But the bottom line was that they, as with just about
everybody except the guys in ski masks who smashed up shop windows,
came away from the meeting with precious little to show for their
months of preparation. By David Lazarus
</P>
