<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1148 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DOW36000-DOW36000_SFC     12-06 1493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW36000-DOW36000 </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Two New Books See Remarkable Stock Market Growth  
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Go to your local bookstore and you will see it prominently
displayed: ``Dow 36,000,'' a recently published book with a flashy
gold, black and white cover.
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Dow Jones industrial average trading around 11,000, you
have to feel energized by that title if you own stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But if you look around a bit more, you will find another new
book (with a still-flashier green, purple, black and white cover)
that bears an even more exhilarating title _ ``Dow 100,000: Fact or
Fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about one-upmanship! This is 64,000-upmanship!
</P>
<P>
   If you are a wild-eyed optimist, you might be tempted to buy the
Dow 100,000 book and spurn the Dow 36,000 book.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its electrifying title, ``Dow 100,000'' is an
unsurprising, run-of-the-mill investment treatise.
</P>
<P>
   The author, Charles W. Kadlec, an investment strategist with
J.&AMP;W. Seligman &AMP; Co., predicts that the Dow will reach 100,000 in
21 years if certain political, social and economic conditions
remain favorable.
</P>
<P>
   That would amount to an average annual gain of about 11 percent
_ not bad by historical standards, but less impressive than the
previous 21-year period _ 1978 to the present _ when the Dow rose
by an average of 13 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   It will reach the 100,000 mark, Kadlec calculates, if tax rates
remain reasonable, currencies remain stable, &LR;  and trade is
permitted to flow freely across international boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow will be less vibrant if taxes shoot up, the world
suffers a currency crisis or the United States imposes severe trade
restrictions on economically important adversaries such as China.
</P>
<P>
   Kadlec also informs us that you can kiss Dow 100,000 goodbye if
the United States gets bogged down in a war or suffers germ-warfare
attacks from terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Duh.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Dow 36,000'' book is by far the more radical _ and
fascinating _ because its authors _ James K. Glassman and Kevin A.
Hassett _ insist that 36,000 is where the blue-chip indicator
should be now. That's right: They think it has the potential to
more than triple overnight.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound like headline-grabbing sensationalism, but the
scholarly and punctilious authors make a persuasive case. The
reasoning and some of the mathematics can be tough to follow at
times, but, by and large, the book is highly readable and witty.
</P>
<P>
   Glassman and Hassett are colleagues at the American Enterprise
Institute, a think tank in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Glassman has also held numerous, high-visibility jobs in
publishing and writes a financial column for Reader's Digest.
</P>
<P>
   The basic premise of the book is that investors historically
have valued stocks too low because they were afraid of them.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the pall cast by the 1929 crash; or the long,
grinding 1973-74 bear market; or the 1987 crash _ or all of the &LR; 
above  &LR; these and more. In any case, investors have perennially
considered stocks more risky than other investments _ in
particular, bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Glassman and Hassett concede that stocks may be risky over short
periods, but they stridently insist that, in the long run, stocks
are no more risky than any other investments _ even U.S.
Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   If you hold on long enough to a diversified portfolio, they
observe, stocks will be ``steady winners through thick and thin.''
They cite research going back to 1802 indicating that there never
has been a period as long as 17 years when stocks have failed to
rise in value, even after adjusting for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there have been numerous 17-year periods when bonds
have produced negative returns.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you had invested $10,000 in the market averages the day
before the October 1929 crash, your holdings _ including
reinvestment of dividends _ would have grown to $93,000 by 1960,
$999,000 by 1985 and $8.4 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   In view of that record, the authors say, investors should have
no qualms about buying stocks _ and paying a lot more for them than
they do now. Yet the fear of stocks persists, causing their prices
to remain unwarrantedly low.
</P>
<P>
   To bring stock returns in line with other investments, the
authors note, the price-earnings (PE) ratios of stocks would have
to rise sharply. The authors figure that, based on their estimates
of future earnings, dividend growth, inflation and interest rates,
an average PE ratio of roughly 100 would be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dow now selling at a PE of around 24, it seems clear
that not all investors agree with the Glassman-Hassett appraisal.
</P>
<P>
   But the authors point out that the average PE for the Dow over
many decades was only 15, so investors by and large must be getting
more savvy.
</P>
<P>
   Some investment professionals have issued dire warnings about
the big jump in PEs, particularly during the raging-bull market of
the past five years, describing it as a mania, &LR;  or a speculative
bubble.
</P>
<P>
   Glassman and Hassett say just the opposite _ that the surge in
PEs is a sign of wisdom, not lunacy. ``The idea that a historic PE
ratio acts as a ceiling on stock prices is nonsense if stocks have
perennially been undervalued,'' they write.
</P>
<P>
   In their view, the higher PEs indicate that today's investors
are wisely recognizing that stocks aren't as risky as yesterday's
investors thought, and that the stocks are worth more than they now
cost.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are paying more for stocks because they have come to
realize that they don't need as great a ``risk premium'' _ that is,
a price discount _ as they demanded in the past. When everyone
catches on, the authors figure, the risk premium will disappear and
the PE will finally reach 100.
</P>
<P>
   Glassman and Hassett have taken a lot of flak from economists,
investment professionals and the press for their theory, which they
first broached last year in an article in the Wall Street Journal.
With the publication of their book, the attacks have accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schlossberg, an economist with Wells Capital Management in
San Francisco, says Glassman and Hassett seem overly optimistic
about the relative safety of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be an extended period when stocks suffer more than
bonds,'' Schlossberg observes. ``There was a period in the late
'60s and early '70s when stocks badly underperformed other types of
assets. There is nothing to say that this sort of thing couldn't go
on for a longer period of time in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   While investors are cheerfully paying higher price-earnings
multiples than before, Schlossberg adds, that doesn't necessarily
signify a sea change for the market in general.
</P>
<P>
   The high PEs are ``centering increasingly on
large-capitalization technology stocks,'' he notes. ``There is a
disparity between those and the rest of the stocks in the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Goldman, investment strategist with A.G. Edwards &AMP; Son in
St. Louis, concedes that annual investment returns from stocks
appear to have moved up more or less permanently, thanks to a
strengthening world economy and a rapidly rising ``global demand
for common stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   He figures that the market averages will rise 14 percent
annually _ dividends included _ in the foreseeable future, well
above their long-term historical rate of 10 or 11 percent. He sees
the Dow reaching 22,000 _ about double its present level _ by 2006.
But, ``I have trouble with 36,000 anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   In a high-powered attack in the December 5 issue of Fortune,
economist Paul Krugman of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
argues that stocks have not been risky in the past precisely
because ``historically, people have been very cautious about buying
stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ``the average return on stocks was high and ...
small changes in expectations about growth or interest rates didn't
move valuations all that much.''
</P>
<P>
   But if investors ``start buying stocks based on the belief that
they are not risky at all, that belief will turn into a
self-defeating prophecy: The new valuations will be very unstable,
swinging widely with the slightest bit of news.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked Glassman and Hassett to respond to Krugman's article.
</P>
<P>
   Glassman notes that their thesis assumes that earnings and
dividends will grow at an annual rate of 2 percent above the
inflation rate and that this assumption is ``extremely cautious and
conservative.'' Going back a half-century, the margin above
inflation has been in the 2.9 percent to 3.3 percent range.
</P>
<P>
   As for volatility, Hassett makes the point that as people come
to ``understand'' stocks better, stock prices might be expected to
become ''more stable than today _ less volatile.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody will know for certain whether Glassman and Hassett are on
the right track until that glorious day when the Dow does indeed
finally surpass 36,000.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
