<HEADLINE>
HOMAGE TO ENDANGERED OBJECTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stumbling upon a box of carbon paper, a person born in the 21st
century might think it mysterious, perhaps an old-fashioned form of
eyeshadow or a kind of tissue in which to wrap navy blue shoes. In
these waning days of the 20th century, we ask readers to submit
nominations of commonplace 20th century items that will be
incomprehensible to future generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These would be similar to a late 20th century resident trying
to figure out the use of a horse collar or chamber pot from the
19th century,'' suggests reader  &UR; Steve Finacom &LR; . Items that have
been updated, like telephones, are disqualified. We're looking for
items that have become obsolete. Send to Leah Garchik, 901 Mission
Street, San Francisco CA 94103 or email to leahg &LR; sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Try to picture the $125 Mercury Messenger Cashmere Cap from
a Mountain View company advertised in The New Yorker: ``This
ribbed, cuffed &AMP; singularly sleek little is the deployment of
everying You like  &LR;  cashmere, 100% cashmere + options: long enough
to fold up 3 Xs + out of control with well, yes, attitude. Rather
left, still quite cashmere right &AMP; everywhere &AMP; between I care/I
really don't care is this cap ...''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. San Francisco jeweler  &UR; Sidney Mobell &LR; 's contribution to a
glittering holiday is a $100,000 working ``Jeweled Art Furby,''
adorned with 63 diamonds, 44 rubies, 39 sapphires and 10 emeralds.
For practicality, the jewels can be snapped off to make a separate
tiara, necklace and earrings. The toy is on display at F.A.O.
Schwarz in New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `ROADSHOW' LESSONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Antiques Roadshow'' fan  &UR; Judy Reimann  &LR; learned everything she
ever needs to know in life _ well, maybe there are a few more
things _ from watching the show. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Never ever clean, polish, repaint or repair your furniture.
What are you, nuts?''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Keep a light coat of oil on it (weapons only).''
</P>
<P>
   _ `Toys are never to be taken out of the box or (God forbid!)
played with by actual children.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CRATCHIT'S FORTUNE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Watching his daughter,  &UR; Jessamy Gloor &LR; , in a Mills College
presentation of ``A Christmas Carol,'' which was written in 1843,
 &UR; Benny Shaboy &LR;  noticed the painting over the Cratchit' &LR; s' fireplace,
Cezanne's ``Boy in a Waistcoat,'' which was painted in 1895.
</P>
<P>
   Shaboy is hoping that &UR; Bob Cratchit &LR; , obviously savvy about the
art market, would have used a Christmas bonus from the reformed
Scrooge to buy a Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Reed Kirk Rahlmann  &LR; is awestruck by lawyer  &UR; Charles &LR; 
 &UR; Ogletree &LR; 's powers of metaphor and imagination. On `` &UR; Larry King &LR; 
Live'' last week, Ogletree likened the government's extreme and
unjustified harassment of his client,  &UR; John Gotti &LR; , to its
treatment of  &UR; Angela Davis &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Richard Branson &LR;  was in Australia last week launching Virgin
Express flights there, and  &UR; Betsy Nolan &LR; , visiting there from San
Francisco, says the Sydney Morning Herald wondered whether it was
smart ``to fly with an airline that doesn't go all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Comedian and director  &UR; Eric Idle &LR;  told Biography magazine that
if he were to choose one stand-up comic for a stay on a desert
island, it would be  &UR; Robin Williams &LR; . ``We always go on holiday
together,'' and said, ``and we go shopping together. If you know
Robin very well, he can actually stop having to be funny.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Firat Yener &LR;  read in Ambassador magazine that one guest at
San Francisco's Triton Hotel stole a duvet, drapes, shower curtain,
soap dishes, pillows and towels.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Annemarie Kiddle  &LR; says that the ``Winnie the Pooh'' menorah a
friend received recently had all the book's characters except
Piglet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Pharmacists in ancient Persia offered the following as an
aphrodisiac for women: nine apple seeds ground together with
whiskers from a man who had been brutally killed, a few grains of
barley retrieved from a grave, the blood of a worm, of a black dog
and of the second finger of the left hand, mixed with semen and
stirred into a glass of wine.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR;   &LR; Homemade Viagra, a recipe from  &UR; Frank Browning  &LR; and
 &UR; Sharon &LR; 
 &UR; Silva &LR; 's ``An Apple Harvest'' (Ten Speed; $17.95).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Men wanting to see their wife-to-be must eat a raw herring _
yes, the whole thing, including bones _ before going to bed.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Advice relating to St. Agnes, the patron saint of virgins,
from ``Heaven Help Us, the Worrier's Guide to the Patron Saints''
by Alice and Clare La Plante (Dell; $9.95).
</P>
</TEXT>
