   BROADWAY-SEASON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A man dressed as a woman who makes phone calls from
the stage and mocks audience members. Cole Porter tunes. Shadow
dancing with choral renditions of Bee Gees tunes. Carol Burnett.
Woody Harrelson. (We repeat: Woody Harrelson.) If you don't think
this season's Broadway shows have something for everyone, then you
either never believe cliches or you haven't read the first five
sentences of this paragraph. By MARK LOWRY. Story will move in
``e'' entertainment category. Accompanied by sidebar
BC-BROADWAY-BEST on 12 of the hottest new shows on Broadway _ and
off. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DICKENS-STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ As a young writer whose star was on the rise in
England, Charles Dickens was upset that his fellow Brits were not
embracing Christmas even though the holiday was back in favor after
Oliver Cromwell (who had banned Christmas) was overthrown by Henry
II. Dickens wrote the prequel to ``A Christmas Carol'' in ``The
Pickwick Papers,'' a series of short stories that earned him
acclaim. In 1843, he reprised his short story _ ``The Story of the
Goblins Who Stole a Sexton'' _ keeping the same theme but changing
the names. One of his protagonists was Ebenezer Scrooge, a
mean-spirited old man who comes to love Christmas. ``A Christmas
Carol'' remains as popular today as it was more than 150 years ago.
By JEFF GUINN. Story will move in ``e'' entertainment categoy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
