<SLUG> BC-COKE-DAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT COKE, SAME NAME BUT DIFFERENT STYLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With COKE-INVESTER) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doug is gone. Long live Doug. And don't confuse the two.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Ivester and Douglas Daft _ the outgoing and incoming
chief executives of Coca-Cola respectively _ share a name and have
worked together closely during their combined 50 years at the
company. Still, their resumes and styles vary greatly, people who
follow the company said on Monday, and those differences indicate
that the public face on one of the best-known brands will change
significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, who abruptly announced his resignation Monday after
more than a year of disappointing results, grew up in Georgia and
spent almost his entire career working out of Coke's Atlanta
headquarters. His background is in finance and while he has a deep
understanding of the company's far-flung businesses, he had spent
relatively few years running any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Daft, who is 56, joined the company in his native Australia in
1969 and next April will become the first person who is not a U.S.
citizen to run Coke. He has worked in Sydney, Australia; Hong Kong;
Tokyo; and Atlanta, running one division after another but never
overseeing any part of the company's North and Latin American
businesses, which account for 55 percent of cases sold.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest difference is in their personalities,
observers said. While Ivester is an intense former accountant,
people who know Daft speak of his sense of humor before almost any
other trait.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have a conversation with him at a dinner party'' about
matters other than ``concentrate shipments in Zimbabwe,'' said
Peter Sealey, a former Coke executive.
</P>
<P>
   In that way, Daft reminds some of Donald Keough, the former Coke
president who was the longtime deputy to Ivester's predecessor, the
late Roberto Goizueta. Both have a knack for making others feel
comfortable even during difficult conversations, a skill that could
serve Daft well as he faces sometimes hostile foreign government
officials and bottling executives.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester never appointed a second-in-command, a sore point among
many analysts and investors. Instead, he kept in frequent contact
with the presidents of Coke divisions. In fact, in an interview
last year, Daft said he would leave Ivester as many as six
voice-mail messages a day while traveling.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts credit Daft with smartly leading a diverse region and
helping to establish Coke as a brand that only McDonald's rivals in
terms of worldwide recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Goldman, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., said that
Daft diversified Coke's business in Japan from virtually all
carbonated soft drinks to one that is almost equally split among
colas, bottled coffee and bottled tea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug has been largely responsible for making sure the company
has been nimble and responsive,'' said John Sicher, the editor of
Beverage Digest, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his tenure has not been free of trouble. Coke has
struggled in India, and its market share in the Middle East and
East Asia is lower than in Europe, Latin America or Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Daft's experience in operations probably
helped him against his two closest competitors for the job, James
Chestnut and Jack Stahl, who like Ivester rose through Coke's
financial group.
</P>
<P>
   A fly fisherman and skier, Daft majored in mathematics at the
University of New England in Australia. He and his wife have two
children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
