<HEADLINE>
HOMAGE TO ENDANGERED OBJECTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stumbling upon a box of carbon paper, a person born in the 21st
century might think it mysterious, perhaps an old-fashioned form of
eyeshadow or a kind of tissue in which to wrap navy blue shoes. In
these waning days of the 20th century, we ask readers to submit
nominations of commonplace 20th century items that will be
incomprehensible to future generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These would be similar to a late 20th century resident trying
to figure out the use of a horse collar or chamber pot from the
19th century,'' suggests reader  &UR; Steve Finacom &LR; . Items that have
been updated, like telephones, are disqualified. We're looking for
items that have become obsolete. Send to Leah Garchik, 901 Mission
Street, San Francisco CA 94103 or email to leahg &LR; sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Try to picture the $125 Mercury Messenger Cashmere Cap from
a Mountain View company advertised in The New Yorker: ``This
ribbed, cuffed &AMP; singularly sleek little is the deployment of
everying You like  &LR;  cashmere, 100% cashmere + options: long enough
to fold up 3 Xs + out of control with well, yes, attitude. Rather
left, still quite cashmere right &AMP; everywhere &AMP; between I care/I
really don't care is this cap ...''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. San Francisco jeweler  &UR; Sidney Mobell &LR; 's contribution to a
glittering holiday is a $100,000 working ``Jeweled Art Furby,''
adorned with 63 diamonds, 44 rubies, 39 sapphires and 10 emeralds.
For practicality, the jewels can be snapped off to make a separate
tiara, necklace and earrings. The toy is on display at F.A.O.
Schwarz in New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
