<HEADER>
A1158 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-TAXES-ART-NYT     12-06 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-TAXES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING NO-NEW-TAXES PLEDGE AN ISSUE, BRADLEY REFUSES TO RULE OUT
INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa _ Saying it would be irresponsible and
dishonest for any presidential candidate to take a ``no new taxes''
pledge, former Sen. Bill Bradley refused Monday to rule out raising
taxes to pay for his plan to make health insurance available to
almost every American.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, who is running for the Democratic presidential
nomination, said he did not think a tax increase would be necessary
to pay for the $65-billion-a-year proposal because of the nation's
robust economy and the projected $1 trillion surplus, which he
contends is large enough to finance the plan over the coming
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, Bradley's lone rival for the Democratic
nomination, has been steadily attacking Bradley's health care plan
as too expensive, and last weekend he began criticized Bradley for
leaving open the option of paying for the plan by raising taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's being dishonest in saying that I want to raise taxes,''
Bradley said Monday in an interview. ``I haven't proposed raising
new taxes. I'm not proposing raising taxes.'' But, he added,
``Nobody can predict the future of a trillion dollar economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also defied Gore to take a no-new-taxes pledge himself,
suggesting that it would be totally disingenuousness for him to do
so. To bolster his point, he noted that Bill Clinton effectively
attacked George Bush's famous 1988 promise of, ``Read my lips: No
new taxes.'' Bush later supported raising taxes to close a budget
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bill Clinton ran in 1992, he said it would be
irresponsible to take a no new taxes pledge,'' Bradley continued.
``I am not taking the no new taxes pledge, and neither is the vice
president. So we have the same position.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is, you be honest with the American people,'' he
continued. ``If you think you cannot predict the future, then it
would be irresponsible to say, no new taxes. But he thinks if you
utter the word, somehow or other it's bad politics. I think people
respect honesty. And think that's the difference. And I truly thing
that people are really tired of politicians who only tell them part
of the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for Gore, said Monday, ``Vice
President Gore has ruled out raising taxes to pay for his programs
barring some drastic change in the economy.'' He said that was a
``far cry from what Bradley says,'' asserting that Bradley seemed
willing to raise taxes even if the economy is not in recession.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley denied that Monday. He said that Gore was making a
mistake in being willing to raise taxes to finance programs during
an economic downturn, asserting that recessions are the best time
to cut tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't raise taxes in bad economic times,'' Bradley said.
``That's when you cut taxes. Raising taxes in dire economic times
makes the economy worse. That's when you put money in people's
pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley tried to turn Gore's latest attack on its head, saying
that the vice president was resorting to the ``ultimate
conventional approach to politics'' by being negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the old politics,'' Bradley said. ``If you don't have
confidence in your own positive vision you attack somebody else.
And you try to do that as often as you can. That's what the name of
the game is. I think people are fed up with it. They've been fed up
with it for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president launched his latest attack in reaction to
remarks Bradley made to the Washington Post last week about his
health care plan. In that interview, Bradley was asked if he would
consider raising taxes to pay for the plan. Bradley said it would
depend on the health of the economy. He said he would consider it
only after other options had been reviewed, including closing tax
loopholes and reducing federal subsidies for certain industries.
</P>
<P>
   Gore seized on that opening in an interview with the Post on
Saturday, saying, ``I'm talking about tax cuts, Senator Bradley is
talking about tax increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Gore campaign accused Bradley of making
contradictory and confusing statements about taxes and the economy.
``Senator Bill Bradley's zigs and zags over the past few weeks
raise questions about his steadiness as a possible steward of the
American economy,'' said Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, the chairman of the Republican National
Committee, had also leaped into the fraying, asserted that anyone
who refuses to rule out tax increases is likely to increase taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Told of that remark, Bradley said Monday, ``Tell him to ask
George Bush,'' referring to the former president. After pausing, he
turned the remark toward Bush's son, the Republican presidential
candidate: ``Tell him ask George W. Bush to take a no new taxes
pledge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
