<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1159 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BIRD-APPRECIATION-SFC     12-06 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRD-APPRECIATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GOODBYE TO A ROSE THAT THRIVED IN EVERY CLIMATE  &HT;     By MIKE WEISS 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Right to the end, which came Saturday in
Stanford hospital, Rose Bird kept her sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   The friend who persuaded her to enter the hospital, a
neurologist, was surprised to hear that she was 63. ``I thought you
were much younger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So did I,'' she shot back.
</P>
<P>
   You needed a sense of humor to be Rose Bird. She was one of the
great Californians of the century, probably among the least
understood, and undoubtedly one of the most vilified.
</P>
<P>
   You would have thought she had committed murder herself, rather
than defended a principle: her belief that it's unconstitutional
for the state to put anyone to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as she lived,'' said her friend and neighbor Harriet
Pedersen, ``she was always receiving death threats.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Harriet Pedersen, I was also Rose's neighbor. Rose lived
about three blocks from me in a cottage at the end of a cul-de-sac
alongside Matadero Creek in Palo Alto, Calif. I got to know her two
years ago when I wrote a column about her.
</P>
<P>
   The column told how a tallish lady in a hat and sunglasses
showed up at a community law project in East Palo Alto and
volunteered.
</P>
<P>
   She said her name was Miss Bird. The people at the center knew
her type, or so they thought: a do-gooder, with no real world
experience. They put Miss Bird to work photocopying and filing.
</P>
<P>
   The young lawyers going about their business paid scant
attention to Miss Bird, who proved willing to do whatever was asked
of her.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day, clinic director Shauna Marshall, who had been
inspired by Rose Bird's pioneering opinions in law school,
discovered who had been doing her filing.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Rose made it easier for Shauna Marshall. She had that
natural grace that puts people at ease. I know, because after the
column appeared I received a phone call from her out of the blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mentioned in your column that you're a neighbor of mine.
Why don't you come over for brunch?'' she said. ``But as a
neighbor, not as a journalist.''
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I accepted the invitation. We ate in her garden,
which was enclosed by a white picket fence and aflame with the
roses she loved to cultivate.
</P>
<P>
   She talked about her long battle with breast cancer, her
impatience with doctors and especially the health care industry and
its greed.
</P>
<P>
   It shocked her that when her right-wing enemies recalled her and
two colleagues from the California Supreme Court in 1986, the
attacks on her were personal. She had refused to uphold a single
death penalty because, as a matter of constitutional law, she
thought it was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to believe that the consequences of the attacks by
conservatives such as Pete Wilson, and big business, were not
psychologically brutal. She stood for ideas; her opponents wanted
to vanquish a person. And a person they knew almost nothing about.
They made her into a symbol.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy to be a pariah. But politically speaking, she
lived in a cowardly age without ever succumbing.
</P>
<P>
   She talked all the time to Jerry Brown, who as governor had
appointed her as  &LR; chief justice, but when I asked her whether she
would participate in his campaign for mayor of Oakland, she said:
``I can't. Being associated with me would hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably the person who knew her best was her friend Frank.
</P>
<P>
   Frank doesn't want his last name in the newspaper. ``I'm just
Frank the hairdresser,'' he said Sunday. Frank was at Rose's house
when we talked Sunday afternoon, to walk her beloved Australian
terrier, Miss Nellie.
</P>
<P>
   Frank had been unable to keep his last promise to his dearest
friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't want the hospital to be her final destination,''
Frank said. ``I told her, don't worry, I'm not taking you to your
grave. You'll make one last headline: `Rose Bird Kidnapped From
Hospital by Hairdresser.''`
</P>
<P>
   After she had been driven off the high court, her life became
more than private. She made herself obscure. Some said she went
into hiding, but that wasn't true.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hid in plain sight,'' Frank said. ``She went about her
business. She was in and out of every store in Palo Alto. She was
not a recluse, not living on the fringes.''
</P>
<P>
   She went to the opera. She participated in Death Penalty Focus,
an organization opposed to capital punishment. She visited with
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of her friends and admirers thought there was
something sad about Rose. But not Frank, who knew her best.
</P>
<P>
   She was fierce about her privacy, he said, ``but it wasn't that
Rose didn't have anyone _ she had everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   I would see Rose occasionally in the early morning as she was on
her way to swim, and she always stopped to talk. She told me about
stories she thought I should write, stories about injustice done,
especially to people of color.
</P>
<P>
   She was a woman of great kindness, with a generous spirit, an
indomitable will, an integrity that never faltered. Her friend the
law professor, Gerald Uelman, called her ``one of the most
courageous people I ever met. She endured a lot with grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was a glorious autumn day, and early in the morning I
walked to Rose's house to pay my respects. I walked beneath trees
in shades of amber and gold and burnt orange, under a clear blue
sky.
</P>
<P>
   I was thinking about how on the day when the great but often
maligned U.S. Supreme Court Justice William O. Douglas died, the
tallest Douglas fir tree in his native state of Minnesota tumbled
to its death, too.
</P>
<P>
   I half-expected to see her beloved rose bushes withered and
gone. Instead, her favorites, the delicate white-pink flowers
called Simplicity, were in full bloom in December. Great jurists
live and die. Great spirits bloom forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
