<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1167 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-BOARD-COX     12-06 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BOARD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Board leader praises Ivester
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most Coca-Cola directors were reluctant to talk about
Douglas Ivester's planned departure.
</P>
<P>
   The only director contacted who was willing to talk was James B.
Williams, former chief executive of SunTrust Banks. Williams is
chairman of the Coca-Cola board's finance committee, and he also
serves on its executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how much I think of Doug,'' Williams said Monday.
``I've always supported Doug's decisions. And to the best of my
knowledge, he's never made a bad decision. He knows what he's
doing, and I'm supporting him.''
</P>
<P>
   Other directors contacted referred calls to Coca-Cola Co. or to
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Ivester lived, breathed and drank Coca-Cola Co. An
admitted workaholic, Ivester often would be the first one in the
office and the last one to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves the Coca-Cola Co. No question about that,'' Williams
said. ``It's still everything to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivester had been groomed to be the long-term chief executive
officer of company following the death of Roberto C. Goizueta in
October 1997. He had been anointed successor of the company by
Goizueta himself, a nod that carried a great deal of weight on the
board. After being entrusted with the company's future by the
board, why would Ivester retire?
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug doesn't let people down,'' said Williams, who declined to
answer specific questions as to how Ivester's plans to retire came
about.
</P>
<P>
   Charles H. ``Pete'' McTier, president of the Robert W. Woodruff
Foundation, which has most of its wealth in Coca-Cola stock, called
the Ivester's decision a personal one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing but the highest admiration for Doug Ivester and
his leadership,'' McTier said. ``Mr. Ivester has contributed
enormously to the success of the Coca-Cola Co. over the past two
decades. The company is in terrific shape. His successor, Doug
Daft, will handle the transition of leadership flawlessly.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Saporta writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
