Ivester, 52, left, has resigned as chief executive of Coca-Cola,
effective in April, ending Invester's short and troubled term as
the successor to Roberto Goizueta. Ivester will be succeeded by
Douglas Daft, right, senior vice president in charge of the
company's Middle and Far East and Africa groups. (Rich Addicks,
left, Coca Cola/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa -- Dec. 6, 1999 - BRADLEY-POLITICS, --
Bill Bradley, right, running for the Democratic Party's
presidential nomination, listens to workers in the cafeteria of the
Quaker Oats plant on Monday. Clockwise from left, Tom Zahn, Chuck
Aiels, Dave Simonson, Frank Aiels (Chuck's brother), and Bradley.
Bradley said Monday he would not propose a tax increase and accused
Vice President Al Gore of distorting his health care reform plan.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PRIMYKANIYE, Russia -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-6
-- A small roadside mosque is seen damaged on a road between Argun
and Grozny, the Chechen capital, on Monday. The area was the scene
of heavy fighting between Chechen fighters and Russian forces. The
Russian military has been raining bombs and artillery on Grozny for
weeks but has been hesitant to storm it for fear that street
battles would cause the kind of heavy casualties that Russia
suffered in the 1994-96 war. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PRIMYKANIYE, Russia -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-5
-- A Russian soldier plays with a puppy, the group's mascot, in
front of their armored personnel carrier in the village on the
outskirts of the Chechen capital on Monday. The Russian military
has been raining bombs and artillery on Grozny for weeks but has
been hesitant to storm it for fear that street battles would cause
the kind of heavy casualties that Russia suffered in Grozny in the
1994-96 war. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PRIMYKANIYE, Russia -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-4
-- A Russian soldier walks through a field of trenches abandoned by
Chechen fighters on Monday near the village some three miles from
the Chechen capital. The Russian military has been raining bombs
and artillery on Grozny for weeks but has been hesitant to storm it
for fear that street battles would cause the kind of heavy
casualties that Russia suffered in Grozny in the 1994-96 war.
(James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PRIMYKANIYE, Russia -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-3
-- A Russian soldier looks through a periscope from a trench some
three miles outside of the Chechen capital on Monday. The Russian
military has been raining bombs and artillery on Grozny for weeks
but has been hesitant to storm it for fear that street battles
would cause the kind of heavy casualties that Russia suffered in
Grozny in the 1994-96 war. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SANTA BARBARA, Calif. -- Dec. 6, 1999 --
SCI-PLANCK-LENGTH, 12-06 -- ``We've long suspected that space-time
had to be quantized,'' says Dr. Steven B. Giddings, a theorist at
the University of California at Santa Barbara. ``Recent
developments have led to some exciting new proposals about how to
make these ideas more concrete.'' (Davis Barber/New York Times)
</P>
