<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, DECEMBER 7
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-OCKRENT-NYT (moved on Thursday, Dec. 2)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Mike Ockrent sent by the New York Times News
Service on Thursday, Dec. 2, misstated the surname of the children
who survive along with his wife, the choreographer Susan Stroman.
And a correction in this space on Saturday misstated their
relationship to Mr. Ockrent. The children are Natasha and Ben
Ockrent, not Stroman. They are his children from a former marriage,
not stepchildren.
</P>
<P>
   BC-HONGKONG-TABLOIDS-MEDIA-NYT (moved on Sunday, Dec. 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Dec. 5,
about The Apple Daily, a Hong Kong newspaper whose offices were
searched by government agents, misstated its format. It is standard
size, not a tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   BC-RITE-AID-MANAGE-NYT (moved on Sunday, Dec. 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Dec. 5,
about new management at the Rite Aid Corporation misstated the type
of legal action faced by the company. The Florida attorney general
has filed a civil complaint accusing the company of overcharging
customers; Rite Aid has not been indicted.
</P>
<P>
   BC-Y2K-BUG-NYT (moved on Friday, Dec. 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Dec. 3,
about a malicious computer program that masquerades as the Year
2000 problem misidentified the maker of McAfee antivirus products.
They are made by Network Associates of Santa Clara, Calif., not by
Computer Associates, based in Islandia, N.Y. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
