<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 12/06/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT43) SAN FRANCISCO -- Dec. 6, 1999 - HOMELESS-CRACKDOWN-6, --
Homeless men sleep on the grass behind the weekly Farmers Market at
United Nations Plaza near City Hall in October. At the richest time
in the nation's history, housing that the poor can afford is at an
all-time low, fueling an increase in homelessness, according to the
United States Conference of Mayors. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT42) WORCESTER, Mass.-- Dec. 6, 1999 -- FIRE-WORCESTER-5-BOS,
-- Matthew McCarthy, a West Hartford, Ct., firefighter, along with
his wife Kelley, and their 21-month old son Devon, embrace on
Monday after adding their floral tribute to several hundred left on
a fire engine near where six firefighters were killed in a
warehouse blaze. The loss of the six men Friday night were believed
to be the nation's highest death toll involving firefighters since
1994, when 14 firefighters perished in a forest fire in
Colorado.(Jim Davis/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) AUSTIN, Texas -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- FRONT-ROW-FASHION --
Susan Dell, with her husband Michael, left (chief executive of the
computer company that bears his name), at the Wooldridge Elementary
School in Austin recently. Susan Dell clothes - quiet suits, shift
dresses and gowns that wouldn't have appeared on ``Dallas'' - will
be sold only at Susan Dell, the Charles Gwathmey-designed store she
has just opened in Austin - a city filled with Dell millionaires
but few up-market boutiques to cater to them. (Rebecca
McEntee/Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) NEW YORK -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- VH1-FASHION-3 -- The actress
Charlize Theron, a presenter at the VH1/Vogue Fashion Awards, in
Armani. Everyone who had been nominated for an award knew in
advance whether he or she had won, due to a distribution glitch by
Vogue, which last week announced the winners on the cover of its
January issue. (Barbara Alper/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) NEW YORK -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- VH1-FASHION-2 -- Models
wearing python from Calvin Klein, a nominee at the VH1/Vogue
Fashion Awards. The show moved swiftly, without windy speeches or
bombing jokes, and the fashion segments, all coordinated by Candy
Pratts Price, a former Vogue editor, reflected Vogue's sense of
mainstream fashion tastes as well as its powerful clout with the
industry. (Barbara Alper/New York Times)
