<P>
   (NYT25) NEAR THE SOUTH POLE, Antarctica -- Dec. 6, 1999 --
BYRD-ANNIVERSARY-2 --Antarctic ice, marked only by the shadow of a
passing aircraft. Seventy years ago last week, Adm. Richard E. Byrd
became the first person to fly over the South Pole, in a Ford
tri-motor aircraft that had a cruising speed of about 90 miles per
hour. (Josh Landis/National Science Foundation)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) AT THE SOUTH POLE, Antarctica -- Dec. 6, 1999 --
BYRD-ANNIVERSARY-1 -- The crew of an LC-130 unloading cargo at the
South Pole base last week. Adm. Richard E. Byrd made the first
flight to the pole on Nov. 29, 1929. Today, such trips are almost
routine. (Josh Landis/National Science Foundation) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) BOSTON -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- SCI-VACCINES-BOS -- A brave
George Brown, 4, gets immunized by Dr. Sean Palfrey at Boston
Medical Center. Widespread immunization programs have been deemed
one of this century's biggest public health successes. Vaccination
involves exposing the body to either a weakened or killed virus to
build immunity to a given disease. Although rare, side effects do
occur. (David L. Ryan/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WORCESTER, Mass.-- Dec. 6, 1999 -- FIRE-WORCESTER-4-BOS,
-- Deputy Fire Chief John Fenton talks to reporters on Monday about
the events that left six firefighters dead at a vacant warehouse.
Searchers on Sunday recovered the body of the first of six
firefighters who perished in the fire Friday night. The loss of the
six men were believed to be the nation's highest death toll
involving firefighters since 1994, when 14 firefighters perished in
a forest fire in Colorado.(Tom Landers/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 6, 1999 --
SCI-SCHIZOPHRENIA-RESEARCH, 12-06 -- Dr. Thomas H. McGlashan, left,
of the Yale School of Medicine, and Patrick D. McGorry of the
University of Melbourne in Australia, are leading studies in which
people at risk are given anti-psychotic drugs to prevent the onset
of schizophrenia. The studies are controversial and have found no
shortage of critics. (Shana Raab/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- MRSCLINTON-BOOK-REVIEW --
``Hillary's Choice,'' by Gail Sheehy, puts the first lady on the
shrink's couch. Ms. Sheehy's assessment: that Hillary Rodham
Clinton is addicted to her husband, Bill, that ``he is her only
rebellion, the one thing she can't logically explain,'' that she
sought in him the approval her withholding father never gave her
but found herself ``living out the same dynamic'' with another
``emotionally unavailable'' man. (Random House/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- SCI-DIABETES-BRACELETS, 12-06
-- The MiniMed sensor measures the glucose in tissue rather than in
blood, and then extrapolates from this measurement. ``We hope to
add hypo- and hyperglycemic alarms to the system to let patients
know when their blood sugar levels are too high or too low,'' says
Robert Murtfeldt, director of business development for MiniMed. He
expects the next phase of the monitor to be a consumer version in
which continuous glucose readings are transmitted wirelessly.
(Marissa Roth/New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- SCI-HUBBLE-RESCUE, 12-06 --
If all goes according to plan, the Hubble Space Telescope, a window
through which humans have viewed the edges of space for almost a
decade, will soon be reawakened by the nudging, gloved hands of
astronauts replacing and repairing the failed inner works that
forced it into hibernation. Next week, the space shuttle Discovery
is scheduled to blast off on a mission to restore the observatory.
(NASA/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- TIMES-SQUARE-FLOATER -- The
new 7-foot tall numerals for the Times Square 2000 celebration
arrived at One Times Square on Monday. In addition to the new
numbers, the arrival of the millennium will be celebrated by the
falling of a new Waterford crystal ball at the midnight. (Ruby
Washington/The New York Times) LITE
