<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- MUSICAL-RIGHTS-3 -- ``Kiss
Me, Kate,'' by Sam and Bella Spewack, was updated by John Guare,
right, with the approval of Lois and Arthur Elias, at left. The
couple, who live on the Upper West Side of Manhattan, were
entrusted with ``Kate'' by Mrs. Spewack, with whom they had been
good friends and who died at 90 in 1991. She wrote the musical's
book with her husband, Sam, in 1948. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- MUSICAL-RIGHTS-2-B&AMP;W --
Christopher Durang and Wendy Wasserstein were among the writers who
wanted to update ``Kiss Me, Kate.'' Ms. Wasserstein says her
proposal some years ago broke down because of Lois and Arthur Elias
- to whom the musical's book has been entrusted. ``They were
concerned that I would take credit,'' Ms. Wasserstein says. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Dec. 6, 1999 -- MUSICAL-RIGHTS-1 -- Marin
Mazzie and Brian Stokes Mitchell in ``Kiss Me, Kate.'' And at a
time when revivals are all the rage, the story of this musical's
hesitant return raises the curtain on an obscure, insular world of
rights organizations, estates and family members, all jealously
holding the keys to some of the musical theater's most valuable
treasures. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times) LITE
