<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1173 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-NASA-MARS-HNS &LR;      12-06 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-MARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARS EXPLORATION FAILURES WILL BE FELT AT NASA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The almost certain loss of the Mars Polar
Lander has thrown NASA's faster, better, cheaper strategy of
exploring the Red Planet into disarray with some experts
questioning whether the agency is attempting too much with too
little.
</P>
<P>
   The Polar Lander has been silent since it was to land on the
Martian south pole Friday. Its seeming demise follows the Sept. 23
loss of NASA's Mars Climate Orbiter, a small weather satellite.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency invested $371 million to develop, launch and
operate the two missions, which were to work in concert to help
scientists determine whether water once flowed across the now arid
surface of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Landers and orbiters are slated for launchings in 2001, 2003 and
2005. The two later missions are to robotically gather samples of
Martian soil and rock and return them to Earth in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the similarity of the designs in the 1998 (Polar
Lander) and 2001 landers, if the '98 lander were lost, that will
surely have an impact on what we are going to do,'' said Carl
Pilcher, NASA's director of solar system exploration. ``But it's
impossible to say now what that impact will be.''
</P>
<P>
   The space agency announced a more aggressive, lower-cost program
of Mars exploration in 1993 after the loss of its $1 billion Mars
Observer, the first American probe dispatched to the planet in 17
years. Lost as it neared its destination, the Mars Observer
included all of the instruments later divided between the smaller
Global Surveyor and Climate Orbiter.
</P>
<P>
   A change in approach, outlined by NASA administrator Dan Goldin,
was to increase the frequency of the missions by lowering their
cost and cutting their development times.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe, though, that NASA has been forced to carry the
strategy too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic idea that we should be flying more at less cost per
missions is basically sound,'' said John Pike, director of space
policy for the independent Federation of American Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I hope they will take the opportunity to make a little
mid-course correction with cheaper, better, faster,'' Pike said.
``I don't see any problem that couldn't be fixed with an extra few
hundred million dollars. As long as they are trying to do things on
the cheap rather than just cheaper, you run the risk that simple
problems will slip through the system and all the money will go to
waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Polar Lander and Climate Orbiter were the latest salvo in a
succession of low-cost missions begun in 1996. They included the
successful $262 million Mars Pathfinder mission that reached the
surface of the planet with a small robotic rover on July 4, 1997.
The $247 million Mars Global Surveyor has been circling the planet
since late 1997 photographing the planet.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, NASA lost contact with its Climate Orbiter probe
as it maneuvered into Martian orbit. Investigators quickly tracked
the cause to navigational errors attributed to a mix-up between
NASA and its contractor, Lockheed Martin, over the use of English
and metric units of force to calculate maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation into the Climate Orbiter mishap identified a
list of contributing causes, many of them linked to inadequate
staffing and poor communication among development, navigation and
spacecraft operations teams. It found that flight control teams
were not thoroughly familiar with design limitations on the
spacecraft, and it questioned the wisdom of operations teams
attempting to manage the inflight activities of the Global
Surveyor, Climate Orbiter and Polar Lander simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks leading to the Climate Orbiter's arrival at Mars,
NASA was battling a surprise decision by congressional
appropriators to cut the agency's 2000 budget by more than $1
billion. Warning the cuts would devastate his scaled-back Mars
program and other initiatives, Goldin managed to stave off the
threat in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they do these projects needs to be carefully examined,
but I don't think it's a basic indictment,'' said Louis Friedman, a
scientist and the executive director of The Planetary Society, the
Pasadena, Calif.-based non-profit pro-space organization started by
the late Carl Sagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``These Mars missions really push the envelope. They try to do
as much as they can for the buck, which is laudable,'' said
Friedman. ``But if it risks the safety of a mission, maybe it's not
the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, he points to the Polar Lander team's decision to
exclude a transmitter on the probe that could have kept signals
streaming to Earth during the descent and landing. As planned by
mission managers, the transmissions stopped about 12 minutes before
the landing so the spacecraft could assume a protective posture for
its high-velocity descent.
</P>
<P>
   The signals were supposed to resume when the Polar Lander was
safely on the surface, generating electrical power and preparing to
photograph its surroundings. When the signals never came, it raised
the question of whether the Polar Lander and the attached Deep
Space 2 probes ever separated from the rocket stage that delivered
them from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Functioning much in the role of the ``black box'' that
investigators attempt to recover after an airline crash, even
limited transmissions from the descent could have revealed what
really happened to the Polar Lander, allowing those involved in the
development of future missions to correct a design flaw.
</P>
<P>
   Polar lander engineers say they elected to dispense with such a
transmitter because they could not have responded even had they
received a hint of a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black box is important to everyone but those on the
airplane,'' said Friedman. ``I think that's the way the people on
this project felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Early flight control teams at the agency's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory hoped to hear signals from a backup transmitter on Polar
Lander. The spacecraft and its two soft-ball sized companion probes
have not been heard from since Friday, when they were to begin
their descent to the planet's south pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've pretty much reached the point where we've used up our
final silver bullets,'' NASA's Richard Cook, the Polar Lander's
project manager, said Monday. He characterized the sixth attempt to
communicate with the probe since it failed to make a post-landing
transmission on Friday as the ``last high-probability attempt we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Though less intensive efforts to locate the squat lander will
continue for several more weeks, the odds get longer that the
spacecraft survived its descent before sustaining multiple failures
of computer and communications equipment. Battery power on the Deep
Space 2 companion probes likely exhausted Monday, the space agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
