<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FORECAST-AD-COLUMN-NY     12-06 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORECAST-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDUSTRY GROWTH IS GOOD FOR 1999; FORECAST FOR 2000: MORE OF THE
SAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How upbeat are the two leading forecasters of
advertising spending about the prospects for the marketing and
media industries in 2000?
</P>
<P>
   At a conference Monday, they almost warbled a medley of ``Blue
Skies'' and ``Cockeyed Optimist'' in outlining their predictions
for strong, sustained growth next year.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe that was an exaggeration. But unusually rosy glows
permeated the presentations of Robert J. Coen, senior vice
president and forecasting director at Universal McCann in New York,
and John Perriss, chairman and chief executive at Zenith Media in
London, at the opening session of the 27th annual PaineWebber Media
Conference. The conference, in Manhattan, continues through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The fluctuations of ad spending are closely watched because they
often prove to be important indicators of the strength of the
overall economy, especially offering clues about consumers' intent
to spend. There had been some concerns that the economic turmoil in
late 1998 in Asia and Latin America would seriously slow the growth
in ad spending, but Madison Avenue has emerged virtually unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financial people were running around wondering if the world
would end in 1999,'' Coen said. ``But 1999 turned out better than
we thought possible.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason, said Christopher Dixon, a managing director at
PaineWebber who introduced the presentations, is ``the
extraordinary growth of dot-com advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thought that 10 or more companies that didn't
exist two years ago would be willing to spend up to $3 million on a
spot on the Super Bowl?'' he asked with a trace of surprise in his
voice. His reference was to the record sums being spent to
advertise during ABC's coverage next month of Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, our forecast was more conservative,'' Perriss
said. ``I'm delighted to say we've been proved wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The global economy has been extraordinarily strong,'' he
added, ``and we expect three years of very steady growth'' in ad
spending from 2000 through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Coen predicted that marketers would spend a record $233 billion
to advertise in the United States next year, an increase of 8.3
percent from the $215.2 billion that he now forecasts for 1999
after revising upward some previous estimates. Both he and Perriss
make their predictions twice a year and then revise them based on
updated data.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 figure from Coen represents a 6.8 percent increase from
the $201.6 billion spent in 1998. That gain is the smallest in
percentage terms since 5.2 percent in 1993, reflecting to some
degree the worries early this year about the tumult in overseas
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The 8.3 percent increase for 2000 would be the largest in
percentage terms since 1994, when American ad spending rose 8.7
percent. And it would also set a record for ad spending as a
percentage of gross domestic product at 2.48 percent, compared with
2.37 percent in 1998 and 2.4 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when advertising has reached about 2.3 percent of GDP,
it then grows less rapidly than GDP,'' Leland A. Westerfield,
senior analyst for broadcasting and publishing at PaineWebber, said
in an interview after the presentations. ``The numbers today could
signal a breakout from historic norms.''
</P>
<P>
   Westerfield suggested two trends are powering ``this increased
level of consumer brand competition.'' One is ``broadband coming
into the home, cable modems, which will be a driving force of new
advertising'' in the interactive realm. The other is ``deregulation
in Washington, which is enabling increased competition in
telecommunications, drugs, health care, financial services,
utilities.''
</P>
<P>
   When Coen initially predicted ad spending for 2000 at a
presentation in June, he estimated it would total $230 billion. The
rise reflects the fact that ``we see strong, heavy spending by
national marketers'' next year, he said, in part because of the
millennium and the Summer Olympics, and also because of spending
for political ads and the first paid ads to promote participation
in the federal census.
</P>
<P>
   Increased budgets are likely for traditional advertisers, Coen
said, in categories like automobiles, computers, drugs, mutual
funds and telecommunications as well as for dot-coms. And the gains
are likely to be registered in traditional media like national
cable and broadcast television networks, he added, as well as in
the new media.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of new media, for the first time Coen broke out
spending for online advertising as a separate category, which he
estimated at $1 billion in 1998, $1.8 billion in 1999 and $3.2
billion in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas in 2000, Coen forecasts ad spending of $231.4 billion,
up 7 percent from a revised figure of $216.3 billion for 1999. That
too represents an increase from his initial prediction in June,
when he estimated ad spending overseas next year at $224 billion.
The 1999 figure represents a 5.3 percent rise from $205.4 billion
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The change in Coen's international figures for 2000, he said,
reflected strengthening economies in countries like Brazil,
Indonesia, Mexico and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Coen's worldwide total for 2000, then, is $464.4 billion, which
would represent an increase of 7.6 percent from a revised worldwide
total of $431.5 billion for 1999. The 1999 figure marks a gain of 6
percent from the $407 billion spent in 1998. The rise in 2000, if
it occurs, would be the largest since 1995, when world ad spending
rose 11.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Though Perriss uses a different methodology than Coen, tracking
only major media, he was similarly effusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world looks pretty rosy going forward,'' Perriss said.
``There don't seem to be any clouds of any consequence on the
horizon.'' Two reasons he listed involved the American economy,
which accounts for more than 40 percent of the world's ad spending.
One was this country's ``consumer boom'' and the other was the
``incredible'' growth of dot-com ad spending in the United States,
where he tracked campaigns from ``over 800 brands'' through the
first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Other reasons for Perriss' optimism were the nascent trend of
``dot-coms becoming a European phenomenon in ad spending'' and
improvements in Asian economies, except for Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Perriss predicted worldwide ad spending of $319.1 billion for
2000, which would represent an increase of 6.5 percent from his
revised estimate of $299.7 billion for 1999. The 1999 figure marks
an increase of 4.9 percent from $285.6 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Perriss also offered forecasts beyond 2000: $338.8 billion in
2001, an increase of 6.2 percent from his expected total for 2000,
and $359.2 billion in 2002, a gain of 6 percent from his predicted
total for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Universal McCann is the media services division of
McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising. That agency is a unit of the
McCann-Erickson World Group, owned by the Interpublic Group of
Companies. Zenith is a joint venture of the Cordiant Communications
Group and Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC.
</P>
</TEXT>
