A1179 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-DICKENS-STORY-1200(2T     12-06 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICKENS-STORY-1200(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS AND LITTLE FRED HAD NO TINY PART IN BELOVED CHRISTMAS
TALE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the original version of ``A Christmas Carol,'' Tiny Tim
didn't exclaim, ``God bless us every one'' _ Little Fred said it.
But the name of the most memorable character in this beloved
Christmas story was changed from Little Fred to Tiny Tim by author
Charles Dickens just before ``A Christmas Carol'' was published in
1843.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one of the little-known but intriguing facts about
the holiday novella. While we continue to enjoy numerous movie and
TV productions of ``A Christmas Carol,'' equally fascinating is the
story behind the story and why Dickens was moved to write the
classic.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   England played an instrumental role in establishing Dec. 25 as
the year's pre-eminent holiday. Many historians credit the British
with coining the name ``Christmas'' from ``Christ's Mass'' around
1038.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas traditions survived even when Henry VIII broke from
the Roman Catholic Church and it became politically incorrect for
children to anticipate visits from a Catholic saint. Instead,
``Father Christmas'' arrived on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   But Father Christmas, carols, wreaths and gifts were banned in
1645 after Oliver Cromwell and his Roundheads won a civil war,
beheaded King Charles I and established their conservative
religious rule. Christmas, they declared, was to be treated as an
ordinary day. Anyone celebrating would be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1660, after another civil war, Charles II and the royals
returned to power and Christmas was back in favor. But the 15-year
ban on holiday celebrations had long-term effects. Employers,
overjoyed at keeping staff at work on Dec. 25, enforced their own
regulations and continued to treat Christmas as a working day. ``A
Christmas Carol's'' Ebenezer Scrooge wasn't an aberration, but the
rule.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1830s, when a young journalist named Charles
Dickens began publishing free-lance articles in monthly magazines
(under the nom de plume ``Boz''), Christmas in England was
celebrated by some in church, by some privately in their homes, and
by many not at all.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1836, Dickens was recruited to write a series of humorous
short sketches featuring ``typical'' English gentry _ specifically,
the misadventures of one Samuel Pickwick and friends. The first
``Pickwick'' stories were popular, and by 1837, his collected
tales, titled ``The Pickwick Papers,'' were published in book form.
</P>
<P>
   Dickens loved Christmas and deplored Britain's uneven
celebration of Dec. 25. One episode of ``The Pickwick Papers''
included a character, Mr. Wardle, who recounted a Christmas folk
tale titled ``The Story of the Goblins Who Stole a Sexton.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Grub, a nasty, friendless man, spends this particular
Christmas Eve digging a grave and chastising anyone, especially
children, trying to celebrate the holiday. Alone in a church
graveyard at midnight, Grub begins to imbibe when he is confronted
by goblins. They chastise him for working instead of celebrating;
when he tries to escape, they drag him underground and force him to
witness visions of families who find joy in life, even though their
own lots are so hard.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene, loving parents and siblings gather at the bedside
of a beautiful, terminally ill child. The adults and children are
strengthened by the memory of the boy, and reaffirm their love for
one another.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing this, Grub repents his evil ways. He disappears for a
decade, then returns to his village a happier, kinder man.
</P>
<P>
   In 1843, Dickens was determined to reprise this story. This time
his irritable protagonist was Ebenezer Scrooge, who grudged coal to
his counting-house employees and humbugged anyone foolish enough to
celebrate Christmas. Scrooge's spiritual metamorphosis came via
visits by three ghosts, but anyone reading ``Goblins'' will find
Scrooge's ``encounter'' with the Cratchits to be familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Dickens was certain his star power would make ``A Christmas
Carol'' instantly popular. His main concern was keeping the price
of the book low enough so that everyone could afford to buy it.
When his publisher balked, Dickens contributed his money to keep
the price down, a Victorian equivalent of self-publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Dickens wrote the short novel in a fury, some estimating it was
five weeks. It is believed that only one significant editing change
was made. The sickly and youngest Cratchit child was named Little
Fred, chosen by Dickens supposedly because he said there were so
many people named Fred. It is believed that Dickens' wife suggested
that the character needed a more alliterative name. She suggested
Tiny Tim.
</P>
<P>
   Published on Dec. 19, ``A Christmas Carol'' was a smashing
success. William Makepeace Thackeray, perhaps Dickens' only
literary peer of the time, declared that the book ``seems to me a
national benefit, and to every man or woman who reads it a personal
kindness.'' If any book could make such a claim, ``A Christmas
Carol'' certainly encouraged an entire nation to fully embrace Dec.
25. Dickens had accomplished his objective.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't satisfied. Dickens would write several more short
Christmas tales, beginning with ``The Chimes'' just a year after
``A Christmas Carol.'' He made a point of telling friends that his
new holiday story ``knocked the `Carol' out of the field,'' but,
obviously, it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Dickens continued to write brilliant, socially relevant fiction,
but before his death in 1870, the author turned actor. Dickens had
always enjoyed participating in local theater groups, and in his
declining years he took the stage more seriously. One of his
signature performances was a public reading of ``A Christmas
Carol.'' His first reading took three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Without Oliver Cromwell's Scrooge-like edict, Dickens might
never have felt inspired to write ``A Christmas Carol.'' Had Little
Fred not been renamed Tiny Tim, the story might not have appealed
as much to readers. And if Charles Dickens hadn't loved Christmas
so much ...?
</P>
<P>
   We'll never know. But to paraphrase Tiny Tim, with ``A Christmas
Carol,'' Charles Dickens has blessed the literary world, and every
one.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Contact him at jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
