<HEADER>
A1181 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     12-06 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A LOAD OF BCS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know what I find most disgusting about the upcoming Bowl
Championship Series match between Florida State and Virginia Tech
to decide who has the best amateur football team in America for the
1999 season?
</P>
<P>
   The fact the paterfamilias of them all, the Rose Bowl, isn't
hosting it?
</P>
<P>
   No. Actually, I find Stanford against Wisconsin to be a more
interesting game for an assortment of reasons, foremost of which I
happen to be a friend of the father of the starting Cardinal
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The fact Virginia Tech had a cushy schedule and faced the kind
of weak, willing opponents that Bob Arum has fed Oscar De La Hoya
for most of De La Hoya's career?
</P>
<P>
   No. Oh, the Hokies probably would have lost two or three games
had they been stuck in the Big 10, but I'm sure Florida State also
would have lost a game or two had it had to endure the Big 10
gauntlet.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that I will be bombarded for the next four weeks in the
media with the cornball aphorisms of Bobby Bowden and the riveting
life tale of Frank Beamer?
</P>
<P>
   No. Blessedly, I still have the legal right to choose what
articles I prefer to read on the Internet and in the newspapers and
magazines. And I no longer listen to sports talk radio because I
find the kindergarten ramblings, shallow contrivances and feeble
attempts at humor among the hosts to be even more insufferable than
the appalling swill I once dispensed on the airways.
</P>
<P>
   What stokes a nerve in me and inspires my wrath most is that the
general sporting public and even many in the media, much like
glassy-eyed acolytes in one of those bizarre cults, are reciting
the same cloying spiel, ``Well, at least they got it right this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The hell they did!
</P>
<P>
   It's an absolute embarrassment as we reach the millennium that
the NCAA, with nodding approval from college presidents and bowl
promoters, still has refused to institute a playoff system for
Division I football.
</P>
<P>
   It's an absolute scandal that in a fiercely capitalistic country
that savors competitiveness still decides one of its most
prestigious honors---its national college football
championship---via computer and ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   It's an absolute injustice that Nebraska, Alabama and
Tennessee---teams, incidentally, that all would be favored by the
oddsmakers to beat Virginia Tech on a neutral site---have no chance
to win the national title even though they deserve such an
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   What chills me most is the apathetic acceptance by so many
people of the entire BCS machinery that it is as phony as some of
the pedagogues who thought up the convoluted process in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in light of the widespread silence and lack of emotional
protest surrounding the selection of the Seminoles and Hokies, this
signals a stirring triumph for bureaucrats, technocrats and all
those other `crats I can't stand.
</P>
<P>
   Just great!
</P>
<P>
   And just ridiculous!
</P>
<P>
   If I'm an athletic director at Nebraska, I'm furious.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't I have the good sense to schedule mighty James
Madison---one of Virginia Tech's more renowned victims---instead of
Texas at Austin where my beloved Cornhuskers suffered their only
loss of the season?
</P>
<P>
   As we near the year 2000, we have mind-boggling advances in
every field of endeavor, except Division I football where
championships are decided by the votes of coaches and sportswriters
and the data base of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Well, a lot of college presidents and NCAA officials claim that
a protracted playoff system would take too many hours away from the
study time of the student-athletes.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the reason, then why not shelve the NCAA basketball
tournament, which spans three weeks and also cuts into the
student-athletes' precious study time?
</P>
<P>
   And why does Division II have a playoff system for football
intact that works perfectly?
</P>
<P>
   There is a slight inconsistency here, isn't there?
</P>
<P>
   I don't understand it, but, as everyone knows who's brave enough
to read this prose, there are countless things I don't understand
in this harrowing world in which we reside.
</P>
<P>
   I don't understand how coaches and baseball managers with lousy
resumes keep coming up with choice jobs.
</P>
<P>
   I don't understand how ex jocks with minimal command of the
English language keep winding up with high-profile positions in
television.
</P>
<P>
   I don't understand how so much politically correct claptrap has
managed to take hold across this country and so negatively infested
every layer of one's existence.
</P>
<P>
   And I certainly don't understand why everyone has meekly
accepted Florida State and Virginia Tech as the ultimate showdown
simply because both happen to be undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   Where are the outraged?
</P>
<P>
   What if the NFL had arbitrarily stuck the Minnesota Vikings in
the Super Bowl last season because the Vikings happened to have a
15-1 record, which was the best in the league?
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure the Atlanta Falcons would have liked it.
</P>
<P>
   The Division I football champion should be decided on the field
between two teams who have survived playoff ordeals and not by
reporters and coaches with private agendas and innate biases and by
computer nerds who wouldn't know a Bobby Bowden from a Bobby
Knight.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the BCS is a sham not to be taken seriously.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
