<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-ESPN-BASEBALL-TRIAL-N     12-06 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESPN-BASEBALL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN AND BASEBALL KISS AND MAKE UP, AND BASEBALL IS RICHER FOR IT 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPN and Major League Baseball agreed Monday to an $815 million
contract extension through 2005 _ hours before the start of a trial
that threatened to shatter their decadelong relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's average annual payment of $38.1 million for 2000 to 2002
will remain unchanged from its current contract. But for the three
new years added to the deal, ESPN will pay $175 million in 2003 and
$200 million in both 2004 and 2005. ESPN will also pay baseball a
$125 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The additional money tantalized baseball, which viewed its
payments from ESPN as undervalued and watched Nascar and the NCAA
men's basketball tournament reap huge increases in their new
network deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course the economics are very important, but a number of
things influenced our thinking,'' Bud Selig, the baseball
commissioner, said.
</P>
<P>
   Although ESPN would have preferred to keep its baseball fees
low, it knew that a settlement would require paying dramatically
more.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN could not afford to lose the rights to baseball, not after
bidding too low to retain Nascar races after next year and not
bidding enough to snare the National Collegiate Athletic
Association deal that CBS recently renewed for $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rest assured, ESPN believes this is a a good deal and great
value for all our networks,'' George Bodenheimer, the president of
ESPN, said.
</P>
<P>
   The legal conflict focused on baseball's anger over ESPN's
desire to shuttle three Sunday night baseball games in September to
ESPN2 to make room for National Football League games.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the settlement vastly increases ESPN2's baseball
coverage, which increases the value of this six-year-old network.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN2, which broadcast 10 baseball games last season, will carry
a minimum of 44 games on Wednesday nights and select Sunday nights,
and ``Baseball 2Day,'' a new Sunday night series. Starting next
season, the Wednesday night doubleheaders seen on ESPN will usually
be split between ESPN, which reaches 77 million cable television
homes, and ESPN2, which reaches 67 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to be practical, and when I looked at this entire
deal, it's a different picture,'' said Selig, who denounced ESPN's
plan to move the late-season games to ESPN2 last year, but is happy
now. ``Under these conditions, I find it quite acceptable and it
wasn't difficult to accept in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement ends the conflict over the Sunday night games in
September. ESPN will show the higher-rated NFL games, but for the
next two years, the three disputed baseball telecasts will be
exchanged for six other games _ on Friday nights in September on
ESPN and on Sunday nights earlier in the season on ESPN2. Starting
in 2002, ESPN2 could program baseball against football on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to expanding ESPN2's role, the contract extends ESPN
Classic's rights, increases highlight rights for ESPN's
``SportsCenter,'' adds a daily highlight package to ESPN.com, and
includes a license to create video games. Separately, baseball
renewed the ESPN Radio deal for six years at $36 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people offered all the marketing and hours we needed,''
Selig said. ``They were willing to do all the things we wanted to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   To a considerable degree, Monday's shift from animosity to amity
came at the urging of U.S. District Court Judge Shira A.
Scheindlin, who was presiding over the case. But self-interest on
both sides helped produce the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN desperately needed to retain baseball rights, which are
crucial to its spring and summer schedule. And baseball knew that
it could not achieve the presence and level of marketing it gets
with ESPN if it ended up with another cable partner.
</P>
<P>
   When ESPN first proposed moving the late-season games to ESPN2,
in 1998, baseball was infuriated that potentially crucial telecasts
would be relegated to a lesser network. But ESPN pointed to a
clause in its contract that said baseball could not unreasonably
withhold its permission to move games to ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Although baseball had granted shifts of Wednesday night games to
ESPN2, it had never done so for Sunday broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe it's reasonable to move for early-season
football games,'' a baseball spokesman said last year. The only
football game deemed reasonable for a pre-emption, he said, was the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   As the conflict deepened, baseball refused to grant its
permission the past two Septembers for ESPN to put the games on
ESPN2. Instead, it wrested the games from ESPN to let the teams
show them on their local TV outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after baseball canceled ESPN's contract last April,
effective after this past season but with three years remaining,
ESPN sued in federal court. The cable network accused baseball of
withholding its consent as a ploy to resell its cable rights for a
lot more money in a highly competitive market.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to ESPN earlier this year, baseball proposed
increasing its fees by more than $50 million annually from 1999 to
2001, and extend the contract to 2002 for $125 million and to 2003
for $140 million.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement appears to pay baseball everything it wanted _
and more _ in that letter.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also sets the stage for ESPN's negotiations to extend
its $42 million-a-year playoff contract beyond 2000, and for
baseball's talks with NBC and Fox, which are entering the final
seasons of their deals. NBC and Fox are not expected to more than
triple their payments. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
