<SLUG> BC-BSKYB-KIRCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH SKY MOVES INTO CONTINENTAL EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany)  (mk) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British Sky Broadcasting Group PLC made its first major
move into Continental Europe on Monday with a $1.5 billion deal to
acquire 24 percent of Premiere World, a pay-television service
owned by Kirch Group, the German media company.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is part of an effort by British Sky to build upon its
success in Britain and Ireland by expanding into other European
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Murdoch, whose News Corp. owns 40 percent of BSkyB, has
been eager to move into Continental Europe for some time, and has
been aggressively negotiating with many European media companies
for stakes in their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement announced Monday also means that three of Europe's
top media concerns _ BSkyB, Kirch and Vivendi of France _ are now
linked, in a way similar to the interlocking partnerships that have
connected a number of media companies in the United States. Vivendi
holds a 24.5 percent stake in BSkyB.
</P>
<P>
   BSkyB will finance the deal by selling new shares to raise about
$524 million. The British company will also give KirchPayTV, a unit
of Kirch Group, 78 million new shares of BSkyB, valued at about
$996 million. The deal will also make Kirch a shareholder in BSkyB
with a 4.3 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement came after several failed efforts by Murdoch to
gain a foothold in Europe, and may signal the beginning of more
acquisitions of stakes in similar media companies on the Continent
by BSkyB. Murdoch held discussions with Kirch as early as 1997, but
did not negotiate with Kirch in earnest for its stake in Premiere
World until October.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the deal could still face regulatory obstacles,
though the German government is unlikely to intercede. Peter Voss,
chairman of Germany's state-owned ARD television broadcaster, said,
however, that the acquisition should be rejected because it could
give Premiere World a near monopoly in sports and film rights.
</P>
<P>
   Both BSkyB and Kirch have been losing money as they invest in
digital services and spend aggressively. BSkyB lost 12.1 million
pounds, or $20 million, in its first fiscal quarter. KirchPayTV,
the Kirch unit that operates Premiere World, said it did not expect
to break even until 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
