<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-MINISTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN FINANCE MINISTER EXPLAINS `BITTER TRUTH' ABOUT DEBT, TAXES
AND OLD AGE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Entering the new home of Germany's Ministry of Finance
here is like walking into a time warp. Situated in a Nazi-era
building east of the old Berlin Wall, the facade features a huge
mural celebrating the founding of Communist East Germany. In the
mural, women in blue uniforms march proudly with banners
celebrating socialism, flanked by smiling factory workers and
sturdy farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Eichel, the German finance minister, took up quarters here
when the government officially moved from Bonn to Berlin late in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Eichel is steering Germans toward a future of tax cuts, budget
cuts and what he has called the ``bitter truth'' about the limits
of government.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to understand, first, that the situation we have at
present is one in which the federal budget carries far too much
debt,'' he said. ``They have to recognize the shift of the society
toward older age, that there are ever more elderly people and ever
fewer people of working age.''
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, makes it crucial that the government balance its
budget and ``raises questions about expectations and
entitlements.''
</P>
<P>
   Eichel, 57, has been in the cross-fire of change in Germany
since he took over as finance minister in March.
</P>
<P>
   A former premier of the state of Hesse, which includes
Frankfurt, the country's financial center, Eichel replaced the
left-wing faction leader, Oskar Lafontaine, who quit as finance
minister in a feud with Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Eichel has been almost virtually an opposite of his predecessor.
Lafontaine tried to browbeat the European Central Bank into
softening monetary policy, and he infuriated industry by pushing
for steep business tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Eichel resolutely avoids commenting on monetary
policy and has charted a course to reduce top tax rates, close some
loopholes and cut back the government's share of the total economy.
</P>
<P>
   Late in November, Eichel won a major victory when Parliament
approved budget cuts of 26 billion marks, or about $14 billion. It
was the deepest package of budget cuts reductions in years, and the
finance minister has plans for more.
</P>
<P>
   Eichel wants to increase annual savings to 50 billion marks by
2002 and achieve a balanced budget by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, he has won considerable praise from business
and from many economists. He has also found surprising support
among German voters. In a recent poll conducted by ZDF, one of
Germany's public television networks, 73 percent of those surveyed
backed the recent cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Eichel has hardly been shielded from the
ideological shifts within Germany's governing Social Democratic
Party or strong changes of emphasis by Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor, who ranges between pro-business pragmatism and
more traditional left-of-center policies, has come under heavy
criticism for his stance against hostile corporate takeovers and
his support for a major corporate bailout.
</P>
<P>
   He recently helped engineer a $2.2 billion bailout of the
bankrupt construction company Philipp Holzmann AG. Industry groups
also expressed worry when both Schroeder and Eichel criticized the
hostile takeover steps against Mannesmann AG, the engineering and
telecommunications giant, by Vodafone AirTouch PLC of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Both issues aroused fear among institutional investors that
Germany might be veering toward increased government intervention
in the economy. Wim Duisenberg, president of the European Central
Bank, went so far as to hint on Dec. 2 that the Holzmann bailout
may have helped push down the euro, Europe's new single currency,
to record lows against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Eichel defended the Holzmann bailout, arguing that the
government has a responsibility to step in if a major German
company is about to collapse and cost thousands of people their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Eichel also reiterated Schroeder's criticisms of hostile
takeovers, which have long run afoul of Germany's tradition of
``consensus'' and interlocking corporate relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Eichel carefully avoided saying that the government might block
Vodafone's bid for Mannesmann. ``It is the owners who make the
decisions,'' he said.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he warned ``Anglo-Saxon'' companies against
ignoring what he called the cultural differences in countries where
hostile takeovers are not practiced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who wants to be successful in Europe, and this has been
shown before, is well advised to pay attention to the habits
practiced here,'' Eichel said.
</P>
<P>
   For Eichel, Mannesmann and Holzmann are mostly side issues. The
big challenge will be to advance his long-range goals of cleaning
Germany's convoluted tax system, reducing the huge debt accumulated
through the re-construction of eastern Germany and strengthening
the nation's pension system.
</P>
<P>
   Though German taxes are high in comparison with the United
States, the government also provides far more services _ from
national health care to free universities.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem, Eichel argued, is that top tax rates are too
high and special tax breaks too plentiful. The result, he said, is
that the tax burden falls disproportionately on personal income
taxes and social security payments. That has made labor expensive
and hindered job creation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next four years, Eichel said, he hopes to reduce the
government's share of the economy from 48 percent now to 45.5
percent. That is still far higher than in the United States, where
government consumes about 30 percent of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Will Germany need to trim back more once it reaches the
four-year goal? Eichel is staying quiet. ``I don't want to
speculate about the years after that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
