<HEADER>
A1189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MIRANDA-NYT &LR;      12-06 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MIRANDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MIRANDA REVISITED 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times saidi in an editorial on Tuesday, Dec. 7:
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court agreed yesterday to hear a challenge to one of
the most famous decisions of Chief Justice Earl Warren's era _ the
landmark 1966 ruling in Miranda vs. Arizona that requires police to
advise suspects of their rights before beginning an interrogation.
The oral argument in the case, to take place sometime next spring,
is likely to produce high drama. But as a matter of constitutional
law and sound law enforcement procedure, this should not be a
difficult decision. The intervening years have powerfully
reinforced the essential fairness and workability of the Miranda
rule, which says that criminal suspects must be told of their right
to have a lawyer present and to remain silent, and that any
statement they make can be used against them.
</P>
<P>
   The court required the warning after determining that stronger
safeguards were needed to protect the Fifth Amendment's privilege
against self-incrimination in the inherently coercive atmosphere of
police questioning. There were fears that the ruling would cripple
the police, and over the years some guilty defendants have gone
free because the police failed to read them their Miranda rights.
But these fears turned out to be greatly exaggerated, and by and
large the law enforcement community has come to accept the Miranda
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda has now returned to the Supreme Court because an
appellate court in Virginia ruled earlier this year that the
failure to issue Miranda warnings no longer required automatic
exclusion of evidence in federal prosecutions. To justify that
ruling, the court relied on a dormant federal law that Congress
passed in 1968 in an effort to overrule Miranda by reinstating the
prior rule that confessions could be admitted in federal court as
long as they were ``voluntary'' in light of all the circumstances.
No attorney general of either party has tried to enforce that law.
The reason is that Congress can only overturn a constitutional
ruling by the Supreme Court with a constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration asked the court to repudiate the
mischievous lower court ruling. The court has never precisely said
the Miranda rule was grounded in the Constitution, though if it did
not think so it could not have extended Miranda to the states, as
it has. Miranda remains sound law and policy, and the court should
say so unequivocally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1190 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-DEBATE-BOS &LR;      12-06 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DEBATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW-KEY DEBATE OFFERS BUSH CHALLENGING QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four days after a spark-filled New Hampshire
debate, the six Republican candidates conducted a low-key, mostly
friendly meeting, Monday agreeing on traditional GOP themes of
lower taxes, stronger national security and disapproval of the
Clinton Administration.
</P>
<P>
   With US Senator John McCain of Arizona participating via
satellite from Massachusetts, the five other Republican
presidential candidates met in his home state capital of Phoenix.
For the second straight debate, McCain was relatively unscathed
while George W. Bush received a disproportionate number of barbs
and pointed questions.
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the most striking line of the night, Senator Orrin
Hatch of Utah turned to Bush and praised him, but then firmly
suggested that the Texas Governor lacks experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been a great governor,'' said Hatch, standing on stage
at the Orpheum Theater and before a national CNN audience. But,
Hatch continued, ``You need more experience before you become
president of the United States and that's why I'm thinking of you
as a vice presidential candidate. You should have eight years with
me and, boy, you'll make a heck of a president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also dealt with one of the trickiest questions of the
night, when CNN anchor Judy Woodruff followed up on his assertion
during the New Hampshire debate that he was reading a biography of
former Secretary of State Dean Acheson. When Woodruff asked what
Bush had learned from the book, Bush gave a generic answer about
the need for America to be a world leader and didn't cite anything
specific about Acheson.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, McCain, standing by in a Watertown, Mass. studio,
leaped on the question, recalling how Acheson walked into the
office of President Truman and discussed whether the United States
should intervene in the Korean conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Truman didn't take a poll,'' McCain said, while implying
that the Clinton administration has done just that before engaging
in military conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, it was a night dominated by those least likely to
win the nomination. All of those struggling in the single digits in
national polls, including Hatch, former Reagan aide Gary Bauer and
talk show host Alan Keyes, used the free-wheeling discussion as an
opportunity to showcase their command of their favorites issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, asked what he would do to prevent school shooting, said
he would allow religion in the schools, particularly the posting of
the Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a gun problem,'' he said. ``I think this is
a problem of the heart and soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes did not repeat his New Hampshire debate complaints about
being the subject of a media ``black out.'' Instead, he spoke
calmly and passionately, agreeing with Bauer about the need to
allow prayer in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we took prayer out, we have seen violence in,'' Keyes
said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who won the Arizona primary in 1996 and is running
advertisement attacking Bush for ``betrayal'' for considering an
increase in the Social Security retirement age, seemed to go out of
his way to put on a friendly face. He told his familiar jokes about
how politicians are attracted to money like bees after honey, and
he urged Bush to call him ``Steve.''
</P>
<P>
   In the friendly spirit of the night, Bush asked McCain about his
views on the involvement of faith-based institutions using
government funds to in help provide social services. McCain then
joked about whether he should call Bush ``Governor, George, or W.,
or Bush'' before going on to praise Bush's work on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you are on the right track,'' McCain told Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush at one point denied that he has called for federal testing
as a means of monitoring to determine whether public schools should
continue to receive public funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in national testing,'' Bush said. ``I strongly
believe in local control of schools.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Bush relied on his Texas background and former
work in the oil business when he was asked by Forbes how he would
lower home heating oil prices in New England. Bush said he would
encourage more oil exploration and the use of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great hope for the natural gas business,'' Bush said,
describing it as ``hemispheric in nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the debate was calm, with few fireworks. Even though the
format allowed the candidates to question each other, most of the
inquiries were friendly. McCain, for example, did not go after his
chief rival, Bush. Instead, his first question was actually a
compliment to Bauer for supporting his campaign finance overhaul
bill. Bauer responded by praising McCain's effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to commend you for what you have done in this campaign
on campaign finance reform,'' Bauer told McCain, who beamed in
return.
</P>
<P>
   After McCain received a number of glowing reviews for his
performance in the New Hampshire debate last week, which helped
land him on the cover of this week's Time magazine, much of the
focus Monday night expected to be on the long-distance participant.
McCain participated by satellite after initially turning down the
invitation due to what he called a scheduling conflict.
</P>
<P>
   McCain seemed nervous during his first response, referring to
CNN panelist Candy Crowley as ``Connie'' and stumbling over his
words. But for rest of the night, McCain looked at ease, smiling in
almost every response. Unlike in New Hampshire, no one raised the
question of whether he has a bad temper, but McCain touched upon
the issue when he joked, ``I win Miss Congeniality every year in
the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate was held in a state that may have one of the most
important primaries. The Arizona Republican primary is slated to be
held on Feb. 22, three weeks after the New Hampshire vote and
before the huge March 7 round of primaries, which include New York
and California.
</P>
<P>
   But for McCain, the Arizona contest is filled with pitfalls. If
he does well, analyst are bound to say he should succeed in a state
where he won reelection with 70 percent of the vote. But if McCain
fails in his own state, his chances of winning the nomination are
likely to diminish.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Bush has poured significant resources into the
state and is preparing to run television advertisements. And
Forbes, who won the Arizona primary in 1996, may spend millions of
dollars in an effort to repeat that success. McCain also has faced
problems in Arizona due to a well-publicized feud with Governor
Jane Dee Hull, a Bush supporter who has said McCain has a bad
temper but said Monday that the issue has been overblown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
