u s BC-BKN-KINGS-STARK-2TAKE     12-06 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KINGS-STARK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HARD WAY IS THE ONLY WAY FOR STARKS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In October 1990, the Knicks were moments away from
wrapping up their final practice and breaking the news to an
undersized shooting guard that his dream of playing in the National
Basketball Association was over. John Starks, a 25-year-old veteran
of three junior colleges, the Memphis Rockers of the World
Basketball League and the Piggly Wiggly supermarket in his
hometown, Tulsa, Okla., where he bagged groceries, was about to be
waived from his second NBA roster in two years.
</P>
<P>
   He had no job prospects outside basketball when, during the
team's final scrimmage, he launched his 6-foot-3-inch frame high
into the air, boldly trying to dunk over an agile 7-foot Patrick
Ewing. Basketball was not Starks' career as much as it was his
life. Both hung in the balance as he took flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blocked it,'' Ewing said, smiling at the memory. ``I
remember the whole play.''
</P>
<P>
   Starks, who will play in Madison Square Garden Tuesday night for
the first time since he was traded for Latrell Sprewell last
January, said: ``Yeah, the Big Fella got me. I twisted my knee on
the play. Had to go on the injury list. You can't predict how
things are going to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he was on the injury list, the Knicks could not release
Starks. They had to wait until he was healthy. A month later, Trent
Tucker went down with an injury and Starks got his shot.
</P>
<P>
   Pounding his chest after slashing layups, pointing to the New
York insignia on his No. 3 jersey after a long jump shot, he
head-butted his way into the hearts of jaded Knick fans. He refused
to let anyone tell him again that he was not good enough to play in
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no idea he was going to be cut that day,'' said Jeff
Van Gundy, then a Knicks assistant and now the head coach. ``I
think about that Miami game last year with us, how everything was
riding on Allan Houston's shot. John had already been cut the year
before. Who knows if he gets another shot and makes it? You
couldn't make his story up.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he made you throw food at the television that night in
1994, when he could not make a shot in the NBA finals, connecting
on 2 of 18 attempts in Game 7 against Houston. But if you are a
Knick fan, at one time or another Starks _ Horatio Alger in
hightops _ had a magnetic pull on you. He either charged your heart
because he played with so much passion or he so infuriated you that
you screamed, ``Hey, psycho boy!'' _ as the deranged Pacer fan
behind the Knicks' bench did in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a Golden State Warriors jersey, Starks comes home to the
place where he forged his career. He is no longer the player who
deposited a left-handed lean-in slam over Michael Jordan and Horace
Grant in 1992, a play referred to simply as the Dunk. Starks, at
34, is nursing a sore knee, shooting poorly and playing on one of
the NBA's most moribund teams.
</P>
<P>
   His legs are not as spry and his shot is often short. But his
memories are intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't pinpoint my emotions on Tuesday night, how I'll feel
or what I'll do when I step on the court,'' Starks said by
telephone over the weekend. ``The biggest thing will be seeing all
the old faces again. I left a lot of friends there.''
</P>
<P>
   Starks said he might kneel down and kiss the Garden floor. Spike
Lee, who quickly purchased a No. 8 Sprewell jersey after the trade,
was prepared to wear his No. 3 jersey in honor of Starks' return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up having to go to L.A.,'' said Lee, the filmmaker and
Knick fan. ``But I would have worn it. He's one of my all-time
favorites. You have to admire someone who was bagging groceries at
the Piggly Wiggly and despite being cut and in the CBA saying to
himself: `They're not going to hold me down. I'm going to make
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Starks actually returned to the Garden last May during the first
round of the playoffs. He watched Game 3 against Miami from the
tunnel leading to the locker rooms. When his face was shown on the
scoreboard, a standing ovation almost brought him to tears. He hung
out in the locker room after the game like the tag-along little
brother no one had the heart to completely ditch.
</P>
<P>
   Starks was especially close to his former teammates, including
Ewing, Houston and Chris Childs. After that training-camp play in
1990, Starks and Ewing became the best of friends and their
families spent considerable time together. One of the more
endearing moments at the team's SUNY-Purchase practice facility
came a few years ago when Ewing's gangly teenage son, Patrick Jr.,
and Starks' son, John Jr., were playing against two college
students. As young Patrick dribbled inside, John Jr. stood
positioned on the perimeter, repeating over and over: ``I'm open!
I'm open!'' Like fathers, like sons.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he considered Starks one of his favorite teammates,
Ewing responded, ``He is my favorite teammate.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston recalled meeting Starks on his first day as a Knick,
hours after Houston had signed a $56 million contract to become the
team's new and improved shooting guard. There was no uncomfortable
moment. Starks embraced his new teammate and never once treated
Houston like the guy brought in to take his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father always said a first impression is a lasting
impression,'' Houston said. ``I remember that day. He was always a
dude that no matter what happened, whatever people thought about
him, what people didn't know about him, he ultimately wanted to win
a game. He was one person I know, more than anybody I ever played
with, that would do whatever it took to win a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, Starks and Houston signed autographs at
3-point Wireless, a cell phone business they co-own near the
Garden. Starks plays golf at some of the Bay Area's most exclusive
clubs and no longer asks the waiter to take his lobster off the
bone, as he once did at a Boston restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is where John learned a lot about life, too,'' Van
Gundy said. ``If you would have interviewed him in his first years,
he would have appeared less sophisticated. As he got older, he
spoke better, became community-minded. He's one of those guys who
truly cares about kids. And he understood New York fans, one of the
few guys who really understood the mentality of where they came
from.''
</P>
<P>
   The day he was traded last January, Starks sent personalized
letters to every New York newspaper thanking the fans for their
support over the years. ``A lot of the players in the league today
had crowds cheering for them in college and high school everywhere
they went,'' Starks said. ``I never really had that. I was just
happy anyone was cheering for me when I got to the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Starks hit his nadir twice in New York. Once after that Game 7
against Houston _ he spent an hour weeping in the shower _ and
again when Don Nelson, the former coach, waged a feud with him,
relegating him to the bench and openly questioning his talent.
Nelson had cut him after 36 games with Golden State in the 1988-89
season, and Starks felt Nelson was trying to undermine his career
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone talks about our blow-ups and incidents,'' said Van
Gundy, who had some of his most heated exchanges with Starks over
the years. ``The thing I'll remember is him calling me after Coach
Nelson was let go. With Hubert Davis starting, there was a possible
conflict. So John calls me up and says: `Jeff, you can start me,
bring me off the bench, do whatever you want. I'll understand.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere could Starks find more empathy than from Van Gundy, who
had waged his own war against perceptions to become an NBA head
coach. After Starks' first season, Van Gundy began annual visits to
Tulsa, where he would help Starks develop his skills at Oral
Roberts University over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a closeness there that came over time,'' Van Gundy
said. ``John wasn't blessed with any one great skill, but he had
such unusual hustle and heart. People who say his career was about
2 for 18 should be ashamed. What they forget is, with four weeks to
go in the regular season, John had knee surgery that year. He was
back in time for the first playoff game. Think about that. His pain
threshold and his desire was so high.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I remember most about John? That once he got in, he
never let go. He never let anybody even think about taking it away
from him.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Knicks, nothing has been planned for tonight to
commemorate Starks' nine years with the team. Not a video montage
nor a pregame announcement for a player who, in Game 6 of the 1994
finals, came within a jump shot of bringing the Knicks their first
title in two decades. With Starks, what might have been is not the
point. The point is what might not have been had a Continental
Basketball Association refugee not had the gumption to try to dunk
on the franchise center on the last day of practice in the final
minutes of a scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all ready to bring him aside and tell him he was
cut,'' Van Gundy said. ``He had no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, John Starks can be celebrated for making it at
all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
