<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SWISS-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE DECEPTIONS OF SWISS BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Dec. 7:
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland's reputation and especially that of its banks has
been battered in recent years as new evidence revealed surprisingly
close cooperation between Swiss institutions and those of
neighboring Nazi Germany and in particular called new attention to
disgracefully shabby Swiss treatment of Nazism's Jewish victims.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's long-awaited report on the Swiss banking industry's
handling of Nazi-era Jewish accounts added little fresh damage,
finding no conclusive evidence that Swiss banks had systematically
conspired to conceal or loot those accounts. But the report, by an
international panel headed by Paul Volcker, the former Federal
Reserve chairman, found that Swiss banks had somehow managed to
lose track of a shockingly large number of these accounts over the
intervening decades and that many banks had cruelly and deceptively
turned away family members trying to recover lost assets. The
Volcker panel was able to trace some 54,000 of these missing
accounts, far more than the Swiss have previously acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   To ward off court suits and pressure from every level of the
American government, Swiss banks last year agreed to a $1.25
billion settlement that resolved claims arising from these and
other Nazi-era financial abuses. That total will not be affected by
the new Volcker findings. But the report substantially reinforces
the evidence supporting that settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss bank settlement, the first in which a major European
industry agreed to repay victims of Hitler-era economic crimes, set
an important precedent that surviving Nazi victims are now rightly
trying to follow up in other areas, most notably in talks with
German industry about compensation for their use of slave and
forced labor.
</P>
<P>
   The German government, to its credit, has tried to nudge these
negotiations toward a successful conclusion. But Switzerland's
government has thus far been defensive and even resentful about
acknowledging its responsibilities. That lack of leadership may
have contributed to the growing anti-Semitic tone in Swiss politics
in recent months. With the release of the Volcker report, and
another report due later this week on Switzerland's treatment of
refugees fleeing Nazism, Swiss leaders have a fresh chance to
acknowledge the less attractive features of their country's wartime
record and embrace efforts to compensate the victims.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
