<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-PAYTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS RESPOND TO A BRASH COACH NOW CALLING THE PLAYS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Tiki Barber stood in the huddle near the
end of Sunday's game against the Jets, waiting to hear what play
would be called.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ahead, 34-21, it's third-and-10, we're on our own 20,
and there's less than four minutes left,'' Barber said. ``I figured
we're going to rsn the clock out.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sean Payton, the Giants' first-year quarterbacks coach,
who haD been handed the play-calling duties by the head coach, Jim
Fassel, called for a pass deep down the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the huddle going, `What?''' Barber said afterward.
``Here we are leading late in the game and Sean is throwing bombs.
I was flabbergasted, but I was impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   The play would become an 80-yard touchdown, with quarterback
Kerry Collins finding Amani Toomer in another artful combination: a
precisely run pass route and a perfectly thrown pass. It was the
last of the Giants' 490 yards in their 41-28 victory, more yards
than any other Giants team had gained io 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   To Giants fans, there was greater meaning beyond the statistics.
If for a day, their team was entertaining. They liked what they
saw, even if they did not know Sean Payton from Sean Penn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean is a cocky guy,'' Barber said of the Giants' new
offensive wizard. ``He goes for it, and that's fun for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Hired in January after two seasons as the quarterbacks coach
with the Philadelphia Eagles, the 35-year-old Payton, unassuming in
his mannerisms, appeared neither brazen nor bold in his first
several months with the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   That began to change in recent weeks as Payton became more vocal
around the offensive unit. In practice between plays, the coaching
conversation increasingly revolved around the spot where Fassel and
Payton stood, frequently side by side.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was Payton's coming-out party, and while he was far from
showy, he was hard to miss on the Giants' sideline.
</P>
<P>
   While it has always been the Giants' routine to have the entire
coaching staff dress in matching outfits like a band of valet
parking attendants, on Sunday, Payton wore a bright red sweater.
His colleagues wore white golf shirts and plain blue windbreakers.
</P>
<P>
   This was probably done so that Payton could be more visible to
Collins, who received the plays from Payton via the
headset-to-helmet communications system but might have needed to
find Payton should they want to communicate with hand signals. In
any case, Payton wore his gaudy sweater with a certain aplomb, a
figure in repose for most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   He calmly called the plays, usually standing 10 to 15 yards from
Fassel, who also had a headset through which he heard Payton's
calls.
</P>
<P>
   It was Payton who held the large white chart of plays, not
Fassel. And if the head coach made subtle suggestions, he never
vetoed a call. Indeed, Fassel spent much of his day keeping others
away from Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put the hammer down on that,'' Fassel said Monday. ``I told
people: `Get away from him. Let him call the game.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in eight years _ when Fassel was a
first-year Giants quarterbacks coach _ that he stood on the
sideline of a National Football League game without calling the
plays.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Fassel said he found the experience
liberating. ``I felt more in control of things over all,'' he said.
``It frees you up to assess the whole game, to get a feel for
what's going on all over the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' offensive players were also elated to have Payton at
the helm. For weeks now, they have felt that Payton was the coach
who best explained the intricacies and goals of the offensive
system. He used terms they readily understood and was more
free-wheeling, which may be a natural function of his role as an
assistant to the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coaches who call a team's plays are often aggressive
because they are ultimately trying to impress, hopeful that they
may someday become a head coach. Head coaches are usually more
fixed on keeping the jobs they have, a situation that can lead to
conservative play calling.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the motivation, Payton attacked on Sunday. When the
Giants approached the Jets' end zone, Collins said Payton's play
calling was ``courageous.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Payton played down his role, deflecting praise
to Jim Skipper, the Giants' offensive coordinator, and other
assistants. He admitted to being nervous but credited the players
with the real heroics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those calls, what you're doing is challenging them to
come through,'' Payton said. ``And they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton came to the Giants on the recommendation of their
defensive line coach, Denny Marcin, who worked with Payton at the
University of Illinois in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Since Rod Dowhower, Fassel's quarterbacks coach in 1997 and
1998, had taken a job as the offensive coordinator at Philadelphia,
Fassel interviewed a handful of candidates for the job. He canceled
his trip to the Super Bowl last January to bring Payton to Giants
Stadium and ended up offering him the job that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was intrigued by him and felt very comfortable right away,''
Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Payton is the man who made even the Giants' offense
look interesting. The guy with the guts to call a double reverse
and the sense to run the football 45 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called the same plays we always do,'' Payton said. ``The
difference was they were executed.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but others noticed a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean takes risks,'' Barber said. ``As a player, that gets your
attention. You're a little on edge. And we need that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
