<HEADER>
A1197 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MCCAIN-NYT &LR;      12-06 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: SENATOR McCAIN'S HEALTH  
(sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Dec. 7:
</P>
<P>
   The whispers about Sen. John McCain's temperament seemed to grow
in intensity as he moved up in the polls as a Republican
presidential candidate. So McCain's decision to release 1,500 pages
of medical records about his physical and mental health _ along
with a volley of self-deprecating jokes about his temper _ has the
look of a tactical coup. It also marks the start of the nation's
quadrennial discussion about how much the public is entitled to
know about a candidate's personal history.
</P>
<P>
   The tactical analysis is the easy part. McCain is running as the
candidate of self-revelation, even when the personal history that
is revealed has a few rough spots. The Arizona senator is betting
that the public will prefer candor about his past over packaging or
evasion. The approach has the obvious advantage of contrasting him
with Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who has refused to answer
questions about alleged cocaine use during an admittedly reckless
youth.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the underlying civic question? Voters have a
legitimate interest in the health and stability of potential
presidents. They clearly factor that information into their choices
in a variety of ways. The ``age issue,'' widely discussed in 1976
and 1980, did not stop Ronald Reagan. George McGovern's 1972
campaign never really recovered after it was disclosed that his
running mate, Sen. Thomas Eagleton, had received shock treatments
for depression. Paul Tsongas of Massachusetts, a presidential
candidate and cancer victim, called for a commission to study rules
for medical disclosures by candidates. History shows, of course,
that being president does not require either physical or
temperamental perfection. Consider Abraham Lincoln's gloominess and
Franklin Roosevelt's paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's disclosure should not set off a browbeating of other
candidates to match him detail for detail. But it does outline a
common-sense approach. Presidential health, like presidential
character, is an important public concern. Voters have a right to
look at anything that relates to ability to serve, including major
health issues in a candidate's life. Journalists have a
corresponding duty to be responsibly curious about these matters.
McCain's particular way of releasing information need not become an
exact requirement for other candidates, but it ought to prompt them
toward a corresponding openness appropriate to their own histories
and candidacies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
