<HEADLINE>
NESTLE SELLS COFFEE LABELS TO SARA LEE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SUZIE ST. JOHN 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Nestle USA Inc. committed to the company's new
Nescafe coffee line Monday by announcing the sale of its Hills
Bros., MJB and Chase &AMP; Sanborn coffee brands to Sara Lee in a deal
that includes the sale of Nestle's coffee plant in Suffolk, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the sale were not disclosed, but the purchased assets
have combined annual sales of about $280 million, according to Sara
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upon careful review of our coffee brands in the U.S. market,
we determined that it is best to focus our efforts and resources
toward the long-term growth of our new premium line of Nescafe, in
both retail and food service channels, as well as Taster's Choice,
one of the leading brands of instant coffee in America,'' said Joe
Weller, chief executive officer of Nestle USA based in the city of
Glendale in Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   The new Nescafe line was launched earlier this fall across the
West Coast, including Los Angeles, San Francisco, San Diego,
Sacramento, Denver, Phoenix, Salt Lake City and Boise, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line was designed to deliver a new coffee experience,''
said Terri Haywood, communications manager for Nestle's beverage
division.
</P>
<P>
   The product line offers 20 different coffee beverages in a
variety of flavors and textures, including gourmet whole bean and
ground coffee, gourmet instant coffee, Nescafe Frothe specialty
coffees and frozen coffees.
</P>
<P>
   Haywood said the line is targeting younger coffee drinkers
ranging in age from 25 to 34.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last statistics we have about coffee trends shows an
increase in younger coffee drinkers,'' Haywood said. ``We have an
ad campaign out with commercials being directed by (actor and
sitcom director) Michael Lembeck. They are nontraditional, looking
more like a sitcom.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being sold in retail locations, Haywood said
Nescafe is being sold at college campuses, restaurants, hotels,
movie theaters and self- and full-service coffee bars nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very committed to seeing the success of this brand in
the United States,'' Haywood said.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee has long been a competitor of Nestle in Europe, where
it sells coffee and tea under the Douwe Egberts, Marcila, Merrild
and Pickwick brands. Monday's acquisition adds three well-known
brands to Sara Lee's Chock Full o' Nuts, which the company bought
in October to enter the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sara Lee is in a leading retail position all over the world,
so it's logical that we would want to expand in the U.S.,'' said
Jeffrey Smith, director of media relations for the Chicago-based
Sara Lee Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Sara Lee is offering to hire the 210 employees at the
Suffolk plant in the same capacity or in comparable jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The employees were notified of the sale (Monday) and senior
management was on site to meet with the employees,'' Smith said.
``We plan to continue operating the plant in its current location.
It allows us to be able to better balance production between retail
and food service.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there are no immediate plans to change the three
purchased brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little early to detail a broad marketing plan but
packaging and roasting quality are things we'll be evaluating,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
