<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1201 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ABANDONED-BABIES-NYT &LR;      12-06 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABANDONED-BABIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARAMEDICS' GROUP ARRANGES FUNERALS FOR BABIES WHO ARE ABANDONED TO
DIE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTBURY, N.Y. _ The early morning sun shone brightly on the
tiny coffin coated in white velvet. It sat next to a heap of earth,
ready for burial, among the brass plaques marking graves adorned
with rubber ducks, pacifiers and toy Santas.
</P>
<P>
   The newborn girl, Mary Hope, had been found dead in a bag by
workers sorting through recyclables and trash trucked to a Brooklyn
plant. So for the 11th time in a year and a half, Timothy Jaccard,
a Nassau County paramedic, stood graveside on Saturday with a
clutch of fellow paramedics, police officers and strangers,
grasping for the right thing to say about a baby found in the
garbage.
</P>
<P>
   ``She will rest in peace with her brothers and sisters,''
Jaccard said, his voice catching.
</P>
<P>
   Her ``brothers and sisters'' _ tossed away in the trash,
suffocated in bags, smothered in shallow graves _ lay in a long row
to her right, two to a grave on a triangular median at Holy Rood
Cemetery in Westbury.
</P>
<P>
   There is Jonathan Hope, found in March 1998 in a bag tucked into
some bushes in Albertson and buried on April 14 of that year.
Matthew Hope, found that same month in a pile of garbage at a Bay
Park sewage plant. Faith Hope, found in a shallow grave in Freeport
by a curious dog. Holly Hope, wrapped in a blanket with a piece of
holly, found in May 1998 decomposing in a shallow grave at, of all
places, Holy Rood. Noel Hope, discovered by a passer-by in December
last year, in a garbage can in the Bronx. Christina, Gabriella,
Angel, Christine _ all abandoned, all dead.
</P>
<P>
   Jaccard, 50, could save none of them, but at least, he said, he
has found a way to accord the most vulnerable victims the ``dignity
and identity that every human being deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been this way since he and fellow ambulance medical
technicians of the Nassau County Police Department on Long Island
formed the nonprofit amT Children of Hope Foundation Infant Burial
Inc. last year.
</P>
<P>
   Run largely from a table in the recreation room of Jaccard's
home in Wantagh and financed with money from fraternal lodge dances
and Heart of Hope pins, the foundation legally adopts the babies
after police officers have exhausted their investigations; the
members then arrange a funeral Mass and burial, full of ceremonial
touches normally reserved for fallen comrades.
</P>
<P>
   A motorcade escorts the hearse to the church and cemetery.
Bagpipes wail ``Amazing Grace.'' Crisp salutes abound as two
pallbearers, often Jaccard and a fellow paramedic, carry the
coffin. All of the infants are given the surname Hope, but the
first names have come from Jaccard or people involved in their
cases.
</P>
<P>
   The paramedics involved with Children of Hope say it provides
closure, a way to resolve the inner emotional turmoil that keeps
eating away as they rush from pumping the chest of the crumpled
child at a car accident, to picking up the pieces after a ``suicide
by train,'' to clutching the hand of a moribund gunshot victim
begging not to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a professional,'' said Ronald Kahl, a paramedic and a
member of the foundation's board. ``You do what you have to do, and
then you go home and cry and hug the kids and go back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaccard, a paramedic for almost 25 years, knows the drill. But
the stiff upper lip began to quiver after his assignment to the
morgue detail a few years ago. He drives the white unmarked van
that arrives to pick up the dead, whether at a crime or accident
scene or hospital. He collects the evidence, photographs the body,
straps it to a gurney and wheels it away.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1997, he was called to the Nassau County courthouse in
Hempstead. He entered a bathroom stall and found an infant only
hours old stuffed in a toilet bowl. He began to weep and could not
stop. He is not sure why. Maybe, he figured, it was because his own
daughter was enduring a difficult pregnancy. Court officers and
paramedics arranged a funeral for the child _ named Baby Angelica
by a court officer _ after she remained unclaimed for three months
in the morgue, nagging at Jaccard as he returned from his rounds.
Jaccard, a former florist, arranged the flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Several months later came another call. A newborn stuffed in a
plastic bag discarded in bushes in Albertson. Jaccard picked up the
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, my God, not another child,'' he recalled. ``Why is
this happening? Why am I getting it?''
</P>
<P>
   Motivated by the senselessness and his Roman Catholic faith, he
resolved to ensure that such children at least had a dignified
burial.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation enlisted nearly every paramedic in the county,
close to 100, though the 7 on the board do most of the work. They
got a local funeral home, Charles J. O'Shea, to donate most of the
cost of preparing and transporting the bodies. They bought plots at
Holy Rood. They now have space for only six more infants.
</P>
<P>
   They began raising money, $22,000 so far this year, through
dances at the Knights of Columbus hall and the sale of Heart of
Hope pins for $10 apiece, and by accepting donations.
</P>
<P>
   They sponsor a help line _ (516) 679-1111 _ for mothers or
fathers who may be inclined to abandon or dispose of their infants,
referring them to the Long Island Crisis Center in Bellmore.
</P>
<P>
   Jaccard often answers the phone calls himself, and sometimes,
with his wife or a friend in tow, he meets the callers, so far all
women, to encourage them not to dump their babies. He said he was
confident that of the 100 calls to the line, at least 7 women
intent on abandoning their babies chose to give them up for
adoption or made arrangements to keep them.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has posters and pamphlets displayed at clinics,
counseling centers and train stations imploring people not to
abandon their babies.
</P>
<P>
   Jaccard's ambition hardly flags. He operated his first business,
a car wash, as a 15-year-old growing up in Wantagh. After college,
he opened two floral shops. In the early 1970s, when the economy
slowed during the energy crisis, he got a job with the county
Police Department as a paramedic.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, more than 80 turned out for the Mass at St. Agnes
Cathedral in Rockville Centre. The Blue Knights of New York, a
police motorcycle club, provided an escort. The Hempstead Police
Department color guard handled the flags. The service drew mostly
paramedics and their friends as well as prayer groups and some
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, as the cathedral bell pealed, Mary Hope was carried
to the hearse for the procession to the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   O'Shea of the funeral home said a few words and then Jaccard
stepped forward. He paused, cleared his throat and took notice of
the other infants his group had buried. ``I find it hard to
wonder,'' he said. ``How do I hold back? But I do. I go on hoping
that we do not have to do this again. Thank you for coming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1202 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-RYAN-ART-NYT &LR;      12-06 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RYAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES RYAN, 57, RESTORER OF HISTORIC MANSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Kan.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Ryan, the manager of the Olana State Historic Site near
Hudson, N.Y., who oversaw most of the restoration of the
Persian-style Victorian mansion that the 19th-century painter
Frederic Edwin Church built high above the Hudson, died on Nov. 29
at Albany Medical Center in Albany, N.Y. He was 57 and lived in
Catskill, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was renal failure, said Karen Zukowski, curator at
Olana. Ryan received a kidney transplant 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When Ryan became manager of Olana in 1979, it had been owned by
the state for 12 years, and much of the work had already been done
to make its extraordinary hilltop location publicly accessible. But
the house was in dire need of repair and restoration, even though
its ground-floor rooms had been maintained much as Church had left
them when he died in 1900. (The home's last occupant had been
Church's daughter-in-law, who died in 1963.)
</P>
<P>
   Church made his fortune as a painter of the New World, but the
house, which many consider an artwork equal to his paintings,
reflects his later interest in ancient cultures and was stimulated
by trips to the Middle East in the late 1860s, just as he was
beginning to build Olana.
</P>
<P>
   The house's interior was accented with Persian and Persian-style
tiles and, like its exterior cornices, was elaborately stenciled
with patterns that Church borrowed from books about Persian
culture.
</P>
<P>
   The decor represented an eclectic sensibility and a lifetime of
collecting, mixing Aesthetic Movement furniture and paintings by
Church and his contemporaries with old master paintings and objects
from all over the world, among them Mexican folk art, painted
chairs from India, Middle Eastern armor and Far Eastern ceramics.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan knew Olana's elaborate history inside out. He gave
fascinatingly comprehensive house tours that chronicled the
restoration process, provided detailed origins of individual
objects and their roles in Church's vision of each room, and he
explained how the house was a carefully constructed reflection of
Church's ideas about art, religion and nature.
</P>
<P>
   For some visitors Ryan might end the tour with a clamber through
the attic, up the ladder on Olana's fourth-story porch and into the
crow's nest, with its stupendous view of the Hudson stretching
north and south against the green shoulders of the Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan was involved with history and its objects for most of his
career. He was born in Kansas City, Mo., in 1942, and graduated
from the University of Notre Dame in 1966 with a degree in American
intellectual history. In the late 60s he worked at the Kansas State
Historical Society in Topeka, and from 1970 to 1975 he was the
curator of the Kansas City Museum of History and Science in
Missouri, where he was also a researcher for the landmarks
commission from 1972 to 1974.
</P>
<P>
   He worked briefly for the Society of the Preservation of New
England Antiquities and came to the Hudson River Valley in 1977,
first as site manager for the Senate House State Historic Site in
Kingston, N.Y. That year he also earned a master's degree in museum
administration from the Cooperstown Graduate Program, part of the
State University of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan also applied his preservationist instincts to the landscape
surrounding Olana, becoming deeply involved with land management
issues in the Hudson Valley. In the early 80s he was part of a
legal effort that blocked the construction of a nuclear power plant
near Olana, the first case that brought a denial on aesthetic
grounds for the preservation of a historic site's view.
</P>
<P>
   He was a proponent of scenic easements, in which landowners are
compensated for clauses in their deeds that prohibit development,
and he served on the boards of the Columbia County Historical
Society, the Catskill Public Library, the Greene County Historical
Society and Hudson River Heritage. His house in Catskill was
perched above the river and had a direct view of Olana.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan is survived by his companion, David Seamon, a professor of
architecture and environmental psychology at Kansas State
University in Manhattan, Kan.; his sister, Esther, and his brother,
John, both of Kansas City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
