<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBLICANS-DEBATE-NY     12-06 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICANS-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURTESY RULES AT DEBATE OF 6 GOP CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Resisting their first opportunity to attack one
another directly on national television, six Republican
presidential candidates treated one another courteously Monday
night as they touted their stance on foreign policy, taxes,
education and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a forum last week in New Hampshire, in which Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas took part for the first time and was the favorite
target of the other candidates, this time the contenders were more
subtle in contrasting themselves with Bush, the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates, gathering at the Orpheum Theater, were allowed
to question one another. But mostly their questions sounded like
recitals of their own credentials.
</P>
<P>
   When the candidates had the opportunity to ask questions, it was
no surprise that the first up, Gary Bauer, turned his attention
toward Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, who has made human rights abuses in China a principal
issue in his campaign, asked Bush why he, like President Clinton,
favored more open trade with China, as opposed to a sharper
confrontation with China.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the way President Reagan dealt with the Soviet
Union, Bauer asked Bush, ``Why not follow a Reagan policy rather
than a Clintonian policy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how to insult a guy,'' Bush said, adding: ``I believe
competitors can find common ground. I think it's in our country's
best interest to open up China to Arizona farm products, to Iowa
farm products.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also in our best interest to make sure the
entrepreneurial class in China flourishes,'' Bush said. ``If you
give people a breath of freedom, a taste of freedom, I think you'll
be amazed, Gary, at how soon democracy will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer asked, ``Is there no atrocity that you can think of that
would tell you to put trade on the back burner?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush replied: ``If we turn our back on China and try to isolate
China, things will get worse. Imagine if the Internet took hold in
China. Imagine how freedom will spread.''
</P>
<P>
   The first round of questions for all six candidates concerned
education, and each candidate used his response principally as an
opportunity to state his general views on the federal government's
role in public education. Those views were alike to the point of
being nearly identical: All the candidates emphasized clear, finite
limits to federal involvement and many advocated at least some
experimentation with vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bauer and Alan Keyes rued the flight of prayer and religion
from classrooms, with Bauer citing that as a reason for violence in
schools. ``I don't think this is a gun problem, as some might
suggest,'' Bauer said. ``I think it's a problem of the heart and
soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes agreed, saying, ``Since we took prayer out, we seem to
have let violence and decline in.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah and Bush talked up the virtues of
vouchers, although Bush did not use that word. Bush reiterated his
frequently stated belief that schools that receive federal funds
should face consequences if the children in those schools are
failing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that if the federal government spends money on the
poorest of the poor children, we need to ask a simple question,''
said Bush. ``What are the results? What are the results?''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona was reminded of a statement he has
repeatedly made that good teachers should make more than bad
senators, whose salary will rise to $140,000 in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that I would never allege that there are any bad
senators,'' McCain joked. Then, making light of questions that have
been raised about his temper, added: ``I win Miss Congeniality
every year in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes said that tax reform would in fact help improve
education, because parents would be better able economically to
choose schools for their children. ``The combination of genuine tax
reform, where parents can make quality of life decisions, and
allowing parents to choose the schools that work for their children
_ that's the way to move forward,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   In a move to prevent his rivals from ganging up on Bush, CNN set
ground rules that prohibited the candidates from all using their
allocated question for another candidate on the same person.
</P>
<P>
   McCain did not travel to Arizona to share the stage with his
competitors because, his campaign said, he had long-scheduled
events in New Hampshire and New York on Monday and Tuesday. But
after CNN agreed last week to include him by satellite, McCain put
off a town meeting set for Guilford, N.H., Monday night and agreed
to participate. Polls here show that McCain faces a potent threat
from Bush in Arizona, where the primary is Feb. 22. The Republican
governor, Jane Dee Hull, has endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The battle between McCain and Bush in New Hampshire, the state
with the first primary, has grown particularly competitive. Three
new polls in that state _ by Newsweek, Gallup and Quinnipiac
College _ show the race is statistically even.
</P>
<P>
   In an interesting indication of how eager McCain's campaign is
to nullify the lingering issue of his temper and contradict any
assertions that McCain will have trouble winning Arizona, his home
state, three lawmakers who support him held a news conference an
hour before the debate to promote their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., underscored the public release of
McCain's medical records and basically implored the scores of
reporters in the press room near the Orpheum Theater to let that be
the end of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to put an end to it and focus on the issues in the
campaign,'' Kyl said. ``If anything, he has a right to brag about
his temperament,'' given everything he has been though.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz., said: ``Releasing those records is
not a smoke screen. If anything, it's a shining light.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Groscost, speaker of the Arizona House, noted that about 60
mayors in Arizona had endorsed McCain and that more were being
added to that list every day. He acknowledged that a few Republican
officials have not chosen to support McCain. Gov. Hull was clearly
on his mind, though he did not specify her.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost also, interestingly, took pointed note of the fact that
McCain was a master of policy who, if people would stop asking him
about his temper, would be able to show that. The unspoken
comparison was with Bush. ``He gets into the meat of the issues,''
he said. ``He understands them. He can articulate them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
