<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-VH1-FASHION-ART-910&AMP;A     12-06 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VH1-FASHION-ART-910&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOGUE PAINTS A FACE ON VH1 AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Heaven forbid that Minnie Driver, or any other hip
celebrity with nothing better to do on a Sunday night than to
stroll up another red carpet in New York, should wander backstage
in her ravishing couture frock with little sparkles scattered
around the hem and encounter ... a reporter. How hideous! How rude!
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to ask any questions, are you?'' a press
agent said to a reporter on the way into the green room, marked
``Talent Holding,'' at the 69th Regiment Armory on Lexington
Avenue, where the VH1/Vogue fashion awards were being broadcast
live.
</P>
<P>
   Out front, about 1,200 guests were packed into chairs and
risers. Sharon Stone and Rupert Everett were there. So were Tom
Ford, Alexander McQueen, Donatella Versace, Faith Hill and Sandra
Bullock. Beck had just finished performing. As he and his handlers
were rushing backstage, the photographer Roxanne Lowit, in the
voice of Eliza Doolittle calling for tuppence, asked if she could
take one picture. But the singer never looked up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the extravagantly named green room, the only thing
holding seemed to be a doubt about whether anything spontaneous
would happen that evening _ a glimmer of flesh-and-blood life
beyond the red-carpet smiles and artificial-plant poses, a sign
that the fashion crowd, at least, could still be counted on for
some real thrill and surprise.
</P>
<P>
   But alas, everyone who had been nominated for an award knew in
advance whether he or she had won, as a result of a distribution
glitch by Vogue, which announced the winners last week on the cover
of its January issue.
</P>
<P>
   And as if to underscore the evening's sense of predictability,
all the designers nominated for the top design award _ Calvin
Klein, Ralph Lauren, Donna Karan, Giorgio Armani, Ford of Gucci _
not only appear regularly in Vogue, but are also, through their
companies, among the magazine's top advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Driver, she had barely entered Talent Holding, when,
seeing no one but a couple of technicians and photographers eating
rolls and what looked like Green Giant Corn Niblets, she suddenly
turned and bolted.
</P>
<P>
   Undeniably, Vogue and its editor in chief, Anna Wintour, brought
flair and status to the VH1 awards. The show moved swiftly, without
windy speeches or bombing jokes, and the fashion segments, all
coordinated by Candy Pratts Price, a former Vogue editor, and
modeled by runway pros like Giselle and Maggie Rizer, reflected
Vogue's sense of mainstream fashion tastes as well as its powerful
clout with the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're getting what you want,'' Ms. Price said _ meaning that
Vogue was getting what it wanted _ one afternoon before the show.
For instance, when she asked Klein to produce more styles in the
blue-dyed python he had used sparingly, but effectively, in his
recent spring collection, he did so. When she called Manolo Blahnik
for shoes, hundreds of pairs arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We offered the design world to all the presenters,'' Ms. Price
added. That might mean, she said, ``a video, a look-book from the
collection, sometimes a rack of clothes'' delivered to their homes.
``It's not like they're going over to 550, you know what I mean?''
Ms. Price said, referring to 550 Seventh Ave., where Ms. Karan,
among others, has her headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   She worked with the show's hosts _ Heather Locklear, who during
the two-hour program changed from Versace into Dolce &AMP; Gabbana into
Gucci, and Puffy Combs, who wore, among other things, a full-length
Fendi chinchilla coat, a white fedora wrapped around a head scarf
and many diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Price recalled that Combs, who conducted his fittings in a
suite at the Peninsula Hotel, told her that his credo was
``marination creates style'' _ that is, he likes to mix things up _
and that she immediately telephoned Ms. Wintour and the magazine's
editor at large, Andre Leon Talley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Anna, I told Andre,'' Ms. Price said with
characteristic stage presence. ```Marination was it for me. I
marinate!'''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly guests arriving at the armory were counting on Vogue
to add some glamour to the event, which was the first in a week
heavy with fashion galas, including the annual Costume Institute
dinner Monday night at the Metropolitan Museum, and the opening of
the LVMH Tower on East 57th Street Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vogue has a point of view,'' Ms. Karan said, clutching her
wrap, ``and it will be very interesting to see how the whole thing
gets orchestrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Mizrahi, who designed the show's shiny white curvilinear
set, acknowledged that such events can be boring but said Ms.
Wintour ``knows how to make something great when she has her way.''
As for his set design, Mizrahi added: ``Oh, I wanted it to look
like an airport. I don't know, airports are so pretty and modern,
and when I was little my mother used to take us to JFK for lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Ms. Wintour, who was dressed in Gucci (Ford was
named designer of the year during the evening), said, ``It was a
show very much with a life of its own before we joined up, and
although we'd been advising behind the scenes, we have a more
active role this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Ms. Price described the magazine's role, ``We know how to
make it look like Vogue.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a way, that was precisely the trouble with the show. It
didn't reflect the diversity of fashion or popular culture. It was
slick, all right, but without the element of surprise or
spontaneity that would lift it from the banally commercial.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The mood showed up, too, in the controlling atmosphere
backstage, with all the handlers. ``They don't allow you to catch
the moment,'' a photographer said. ``You just have a movie star or
celebrity smiling at you, and every picture looks the same and
every photographer has the same picture. And at fashion shows, the
models used to walk down the runway in Pat Cleveland's era spinning
and turning and relating to the editors. Now they go straight
toward the video camera. They're not expected to have
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   There were exceptions, notably Lil' Kim, who looked like a
gossamer butterfly in see-through tulle pants and a sequined mask.
And then there was Combs, who was hardly ready to be cowed by
establishment fashion. Asked about his fantastic-sounding credo, as
Ms. Price had related, he broke into a huge grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to let my clothes sit in the closet for about three
months and marinate, like a steak,'' he said. ``Then, gradually,
you know, I go in and figure it out. I mixed a lot of designer
labels with my own things. Which they don't like me to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's marination, not just conformity. Know what I'm
saying?''
</P>
<P>
   Standing backstage after the show, Combs seemed unusually
talkative, a relief after the one-liners offered by most of the
other celebrities. ``I don't have no fear when I dress, you know?''
he said. ``I don't go with majority rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all his exotic wardrobe changes in the show, he couldn't
single out a favorite. ``I loved it all,'' he said. ``The fur coat.
The classic things. The suit I'm wearing now.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed. ``I'm not trying to be political about it. I took my
time and marinated it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought he had outdone Ms. Locklear, his co-host, in
the style department, he put on a tough face. ``Heck, no,'' he
said. ``She had, like, 20 stylists, so she didn't fight fair.''
Then he laughed again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
