<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SUNDAY'S BIG WINNER IS FASSEL, WHO WILL BE BACK 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Monday morning, hours after perhaps the New York Giants'
biggest victory since they beat the Dallas Cowboys on the road in
the last game of the regular season two years ago to capture the
division with a 10-5-1 record. The Giants' hierarchy remained abuzz
Monday over the stunning victory against the Jets, and while the
status of Coach Jim Fassel was not a central topic among
management, it was definitely discussed, and a consensus emerged as
the day concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a collapse, Fassel will be back.
</P>
<P>
   It has been decided.
</P>
<P>
   Count on it.
</P>
<P>
   The owners Wellington Mara and Bob Tisch, the executive vice
president John Mara and the general manager Ernie Accorsi all want
Fassel back. And the desire for him to return is not lukewarm. It
is strong, almost gushing, spurred by the dominating victory over
the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   A high-ranking Giants executive said Fassel would be given a
multiyear contract extension at the end of the season because the
organization is more than happy with the head coach's dedication,
toughness and the way he handles his life in general, which is
exemplary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we go 1-3 or 0-4,'' the executive said, ``he will be
back. As long as this team keeps fighting the way they are, which I
expect, he will be back.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive added: ``The only way the thinking changes is if
there is a total collapse in the effort of the players, but I don't
see that. No one does.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his guess was that Fassel would sign a two-year
extension once the season was over.
</P>
<P>
   They could indeed lose their four remaining games, but a more
realistic scenario is that the injury-riddled Giants steal one, or
with a great amount of luck, two. The Giants, who are 6-6, probably
play the most brutal final four of any team in the National
Football League: at Buffalo, at St. Louis, home against Minnesota
and then Dallas on the road. The Rams and Vikings are Super Bowl
contenders, the Bills are always tough to beat at home, and Dallas
is a bitter division rival. The combined record of those four teams
before last night was 31-16.
</P>
<P>
   But do not be shocked if Fassel pulls a few miracles. Right now
the Giants are dangerous, and their hierarchy, wisely so, thinks
Fassel can build something off the drubbing of the Jets, not just
for this season, but over the next few years as well.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership wants Fassel back because his calm demeanor and
golly-gee looks betray an inner toughness that allowed him to
overcome the death of his mother and the rumors of his firing.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership wants Fassel back because he will never embarrass the
Giants: he is a good man with a good heart, and that does matter.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership wants Fassel back because he put his ego aside, handed
off the play-calling against the Jets to an assistant and then
publicly admitted such to reporters. How many coaches would be
secure enough to do that? Fassel saw that something needed to be
done about his offense and that he might have been the problem. He
stepped aside, for the good of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership wants Fassel back because he beat the Jets. Badly.
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons to feel encouraged about the future of
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   First, Accorsi is one of the most underrated talent evaluators
in the league, and two of his players are proving to be solid
choices. While it is still early to anoint quarterback Kerry
Collins as the next Phil Simms, Accorsi was right in that Collins
throws one of the most accurate footballs in the NFL, pretty
spirals that drop into the hands of receivers like apples from a
tree. Collins has turned into a leader on this offense, something
that Accorsi predicted but know-it-alls like me doubted. And
Accorsi was right about his second-round pick, Joe Montgomery, who
demonstrates the kind of excellent field vision that Rodney Hampton
once did.
</P>
<P>
   Second, defensive end Michael Strahan, after his chaotic week,
deserves credit for the victory over the Jets by keeping the
defense from disintegrating. Strahan's critical remarks about
Fassel last week while the coach attended the funeral of his mother
might have been ill-timed, but they were needed. Strahan saw how
his defense was sagging, on the verge of giving up on the season,
and knew something needed to be done to rally his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   What most people do not know is that Strahan has spent
inordinate amounts of energy trying to keep the spirits of his
defensive teammates up, meeting with some of them individually in
the locker room or on the practice field, asking everyone to stay
focused.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a day, months or years from now, when Fassel looks
back at this brutal past week and feels both exhilaration, because
he and his staff completely outcoached Bill Parcells, and sadness,
because his mother died.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel did both, and more, these past few days. He also saved
his job. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
