u s BC-FBC-ARMY-SUTTON-NYT     12-06 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARMY-SUTTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUTTON DISCHARGED BY ARMY AFTER 9 YEARS AS COACH 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years after he guided Army to a record 10 victories and
won the Bobby Dodd Coach of the Year Award, but two days after his
team's third consecutive losing season, Bob Sutton was fired Monday
as Army's coach.
</P>
<P>
   The firing of the 48-year-old Sutton after nine years at West
Point was announced in the wake of the Cadets' 19-9 loss to Navy on
Saturday, their fourth consecutive defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Taking over as the coach after eight seasons as an assistant,
Sutton had had only two winning seasons, in 1993 when the Cadets
were 6-5, and 1996 when Army went 10-2.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the loss to Navy cost Sutton his job, Army's first-year
athletic director, Rick Greenspan, who announced Sutton's
dismissal, said: ``The way we played reinforced the concerns we had
over the course of the year. It was a huge game and in some degree
it was a reflection of games throughout the season. Wins and losses
are a huge factor in these decisions, and we feel that we did not
perform particularly well at the end of the season, particularly on
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   No successor was named, but Greenspan said he had already begun
a search.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a number of people in mind,'' Greenspan said. ``We've
already been visiting with some people and have fielded some phone
calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan indicated that academy officials had hoped to be more
competitive in Conference USA, which Army joined last year.
</P>
<P>
   Army had been an independent, whose schedule usually included
several Division I-AA teams such as Lafayette, Colgate, Yale and
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   This year's schedule, by contrast, included games _ both
one-sided loses _against two top-25 teams, East Carolina and
Southern Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that we have upgraded but we feel we should
compete for the conference championship,'' Greenspan said, ``and we
will compete.'' Sutton's teams had competed well against Navy,
winning six of nine games, including five straight from 1992
through 1996 when the Cadets, led by quarterback Ronnie McAda, made
only their fourth bowl appearance. Army had beaten Navy last
season, but that was only the Cadets' third victory of the year.
This season, Army finished at 3-8 for a second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand college football, I understand the coaching
profession, I understand bottom-line philosophy,'' Sutton said. ``I
was only interested in having the opportunity to finish what I
started and to finish what I was promised. I was probably too
idealistic because I felt the academy would not compromise one of
its principles and one of its real bedrock values.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had been under pressure from West Point's alumni,
Greenspan said, ``There are a number of constituencies that we seek
advice from, and we do seek advice and counsel from our grads,
absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton's nine-year tenure as coach, during which his teams won
44 games, lost 55 and tied 1, is surpassed in longevity only by
Earl (Red) Blaik who was the coach for 18 years, from 1941 through
1958.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said the decision to dismiss Sutton was reached in
Philadelphia Saturday night following the Navy game, and that
Sutton had been informed of his firing Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will fulfill our contactual obligations to Bob Sutton,''
Greenspan said. ``We just felt that we weren't progressing and that
the program required a change.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2236EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POST-EDITOR-NYT     12-06 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POST-EDITOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. POST EDITORIAL PAGE EDITOR, NOTED FOR SHARP TONGUE, STEPS
DOWN
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The editorial page editor of The New York Post, which
is known for its astringent, sometimes acerbic but always
conservative political voice, has resigned to focus on a variety of
writing jobs, including a twice-weekly column and a planned book
about the 2000 political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the editor, John Podhoretz, from top editor to
multimedia contributor to various outlets of Rupert Murdoch's
empire, followed a meeting on Friday afternoon with Kenneth
Chandler, The Post's publisher. Chandler characterized the move as
a reassignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been apparent to me for some time that we'd piled a lot
on his plate,'' Chandler said. ``He was responsible for the
editorial pages and the arts and leisure section seven days a week,
and it seemed to me it was too much. We had a discussion on Friday
and he basically agreed. I offered him the column and he agreed.
It's a good outcome for all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his twice-weekly Post column _ an expansion on
his earlier, occasional columns _ Podhoretz writes for the magazine
The Weekly Standard and is a commentator on Fox News. He said he
had resigned to concentrate on his writing. ``I'm burned out,'' he
said. ``It's been a wonderful but a very rough two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Podhoretz, 38, returns to writing in the midst of the undeclared
political battle between Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and Hillary
Rodham Clinton for the Senate. The Post has been quick to point out
actions and statements that seem to reflect badly on Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's tack on the campaign has been the subject of
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The attention prompted Podhoretz to write, in a column published
on Friday: ``Forgive me if I'm a little self-obsessed, but just
from reading this week's press clips on The New York Post, I have
grown drunk on my own power. Make no mistake, buddy _ cross me and
I'll squash you like a bug. Hey, if I can do it to Hillary Clinton,
the first lady of these United States, just imagine what I can do
to you!''
</P>
<P>
   Podhoretz's keen intellect and sometimes abrasive style won him
mixed reviews in his editing role. He made a public gaffe in July,
after the airplane crash that killed John F. Kennedy Jr., when he
wrote a satirical column along the lines that Joseph P. Kennedy had
sold his soul to the devil in return for his family's success.
</P>
<P>
   That column, which Chandler pulled from the July 22 newspaper
after it ran in one edition, was forgotten by the time Chandler met
with Podhoretz on Friday, Chandler said. The strongly negative
reaction to the column, he added, ``lingered only a couple of
weeks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
