<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FRONT-ROW-FASHION-ART     12-06 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONT-ROW-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE SILICON PLAINS OF TEXAS  
 REVVING UP HALSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike many of her generation, Ellen Enders, 34, is not readily
able to recite the history of Netscape or allude to things in Wired
magazine or otherwise speak with a cocktail-party knowingness about
this decade's high-tech revolution. Still, high tech has been good
to her.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1998, Ms. Enders, who had just completed turns working
as a design assistant for Oscar de la Renta and Randolph Duke,
received a call from Lori Light, a headhunter, that was nearly as
life-changing as a stock tip from Paul Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Light asked Ms. Enders if she'd be interested in meeting a
well-to-do Texan who hoped to start a fashion house and needed a
designer. The Texan happened to be Susan Dell, wife of Michael
Dell, chief executive of the computer company that bears his name,
the No. 1 personal-computer maker in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Dell clothes _ quiet suits, shift dresses and gowns that
wouldn't have appeared on ``Dallas'' _ will be sold only at Susan
Dell, the Charles Gwathmey-designed store she has just opened in
Austin, Texas, a city filled with Dell millionaires but with few
up-market boutiques to cater to them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dell studied fashion merchandising at Arizona State
University but was working in commercial real estate when she met
her future husband on a blind date in Austin in the late 1980s.
Finding no wedding dress that she truly loved, she decided to
design her own.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, she said, she began designing suits and evening
clothes for herself, as well as for friends and clients. Recently,
Ms. Dell, a mother of four, decided that she wanted to start a
full-fledged label and hand the designing duties to an expert.
</P>
<P>
   She met 10 young designers before choosing Ms. Enders. ``Ellen
has amazing hands,'' she said. ``I've taken pictures of her hands.
Her drawings dance off the page. My drawings lay there flat.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Enders left the University of Maryland to attend the Parsons
School of Design in New York. She helped produce fashion shows
before moving to Los Angeles at the encouragement of a childhood
friend, Adam Spiegel, now known as Spike Jonze, the movie director.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Enders had thought about working for Spiegel's skateboard
company, but landed a job instead with Richard Tyler. ``I owe him
everything,'' she said of the designer. ``He really let me develop
my talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Enders' first effort under the Susan Dell label was a
wedding dress decorated with seashells, which she designed for her
friend Julie Taubman, who married in August. The dress won raves
from guests like Tiffany Dubin, head of Sotheby's fashion
department and the bride's sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Dell's store is not offering menswear, though Dell is one
of the few high-tech billionaires who don't dress as though they
are going windsurfing. ``He's not a flannel-shirt dude,'' Ms. Dell
said. ``I would have changed that years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Revving Up Halston
</P>
<P>
   During the four seasons that Kevan Hall designed for Halston,
the label, alas, stirred as much buzz as an episode of ``Walker,
Texas Ranger.'' For its spring 2000 collection, in fact, Halston
did not even hold a runway show.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the company, which has been bought by Neema Clothing
Ltd., a men's clothing concern, announced that Hall had been
replaced by Craig Natiello, who worked for Bill Blass for 10 years,
most recently as Blass' senior designer. (Blass retired in
September. The fate of future ready-to-wear collections bearing his
name is uncertain. Another of his head designers, Laura Montalban,
has just moved to Oscar de la Renta.)
</P>
<P>
   Halston's chief executive, Nicholas DeMarco, said that Natiello
was chosen because he understood ``today's woman and her
lifestyle'' and has the talent to expand the Halston line into day
wear. DeMarco also acknowledged that Natiello's connection to
high-profile shoppers like Marina Rust (for whom Natiello designed
a wedding dress this year) was important in making the decision.
</P>
<P>
   One could argue that socialites might not be the best
representatives of ``today's woman.'' But Natiello promised that he
would be designing clothes ``not just for the lady who lunches, but
for the lady who works.'' He made another promise, too, which
should delight fashion editors and buyers. He said his fashion
shows would last no longer than 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Lazy, he is not. Natiello got his new job on Saturday and turned
out his first Halston piece, a velvet dress made over the weekend
for the house's public relations director, Laura Henson. She wore
it to the Costume Institute gala at the Metropolitan Museum of Art
on Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
