<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1212 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEBATE-COX     12-06 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Polite for the most part, candidates share views in debate
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The six GOP presidential contenders mixed it up Monday
night, albeit cordially, taking advantage of a debate format that
allowed them to question each other.
</P>
<P>
   The event was televised nationwide by CNN, with Arizona Sen.
John McCain participating via satellite from Boston, near where he
has been campaigning in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The event marked Gov. George W. Bush's second debate of the
season. He skipped several debates prior to showing up last
Thursday in Manchester, N.H. for a forum that was more simultaneous
news conference than debate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules of Monday's night at a Phoenix theater, each
candidate had two chances to question an opponent of his choice.
But in each round, each candidate could be targeted only once.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing the candidates to question each other hardly produced
fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They laid out their own positions, and they were all very safe
questions,'' said Diana Carlin, a professor of communication
studies at the University of Kansas. ``I was disappointed. I
expected a little bit more of going after what the other people are
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   In both rounds, the first questioner chose to question
frontrunner Bush. Bauer challenged him on China. Publisher Steve
Forbes challenged him on rising oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer noted that President Ronald Reagan never proposed trade
breaks for the Soviet Union. Bush wants the World Trade
Organization to accept China. Bauer said China, through human
rights abuses, has not earned it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there no atrocity you can think of that would tell you to
put trade on the back burner?'' Bauer asked Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush wouldn't budge from his belief that trade leads to
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we make China an enemy they will end up an enemy,'' he
said. ``If we trade with China and give people a taste of freedom I
think you will be amazed, Gary, at how soon democracy will come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we turn our backs on China and isolate China things will
get worse,'' Bush said. ``Imagine if the Internet took hold in
China. Imagine how freedom would spread.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes got to ask the first question in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will surprise you, Judy,'' he told moderator Judy
Woodruff of CNN. ``It goes to George Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes challenged Bush to come up with a plan to reverse recent
hikes in oil prices, triggered by OPEC production cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had no immediate plan, but said he would ``encourage
exploration'' and has great hope for the continued expansion of
natural gas use.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes was unsatisfied with the response, but Bush countered by
saying, ``Governors don't control the price of oil in America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to wean ourselves off foreign oil and rely on other
products,'' he said, echoing a popular political mantra dating back
to the gasoline lines of the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Bush used his two questions to elicit praise of his programs. In
the first round, though he could have questioned Forbes, Bush opted
to ask Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch what he would do to help the GOP draw
more minority votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You deserve a lot of credit,'' Hatch told Bush. ``You are one
of the Republicans who reached out to women and minorities. I think
that's one of the strongest things you have going for you.''
</P>
<P>
   In a follow-up, Bush spoke about his efforts to abolish social
promotion in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been a great governor,'' Hatch told Bush, adding,
however, that a term and a half as governor does not qualify Bush
for the White House. ``I should be president and you should have
eight years with me and, boy, you'd make a heck of a president
after eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, Bush asked McCain what he would do to
encourage faith-based organizations to provide social services, a
key plank in the Bush platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you are on the right track governor or George or W.
Bush,'' replied McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain took advantage of a Bush follow-up question to
challenge the Texan's belief that continuing surpluses will pay for
his proposed $483-billion tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not envision surpluses forever,'' said McCain. ``I take
the money for tax breaks out of wasteful spending and corporate
welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did last Thursday in New Hampshire, Bush played it close
to the vest, dishing out sound-bite-sized-chunks of his stump
speech whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only one.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are saying that he's just reciting lines from his
speeches aren't being fair. Yes, he's doing that, but so are the
others,'' said Dartmouth government professor Linda Fowler.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, McCain even pulled a line out of a Forbes speech
and asked, with a sly grin, ``Where have I heard that before?''
</P>
<P>
   Polls here have shown Bush in second place in Arizona, within
striking distance, of McCain. McCain led Bush 39 percent to 31
percent in Arizona in a late-October poll by the Media Research
Program at Arizona State University, but 18 percent of the voters
were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Republicans, who backed Steve Forbes in the 1996
primary, vote Feb. 22. McCain has been a ballot-box monster in his
Senate races, grabbing 70 percent of the vote in his 1998
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Since the New Hampshire debate, where his temperament came under
question, McCain has released more than 1,000 pages of medical
records related to treatment after his five years of captivity in
North Vietnam. The records show no reason why McCain, who
acknowledges he has a temper, can't serve as president.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Gov. Jane Dee Hull, who says she has seen McCain's
temper in action, is a Bush backer.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also was noted for his temper when he was an aide to
his father, although he hasn't lost as cool as governor. Fowler
said she detected signs of his old testiness during an exchange
with Forbes in Monday's debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the warmth and personal charm that he's noted for
simply doesn't come across on television,'' she said. ``People may
start to tease him about his temper.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's debate came as polls continued to show Bush with a
substantial lead nationwide, but in a neck-and-neck battle with
McCain in New Hampshire, where the Arizona senator hopes to turn a
Feb. 1 victory into a springboard to an upset.
</P>
<P>
   Several recent New Hampshire polls show McCain has closed the
gap to a statistical dead heat with Bush, who had double-digit
leads there in October.
</P>
<P>
   A Quinnipiac College poll released Monday showed Bush with
support of 37 percent of the 514 Republican respondents, putting
him just a point ahead of McCain. The poll, with a margin of error
of 4 percentage points, was conducted Friday through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
