<SLUG> BC-BELL-VODAFONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC-VODAFONE VENTURE CLEARS A HURDLE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic and Vodafone Airtouch PLC of Britain won
conditional approval from the justice department Monday for their
September deal to combine their United States wireless operations.
</P>
<P>
   But the two companies, along with GTE, which has agreed to merge
with Bell Atlantic, will have to get rid of billions of dollars
worth of cellular systems and millions of customers before they
allowed complete the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to foster competition, federal rules prohibit companies
from owning more than one major wireless system in any given
market. Because the three companies are each big wireless players,
they have significant overlaps from San Francisco to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   So the companies have agreed to dispose of systems with about
three million customers, covering almost a fifth of the United
States population, about 49 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the combined United States operations of the three
companies will become the nation's No. 1 wireless phone carrier,
with about 21 million ``proportionate'' customers and systems
covering about 90 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless companies use proportions to count their partial
interest in other carriers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
