<SLUG> BC-NY-BULLET-ART-ARREST-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES DROPPED IN DEALER'S BULLET EXHIBIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Charges were dismissed Monday against a prominent
Manhattan art dealer who was arrested two months ago after
displaying a sculpture of shotguns and pistols in her gallery and
having a vase full of live 9 mm cartridges for visitors to take
home.
</P>
<P>
   The dealer, Mary Boone, who called her brush with the criminal
justice system ``an adventure,'' had been charged with unlawful
distribution of ammunition. At the time, a police official said it
was ``irresponsible, at the very least'' for Ms. Boone to be
distributing the live ammunition to the public.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Barbara Thompson, a spokeswoman for Manhattan
District Attorney Robert Morgenthau, said that Morgenthau asked the
judge to drop the charges ``based on the facts of the case and a
review of the criminal evidence.'' If Ms. Boone does not break the
law in the next six months, the charges will be dropped and her
case sealed.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ms. Boone called the judge's decision ``a win
for the First Amendment'' and said that the night and day she was
held in the Manhattan Detention Complex was a ``kind of interesting
adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Art is the only thing I believe in, and I'm glad to be
arrested over it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Boone said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's battle with the Brooklyn
Museum of Art over the ``Sensation'' exhibition amounted to saying
that art is ``dangerous and bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken decades to make people feel safe and interested to
come to art galleries, and I want that to continue,'' Ms. Boone
said. She also said that what she called the mayor's censorship has
``strengthened the art world.'' Ms. Boone was arrested and the guns
and ammunition were confiscated after a New York Post reporter
questioned the police about them, officials said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Boone said that the artwork, by Tom Sachs, was a statement
against the commonness of violence and weapons. Visitors could take
the ammunition home in orange air-sickness bags as souvenirs. ``The
irony was the artist was making a statement against the
accessibility of guns and bullets,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, while praising Morgenthau for moving to drop the
charges, said Ms. Boone's arrest was not necessarily a First
Amendment case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very possible that she cannot display live bullets,'' he
said, but he added that he thought ``dragging her off, putting her
in jail,'' instead of simply warning her, was excessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the art in Brooklyn were not such a controversy, it would
have been handled in a low-key way,'' he said. ``The mayor is
creating a climate in New York that is chilling to expressive
people, to creativity.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Amy Adler, a New York University professor who teaches First
Amendment and art law, agreed that the arrest of Ms. Boone might
have been based on a bias against art or intellectuals. But Ms.
Boone was arrested because the artworks violated public-safety
standards, not because of their content or meaning, and so the
First Amendment protection of free expression would not protect the
display, Ms. Adler said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the police nor the mayor's office responded to telephone
calls on Monday asking for their comments.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Boone said she did not expect the current display at the
Mary Boone Gallery to draw any visits from the police. It shows
photographs of 700 artists and art dealers, collectors and critics,
and she has included a portrait of Giuliani among the critics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
