<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDERS EVENTS TO GO DIGITAL IN DEAL WITH CENTERSEAT.COM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Borders.com, the online spinoff of Borders Group, the nation's
No. 2 bookseller behind Barnes &AMP; Noble, has struck an alliance with
an Internet start-up to create virtual entertainment from thousands
of author lectures and appearances at Borders bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Called Borders Vision, the bookstore events will become video
material for Centerseat, a digital company based in New York that
was founded in the spring and is developing Internet programming
that will mix filmed scenes with opportunities to order products.
</P>
<P>
   For example, filmed segments of a Borders appearance by J.K.
Rowling, the author of the popular Harry Potter children's books,
will be shown online along with separate promotions for the books,
which can be ordered at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about moving the Borders brand name into an
entirely new arena,'' said Rich Fahle, a spokesman for Borders.com.
``I don't know where this will go, but we're creating a digital
media version of Borders that we're pretty excited about.'' He
estimated that Borders holds as many as 90,000 events featuring
authors and artists.
</P>
<P>
   Centerseat is preparing to introduce its new Web site,
Centerseat.com, which it calls ``an integrated entertainment,
information and commerce experience,'' early next year. Over the
last few months, the company has been signing deals with an
eclectic assortment of personalities to develop its Internet
programming.
</P>
<P>
   The Prague Symphony Orchestra and the State Opera of Prague
agreed in October to create programming for Centerseat, as did Ken
Robinson, host of the Travel Minute radio show. In November,
Centerseat announced programming deals with George Hirsch, a chef
who was also the host of a series on grilling for PBS, and James
Hong, an Asian-American actor who will be the host of a martial
arts show and a celebrity cooking show, ``In the Kitchen with James
Hong.''
</P>
<P>
   Centerseat was founded by its chief executive, Scott Harmolin,
who sold his company, Icon CMT, to Qwest Communications last
September in a $185 million stock trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
