<SLUG> BC-NY-BALLET-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLET AND STRIKING ORCHESTRA REACH TENTATIVE PACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A tentative agreement has been reached between the
New York City Ballet and its orchestra, which has been on strike
for two weeks over proposed new work rules.
</P>
<P>
   The ballet has performed its traditional holiday offering, ``The
Nutcracker,'' to taped music in the orchestra's absence.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was reached on Friday between the ballet
management and a negotiating team from Local 802 of the American
Federation of Musicians. Before the agreement can take effect, it
must be ratified by the orchestra's 70 members. A vote began Monday
and is expected to conclude Tuesday afternoon, when the tally will
be announced.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the company said it hoped the musicians would
return to work in time for Tuesday night's performance at the New
York State Theater at Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has had little effect on ticket sales, which are
always strong for this perennial seasonal classic.
</P>
<P>
   The main issue in the negotiations, which began early last
month, was a demand by City Ballet for more stringent attendance
rules at rehearsals and performances. Musicians and management were
said to have agreed on attendance rules that would apply to all
members of the orchestra, rather than to new members only, as the
ballet had proposed.
</P>
<P>
   The union had feared that two sets of work rules would divide
its membership and weaken the union.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side would divulge details of the settlement before the
conclusion of the ratification vote.
</P>
<P>
   The company wanted newly hired musicians to play six
performances a week and rehearse twice weekly. There is no
rehearsal requirement now. Under the company's original plan,
current orchestra members could voluntarily accept the new rules
and receive pay increases.
</P>
<P>
   The City Ballet had also offered the musicians a 3.7 percent
increase in the first year of a multiyear contract. The musicians
are under contract to play 23 weeks a year, with a base salary of
$35,000. The ballet said orchestra members earn an average of
$66,000 a year when seniority and benefits are included.
</P>
<P>
   For years, union musicians playing for City Ballet and other
dance troupes have been allowed unpaid leaves from rehearsals and
performances if qualified substitutes could be found. Christopher
Ramsey, the company's director of external affairs, said the new
attendance rules were ``to ensure the highest possible level of
quality for our performances.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Macourt, a bassoonist, said the company's scheduling created
problems for musicians with other commitments, particularly since
rehearsal schedules are announced just before the start of each
season. By that time the musicians have often booked other
engagements. ``Other jobs don't fit neatly into holes in the New
York City Ballet schedule,'' Macourt said.
</P>
<P>
   The musicians walked out on the evening of the company's
opening-night gala performance, which was canceled. Management
turned down a musicians' offer to continue performing for six
months under an extended contract during negotiations, with a 4.5
percent wage increase. Both sides agreed that the musicians would
play through holiday performances of ``The Nutcracker,'' which
opened on Nov. 26.
</P>
<P>
   But the musicians refused to play through the spring if
negotiations were not concluded. City Ballet then said it would
perform ``The Nutcracker'' to taped music, an action that the
musicians said amounted to a lockout.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers, represented by the American Guild of Musical
Artists, and the stagehands, members of Local One of the
International Alliance of Theatrical Stage Employees, have
continued to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
