<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 ARRESTED AT RALLY AGAINST CRACKDOWN ON HOMELESS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saying they wanted to test the mayor's pledge that
homeless people would not be arrested merely for being homeless, 10
people, including the Rev. Al Sharpton, were arrested Monday night
after they spread tents and tarps and sat down on a wet concrete
patch of City Hall Park.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the protesters were arrested because they had
broken Parks Department rules by trying to camp. One by one, the
three women and seven men were handcuffed and led to a police van
on Broadway. A clutch of other protesters, who seemed to be
outnumbered by police officers, kept up a steady refrain. ``No
housing, no peace,'' they chanted. ``No jobs, no peace. No justice,
no peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The exercise, part of larger rally that police say drew about 50
people, took no more than 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Vincent Gravelli, a police spokesman, said the
protesters were cited for unlawful camping, erecting a structure in
a park, demonstrating with more than 20 people without a permit,
and failing to comply with police orders.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the protesters, Michael Hardy, said camping was not
part of their plans. ``They took the tarpaulins to sit on because
the ground was wet,'' he said. ``They weren't trying to camp.''
</P>
<P>
   The protest Monday night was the latest display of public outcry
directed at Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's recent initiatives against
homelessness. Giuliani has said he will require the homeless to
work for their shelter, and the police have begun to arrest
homeless people who refuse shelter and insist instead on sleeping
on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, protesters led by the Coalition for the Homeless, a
citywide advocacy group, held a rally and an all-night vigil in
Union Square Park. The police warned that the protesters would be
arrested if they fell asleep or lay down on the ground. With the
help of coffee and conversation and a man who sang Neil Young
tunes, they managed to stay awake and avoid arrest. Organizers said
the vigil drew about 90 people. Between 2:30 and 3 a.m., a renegade
group of six men and women walked across the street and lay down on
the sidewalk. They were issued summonses for disorderly conduct and
released.
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday, Police Commissioner Howard Safir had warned that
protesters who planned to erect what they described as a ``a tent
city'' at City Hall Park would be arrested. ``If you do set up a
structure, you are violating city regulations,'' Safir said at his
daily news briefing. ``If someone attempts to do that they will be
arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Reiterating the administration's position, Safir said that since
the heightened enforcement against homelessness, police officers
have arrested only those homeless people who break the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not arrest people for being homeless; we arrest people
who commit crimes,'' he said. ``Our people approach the homeless
and offer them assistance, offer to take them to a hospital, offer
to take them to a shelter. They are only arrested if they are
committing a separate crime which has nothing to do with the fact
that they are homeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Sharpton said he wanted to test the Mayor's promise.
``He said he's not arresting people for sleeping in the streets,''
Sharpton said of Giuliani. ``Only for breaking the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip Blumberg, who lives nearby, brought his 9-year-old son and
another child to watch the protests Monday night. It was not only
outrage at the mayor's crackdown on the homeless that brought him,
he said, but also his support for public protest in the newly
refurbished and sealed-off City Hall Park.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who was in Rochester Monday for a fund-raiser for his
potential United States Senate bid, said that in recent weeks, the
police had ``approached'' about 2,000 people who appeared to be
homeless and that 190 of them had been arrested. The charges
against them ranged from disorderly conduct and urinating in
public, to robbery and trespassing. He did not speak specifically
about the City Hall Park protest.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Hyatt Hotel in Rochester, a circle of nine
protesters greeted Giuliani with messages resembling those he has
heard in the city. They chanted, ``Stop picking on the homeless,
Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   One sign read, ``Giuliani kicks people when they're down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard terrible things from people in New York City,''
said one protester, Sister Rita Lewis, of the House of Mercy, a
religious group that works with the homeless in Rochester. ``We
don't want him representing us. He's just too mean, too mean to
poor people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
