<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ADAMS-MEMORIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT JOEY ADAMS MEMORIAL, A FEW MORE LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So there was this state senator who had to introduce
the other speakers at a memorial service, see. So to get things
going, he read a passage not from the Bible, but from Chapter 32 of
the bible of that club for aging comedians, the Friars.
</P>
<P>
   With not one but two jokes _ and an explanation, State Sen. Roy
M. Goodman began Sunday's service for Joey Adams, the borscht belt
comedian and humor columnist who died last week at 88.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joy was Joey's mantra,'' said Goodman, a Republican from
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Half the pews in the second-floor chapel had been set aside for
Friars Club members, and among the Friars who attended were Alan
King, the group's abbot, and Freddie Roman, its dean.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the crowd was a blend of figures from entertainment,
politics and the news media, including the New York City police
commissioner, Howard Safir, and Rupert Murdoch, the chairman and
chief executive of the News Corp., which owns the New York Post,
where Adams had worked.
</P>
<P>
   Others who attended the service included the actors Danny
Aiello, Alan Alda, Anthony Quinn, Jerry Stiller and Anne Meara; the
talk-show hosts Joan Rivers and Joe Franklin; the comedian Pat
Cooper; the theatrical producer Martin Richards; former Sen.
Alfonse M. D'Amato and Imelda Marcos, the widow of the dictator
Ferdinand E. Marcos. Mrs. Marcos had sung ``Happy Birthday'' to
Adams when he turned 80.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Goodman also quoted from a book by Adams, ``The God Bit''
(Manor Books, 1974). ``For a funny guy, there's a lot of theology
in there,'' Goodman said later. ``I actually found myself reading
it as a theological tract.''
</P>
<P>
   The passage he read from ``The God Bit'' was about a trip to
Indonesia _ where Adams said the temperature had been 105 degrees,
but his wife, Cindy, had had a fever that was higher. Then in a
torrent Adams remembered and recited all the spiritually based
one-liners that she had pasted on the refrigerator, her night table
and the bathroom mirror back home. They sang a few hymns, and she
got better.
</P>
<P>
   Monday Mrs. Adams, a celebrity columnist for the Post, said she
could not cry, explaining, ``I have false eyelashes on.'' She also
said that after her husband died, the first two calls she received
were from ``Rudy and Hillary'' _ in that order _ referring to Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani and Hillary Rodham Clinton, two likely
opponents in next year's race for the United States Senate seat
being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan. She added, ``I don't know
whether it's anything about the polls, but it was first Rudy.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at the Riverside Memorial Chapel laughed, as it did
often during the 45-minute service. After another joke or two,
Goodman introduced Rabbi Joseph Potasnik _ ``the radio rabbi,''
Goodman called him, referring to his appearances on a local news
station _ who led the crowd in reciting the 23rd Psalm. ``I don't
know if it's in the Friars' bible,'' Rabbi Potasnik said, ``but I
suppose the Friars know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Giuliani said that Adams ``loved people and he knew how to
make them laugh.'' Referring to Adams and his reverence for
Fiorello H. La Guardia, whom Giuliani called ``the legendary
greatest mayor,'' Giuliani suggested he might name the next airport
after Joey Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Adams talked about how Adams had introduced her to
celebrities and their world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did everything for me,'' she said, including starting her
on her career _ ``he gave me the Rolodex,'' she said at one point.
``And then I began to do everything for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Dr. David James Randolph, a former pastor of Christ
United Methodist Church in Manhattan, said Adams was ``the only
person I know who sang with Al Jolson, marched with Martin Luther
King and seemed to have lunch every day at the Friars Club.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I saw him, he was sitting up, a nurse at each
side,'' Dr. Randolph went on. ``I said, `Joey, are you
comfortable?' One beat and he said, `I make a living.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
