<SLUG> BC-NY-SUNY-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. UNIVERSITY SYSTEM PICKS PATAKI'S BUDGET CHIEF   AS
CHANCELLOR 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Struggling with a large deficit, the State University of New
York, the nation's largest university, is on the verge of choosing
Gov. George E. Pataki's budget director as the next chancellor of
the 64-campus system.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of the budget director, Robert L. King, announced
Monday by a search committee headed by the chairman of SUNY's
trustees, strengthens Pataki's influence at the university. Since
he took office, several former officials and allies have taken jobs
there.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas F. Egan, SUNY's chairman and head of the search
committee, said he thought King had the skills to work with the
campuses and to advance SUNY ``to the front ranks of American
public higher education.''
</P>
<P>
   But some critics have questioned whether the appointment of
leaders linked to the governor has politicized the university. They
say they fear that Pataki's intention is to install administrators
who will stress budget-cutting and efficiency, rather than academic
quality, and raise tuition while reducing the share of the budget
carried by taxpayers. Students at the four-year colleges pay $3,400
a year.
</P>
<P>
   The search committee voted unanimously to recommend King to the
full board of trustees, which is expected to approve the
appointment when it meets Dec. 14.
</P>
<P>
   King will replace John W. Ryan, an experienced educator and
longtime president of Indiana University, who started as interim
chancellor in 1996 and became permanent chancellor the next year.
He will remain a consultant and chancellor emeritus.
</P>
<P>
   The selection comes at a time when the university, which has
370,000 students and 27,000 faculty members, is facing a $77
million deficit in its $1.65 billion annual budget, caused by the
impact of the managed care era on teaching hospitals affiliated
with SUNY campuses.
</P>
<P>
   The State University is a sprawling archipelago of campuses in
virtually every corner of the state. It includes four research
universities _ in Binghamton, Stony Brook, Albany and Buffalo _ as
well as four-year colleges, community colleges and specialized
agricultural and technical colleges.
</P>
<P>
   But to the frustration of its own officials, none of the
campuses have the reputation of the great flagship campuses in
state systems like those in California, Texas and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   King, 52, has little experience in higher education other than
his work as a trustee for the Monroe County Community College
Foundation. But he is well versed in politics, finance and
administration, having served as a state assemblyman, the county
executive of Monroe County and, most recently, as state budget
director.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Daniels, a trustee who served on the search committee,
said King's extensive knowledge of the state and its budgetary and
political environment were significant factors in his choice.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McKeon, a spokesman for the governor, said King had
``played an important role in the changes Governor Pataki has
brought about in this state over the last five years.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, King, who describes himself as a strict
conservative politically and fiscally, said he thought his
friendship with the governor would be an asset for SUNY.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone can persuade the governor about the rightness of
something for the university, it is me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether that relationship might give the governor a
greater chance to shape SUNY policy, rather than the other way
around, King answered, ``Whatever it is I've been asked to do or
chosen to do, I've done with the guideposts of the best interests
of the people I'm serving.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The last thing that he would want or that I would
want at the end of the day is for someone to say, `These are the
guys who ruined the university.'''
</P>
<P>
   King will be SUNY's first chancellor appointed from outside the
academic life, at a time when universities and higher education
systems in states like Massachusetts, Oklahoma and Ohio have
increasingly looked outside their own ranks for top administrators
to bring managerial skills and a sense of accountability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2323EST &QL; 
