u a BC-MEDICAL-ERROR-ADVISER     12-06 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-ERROR-ADVISER-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HEALTH PROFESSION IS HIS WORST PATIENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During the dozen years he worked in emergency rooms,
Dr. Mark Chassin must have won high marks for his bedside manner.
Because even when he is agitated, his voice rarely registers above
a reassuring whisper, the kind you hear on classical radio stations
in the middle of the night when the DJ is introducing Debussy.
</P>
<P>
   The voice comes in especially handy these days, as Chassin finds
himself attending to another kind of patient, one that can be
notoriously resistant to treatment: the health profession itself.
</P>
<P>
   Chassin was one of a group of researchers who helped write a
recent report that gave credence to the worst fears of everyone who
has ever seen a loved one wheeled into an emergency room. The
report, issued by the Institute of Medicine, found that 44,000 to
98,000 hospital patients die every year from medical mistakes like
prescription mix-ups, misuse of equipment or surgical errors.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths outnumber those caused by highway accidents or by
breast cancer or by AIDS. As if the number needed to be further
underscored, another author said it was comparable to the death
toll from three jumbo jets filled with patients crashing every two
days.
</P>
<P>
   For many in the medical profession, it was a stunning
revelation. But it did not surprise Chassin, a former New York
state health commissioner and now a professor of health policy at
Mount Sinai Medical Center in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   It has been his calling, his obsession and, off and on through
the years, his paying job to serve as a kind of industrial engineer
for the medical profession, asking the same questions that airlines
ask of their pilots or even _ doctors might want to skip the rest
of this sentence _ carmakers of their assembly-line workers.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion that Chassin and others in the field have reached
is that medicine, the quintessential life-and-death business, lags
dangerously behind many other industries in its approach to errors.
While individual doctors are, by and large, zealously committed to
the safety of their patients, they work in a pressure-filled
environment with not enough thinking about how to ensure safety for
all patients.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Chassin put it the other day in his office: ``For years,
if quality ever came up, it was something like `We got rid of Dr.
Jones because he was drunk all the time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Manhasset as the grandson of a general
practitioner, the son of a general surgeon and the nephew of an
internist _ ``I've always had a stethoscope around my neck _ I
should have brought the baby pictures to prove it,'' he says _
Chassin was wondering about these issues by the time he was a
teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   On rounds with his father at the old Booth Memorial Hospital in
Queens, he would ask: ``What happens when someone isn't so good?
How do you fix that?''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was a doctor himself, in emergency rooms in
Southern California, he discovered that the problem was about much
more than questions of a doctor's competence.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled an incident he witnessed while on duty in which a
patient needed a dose of lidocaine to treat an irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   A surgical intern quickly grabbed a vial of the drug from the
emergency-room crash cart. Thinking that it would take too long to
inject it with a needle, he squirted it directly into the patient's
intravenous tube. But instead of the 100 milligrams he thought he
was using, the intern had grabbed a vial containing 2 grams of
undiluted lidocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he killed the patient,'' Chassin said.
</P>
<P>
   The story is the stuff of television dramas, but he tells it to
make a less dramatic point: ``This thing was sitting there, and it
was physically possible for it to be manipulated to connect it to
the wrong thing.'' After the mistake, he said, no one thought to
take the vial containing the higher dosage off the cart, and the
same mistake could have been repeated.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Over the years, Chassin, 52, has often been the bearer of
warnings that some in the medical establishment would rather not
hear.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he believes that traditional one- and two-doctor
medical practices are obsolete because most do not have the capital
to buy computers and other equipment needed to remain current with
rapidly changing medical technology.
</P>
<P>
   He believes that many medical schools are not preparing students
for a world in which scientific knowledge is expanding too quickly
for them to memorize even a fraction of it.
</P>
<P>
   Most strongly, he believes that the reluctance of hospitals to
admit and monitor mistakes must change if the system is going to
change. Borrowing from W. Edwards Deming, the late management guru,
he said, ``The guys don't come to the assembly line in the morning
wanting to screw up the parts as they go by.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the more complicated the systems are that we put people
in, the more liable they are to have circumstances where it's hard
to do a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a long interview in which Chassin expounds on
these issues in his soothing exam-room voice, a question naturally
comes up. What does his father, who recently retired, think of his
role as a kind of doctor to the doctors?
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably should not tell you this,'' he says, ``because I
don't think he'd like to see it in print, but he said he never
thought I'd make a living at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-06-99 2324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991206.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-06 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1364 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-NYT &LR;      12-06 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL SYSTEM IS FAULTED IN PAST DEALINGS WITH BRICK CASE SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVID ROHDE and SOMINI SENGUPTA    
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Judges, prosecutors and legal experts say last week's
arrest of Paris Drake, the man accused of bashing a woman with a
brick in Midtown, starkly revealed the inability of New York's
courts, prisons and parole system either to rehabilitate
drug-addicted petty criminals or to get them off the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Drake, 32, had been jailed nearly two dozen times since he was a
teenager, racking up a lengthy criminal record as a burglar, fare
beater and small-time drug dealer with a penchant for brawling. In
the past eight years, the longest he stayed out of jail was 17
days.
</P>
<P>
   As the extent of his record emerged in recent days, those most
familiar with New York's criminal justice system said in interviews
that it lacked the tools for dealing with low-level career
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and Gov. George E. Pataki, portraying
Drake as a dangerous predator who received too many slaps on the
wrist from judges, have proposed legislation that would sharply
increase the penalties for chronic low-level offenders. Robert M.
Morgenthau, the Manhattan district attorney, and others have called
for the appointment of more Criminal Court judges, so that the
overburdened system would rely less on plea bargains in misdemeanor
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Others have pointed to the system's failure to address what
could have been the engine of Drake's criminal career _ his drug
addiction. Two of the three felony convictions that landed Drake in
state prison were for drug sales. He was caught with drugs in
prison during his most recent stint. Almost every time he came up
for parole, he was ordered to seek substance abuse treatment. He
never did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly would appear to be a candidate for drug
treatment,'' said Tom Grant, a spokesman for the state parole
board. ``Except he didn't cooperate one iota.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake's first drug arrest came in 1991. By then, he already had
two felony convictions _ for attempted assault in 1987 and burglary
in 1988. Under the state's mandatory sentencing guidelines, he had
effectively forgone his chance at drug treatment as an alternative
to prison. Prisoners' advocates have called for the scrapping of
such mandatory sentencing guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mitchell Rosenthal, president of Phoenix House, the
country's largest drug treatment agency, said Drake's punishment
should have included treatment based on his ``total state of
dysfunction.'' But only during his third and latest stint in state
prison was Drake ordered into substance abuse treatment. James
Flateau, a spokesman for the State Department of Corrections, could
not provide details.
</P>
<P>
   Steven M. Fishner, the mayor's criminal justice coordinator,
said the laws proposed last week by the mayor and governor for
repeat misdemeanor offenders would remove chronic criminals like
Drake from the street. But Morgenthau, judges and the city bar
association have long said that the best way to ensure longer jail
terms for petty criminals is to pressure the state legislature to
appoint more Criminal Court judges.
</P>
<P>
   For the last five years, court officials have asked the
legislature to create 23 more Criminal Court judgeships in the
city, but disputes over political patronage have repeatedly
scuttled a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau said that New York's criminal courts, overwhelmed by
the crush of cases generated by the mayor's crackdown on quality of
life crimes, have been granting plea bargains in 99 percent of
misdemeanor cases in part because there are so few judges available
for trials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
