<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIGLE SETS THE TABLE FOR RANGERS' REVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If there is one thing that has hurt the New York
Rangers more than anything else this season, it has been their
inability to score on the power play. But the Rangers can score on
occasion with their goaltender pulled for an extra skater.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened Monday night at Madison Square Garden,
where Adam Graves tapped in a perfect pass from Alexandre Daigle
with 35.2 seconds left in regulation, enabling the Rangers to force
overtime against the Calgary Flames.
</P>
<P>
   Just 32 seconds into overtime, another pass from Daigle set up
Tim Taylor for the goal and a 3-2 Rangers victory. For Daigle, it
was his third assist of the game.
</P>
<P>
   For Taylor, who snapped Daigle's pass past Calgary goaltender
Fred Brathwaite, it was a vindication of sorts after the Flames had
nearly knocked him out of the game in the first minute.
</P>
<P>
   And for the Flames, who had been 5-0-2 in the overtime session
before Monday night, it was not only their first overtime loss of
the season, but it also prevented them from becoming the first
National Hockey League team to sweep the three metropolitan area
teams _ the Islanders, Devils and Rangers _ in successive road
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were 29 seconds away from entering the third period
with a two-goal deficit.
</P>
<P>
   But when Mathieu Schneider scored on a power play, it not only
halved Calgary's 2-0 deficit, but also marked the Rangers' first
goal this season with a five-to-three manpower advantage.
</P>
<P>
   It came on the Rangers' seventh power play of the game, and it
came after the Rangers had gone 0 for 6 with a man advantage,
dropping them to 8 for 109 on the power play this season.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider's third goal of the season came with Bobby Dollas in
the penalty box for interfering with Michael York at 18:56 of the
second period, just 14 seconds after Jarome Iginla had given
Calgary a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Dollas' penalty was compounded by one the Flames took at 19:35,
when they were caught with too many men on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   York won the ensuing face-off from Clarke Wilm. And after Wilm
slipped, the Rangers essentially had a 5-on-2 advantage, which
enabled Schneider a clear look at the net when Fleury slid a pass
to him at the top of the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider's one-timer eluded Calgary goaltender Fred Brathwaite,
stick-side, at 19:41. And the Rangers were back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Fleury, hounded by his former teammates all game, took a bad
penalty after the buzzer sounded to end the period. That offset the
final 1:25 of the the Flames had drawn for having too players on
the ice.
</P>
<P>
   The call against Fleury was for high sticking Martin St. Louis
well after the period had ended. St. Louis, a 5-foot-9-inch rookie
center, had gotten under Fleury's skin midway through the first
period, after Calgary defenseman Denis Gauthier had ridden Fleury
into the glass. Fleury was apparently going for a bit of revenge
when Referee Blaine Angus whistled him.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as St. Louis was bothering Fleury, Gauthier was
bothering the Rangers even more. He entered the gamet with only 16
penalty minutes in 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   But 34 seconds into the game, he leveled Taylor, who had his
head down along the right boards in the Calgary zone, with a
leaping left elbow to the head.
</P>
<P>
   That check went unpenalized. But when Darren Langdon retaliated
against Gauthier for the hit on Taylor at 2:42, Angus called it.
When Adam Graves retaliated against Gauthier for the clean hit on
Fleury at 10:28, Angus called that one, too. And when the Rangers
could not clear the puck from their zone for nearly a minute after
the double minor to Graves ended, the Flames scored the first goal
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   A former Ranger got it: Marc Savard, who poked a loose puck past
Mike Richter at 13:10 of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor came back for the second period after sitting out the
final 19:26 of the first. He too went after Gauthier, and drew a
double minor at 2:01. But the Flames came up empty; they went 0 for
4 on their power plays over the first two periods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
