<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-KINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST FOR ONE NIGHT, NETS SHOW HOW THEY CAN WIN 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N. J. _ For one night, the New Jersey Nets
finally got it right. They did not self-destruct when victory was
at hand. They did not let an early 10-0 deficit doom them for 48
minutes. And when Monday night's game was over, the Nets looked at
the final score and actually liked what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   Winning for only the third time this season, and ending a
five-game losing streak, the Nets defeated the Sacramento Kings,
109-95. The victory put New Jersey's record at a still-dismal 3-15,
but the team hoped Monday night's victory would be the start of
better things to come.
</P>
<P>
   There were many positives for the Nets, beginning with their two
best players, Stephon Marbury and Keith Van Horn, who led the way,
but who also received plenty of help. Van Horn led all scorers 27
points, 21 of them coming in the second half, while Marbury was
sensational throughout the night with 26 points and 14 assists.
Meanwhile, the Nets received key contributions from the bench, led
by forward-center Jamie Feick (16 rebounds), guard Lucious Harris
(14 points), and forward Scott Burrell, (9 points, three
3-pointers). This was how they Nets envisioned themselves when this
nightmarish season, but as injuries and losses snowballed, their
psyche took a beating. The Nets needed a victory against anyone,
anywhere. And Monday night, they finally got one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how I thought we would play every game,'' said
Marbury, who has been openly frustrated much of season, but who had
reason to smile Monday night. ``We got loose balls. We played
harder than them and wanted the game more. Any win is a plus,
because I hate losing. Tonight I can sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Webber led Sacramento with 25 points and 14 rebounds,
while Vlade Divac added 21 points, but Corliss Williamson (12
points) was the only other Sacramento player in double figures.
Trailing 54-52 at halftime, the Nets took control in the third
quarter, outscoring the Kings, 30-15, to take an 82-69 lead into
the fourth quarter. And instead of finishing with a fourth-quarter
fold, the Nets never wavered. Sacramento never got closer than 12
points thereafter, and the Nets showed character early, erasing
deficits of 10-0 and 34-24 and changing the momentum in their
favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, that's when we put our heads down,'' said Marbury of
the early deficits. ``That's when the other team smells blood. But
tonight, we played scrappy. It was a total team effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets caught Sacramento at a good time, at the end of a
five-game trip. Yet, the outcome had more to do with New Jersey's
play rather than Sacramento's fatigue. The Nets can be difficult to
handle when Marbury and Van Horn play well together, but Van Horn
has struggled with his shot and his confidence most of the year.
But in the second half, Van Horn was aggressive with his moves and
accurate with his shot, and with Marbury orchestrating the game's
flow, the Kings had no answers.
</P>
<P>
   `Stephon did a great job controlling the game,'' said Van Horn,
who was 9 for 17 from the field, and 6 for 6 from the line. ``I
played looser. I played more relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, the Nets lost by 13 points to the Kings, an
exciting, up-tempo team that is capable of scoring in bunches and
providing must-see highlights. But New Jersey's defense kept
Sacramento in check, and Marbury badly outplayed Jason Williams,
Sacramento's flashy point guard, who finished with just two points
and five assists.
</P>
<P>
   The first half set the tone, when Sacramento raced to a 10-0
lead, only to see the Nets bounce back quickly, tying the game at
20. Then when the Kings pushed their lead to 34-24 late in the
first quarter, the Nets had their most impressive spurt of the
season, scoring the next 15 points to take a 39-34 lead. Feick and
Marbury were the catalysts during that stretch, and while the Nets
trailed at halftime, 54-52, they had sent a message that they would
not be pushovers. The Kings were flustered into 24 turnovers, which
the Nets turned into numerous fast break opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense was the key,'' said Feick, who had seven offensive
rebounds, nine defensive rebounds, 8 points, and several floor
burns. ``Guys were flying around out there creating turnovers, and
that starts our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, who shot 12 for 22 from the field, was solid from start
to finish, and while he committed seven turnovers, he also had four
steals. This was Marbury at his most effective, creating offense
not only for himself, but for others. And the opposition was
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give a lot of credit to Stephon,'' said Webber. ``I still
think he's one of the best guards in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory stopped a six-game home losing streak for the Nets,
who will host the Milwaukee Bucks on Wednesday night to end a
five-game home stand. It remained to be seen whether the Nets would
build on Monday night's effort, or whether it was just a one-game
reprieve. But at least for one night, the smiling faces in the
locker room represented a welcome change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time coming,'' said Nets coach Don Casey.
``The way Stephon moved the ball around and the way Keith got back
his confidence back was a really good sign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
