<HEADLINE>
BRYANT COULD START BY END OF WEEK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kobe Bryant's first start of the season is coming
sooner rather than later _ probably by the end of the week _ but
Bryant is the first to admit he's needed time to re-acclimate to
his Los Angeles Lakers teammates while playing off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   By all outward appearances, Bryant has hardly missed a beat
after sitting seven weeks with a broken right hand. In three games
back, he's averaged 19.0 points, 5.7 rebounds and 2.0 assists in 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much to criticize there, though Bryant said he's far
from playing at his peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really pleased at all,'' he said Monday. ``I feel I
can play much, much, much better. Just an overall game _
rebounding, passing, steals, setting picks, timing of the offense.
Just feeling the rhythm of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been away from it for quite a time. The team has figured
out their own type of rhythm. You're stepping in, you're trying to
see, OK, what type of rhythm are they going with tonight?''
</P>
<P>
   Ready or not, Bryant will rejoin the starting lineup soon. Coach
Phil Jackson won't specify a date but said, ``I think it's
reasonable to tell you that probably within the week, he'll
probably start.... Right now, there's still kind of an adjustment
to playing ball with him and without him.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Jackson is enjoying Bryant's return as much as anyone.
While Bryant's improvisation still gets him in trouble now and
then, Jackson loves the added threat those one-on-one skills
provide the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, the energy is so good for us, to have that kind of
just good energy on the floor. It's quick-hit,'' he said.
``(Sunday) night for us, it just jumped the (lead) from 12 to 20
points. He just moved the game up another eight points and
stretched our lead. So I'm not going to try to harness him in that
regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that energy, I like that unbounded sense of optimism
that he brings to his game. Just trying to get him to do the
combination of attack, both off the pass and in the offense and off
the dribble ... the possibility of carrying that threat of scoring
but actually not trying to score every time he touches the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant can hardly wait to do all that from the opening tip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm eager to get back into the flow of things,'' he said of
starting. ``I've been pressing really, really hard with my game,
trying to learn the team, trying to get back as fast as I possibly
can.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he'll provide those bursts off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``For now I'm just takin' it back to 1996,'' he joked, referring
to his rookie year. ``All I need is the bald head.''
</P>
<P>
   Honored again: Shaquille O'Neal, the NBA's player of the month
for November, was named the league's first player of the week in
December.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal averaged 25.9 points, 14.8 rebounds, 4.3 assists and 3.0
blocks in 38.8 minutes for the week of Nov. 29 through Dec. 5. The
Lakers went 4-0 in that span.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
