<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICANS-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN KEEPS A DEBATE DATE BY SATELLITE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERTOWN, Mass. _ Sen. John McCain was a little bit like the
virtual candidate Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was not noticeable on television, thanks to matching
backdrops. But as the five other Republican contenders for
president debated in the Orpheum Theater in McCain's home state,
Arizona, the senator stood at a lectern across the country in a
television studio in the Boston suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   He was beamed into the event by satellite, as Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas chose to remind everyone when he tossed a question to
McCain ``wherever you are out there.''
</P>
<P>
   With  &LR; McCain running even in the polls with Bush in the first
primary state of New Hampshire, both men were under pressure to put
on a commanding performance Monday night, four days after the first
encounter among all six Republican candidates, in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   And one unknown was just how the satellite hookup would affect
public perceptions. Joking before the debate, McCain told reporters
that perhaps he could be beamed in as a large backdrop, towering
above the other candidates like Big Brother. He also tried to
minimize the significance of the evening, saying, ``I don't think
any single debate is of great importance.''
</P>
<P>
   He had to maneuver with a television camera to one side of him.
A television monitor brought in the events in Arizona with a
several-second time delay. And McCain's aides fretted about
microphone feedback.
</P>
<P>
   The night's odd format was indicative of the jousting that has
gone on as five contenders have sought to share the stage with
Bush. The Texas governor skipped an earlier debate in Arizona. So
the party arranged a new one.
</P>
<P>
   This time, McCain, who participated in the earlier matchup, had
campaign events in New Hampshire and New York that he refused to
cancel, and he initially said he would not participate. Then the
debate sponsors agreed to the satellite hookup.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the senator's day was consumed with town meetings in New
Hampshire. In Farmington's Town Hall, McCain vowed that as
president he would push for an overhaul of the campaign finance law
and veto every measure containing pork-barrel special-interest
projects. If Congress overrode his veto, he said, he would use the
president's bully pulpit to publicize which members of Congress
were pushing such projects.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he would veto such spending bills and risk a
government shutdown, he said, ``Sure I would, because if we don't
change business as usual in Washington, more and more people will
be deprived of their representation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
