<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S PRINCE CHARMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The reporter from Atlanta wanted to know what the problem was
between Arizona Sen. John McCain and ``The Arizona Republic''.
</P>
<P>
   He said McCain's campaign people told him not to talk to
reporters in Arizona, not if he wanted to get to know the ``real''
McCain. Instead, the writer from Georgia was advised to speak with
reporters in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would the McCain folks say that?'' he asked me.
</P>
<P>
   Because they're smart, I told him.
</P>
<P>
   Just about any member of the Washington press corps will be able
to reel off three things about Sen. McCain:
</P>
<P>
   1) He's a war hero, having suffered through 5{ years in a North
Vietnamese prison camp.
</P>
<P>
   2) He's a maverick who's taken on his own political party in
fights with Big Tobacco and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   3) He's a straight-shooter, a lovable rogue who admits raising
hell as a young man.
</P>
<P>
   The boys from Washington will also tell you McCain has learned
from his mistakes. They'll tell you he's tough, funny, even a
little bawdy at times. And they're correct.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is the most attractive political candidate in America, on
the surface. And that's exactly where McCain's presidential
campaign wants to keep it.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Hero worship
</P>
<P>
   In Washington and elsewhere, reporters seem happy to go along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Esquire'' magazine printed a profile of McCain under the
headline, ``John McCain Walks on Water.'' The senator has been
fawned over in the ``New York'' ``Times,'' the ``Boston Globe,''
the ``Wall Street Journal,'' the ``Washington Post'' and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``60 Minutes'' star Mike Wallace once said, ``I'm thinking I may
quit my job if (McCain) gets the nomination. I'm impressed by his
independence, by his willingness to take on the tough ones. By his
honesty about himself. As I look at the current crop, there's
something authentic about this man.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I envy Mike Wallace and the writers for ``Esquire'' and the
``Times'' and the ``Post'' and all the other journalists from
outside Arizona who are covering McCain.
</P>
<P>
   He's new to them, mysterious, tough, attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Every reporter outside of Arizona wants to date John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   We're married to him.
</P>
<P>
   They're infatuated with the image. We're stuck with the man.
</P>
<P>
   They're head over heels for a guy who seems to be the opposite
of the guy currently in the White House. They don't want to know
what Arizona reporters could tell them about McCain's political
table manners, or where he leaves his dirty socks, or how he treats
the family dog when no one's looking.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Gwen Ifill told one newspaper, ``John McCain intrigues
reporters because he seems to be a maverick. He takes on popular
issues that can't necessarily pass, and we like that. Plus he's a
war hero, and we're kind of desperate for heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Watch and learn
</P>
<P>
   That's how it was for us in the 1980s, when McCain was first
elected to Congress in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, though, contradictions surfaced. The campaign
reformer cozied up to bigwigs he's supposed to regulate. The
iconoclast trashed Big Tobacco but not Big Alcohol, financing
campaigns with money from a beer distributorship owned by his
wife's family.
</P>
<P>
   There were stories of his temper, of occasional cruelties. (No
one mentions anymore the nasty joke he told about Chelsea Clinton.)
</P>
<P>
   For us in Arizona, it's become a marriage of convenience. We
give McCain a platform; he gives the state some national exposure.
But, Prince Charming has turned back into a frog. McCain didn't
even come home for Monday's presidential debate in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's people don't want out-of-town reporters to hear
that stuff. They want allure, romance.
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted a reporter to hear only good things about a guy,
who would you send him to?
</P>
<P>
   The wife, or the mistress? &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini(at)arizonarepublic.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
