<HEADER>
A1384 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEBATE-1STLEDE-COX     12-06 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Candidates question each other but avoid pit-bull politics
 &HT;    (EDS: 1st Lede.)
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The six GOP presidential contenders mixed it up Monday
night, albeit cordially, taking advantage of a debate format that
allowed them to question each other.
</P>
<P>
   The event was televised nationwide, with Arizona Sen. John
McCain participating by satellite from Boston, near where he has
been campaigning in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The event marked Gov. George W. Bush's second debate of the
season. He skipped several debates prior to showing up last
Thursday in Manchester, N.H. for a forum that was more simultaneous
news conference than debate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules of Monday night's debate at a Phoenix theater,
each candidate had two chances to question an opponent of his
choice. But in each round, each candidate could be targeted only
once.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing the candidates to question each other hardly produced
fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They laid out their own positions, and they were all very safe
questions,'' said Diana Carlin, a professor of communication
studies at the University of Kansas, who serves on an advisory
board on presidential debates. ``I was disappointed. I expected a
little bit more of going after what the other people are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   In both rounds, the first questioner chose to question
front-runner Bush. Gary Bauer challenged him on China. Publisher
Steve Forbes challenged him on rising oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants the World Trade Organization to accept China. Bauer
said China, because of human rights abuses, has not earned it. The
governor wouldn't budge from his belief that trade leads to
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we trade with China and give people a taste of freedom, I
think you will be amazed, Gary, at how soon democracy will come,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes got to ask the first question in the second round,
challenging Bush to come up with a plan to reverse recent increases
in oil prices triggered by production cuts from the Organization of
the Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would ``encourage exploration'' and has great hope
for the continued expansion of natural gas use.
</P>
<P>
   Bush used his two questions to elicit praise of his programs. In
the first round, Bush opted to ask Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch what Hatch
would do to help the GOP draw more minority votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You deserve a lot of credit,'' Hatch told Bush. ``You are one
of the Republicans who reached out to women and minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, Bush asked McCain what he would do to
encourage faith-based organizations to provide social services, a
key plank in the Bush platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you are on the right track, governor or George or W.
Bush,'' replied McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain took advantage of a Bush follow-up question to
challenge the Texan's contention that continuing surpluses will pay
for his proposed $483 billion tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not envision surpluses forever,'' said McCain. ``I take
the money for tax breaks out of wasteful spending and corporate
welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes drew some of the loudest applause of the evening,
particularly when he went after the current income tax system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are worse off than the serfs,'' he said. ``The serfs used
to pay their masters after they were fed and clothed. We have to
pay our masters before we are fed and clothed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hatch also came on strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been a great governor,'' Hatch told Bush, adding,
however, that a term and a half as governor does not qualify Bush
for the White House. ``I should be president and you should have
eight years with me,'' Hatch said. ``And, boy, you'd make a heck of
a president after eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did Thursday in New Hampshire, Bush played it close to the
vest, dishing out sound-bite-size chunks of his stump speech
whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only one.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are saying that he's just reciting lines from his
speeches aren't being fair. Yes, he's doing that, but so are the
others,'' said Dartmouth government professor Linda Fowler.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, McCain even pulled a line out of a Forbes speech
and asked, with a sly grin, ``Where have I heard that before?''
</P>
<P>
   Polls here have shown Bush in second place in Arizona, within
striking distance, of McCain. Arizona Republicans, who backed Steve
Forbes in the 1996 primary, will vote Feb. 22. McCain has been a
ballot-box monster in his Senate races, grabbing 70 percent of the
vote in his 1998 re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Since the New Hampshire debate, where his temperament came under
question, McCain has released more than 1,000 pages of medical
records related to treatment after his five years of captivity in
North Vietnam. The records show no reason why McCain, who
acknowledges he has a temper, can't serve as president.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Gov. Jane Dee Hull, who says she has seen McCain's
temper in action, is a Bush backer.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also was noted for his temper when he was an aide to
his father, although he hasn't lost his cool as governor. Fowler
said she detected signs of his old testiness during an exchange
with Forbes in Monday's debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the warmth and personal charm that he's noted for
simply doesn't come across on television,'' she said. ``People may
start to tease him about his temper.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's debate came as polls continued to show Bush with a
substantial lead nationwide, but in a neck-and-neck battle with
McCain in New Hampshire, where the Arizona senator hopes to turn a
Feb. 1 victory into a springboard to an upset.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. Scott S. Greenberger contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
